from copyrights to civil rights, congress has overridden nine of the 63 vetoes president reagan has exercised since he took office in 1981
this gives reagan a better batting average than his last republican predecessor, president ford but not as good a one as president carter, who had democratic majorities in both houses of congress
ford, with the opposition party controlling both the house and senate, sent up 66 vetoes and had 12 of them, or 18 percent, knocked down
carter vetoed 31 bills and had only two of them overridden, well under 10 percent
counting tuesday's override of his civil rights bill veto, reagan has struck out 14 percent of the times he has used his constitutional power to disapprove legislation
reagan has faced democratic control in the house throughout his more than seven years in office. the senate, however, was under republican control from 1981 until last year
it takes a two-thirds majority of both houses to overcome a presidential veto
records of the white house executive clerk's office show that five reagan vetoes have been sustained. in the other 49 cases, the question of an override was not put to a vote
once, reagan squeaked through by one vote. that was on june 5, 1986, when the senate sustained a presidential veto allowing a weapons sale to saudi arabia to proceed. the count was 66-34, just shy of the 67 votes needed for a two-thirds majority with all senators voting
on another occasion, it took nearly eight months to round up the votes to block the house from overriding the president's veto of trade legislation curbing textile, apparel and shoe imports. reagan vetoed the bill on dec. 17, 1985. the house put off action until next year and it was not until aug. 6, 1986, that it voted. the count was 276-149, or eight votes short of the two thirds needed to override
tuesday's house and senate votes marked the 101st time in u.s. history that a presidential veto has been overridden. there have been 2,452 vetoes, beginning with the administration of george washington
andrew johnson had the worst veto record in history. the post-civil war president vetoed 29 bills and was overridden 15 times
the bills previously put into law over reagan's veto were:
_an act to amend the manufacturing clause of the copyright law, vetoed july 8, 1982
_a $14.2 billion supplemental appropriation for the fiscal year ending sept. 30, 1982, vetoed on aug. 28, 1982
_an act authorizing a transfer of federal land in lane county, ore., vetoed oct. 19, 1983
_an act to authorize continuation of a program of water resources research, vetoed feb. 21, 1984
_an act revising authorization laws governing the national institutes of health and national research institutes, vetoed nov. 8, 1985
_an act providing economic sanctions against the white minority government of south africa, vetoed sept. 26, 1986
_the water quality act of 1987, a $20 billion anti-pollution measure, vetoed jan. 30, 1987
_the federal aid highway act of 1987, an $88 billion highway and mass transit measure, vetoed march 27, 1987. from tribes</head>
it has been more than 160 years since the first american indian newspaper was published and its editor clashed with tribal leaders, and newspapers on the reservation still struggle for their independence today
elias boudinot opened the cherokee phoenix on feb. 21, 1828, in new echota, ga., and resigned four years later rather than accept censorship from the cherokees' primary chief
things haven't changed much in 160 years, journalists reported at a meeting of the native american press association. tribal leaders still are not convinced of the value of objective reporting on tribal politics and other news
although some tribal constitutions had free press provisions as early as the mid-1800s, the u.s. constitution's first amendment rights did not extend to the reservations until 1968, when congress passed the indian bill of rights
today's indian journalists, the first generation to try to exercise those rights on the reservation, are hampered by reservation poverty that limits advertising revenue and forces tribal governments to underwrite the newspapers
ten financially self-sufficient newspapers are operating, most begun in the last decade ``precipitated by the need for editorial independence,'' said richard lacourse, a yakima indian writing a book on the native american press
the rest of the 464 indian newspapers and bulletins on reservations and in urban indian communities are owned by the tribes _ and controlled by tribal leaders who often interfere with news operations, lacourse said
tribal leaders have fired editors for taking opposing sides in elections or in editorials; cut off newspaper funds; forced the hiring of their unqualified relatives; excluded reporters from meetings and suppressed stories by threatening editors and reporters, lacourse said
at the napa meeting last week, one editor reported being ordered by tribal leaders not to report the conviction of one leader on a child molestation charge
the editor said she agreed because, as a single parent, she felt she could not risk losing what was one of the few full-time jobs she could find on the reservation
a reporter for one of 25 indian-owned radio stations said her tribal leaders once took over the station for several hours to air their views on a subject they thought the station had not covered sufficiently
tim giago, a co-founder of napa who owns two independent tribal newspapers, says the interference will continue until journalists buy their publications from the tribes and operate them as profit-making businesses
if the tribe is paying your salary, why should they let you say anything that is going to undermine their position?'' he asked in a telephone interview from his offices in rapid city, s.d
because his lakota times of martin, s.d., and ojibwe times of bemidji, minn., rely on advertising revenue, giago said, ``we have the freedom to criticize the tribal government. my responsibilities are to my readers. i'm not beholden to the tribal government.''
an example of tribal leaders' influence was the navajo times today, a one-time weekly that became the first and only daily native american newspaper in 1984 and was closed in 1987
shortly after his election, tribal chairman peter macdonald ordered an audit that found the newspaper was $750,000 in debt. he shut it down and fired its 49-member staff
the times reopened as a weekly with a new, mostly non-indian staff several months later
the main reason the times was killed was because we couldn't be controlled,'' former editor and publisher mark trahant, who made the times a daily newspaper, said in a speech to about 150 napa members
trahant, an investigative reporter for the arizona republic in phoenix, said the times apparently caused animosity when it sponsored a tribal election campaign debate that degenerated into a name-calling shouting match
macdonald did not return a telephone call to tribal headquarters in window rock, ariz., seeking comment
the first indian publisher, boudinot, clashed with cherokee chief john ross, who wanted to fight the relocation law that eventually forced the cherokees and four other tribes to give up their east coast lands and move west
ross tried to fire him but boudinot resigned first, in the summer of 1832, and moved his family to oklahoma in 1838 in advance of the ``trail of tears,'' when 4,000 cherokees died on a forced march from appalachia
on june 23, 1839, in park hill, okla., boudinot was stabbed and hacked to death in what was described then as a revenge killing
japanese curbs on beef and citrus imports are costing consumers in tokyo two to four times what their american counterparts pay and should come down, u.s. farm and trade officials say
it seems to us the japanese consumer should have a right to choose the products at a price that is much better, and they would if the quotas were eliminated,'' agriculture secretary richard lyng said tuesday
lyng and u.s. trade representative clayton k. yeutter said at a news conference, however, that thus far the japanese have not budged on quotas that limit imports of american beef and citrus
we still have to hear from the japanese on their willingness to liberalize beef and citrus,'' lyng told the session, called to spotlight the march 31 expiration date of a beef and citrus agreement with the japanese
under the 4-year-old agreement, the united states has not challenged the quotas. but officials are now saying that it is time for them to end
in response, japanese officials say that lowering the barriers would bring on a torrent of low-priced american products that would wipe out their home country's beef and citrus sector
the two american officials produced charts showing that american navel oranges that sold for 33 cents each in washington on march 1 were selling for 65 cents each in tokyo
grapefruits selling for 32 cents each in washington sold for 73 cents in tokyo on the same day, they said. they said consumers in the nation's capital were paying $4.99 a pound for strip sirloin while consumers in japan's capital were paying $20.56 a pound for comparable steak
it remains unclear whether eliminating the import curbs would bring on unemployment among japanese cattle ranchers and citrus growers, yeutter said. he said it would depend ``on whether our japanese friends are resilient'' enough to cope with intensified competition
if it did mean some structural adjustment, that's the price we pay for a free and open trading system,'' yeutter said. ``we've had some adjustment, too.''
one option open to the united states would be to seek a ruling against the japanese for unfair trade practices under the general agreement on tariffs and trade, the officials said. they said another would be to start action possibly leading to retaliation against the japanese barriers
the nikkei stock average closed at 25,895.23 points, up 52.48 points, on the tokyo stock exchange on wednesday
a group of women serving long prison terms at an underground facility in lexington, ky., allege in a suit that they are being treated inhumanely because of their political beliefs
the suit in u.s. district court in washington, filed by civil liberties groups on behalf of the five inmates at the lexington control unit, names attorney general edwin meese iii and eight other federal officials
it seeks the immediate transfer of the inmates from the high-security facility to the general population of a federal women's prison
opened in november 1986, the ``small basement facility'' has ``virtually no natural light'' and is illuminated 24 hours a day by fluorescent lights, said the suit, prepared by the national prison project of the american civil liberties union and other attorneys
the women, the suit said, are monitored continuously by staff and video cameras, have no opportunity to participate in any of the activities available to the general prison population and are subjected to random strip searches
we believe the women's lives are in danger,'' said susan waysdorf, a spokeswoman for civil libertarians supporting the suit. ``they're beginning to experience signs of behavior modification, general disorientation, vision problems, loss of appetite, sleeplessness.''
among the inmates are silvia baraldini, convicted of racketeering and conspiracy in aiding a $1.6 million brink's armored car heist in nyack, n.y., that left a guard and two police officers dead. another inmate at lexington is susan rosenberg, linked by law enforcement officers to the same bungled brink's robbery
baraldini, serving a 40-year term, was transferred to lexington after refusing to be interviewed by an fbi agent, the suit said
rosenberg, serving a 58-year term for possession of weapons and explosives in connection with a 1985 police raid in new jersey, was told that she would be confined to the unit until she changes her political beliefs, the suit alleges
the u.s. bureau of prisons said in october it will phase out the unit, the only high-security unit for women in the federal prison system
a new medium- and high-security facility for women will be opened in june in marianna, fla., and the phase-out in lexington will be completed shortly thereafter, said bureau of prisons spokeswoman kathryn morse. she declined to comment on the suit
the primary purpose for the creation of the unit was to confine prisoners whose political associations and affiliations were determined to pose a security threat,'' said the suit, which alleges violation of the women's constitutional rights. ``all the women in the unit are suffering psychological and physical harm as a direct consequence of their isolated confinement in this underground segregation unit.''
when civil liberties groups began to expose lexington as a ``political prison, federal officials hurriedly brought in two other women serving long sentences,'' a coalition of civil libertarians said in a statement about the lexington unit
one of the women brought in later, sylvia brown, serving a 27-year term for probation violation and escaping from a federal prison, was told that her release from the unit would depend on her lack of interaction with the political activists, the suit said
baraldini, rosenberg and brown filed the suit
sen. paul simon, calling himself an ``underdog fighting for the underdog,'' says he hopes wisconsin's progressive political tradition can carry him to victory in the state's april 5 primary
simon, who won the democratic primary in his home state of illinois last week, needs another victory to keep his candidacy alive. while he did not predict a win here, he said he expects a strong finish
i grew up in the progressive tradition,'' said simon. ``i'm an underdog who's fighting for the underdog.''
simon appeared at a news conference at a shopping center built adjacent to the allis-chalmers corp. plant, a once-mighty farm equipment company which filed for bankruptcy reorganization last year
we have to restore and revitalize our manufacturing base,'' simon said, noting how high paying jobs at the factory have disappeared while low paying service jobs at the shopping center have grown
the senator sprinkled his comments with references to former wisconsin sen. robert lafollette, founder of the progressive party, who simon said ``stood up to individual and corporate greed.''
simon said he would try to stop the erosion of the manufacturing sector by offering tax breaks for companies that create jobs while removing tax incentives for companies that move production overseas
simon flew to washington earlier in the day, where he joined the successful majority in the senate in voting to override president reagan's veto of a sweeping civil rights bill
it's another indication of the insensitivity of the administration to women, to people with disabilities, to minorities,'' simon said of the veto
simon has criticized the reagan administration's sending of troops to hnduras
we should use tools of diplomacy rather than weapons of war,'' simon said. ``both sides should concentrate on working out their differences at the negotiating table, not on the battlefield.''
sen. bob dole, all but knocked out of the republican presidential running by vice president george bush, says he needs a comeback _ and wisconsin is just the place to start it
this is a very important state,'' dole told the milwaukee rotary club tuesday. ``voters in this state are going to have an impact. in my case, i've got a big comeback to make _ it may as well start here.''
the kansas senator made his remarks while wrapping up a three-day visit to the state, which will hold its presidential primary april 5
vice president george bush has an overwhelming lead in the delegate totals, but dole said he hopes voters in wisconsin will look past those numbers and examine the issues
i hope people will take a hard look at all of us,'' he said. ``i'm prepared to answer all the hard questions.''
in his speech to the business people, dole stressed his campaign theme of a spending freeze to curb the federal deficit
when that's in place, then we can go down program by program,'' he said. ``i believe i'm the one candidate who can sit down with members of both parties and hammer out a deficit reduction package.''
dole outlined similar themes earlier in a speech to students and teachers at oak creek high school
we're not voting for momentum,'' he said. ``we're voting for candidates.''
one thing i've learned in politics over the years is that nobody's certain what's going to happen from one day to the next. i know some in the media have already written my obituary,'' he said. ``i've read it. sounds pretty good _ i made a gallant fight but lost.''
the last time i looked, the people in this state hadn't even voted,'' he said. ``so i don't think we should write anything off.''
dole also repeated his request for a debate with bush, a challenge the vice president declined in illinois
i would say to my chief opponent: you name one thing you've done that's affected anybody in the state of wisconsin, one thing in the past seven years, and i'll buy you lunch.''
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis was the only democratic presidential contender to outpoll vice president george bush in a washington post-abc news poll, the newspaper reported today
dukakis led bush, 50 percent to 45 percent, when voters were asked which of the two they would vote for if the election were held today
in other matchups, jesse jackson was outpolled by bush 58 percent to 34 percent; sen. albert gore jr. lost out 53 percent to 40 percent; and rep. richard gephardt was behind 53 percent to 40 percent, the post said
new york gov. mario cuomo, who is not a candidate, also lost to bush, 53 percent to 38 percent
the nationwide telephone survey of 775 registered voters had a margin of error of 4 percentage points, the newspaper said. it was conducted thursday through monday
dukakis did about the same against sen. bob dole of kansas, whose prospects of gaining the republican nomination are seen as slim. dukakis polled 48 percent to dole's 44 percent, according to the survey
in the survey, bush had the highest favorable ratings of any contender of either party, the newspaper said. more than three out of five registered voters, including nearly half of the democrats, said they had a generally favorable impression of the vice president. that represents an increase of 11 percentage points since an abc news-washington post survey in january
the poll suggested the popularity of dukakis and jackson has also risen. a total of 57 percent of all voters had a favorable impression of dukakis, the newspaper said, _ about double the january figure
fifty-three percent of all voters said they had a favorable impression of jackson, up from 42 percent in the january survey, the newspaper said
here are the major provisions of the civil rights restoration act as they apply to the four statutes protecting women, minorities, the elderly and the handicapped from federally subsidized discrimination
_compliance with the statutes is required of entire departments and agencies of state and local governments when any part of the department or agency receives federal aid
_compliance is required throughout entire colleges, universities and public school systems if any program or activity receives federal aid
_compliance is required of entire corporations and private organizations if federal aid is extended to them as a whole or if they are principally involved in providing education, health care, housing, social services or parks or recreation. otherwise, compliance is limited to the plant or facility receiving the aid
_ultimate beneficiaries of federal aid, such as farmers receiving crop subsidies or people getting food stamps or social security, do not come under federal civil rights regulation
_small providers such as mom and pop grocery stores are given flexibility in making their facilities accessible to handicapped people
_people with contagious diseases or infections are considered handicapped and protected by civil rights laws unless they pose a direct threat to the health or safety of others or are unable to perform their jobs
_institutions and individuals are not required to perform or pay for abortions or services relating to them. no penalties are permitted against people seeking benefits or services related to an abortion
spending big money on space age hospital equipment is not necessarily the best way to provide quality medical care, says the federal government's top health official
sometimes our high-tech capability lures us into pursuing expensive answers when less costly ones are available,'' dr. otis r. bowen said tuesday. ``our veneration of technology has become a cultural blind spot that sometimes keeps us from pursuing practical solutions to our problems.''
the health and human service secretary's remarks to a conference of the health care quality alliance came shortly after the 28-member coalition issued a report saying cost control should stop where ``quality of care _ and quality of life _ are adversely affected.''
bowen said cost containment and quality care can co-exist
sometimes you can save money and also improve care, like concentrating certain procedures in hospitals that specialize in them,'' he said. ``this not only leads to better results for the patient, it also allows us to benefit from economies of scale
one reason today's health care is so expensive is that the financing of that care is little more than a collection of disincentives to practice cost-effective medicine
hospitals, in order to attract doctors and their patients, have bought and often duplicated the latest in medical hardware in a kind of medical arms race.''
he said exempting employer-paid health insurance coverage from federal income taxes has ``encouraged employers and unions to bargain for ever-greater first-dollar coverage in health insurance plans.''
compounding this folly, most insurance plans cover expensive high-tech procedures and slight preventive services,'' bowen added. ``and all of this has made patients and their families all but oblivious to costs, since they pay so little out of pocket.''
bowen said the establishment of the federal medicare health program for the elderly in 1965 ``created a powerful incentive for the health care industry to develop the technology to treat the chronic, degenerative diseases that afflict the aging.''
while that has ``improved the quality of life for americans of all ages,'' bowen said the nation has yet to face difficult questions of how best to allocate health dollars in the modern era
still to be decided is how much is too much,'' he said. ``how much heroic medical care and how many procedures to keep a dying patient alive are desirable for the patient, the family and, not least of all, for society at large? when is such care merely prolonging the act of dying rather than contributing to longer life, or at least some type of quality to it?''
bowen is a 70-year-old physician whose first wife died in 1981 after a long battle with bone cancer and whose mother recently died in a nursing home
the alliance membership includes the american medical association, the alzheimer's disease and related disorders association, the arthritis foundation, the american cancer society, the american academy of pediatrics and the national council on the aging. assignments</head>
the department of defense has decided to begin aids testing on civilian workers destined for overseas assignments, with an estimated 8,000 men and women to be affected during the first year, officials said tuesday
no date for the start of civilian screening has yet been established, said the pentagon, which already operates the world's largest aids testing program
the aids blood test will be administered to civilian workers during a complete physical examination, which will become mandatory for those drawing overseas assignments
the approach is similar to that now used by the state department, the pentagon officials said
in another move, deputy defense secretary william h. taft iv has authorized the army to draft a legislative proposal that would make it easier to discharge service members on a medical disability if they test positively for the aids virus
such legislation, if ever enacted, could provide the military with a means of discharging servicemen as soon as they test positively for exposure, regardless of whether they're showing any symptoms yet of the deadly disease itself
one way to do that, the sources explained tuesday, is to broaden the legal definition of a military disability
currently, no individual on active duty who tests positively for aids on a blood test can be discharged without showing other medical symptoms of the disease
the decisions involving aids policies were first disclosed early this month by defense sources who requested anonymity. the defense department subsequently confirmed the actions, while insisting in a written statement to the associated press that taft had issued ``preliminary guidance'' without yet signing any final directives
the decision has been made even if a directive hasn't been signed,'' countered one source. ``he was presented options and made up his mind.''
aids _ acquired immune deficiency syndrome _ attacks the body's immune system and its ability to resist infection. no cure has been found for the disease, which can be spread through sexual contact and tainted blood
the pentagon, citing the need to protect military blood supplies, routinely tests all 2.1 million men and women on active duty as well as all recruit applicants. a service member who tests positively _ but who is not disabled by the disease _ is restricted to duty inside the united states and may be limited in job assignments
a recruit who tests positively is denied admission to the military
despite the massive commitment to aids screening, which began in october 1985, the pentagon has until recently focused only on military personnel
according to sources, the army has repeatedly urged aids testing for all defense department workers as well as automatic discharge or dismissal for those testing positively. defense health officials have always rebuffed those suggestions, saying they were too far-reaching
the sources said taft had finally decided to take the middle road when it came to civilians, focusing only on those who draw assignments outside the united states
the new program is expected to cost roughly $1.6 million a year, one official said. struggle</head>
president jose napoleon duarte and the rightists who defeated his party in legislative and municipal elections have declared a willingness to work together on this country's tremendous problems
but the leftist guerrillas waging an 8-year-old war against the u.s.-backed government said tuesday the result of sunday's vote would make the nation ``ungovernable.'' a rebel commander said the electoral result _ an outright majority for the rightist opposition in the national legislature _ favors the guerrillas by giving the people ``a clear alternative.''
in addition to the war, el salvador has crippling economic problems
the central elections council has not yet announced the apportionment of seats in the unicameral, 60-seat national assembly
but the council president, mario samayoa, said on monday the rightist republican nationalist alliance, known by the spanish acronym arena, got a majority of votes cast nationwide, which assured it of a legislative majority. local media projected arena would get 33 or 34 seats. the party said it had 35
the governing christian democrats had 33 seats in the outgoing legislature. they were expected to win about 22 seats, with the remainder going to small rightist parties. arena also won the mayoralties and town councils of about 200 of the country's 262 municipalities, including san salvador
arena is ready to work with the other parties, and with president duarte, so that together we might achieve the solution to the national crisis,'' alfredo cristiani, president of arena and a legislator, said at a news conference. ``it is time to work together on behalf of the heroic people who cast their votes despite threats and terrorist acts.''
the guerrillas had called for a boycott of the elections and had stepped up urban and rural violence in the two weeks prior to the vote. in what they called repudiation of the ``electoral farce,'' they set off three car bombs, sabotaged power lines in large parts of the country and ordered a nationwide transport ban that they enforced by burning more than a dozen vehicles
the rebels contended the elections were part of an american-imposed counterinsurgency plan, and that they were illegitimate in wartime
despite the boycott call, about 70 percent of the 1.6 million registered voters cast ballots. many of them walked long distances to do so
in the same way we have made this effort to strengthen the democratic process, let us contribute our will and capacities to find together the road to peace,'' duarte told the nation in a radio and television address monday night
he said the parties in the legislature were, along with the executive branch, ``co-responsible'' for governing. duarte said once final results were known, he would meet with party leaders to search for consensus on how to solve the nation's pressing problems
besides the war, which has killed 65,000 people and made refugees out of 500,000, el salvador's economy is crippled. both inflation and unemployment are estimated at about 40 percent
what is coming is that we're on the road to a power void,'' guerrilla commander joaquin villalobos said tuesday on radio venceremos, the clandestine rebel station. ``the country will become ungovernable with this composition of forces
the big loser is the counterinsurgency project and the big winner is the people, which has before it a clear alternative _ the fmln, organization and struggle.'' the alliance of five rebel armies is the farabundo marti national liberation front, or fmln
we must prepare to struggle decisively because today we confront a weakened enemy and we must take advantage of that,'' he said
despite the politicans' conciliatory words, there were those who speculated arena would use its position in the assembly to further erode popular support for the chistian democrats by opposing government initiatives
presidential elections are set for march 1989, and arena could benefit from making the duarte administration appear even more ineffectual than it has been in addressing the national crisis
only enough nuclear waste to carry out experiments will be placed in the repository planned as the nation's first resting place for defense-related radioactive wastes, the department of energy says
the department said tuesday it was following the national academy of sciences' recommendations to test whether wipp, the waste isolation pilot plant in underground salt beds near carlsbad, is suitable as a permanent repository
the department also said that by june it would meet the academy's request for a detailed five-year plan for its experimental waste disposal program for the repository, which was designed to contain low- and intermediate level wastes
both recommendations were made in report of the wipp panel of the academy's board of radioactive waste management on march 3, about four months after scientists told congress that water seeping into the repository threatened its ability to safely store wastes that would remain radioactive for hundreds of thousands of years
the academy panel, however, concluded that technical uncertainties regarding brine seepage at the plant were not serious enough to halt research at the site. shipments of waste are to begin arriving in october
energy department officials said tuesday the academy report will assist in resolving the issue of brine accumulation at the site and will be useful in burying waste in a manner that protects of the environment
about 25,000 barrels of waste will be delivered to the site in the first 1{ years of the test, the department's albuquerque office said tuesday. the department originally had planned to entomb 125,000 barrels of wastes during the next five years
republican party figures say george bush is unlikely to break with president reagan on a major issue, even though bush is trying to appeal to some groups reagan has not attracted
bush's statement that he supports reagan's veto of a major civil rights bill, some observers say, reinforces the view of some that bush is incapable of showing any independence from reagan
but bush's top campaign spokesman, pete teeley, called this a non-issue, and said the vice president's loyalty to reagan is more important than a show of independence
the fact is, six months ago everybody was writing that george bush had to disagree with the president in order to get the nomination,'' teeley said tuesday. ``everyone now sees that that was a myth.''
teeley's assessment came a day after bush, when pressed to say whether he agreed with reagan's veto of the sweeping civil rights bill, told reporters that ``i'm not going to start differing'' with reagan after seven and a half years as vice president
i don't think that you're going to see the vice president be critical of the president,'' teeley said. ``i do think you are going to see him lay out his own programs and proposals.''
but two former gop national chairmen said they think bush, sooner or later, will have to show some differences between his views and reagan's
the vice president is in a box,'' said one-time chairman richard richards. ``if he deviates one iota, there are some right-wing nuts out there who will say he cannot carry on the reagan revolution.''
another former chairman, howard ``bo'' calloway, said that ``at some time, there will be something pretty big where the vice president will say, `hey, i love the man, but i just have to disagree.'''
said mitchell daniels, a former white house political director for reagan: ``it points up what you could call the veep's disease. that is to say that every vice president must confront this problem, especially if you're no. 2 to a very popular no. 1
with the (republican presidential) nomination in hand and loyalty to the president no longer the dominant or most powerful theme, he can try his hand at establishing his own identity,'' daniels said. ``but he must be careful that that comes through extension, rather than exception'' to reagan programs and policies
the civil rights bill, which had support from republicans as well as democrats in congress, was seen by some as a chance for bush to break with reagan on an issue that reagan was going to lose anyway on senate and house override votes
some also saw a bush break as necessary, given statements by bush and his top aides indicating that the vice president was going to try to reach out to blacks and minorities _ groups that reagan failed to win in any substantial numbers in his two presidential election victories
arthur fletcher, a black and one-time assistant secretary of labor during the nixon administration, said it was not essential that bush disagree with reagan's veto of legislation to overturn the supreme court's so-called grove city ruling that limited federal protection for many groups
he said that bush, during an appearance before a black group monday night ``made a commitment that he is going to enforce all civil rights legislation. ... the bottom line is that he was not elected by the delegation to be the vice president, he was picked by the president to be the vice president.''
bush has said on occasion that he would speak out on ``my own vision'' of america, or ``how i would do things.'' but he also has steadfastly insisted he would say nothing that could be taken as a direct criticism of the president
last october, for instance, bush seemed to have gone back to his 1980 position on abortion. he said, in iowa, that he supported allowing the procedure to be performed in cases where the mother's life was in danger, or in cases of rape or incest. this was a departure from reagan's position, which is that abortion should be allowed only to save a mother's life
the bush campaign heatedly denied that the vice president was reverting to his position of 1980. bush had muted his differences with reagan on this issue in 1984 when they ran for re-election together
richards said tuesday that ``i think the time may well come when he takes a different position. i'm sure that george bush doesn't agree 100 percent with everything that this administration does. ... he's in a tough spot.''
calloway agreed that bush has been faced with ``a very real problem from the day he announced his candidacy.'' but he said ``i don't think he ought to go out of his way and find differences'' with reagan
i'll bet a nickel the president has told him, `look, george, you're running now. you've got to be your own man,''' calloway said. position</head>
after gaining control of the national assembly, the rightist republican nationalist alliance could block the president's program and mount a strong challenge in the 1989 presidential race
the stinging defeat in sunday's election left president jose napoleon duarte and his christian democrats on the defensive
duarte will be unable to enact economic reforms and the opposition will be able to put its stamp on the national budget and other legislation
the rightist party, known by its spanish acronym arena, is trying to polish its image with an eye to next year's presidential race
former army maj. robert d'aubuisson, the party's founder who has been accused of links to el salvador's death squads, is being kept out of the limelight as much as possible. party chairman alfredo cristiani, a u.s.-educated businessman and coffee grower, now speaks for arena
arena is trying to project an image of a conservative organization that wants to safeguard the country's traditional values and restore law and order. the party once was notorious for its diatribes against the dangers of communism and alleged interference by the united states in salvadoran affairs
both messages are still there, but the tone is more low key
shortly before the elections, cristiani told reporters: ``the most important change the party has made was the decision to make arena a true political institution rather than a movement revolving around an individual, and without the traditional `boss-ism' of salvadoran politics.''
the strategy seems to have paid off, striking a chord among salvadorans tired of eight years of civil war with leftist rebels that has killed about 65,000 people and devastated the once-prosperous economy
arena on sunday wrested control of the 60-member national assembly away from duarte's christian democrats and won a majority of the 262 city and town mayors nationwide, including the traditional duarte stronghold of san salvador
final returns are not in, but projections show arena is assured of at least 30 seats in the new legislature. and arena has as its ally the national conciliation party, which may hold on to most of its 12 seats
the christian democrats are expected to lose most of their 33-seat majority to arena, which had only 13 seats in the old assembly
the outcome will make duarte's last year in office extremely difficult, similar to his first year when the rightist opposition also controlled the assembly. in 1984, duarte defeated d'aubuisson in a presidential race and he has governed with a christian democratic-controlled assembly since 1985
on monday, duarte called on all parties to act responsibly to solve the nation's serious problems
d'aubuisson lost the 1984 election, mainly because of his reputation of having been linked to the death squads that killed thousands of people in the first years of the war. he has denied the accusations, including one that he masterminded the march 1981 slaying of archbishop oscar arnulfo romero, the roman catholic prelate
d'aubuisson, a fiery orator, held on to his seat in the assembly, and seems sure to play a role in party councils
if we get the majority in the assembly, the next thing you'll hear from the `fish' will be from behind bars, because that's where we're going to put the corrupt sons of their mothers,'' d'aubuisson told a crowd last week. the fish is the christian democratic party symbol
cristiani _ a graduate of georgetown university in washington, d.c. _ also won a seat in the new assembly. he promised he would seek a consensus in the legislature on how to deal with the leftist rebels
he said the rebels would be approached with a proposal for ending the war and, if they refused, then the legislature would back the government in declaring an offensive to wipe them out
cristiani's idea is that if only a military solution is left, then the war should be pushed to the hilt, instead of conducting it with a series of small confrontations like now
this low intensity conflict idea should be erased,'' he said
douglas grant mine, ap correspondent in san salvador, formerly worked as news editor in buenos aires
a fire in a hay-filled barn killed 70 breeding horses in an adjoining stable, authorities said
owner ward holasek said he suffered burns as he ran through the stable to get some of the horses out. he, his wife, veterinarian georgene holasek, and workers were able to save 12 horses, said fire chief randy sorenson
the stable included horses brought in for breeding from as far away as california and new york, georgene holasek said. most of the horses killed were arabian and were worth about $10,000 apiece. some, including a prized breeding stallion belonging to the couple, had even higher values, the owners said
the loss from tuesday's blaze, which took 90 minutes to control, was estimated at $1.2 million, sorensen said
the cause of the fire was under investigation
the head of the environmental protection agency plans to look at the ethics of using scientific data from nazi concentration camp experiments but is banning use of such information in a report on a toxic gas, an agency official says
epa administrator lee m. thomas learned in a letter from about 20 epa employees friday that data from experiments on concentration camp prisoners were included in an outside consultant's draft report on phosgene gas, thomas' chief of staff craig deremer said tuesday
as soon as we got the letter ... the administrator said, `there's no reason to proceed with that information in the report. we don't need this data. let's just not use this and then let's look at the broader issue,''' deremer said
thomas plans a broad review ``to look at the ethical issues on using this kind of data,'' deremer said. ``it's sort of a new issue that we haven't dealt with before
there may be some arguments on the other side,'' he added. ``if there is data available, no matter if it was raised in questionable means, some people might argue that if it's for the good of humanity we should use it.''
the consultant's study was designed to determine whether epa's computer-generated predictions on how phosgene gas would affect humans were in line with what would actually happen due to exposure to the toxic chemical
phosgene gas in high concentrations was used as a weapon in world war i and 52 prisoners were exposed to it in 1943 and 1944 by the nazis to test a possible antidote, the new york times reported in today's editions
four of the prisoners exposed at fort ney near strasbourg, france, died and many others who already were weak and undernourished developed pulmonary edema, which causes extreme irritation in the lungs, the newspaper said
eight-year-old deandra anrig says she felt like winnie the pooh when an airplane snagged her kite line and lofted her on a 100-foot ride
i read about how winnie the pooh flies in the air on kites, but i never wanted to try it,'' said deandra, who let go just as the kite carried her toward a tree. ``i wasn't thinking anything but how scared i was.''
she said it was just a big jerk that lifted her (10 feet) into the air,'' said deandra's mother, debby. ``it carried her right over my husband's head. all he saw was a shadow going over his head. i'm just thankful she let go.''
deandra escaped from her ride with bruises. sympathetic neighbors delivered cupcakes tuesday to her home in dublin, 30 miles southeast of san francisco, where she rested on an air mattress surrounded by ice packs and two of her stuffed animals
deandra and her parents were picnicking sunday with friends at a park 2 miles from the palo alto airport when the accident occurred
deandra was taking her turn flying the 12-foot, glider-type kite when a twin-engine plane descending toward the airport caught the kite's 200-pound nylon test line
mountain view fire marshal frank moe said the 70-pound child was carried about 100 feet before letting go
there was no way the people in the plane could have known what was happening,'' said ken markowitz, a lawyer for the reno flying service, owner of the care flight medical transport plane that tangled with the kite
pilot jack uranga of reno, nev., was flying a patient to stanford university hospital when the propeller snagged the line, markowitz said
despite damage to one propeller blade, uranga managed to land safely, but the plane is grounded until repairs are made, markowitz said. uranga said tuesday that company regulations prevented him from discussing the accident
in san jose, federal aviation administration official edge ritter said the plane sustained a 2-inch gouge in one of its two propellers. he was unable to estimate the cost of repair or the height of the plane when it caught the line
mountain view authorities said they would post signs at shoreline park advising that kite flying has been banned there. the public utilities commission prohibits kite flying within 5 miles of an airport
ritter said there frequently are kites in the park area, but this was the first such accident
there had been planes flying over all that afternoon,'' said deandra's father, brad. ``and there were kites everywhere _ 15 to 20 of them, some up as high as 200 feet.''
he and deandra found their kite after the incident _ about half a mile away _ with about 60 feet of line still attached
humorist donald barthelme was named the winner of the $25,000 rea award, given annually to an outstanding writer of short stories
no richer _ or funnier _ discourse exists in contemporary american fiction,'' the jury said in giving the 1988 award tuesday to barthelme, a 57-year-old english professor at the university of houston
the jurors, including one of the two previous rea award winners, cynthia ozick, praised barthelme for blending ``mockery and exaltation'' in his stories. robert coover won the award last year
barthelme's short story collections include ``forty stories,'' ``overnight to many distant cities,'' ``great days,'' ``city life'' and ``unspeakable practices, unnatural acts.''
the role the united states is playing in honduras and panama has heightened latin american fears of a major military confrontation and offended regional pride, officials said
president miguel de la madrid's harsh condemnation of u.s. ``interventionism'' echoed sentiments voiced throughout the region
the sharpest remarks have been reserved for the u.s. deployment of troops in honduras after an alleged incursion of nicaraguan troops pursuing u.s.-backed contra rebels
latin american leaders also have expressed concern about the situation in panama, where the military chief, gen. manuel antonio noriega, is trying to stifle a huge opposition campaign backed by u.s. economic pressure. but other presidents have criticized noriega
some leaders have suggested that the united states, which is often viewed as insensitive to latin america, is thwarting regional attempts to bring peace to central america
it's not with the movement of armies, nor with the financing of subversion ... that the problems of this area, vital to the interests of the mexican people, will be resolved,'' de la madrid said monday in a speech
president vinicio cerezo of guatemala said on tuesday that an isolated border battle could turn into a regional conflict if u.s. troops intervened in the fighting. he was interviewed on the privately-owned mexico city television station televisa
argentina and colombia have expressed what they describe as grave ``concern'' about the deployment of 3,200 u.s. troops to honduras last week
president alan garcia of peru went a step further, vowing to visit nicaragua to demonstrate ``solidarity'' with its leftist government
u.s. officials described the deployment of soldiers as a combined training exercise and show of force against nicaragua
the united states also has about 10,000 military personnel stationed in panama, headquarters for the american military in latin america. its economic sanctions on panama have intensified the demands in that country for noriega to step down as the de facto ruler
de la madrid said ``the force of law'' not the ``law of force'' should be used and said only ``diplomatic and peaceful negotiations can achieve peace in the brother republics of central america.''
the contadora group _ formed in 1983 by colombia, mexico, panama and venezuela to negotiate peace in central america _ issued a statement last week calling for the united states to respect the principles of non-interventionism
several latin american leaders, however, have critized noriega, who was indicted in the united states last month on federal drug trafficking charges
cerezo said on tueday that noriega should resign and he called the government and the opposition to begin negotiating an end to their stalemate
garcia called for immediate elections in panama and brought home peru's ambassador for consultations
an amateur astronomer has discovered his fourth comet in four years after going 19 years without spotting one
i'm getting much more persistent about it, and i'm becoming much more single-minded about it,'' said david levy, a research assistant at the university of arizona's lunar and planetary laboratory, whose latest discovery came last weekend
i take advantage of almost every opportunity to search for comets.''
the find was confirmed tuesday by brian marsden of the international astronomical union, who said levy now has more new comet sightings than any other living u.s. amateur
the comet was designated comet 1988e _ signifying it is the fifth comet discovered this year
levy said he spends between one and four hours each clear night scanning the skies with one of his dozens of telescopes
he has been searching for comets for 23 years. after 19 years without a find, he co-discovered comet levy-rudenko in 1984
in january 1987, he spotted the first comet of that year
levy built a 6-by-8-foot wooden platform atop his home last october to get a better view of the horizon. three days after its completion, he spotted his third comet
he said he found his fourth comet about an hour before dawn on saturday, just above the horizon. he was using a 16-inch telescope
only six to eight new comets are discovered in an average year, and some comet hunters search a lifetime without making a discovery, marsden said. last year, a record 16 comets were discovered, he said
australian amateur astronomer william bradfield has discovered 13 comets, more than any other living comet hunter, marsden said. he said levy is now tied with canadian rolf meier for the north american honors
a growing scandal over allegations of massive embezzlement and corruption by top officials is widely seen as part of a power struggle between president roh tae-woo and his predecessor
former president chun doo-hwan's younger brother, chun kyung-hwan, is the focus of the scandal, an investigation into charges leaders of the powerful saemaul undong development group used government connections to amass fortunes. prosecutors say dozens of government officials also have been implicated
political observers say the saemaul revelations are among efforts by roh to discredit chun doo-hwan by exposing corruption under his government. chun, who stepped down feb. 25, has been fighting to retain power within the government
chun kyung-hwan, the former leader of saemaul (new community), became among the country's most powerful figures while chun doo-hwan was in power
many koreans believe there was corruption under president chun, much of it centered around his family. the korea times, in an editorial tuesday, said the saemaul affair ``should be considered typical of the ... unjust practices during the preceding government.''
former president chun, who has not been implicated directly in the scandal, was to meet today with president reagan in washington. he is on a private tour of the united states that includes meetings with many top american officials
the investigation and the constant stream of revelations would not be possible without high-level government backing, according to officials and observers, who declined to be identified further
you can be sure this is coming direct from the blue house (presidential mansion),'' said one official
the prosecutors general office says an initial investigation of the saemaul group indicates the younger chun and other top officials embezzled government and private subsidies, forced corporations to make illegal donations and peddled government influence and contacts. news reports indicate up to $50 million could be involved
prosecutor kang won-il, who is heading the investigation, says officials of the home, agriculture and fisheries, education, and sports ministries are also being investigated for aiding saemaul officials or covering up fraud to protect president chun and his family
saemaul has evolved into a huge organization since its creation in 1971 to promote urban and rural development, with activities ranging from construction of model communities and organizing city dwellers to keep neighborhoods clean
opposition supporters and other critics contend saemaul also has worked closely with the country's authoritarian governments in the past, organizing government support and handing out patronage
the younger chun, who resigned in 1987 after being linked to gangsters locked in a bloody power struggle, fled briefly to japan last friday when details of the investigation were made public
the former saemaul chief, who was appointed by his brother, said after returning that there had been irregularities, but gave no details
dozens of saemaul officials and their wives are being questioned and have been barred from leaving the country
roh, a former general who helped put chun into power with army backing in 1980, has been trying to distance himself from his highly unpopular predecessor and to take complete control of the government
the two men had been close since their days in the armed forces and chun picked roh to be his successor. but roh started to distance himself from chun when massive anti-government protests occurred last summer
roh backed opposition demands for elections held in december that he won with 36.6 percent of the vote after rival opposition candidates split the anti-government vote
the new president has resisted chun's attempts to retain power, ousting many of the former president's supporters from the governing democratic justice party. roh also curtailed plans for chun to act as a senior adviser to the government, reducing the post to a largely ceremonial role
roh has promised to end decades of authoritarian rule and introduce sweeping democratic reforms and is anxious to build popular support. on the campaign trail, he vowed that any official corruption under the chun government would not go unpunished
daily revelations about the saemaul probe have received maximum attention in the media. the state-run television networks devote much of their nightly news programs to the affair
but some democratic justice party leaders and other officials are concerned the effort to discredit chun could backfire. the opposition party for peace and democracy has charged that roh aided saemaul corruption while he was home minister in 1982 and demanded he be investigated
the governing party also is worried that corruption revelations could hurt its chances in national assembly elections, which are to be held next month
barry renfrew, the ap bureau chief in seoul, has covered asia for the past five years
a lawsuit has been filed against the fbi alleging the agency illegally obtained the financial records of a human rights group with the help of a dallas bank
the u.s. district court lawsuit, filed tuesday by the dallas chapter of the committee in solidarity with the people of el salvador, names the fbi and merchants state bank as defendants
the suit contends that the fbi obtained the chapter's bank records beginning in june 1983 in violation of the 1978 financial privacy act. it also contends that the bank failed to notify cispes as required by law
bank officials and an fbi spokesman declined comment on the suit
under the law, federal law enforcement agencies may obtain an individual's or a group's bank records by subpoena, by written request from a designated fbi supervisor or through a request from the agency's director indicating the records are being sought in the course of an investigation of foreign intelligence activities
the law usually requires that a subject be notified and given time to seek a court review of the request unless the bank records are sought as part of an ongoing intelligence investigation
the human rights group's national organization came under fbi scrutiny beginning in 1981, and the dallas group in 1983, when federal agents began trying to determine whether cispes members had contacts with hostile foreign governments or their agents or were involved in criminal or terroristic activities
the investigation was terminated in 1985 after agents found no evidence linking cispes with terrorist groups in el salvador, fbi officials have said
joe k. crews, an attorney representing cispes, said records obtained from the fbi through the freedom of information act do not indicate that the records request was made through the agency's director as part of an ongoing counterintelligence investigation
officials of cispes say the fbi probe targted the group and dozens of others solely because of their opposition to reagan administration policies on central america
the suit seeks $100 in damages for each of an unspecified number of privacy rights violations. it also seeks unspecified punitive damages, attorney fees and an injunction requiring the fbi to comply with federal privacy laws in future records requests
two young men from london zoo will set off from britain on thursday in search of the world's largest earwig on st. helena, the remote south atlantic island where napoleon bonaparte died
if we find any giant earwigs we will bring them back alive in hopes of getting them to breed in captivity at the zoo,'' said dave clarke, the expedition leader
the nocturnal insect is 3 inches long, reddish brown in color, lives in a burrow and although a fearsome looking creature, with two big pincers at the back, is harmless to man. unlike most insects, it cannot fly
nobody knows if there are any left,'' clarke said in an interview tuesday
clarke said the last giant earwigs were seen by belgian collecting expeditions in 1965 and 1967
st. helena, with a population of 6,000, is 1,200 miles east of angola and 4,400 miles south of england
the island, the only known habitat for the insect, has been occupied by the british since 1659 and napoleon was exiled there after his defeat at waterloo in 1815. he died on the island in 1821
clarke, 25, works in the insect house at the zoo where he is on friendly terms with deadly black widow spiders, tarantulas, giant water bugs, ants and locusts
we've never had a giant earwig at the zoo and few people have seen one. even the saints, as the people of st. helena are known, haven't seen any for a long time,'' clarke said
going with him is richard veal, 24, who works in the zoo's small mammals house. an anonymous benefactor has donated the $6,400 cost of the trip
clarke said the zoo was alerted to the earwig's apparent disappearance by the international union for the conservation of nature and natural resources. the geneva-based group has a chapter in cambridge, england, which monitors rare species
the earwig has been known to be rare for a long time but the union learned only recently that in the past 15 to 20 years it has become rare to the point of a serious threat of extinction,'' said paul pearce-kelly, head keeper of the insect house
there are 1,000 species of earwig in the world, pearce-kelly said
the giant earwig's latin name is labidura herculeana, which could be translated as hercules hardlips,'' he said
pearce-kelly said the search also will be difficult because ``the island habitat has undergone much destruction from goats, rats and 10-inch-long giant centipedes, which came in on ships.''
in their 3{-week search, clarke and veal will scout two other scarce insects only found on st. helena: a giant ground beetle and the st. helena dragonfly
i'm hoping we will be in time to find the giant earwig and save it,'' said clarke
when asked why anyone should bother, he replied: ``everyone asks that.''
the earwig was part of st. helena's life long before we were around and it is unqiue. as man created the conditions which threatened to exterminate it, we should try to save it,'' he said
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis strengthened his lead over jesse jackson in support among michigan democrats and independents, according to survey done by a local television station
missouri rep. richard gephardt, who has said he must win michigan's democratic caucuses saturday which will allocate 138 of the state's 150 delegates to the party's national convention to remain in the race for the party's presidential nomination, showed marked improvement in the wjbk-tv survey over his standing in earlier polls
the survey, released tuesday, of 400 michigan voters identifying themselves as democrats or independents gave dukakis a 35 percent margin of support, wjbk said
jackson, rated virtually even with dukakis earlier this month in polls by the detroit free press and detroit news, had 29 percent. gephardt, hovering at about 10 percent in both newspaper polls, improved to 17 percent in the wjbk survey
sens. albert gore jr. and paul simon of illinois trailed with 6 percent and 5 percent respectively, and another 9 percent of those polled were undecided, the detroit station said. percentages exceeded 100 percent because of rounding
the survey was conducted for wjbk by barry kaplovitz associates of boston and had a margin of error of 5 percentage points
kansas democrats have changed their minds and decided to allow local delegates pledged to the presidential runners-up in saturday's caucuses to vote at district conventions after all
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis won the kansas contest with 278 of the 764 local delegates elected and jesse jackson finished second with 235
however, there was confusion over the local delegates pledged to tennessee sen. albert gore jr. and missouri rep. richard gephardt and those who were uncommitted
under state rules, local delegates who supported a candidate who didn't reach a 15 percent threshold would be non-entities at the district conventions scheduled for april 23
the state decided monday that those local delegates would be unable to vote at the district conventions and would be ignored in computing national delegates from the districts
but after conferring with the democratic national committee's compliance commission, which interprets the national rules for electing delegates to the national convention, the state party decided tuesday that all local delegates will be allowed to vote
ohio republican party chairman robert bennett says that the state party welcomes supporters of pat robertson, notwithstanding his current or possible future bid for the party's presidential nomination
bennett tuesday discounted notions that the former evangelist may try to take over the party from the ashes of robertson's current campaign, either to push friendly candidates for state offices in 1990 or to launch a possible second run for the presidency in 1992
in some states, including ohio, robertson supporters have entered races for local party offices, triggering speculation that they may have an eventual party takeover in mind. bennett said he doubts it
he said the ohio activity is limited to cincinnati, where some local party candidates who support robertson have been pushing for right-to-life legislation in various public forums for years
there is no concerted effort to take over the party organization in ohio,'' bennett said. he said many robertson backers are disenchanted former democrats and others, new to the political process, who seek republican values that he summed up this way: ``married, with 4.2 kids, and go to church on sunday.''
pat robertson's lone presidential campaign office in oregon will close by april 1, according to the head of the republican contender's organization in the state
david crowe said tuesday the national campaign headquarters in virginia instructed him to close the oregon operation, located in an office complex in bend, ``as soon as possible.''
telephone service will be cut off on april 1, crowe said
in a phone interview, crowe said the national campaign staff decided not to spend much money in states with primary elections, where robertson has done poorly
the former television evangelist has picked up most of his delegates in states with caucus processes
former gov. lamar alexander says he voted for vice president george bush on super tuesday but will not endorse him because he wants to avoid mixing politics with his post as president-elect of the university of tennessee
alexander, in an interview, said tuesday that he had no reaction to published reports that he is high on bush's list of potential republican vice presidential candidates if bush, as expected, wins the presidential nomination
alexander, to succeed ed boling as ut president on july 1, said, ``i plan to show up for work july 1 at ut and be there.'' the republican national convention begins in new orleans on aug. 15
i have resolved not to plan my life around the vice presiedential selection,'' alexander said. ``i could get hit by a car or struck by lightning or be selected as a vice presidential candidate and one is as likely as the other.''
he said his feelings on whether to accept the vice presidential nomination have not changed since his selection as ut's next president
i said (then) i thought it was a remote possibility, that i didn't expect to be asked but that i didn't plan to say, `no,''' alexander said
as the government was reporting a slight increase in auto fuel efficiency last year, two researchers said federal fuel-economy standards will cause thousands of traffic deaths in the next decade by discouraging the use of safer, larger cars
fuel economy regulation inevitably leads to smaller, lighter cars that are inherently less safe than the cars that would be produced without a binding fuel-economy constraint,'' said a study released tuesday by robert w. crandall of the brookings institution in washington and john d. graham of the harvard school of public health in boston
they estimated the standards applied to 1989 cars during 10 years of road use would cause 2,200 to 3,900 traffic deaths
also tuesday, the transportation department told congress that passenger cars sold in the united states got 28.2 miles per gallon last year overall, up 0.2 miles per gallon from the previous year
despite the good news on auto fuel economy, transportation secretary jim burnley used the report to reiterate his support for elimination of the fuel-economy requirement, saying it placed u.s. manufacturers at a disadvantage against their foreign competition
the house has voted to continue and expand a program to encourage private companies to develop drugs for combating rare diseases
the bill was passed on a 401-1 vote tuesday and sent to the senate. it extends the so-called ``orphan drug'' program through fiscal 1990. it would also expand the program, which is overseen by the food and drug administration, to include special devices and foods needed to help people with unusual maladies
under the program, companies are given tax credits and seven-year exclusive marketing rights if they develop products for rare diseases. without incentives, the companies would not pursue development of those products because the small number of beneficiaries would not make it profitable, according to supporters of the legislation
the revised statute, while expanding the program, would triple its cost in the next few years. the current annual authorization of $4 million would grow to $14 million in fiscal 1990
the reagan administration has said it has no objection to the legislation
a house committee says it will cost $3.5 million in transitional expenses for president reagan's successor to move into the white house and cost reagan $1 million to move to retirement in california next january
the government and operations committee tuesday approved a bill authorizing the funds although the democratic-controlled panel rejected a republican move to increase the expense allowance to offset the effects of inflation for the outgoing president to $1.5 million from $1 million, the level in effect since 1976
the proposed boost was opposed by rep. jack brooks, d-texas, the panel's chairman, who said the budget squeeze requires congress to ``make some hard choices'' on spending cuts
the panel approved raising the president-elect's allowance for transitional expenses to $3.5 million from $2 million, the level in effect for the past 12 years. it also rejected, 24-9, a move by rep. robert s. walker, r-pa., to forbid the president-elect from accepting private donations to supplement federal transitional funds
the $1 million for reagan's initial retirement expenses, if approved by the house and senate, would cover his moving expenses from the white house to california and the costs of establishing an office for six months, until funds for former presidents become available under a separate law. nazis</head>
thirty-four years after his death, a portugese diplomat who helped 30,000 refugees flee the nazi invasion of france has been restored to full rank in his country's consular corps
aristides de sousa mendes, who died in poverty and disgrace, was reinstated by a unanimous vote last week of portugal's national assembly, his son sebastian mendes, 64, said tuesday
de sousa mendes was portuguese consul to bordeaux, france, in 1940 when during a three-day period, he, his wife and consul staff defied their government's orders and hand-wrote exit visas for 30,000 refugees, including an estimated 10,000 jews
he decided that it was for him to take action and he took the action ... he saw to be the right action,'' mendes said tuesday
my father was very moral and _ not religious _ but very christian. he believed in helping the unfortunate. he wanted to assist the ones who are less fortunate than he,'' he said in a telephone interview from his home in santa clarita 40 miles northwest of los angeles
the diplomat was recalled to lisbon, stripped of his position and retired without pay. barred from practicing law, forced to sell his property for taxes and reduced to poverty, he died in 1954. his wife, angelina, died in 1948
sebastian mendes, one of 14 children, and a brother claimed u.s. citizenship because they were born when their father was serving in the united states. he enlisted in the u.s. army in 1943
discharged in 1945, mendes went to the san francisco bay area and began trying to restore his father's name, writing to newspapers, approaching human rights groups and even writing a small book about his father
portugal might have paid tribute to de sousa mendes sooner, but the dictatorship that repudiated him lasted until 1974
historians subsequently documented de sousa mendes' work and in 1976 portugal's foreign ministry recommended his reinstatement. he was awarded his country's highest civilian medal last year, but not reinstated until last week
until his death at age 69, de sousa mendes's achievement was acknowledged only by his closest relatives, mendes said
nevertheless, mendes said he is glad that the final element of his father's disgrace has been removed. ``in my old age ... it happened and i'm thankful to god,'' he said. ``i thank god for that.''
the tennessee valley authority is moving closer to reviving its long-idled nuclear program after winning unanimous approval from the nuclear regulatory commission
tva chairman marvin runyon said the federal utility would not compromise 2{-years of rebuilding by rushing the restart of sequoyah nuclear plant
it'll start when it's ready. ... it'll be a safe start,'' runyon said tuesday night after the nrc gave tva permission to restart the unit 2 reactor at the chattanooga plant
the commision's 5-0 vote allows unit 2 to become the first of five licensed tva reactors to resume production of power since they were shut down in 1985 because of safety and management concerns
the only condition for the restart was a last-minute problem involving temperature detectors in the plant's pressurizer system
it's a relatively minor thing, but we want everything to be ready,'' said tva nuclear power manager steven a. white, who joined runyon at a chattanooga news conference after both returned from the nrc meeting in washington
with the vote, the nrc also indicated it did not feel a pending justice department investigation of white had anything to do with whether sequoyah is safe to operate
white has been accused of lying to the nrc in 1986 when he certified in writing that another tva nuclear plant, watts bar near spring city, met federal quality assurance standards. white has denied wrongdoing
nrc chairman lando zech said commissioners had found ``no known regulatory reason'' to further delay restarting unit 2
during the next few days, sequoyah workers will complete final testing and documentation, white said. then, the plant will slowly begin generating nuclear power
it will probably be three weeks before unit 2 is at 100 percent power, but it can produce usable electricity for the tva system at 15 percent, white said
this is very similar to the startup of a new plant, and i expect that we will experience a few problems,'' he said. ``however, our personnel are trained and qualified to resolve any problems that are encountered.''
tva, still facing about $15 billion in long-term debts for the nuclear program, hopes to have sequoyah unit 1 back on line in august, with unit 2 at browns ferry following in december
all three browns ferry reactors were shut down in march 1985. sequoyah, which began operation in 1981, shut down five months after the other reactors. white took over the nuclear power program in a management shakeup early in 1986. coverage</head>
the nation's largest insurers conspired to fabricate a liability crisis, which crippled businesses and forced nationwide cutbacks in police, child care and other services, according to suits by seven states
the lawsuits, filed tuesday in u.s. district court here, accuse dozens of insurance companies of collaborating in a global boycott of certain types of general liability insurance through secret agreements and internal pressure
the suits, filed by california, new york, west virginia, wisconsin, minnesota, massachusetts and alabama, named 32 insurance companies, underwriters and associations, including lloyd's of london
arizona planned to sue in the same court today, and texas filed a separate suit in its state court because the state ``has one of the toughest, best antitrust laws in the nation,'' said texas attorney general jim mattox
these defendants have sucked the blood of our nation's economic well-being,'' mattox said at a news conference in austin
new york state attorney general robert abrams said the case was one of the largest ever tackled by a group of states in a federal court, adding that the states had to take action because the federal government did nothing
one of the companies, aetna life and casualty co., condemned the suit as ``another political move by political officeholders who have consistently opposed any and all efforts to address the real problems of the nation's liability system.''
a spokesman for the insurance services office, a 1,400-member industry trade group also named in the suit, called the allegations unfounded
the lawsuits claim the companies targeted for elimination coverage for pollution accidents and general liability for damage discovered after the life of a policy, known as ``occurrence'' coverage
the companies instead favored more limited policies, covering only losses that were suffered and claimed within the policy term, excluding damage that was discovered later, the suits said
the lawsuits said four major insurance companies _ hartford fire insurance co., allstate insurance co., cigna corp. and aetna _ started a campaign in 1984 to curtail coverage that was generally available in the industry
according to the suits, the companies got major u.s. and british reinsurers, including underwriters at lloyd's of london, to threaten a boycott of any u.s. insurance company that provided the broader coverage
at the same time, the suits said, major insurers and reinsurers pressured the insurance services office to stop distributing standard forms, so that it would be impractical for individual companies to continue offering that coverage
as a result, the suits said, property damage insurance for local governments, nonprofit agencies such as child care centers, and various businesses suddenly became unavailable or prohibitively expensive
this illegal boycott was a major contributor to the insurance crisis that forced so many cities and businesses up against the wall,'' california attorney general john van de kamp said
it was the public and the consumer who paid the price for this collusive exercise in corporate greed.''
in california and elsewhere, local governments cut back or eliminated services, such as parks and police, because of insurance expenses, van de kamp said. many local officials blamed rising damage awards in injury suits and joined the insurance industry in efforts to restrict the right to sue
van de kamp said the attorneys general decided to file together here because he has taken the lead on the issue and california law is favorable to the case and might be cited by the federal court
among other things, the plaintiffs seek to restructure the insurance services office by giving non-insurers a majority on its board and making public its data on insurance coverage losses
dave ostwald, the spokesman for the insurance services office in new york city, said rates increased mainly because of ``a demonstrable increase in claims losses and a drop in interest rates, slowing down (insurers') investment income.''
he said pollution coverage was changed in response to expansive court decisions. pollution insurance and ``occurrence'' coverage remained available, with some restrictions, he added
the hartford insurance group called the lawsuit ``totally without substance'' and said it is confident that all charges eventually will be dismissed. it said the rates in question are established from judgments that are legal and involve no other insurer or insurance organization
northwest airlines flight attendants are likely to ratify a tentative contract that forestalled a walkout by 6,500 workers, a union official said
we're optimistic the agreement will be ratified or we wouldn't be submitting it to the membership,'' marvin griswold, secretary-treasurer of the teamsters' los angeles-based airline division local 2707, said tuesday after the carrier and the union announced the tentative pact
flight attendants had continued working through a feb. 26 strike deadline, but set a march 29 deadline that threatened a walkout during the airline's busy easter season
the tentative pact reached tuesday first must be approved by the rank and file flight attendants negotiating committee, which meets today or thursday. then, it must then be approved by the workers, which could take about 30 days
major details of the proposed contract were not released
both sides acknowledged that the march 29 strike deadline provided the impetus to reach an agreement
we wanted to see an agreement reached before the 29th ... the 29th is a sincere and serious deadline,'' griswold told a news conference
it gave us a target,'' said terry erskine, northwest's vice president of law and labor relations. ``it gave us a focus
if it (a strike) had occurred, we would have been ready and would have operated the airline,'' erskine said
the talks for the last two days were conducted with the help of joshua javits, a member of the national mediation board, and federal mediator robert brown, northwest said
javits said the mediators provided a framework for the two sides to reach a settlement, but ``the parties really did it themselves.''
erskine said that, pending ratification, northwest would suspend the contract it was set to impose on april 1. the teamsters agreed not to engage in any job action during the ratification process
the key issue in the dispute was northwest's two-tier wage structure, of which the airline had proposed extending the lower-paid scale to eight years from the current five years
b-scale flight attendants argued that the airline was trying to break a promise that they would earn higher, a-scale wages after five years
the issue had intensified since northwest acquired republic airlines in 1986. about a third of the 2,600 former republic attendants are on the lower scale, and the others said northwest's previous wage offer was inadequate
jeff musto, a teamsters spokesman in eagan, said only one detail of the contract has been disclosed: that all flight attendants hired by northwest will be required to join the union
erskine said northwest found no evidence of ``guerilla warfare'' tactics the union had threatened as a way to keep the company off balance
he also said northwest did not see its traffic diminish during the dispute, although he acknowledged that some people may have booked flights on other airlines
the oom-pah-pah of a tuba and the jangle of a tambourine were the first clues that things were not quite normal in the queens midtown tunnel early today
then a police van came out on the manhattan side with flashing lights. it braked in front of the more than 100 spectators gathered along the road and its megaphone crackled to life: ``do yourself a favor and don't touch the cages.''
what brought out the crowd, which ranged from grandmothers to infants?
word of trunk,'' one spectator said
it was ringling bros. and barnum &amp; bailey circus' annual three-mile parade of animals as the big top moved into madison square garden for its six-week run
the caged lions and tigers came first, 14 of them in two strands of cages linked together and pulled by trucks. the animals paced back and forth
here pussycat,'' someone in the crowd yelled
living things in manhattan that are not people, and are not cockroaches!'' yelled amy slaton, a 30-year-old art critic. ``this is the happiest night of my life.''
the crowd roared as the elephants appeared at the tunnel exit. ninteen were linked with long strands of chains, walking mainly two abreast. the cry went up, ``wooo-oooo! elephants! elephants! aaaall right!''
paula van meter was wearing an elephant nose and ears in honor of her sixth trip to the parade
sometimes dignitaries get to ride on the elephants,'' the 41-year-old brooklyn resident said. ``that would be worth running for office.''
i wish we had a little baby elephant,'' said a child
