a former wedtech corp. official who says he bribed numerous public officials, including rep. mario biaggi, also admits that he stole $1.5 million from the defense contractor
mario moreno, ex-vice chairman of the defunct bronx company, detailed numerous bribes and payoffs by wedtech
during his sixth day of testimony tuesday at the racketeering trial of biaggi and six others, moreno said the payoffs went to bankers, lawyers and union leaders
but under cross examination, he also admitted transferring $250,000 in kickbacks to a swiss bank account, even after he had agreed to cooperate with prosecutors
biaggi; his eldest son; his former law partner and four others are charged with turning wedtech into a racketeering enterprise that paid millions of dollars in bribes to land and maintain government contracts
moreno, the first prosecution witness, has linked the defendants to numerous payoff and fraud schemes but he also admitted personally stealing $1.5 million in wedtech funds
moreno also said he made false statements to the internal revenue service, state tax authorities, the securities and exchange commission, the small business administration, the defense department ``and a few other agencies.''
moreno also claimed wedtech paid $80,000 to rep. robert garcia, d-n.y., for ``political favors.'' garcia, who has not been charged with any wrongdoing, denied moreno's allegation through a spokesman
the payments for ``political favors and political introductions'' were made to garcia ``because he and his wife requested it,'' said moreno
moreno also said wedtech paid $130,000 to two bronx bankers in early 1984 for helping the company obtain a $500,000 cash loan _ at $150,000 interest over three months _ from a bronx businessman; $15,000 to a manhattan banker who helped them launder the $500,000 cash; $10,000 to $15,000 over six years to a consolidated edison manager ``to have con edison on our side whenever we needed it'' and a $100,000 payoff to two teamsters officials in 1985 to settle a dispute with another union
the luck o' the irish was with two elderly women who were trapped in their overturned car. they were rescued by six firefighters from dublin, ireland
azzie harrison, 72, and passenger edna rozar, 73, of dublin, ga., became trapped tuesday after their car plunged over the side of a bridge into a creek near the intersection of u.s. 80 west and shamrock drive
six members of the dublin, ireland, fire brigade, who are visiting to bring greetings from their lord mayor for the millennium of their irish hometown, were sitting in a fire station when the rescue call came
they joined in cutting through the car's hood and breaking its windows to free the women, who were listed in fair condition early today at a hospital
that's the thing about firefighters,'' said seamus o'connor, one of the six firemen. ``we can go anywhere and fit right in.''
a vietnamese refugee has died after she lost a fight against leukemia that prompted the vietnamese government to release her relatives in hope of finding a compatible bone marrow donor
myhanh luong, 21, died of an infection stemming from her leukemia, north shore university hospital spokesman daniel rosette said tuesday
luong came to the united states in 1979 after a seven-day journey from vietnam to the philippines in a small boat with 52 other refugees. in 1986, while attending baruch college, she was diagnosed with the blood cancer
in january, under pressure from the u.s. state department, the vietnamese government granted exit visas to luong's parents and two sisters in ho chi minh city ``on humanitarian grounds.''
doctors had hoped that one of them would have bone marrow that could be transplanted to save luong. tests showed, however, that their bone marrow was not compatible with hers
luong's leukemia had been in remission since november, a step which is crucial if any other life saving options were to be attempted, rosette said
in an effort to boost her spirits, doctors permitted her to go home to long island for five days earlier this month
a week after she returned to the hospital she contracted an infection and never recovered, rosette said
she really enjoyed her stay at home,'' said her sister, mymy luong. ``we are all very upset.'' mymy said family members were at her bedside when she died
funeral services for luong were held monday in new york city's chinatown
the average japanese household in a recent survey had $82,000 in savings at the end of last year, up 14.9 percent from a year earlier, a government report published today said
it was the biggest annual increase in savings since 1979, when average savings rose 15.5 percent from 1978, said namiko mizutani, a statistician at the management and coordination agency, which conducted the survey
mizutani said the increase resulted largely from an increase in stock prices last year
despite last october's worldwide stock market crash, the average prices of 1,058 major stocks listed on the tokyo stock exchange's first section rose about 15 percent in value from 1986, local news reports said
the agency surveyed 6,150 families on dec. 31, but left out those engaged in agricuture and fisheries, and single people
coast guard searchers today found debris they suspected was from an air force f-16 jet that crashed into the gulf of mexico during a training mission, but there was no sign of the pilot, officials said
the unidentified pilot was flying solo 40 miles west of fort myers when the jet went down tuesday night, said air force capt. diane lawhon, a spokeswoman for macdill air force base
officials don't know what caused the crash or if the pilot was able to eject from the plane
searchers flew over a 100-square-mile area early today and found small pieces of debris they believe was part of the plane, said petty officer tom gillespie
the pieces are small. the biggest is 1-foot-by-1-foot. they are collecting the debris and will give it to the air force, (which) will make the decision about whether or not it is from the plane,'' gillespie said from the coast guard's miami office
he said it is ``not unusual'' to not find a pilot's remains after crashes of impacts so strong that the plane is torn apart
the jet was accompanied by another f-16 from macdill. when that pilot lost radio contact with the downed flier, he circled around to look for him but found nothing, ms. lawhon said
a coast guard jet and helicopter searched about 40 miles off sarasota, said sgt. michelle spicer, another macdill spokeswoman. macdill sent a c-130 four-engine cargo plane to aid in the search
the f-16 fighting falcon has a f100 pratt and whitney engine and is manufactured by general dynamics. macdill has about 100 f-16s in its fleet, delivered in 1978
the british ferry, herald of free enterprise, that capsized off the belgian coast last year killing 193 people aboard, arrived at a southern taiwan scrap yard, officials said today
the ferry was in a disastrous state. there's only mud and garbage left inside,'' said wang chin-yeh, an official of chi shun hua steel co., a ship salvage company in the kaohsiung, 220 miles south of taipei
the ferry arrived in the scrap yard tuesday night after being towed on a 50-day, 7,582 nautical mile journey from a dutch port
the herald of free enterprise capsized off the belgian port of zeebrugge on march 6, 1987, in the worst peacetime disaster involving a british ship since the titanic sank in 1912. separates moved.</note>
reyner banham, an influential writer on architecture and the arts, died saturday of cancer at age 66
banham began working at the bristol aeroplane co. after world war ii. he studied art history at london university's courtauld institute while writing about contemporary architecture for the architectural review
banham wrote three widley studied books ``theory and design in the first machine age'' in 1960, ``the new brutalism'' in 1966 and ``architecture of the well-tempered environment'' in 1969
gerhard claas, general secretary of the baptist world alliance, died monday from injuries suffered in a traffic accident near lodi, calif
claas, 59, was the chief administrative officer of the alliance, an international baptist organization with a membership of more than 35 million worldwide. the organization conducts teaching, development and disaster relief efforts in third world nations
claas was a citizen of west germany, where he had served in a number of pastoral and administrative posts
the philippines and the united states today said that on april 5 they will begin a periodic review of the executive agreement under which the united states operates six military bases here
the review of the 1947 military bases agreement is expected to center on u.s. compensation for the right to operate clark air base, subic bay naval base and four smaller installations. the united states currently pays the philippines $180 million in economic and military aid annually
some philippine legislators have suggested the figure be increased to more than $2 billion a year. foreign secretary raul manglapus, chief philippine negotiator in the talks, says $1.2 billion annually would be ``realistic.''
in addition to compensation, the bases also employ 68,000 filipinos. the united states estimates the installations add nearly $1 billion a year to the local economy
a deal to bestow prestigious harvard positions on a texas couple in exchange for a $500,000 donation has drawn fire from a senior administrator of the university's john f. kennedy school of government
executive dean richard cavanagh praised some aspects of the school's ``entrepreneurial style of raising money'' but complained about the tentative deal in a confidential report based on a two-month study of funding efforts
it is clear that this was an unusual, unhappy and unfortunate incident _ the product of misunderstanding, inexperience, sloppy handling and hasty processing,'' said cavanagh
cavanagh's comments were carried in the latest edition of the weekly harvard gazette, published by the university. harvard officials confirmed the accuracy of his statements but declined to release his report
the officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said no decision has been made on whether to conclude the agreement. one official suggested that the controversy surrounding the deal was the reason for putting it on hold
cavanagh was appointed in december and asked to examine the school's fund-raising methods. other harvard institutions also conducted fund-raising surveys on orders from harvard president derek bok
bok's action followed publication by the harvard crimson student newspaper in november of parts of the draft agreement between the school and charles cameron dickinson iii and his wife, joanne
the donors will be appointed by the dean to appropriate positions in the school of government that will accord them status as officers of the university with the privileges associated therewith,'' said the agreement, tentatively approved by kennedy school dean graham t. allison
only full-time instructors and administrators normally are appointed officers of the university, academic, administrative or advisory positions
the crimson also published a in-house memo by an allison aide stating that mrs. dickinson wanted to know the most prestigious title she could buy for $250,000 and asking how much it would cost to be on an advisory committee
kennedy school officials confirmed the existence the memo, but spokesman steven singer declined requests tuesday for telephone interviews with allison or cavanagh
allison described the deal as a mistake shortly after it came to light
dickinson, a 1980 graduate of harvard divinity school, comes from a wealthy texas oil family. no one answered the telephone at the dickinson residence in wichita falls
kennedy school officials, acting on recommendations in the cavanagh report, recently created a position of director of development and gave the develpment office full responsibility for fund raising
many americans say they have heard enough about the iran-contra affair and unrest in israel's occupied territories, a national poll found
a tampa tribune-gallup poll of 1,211 registered voters, conducted by telephone between march 10-12 and released today, found that 64 percent wanted to hear less about the iran-contra scandal. only 29 percent wanted more information about the affair
on social unrest in israel, 42 percent wanted to know more and 47 percent wanted less information, according to the poll, which had a 3 percent margin of error
the poll also found that most americans care more about issues such as drug abuse, long-term health care, quality education and aid to the homeless
of those polled, 84 percent said they wanted to hear more about battling illegal drugs. at least two-thirds of the polled voters wanted more information about efforts to fight aids, making american businesses more competitive with foreign imports and negotiating arms control agreements with the soviet union
nasa scientists are planning an international satellite system to study the atmosphere more completely, a program moved into high gear because of recent ominous changes in the ozone layer and other problems
the earth observing system will be an international network of space-based polar laboratories focusing on the planet's weather and ecology, national aeronautics and space administration project scientist dixon butler said tuesday
this will bring about a revolution in our understanding of the earth as a whole system,'' butler said via satellite to scientists at agency centers across the country, including the jet propulsion laboratory in pasadena
the schedule for the program was recently accelerated because of worrisome changes in the earth's atmosphere, such as depletion in the protective ozone layer, butler said from nasa's goddard space flight center in greenbelt, md
the six satellite labs will also monitor the so-called ``greenhouse effect,'' in which the earth's temperature is gradually rising because of increased carbon dioxide in the atmosphere, butler said
the agency is asking for $20 million in next year's budget to finalize planning and preparations for launches beginning in 1995, said charles redmond, a spokesman for nasa's science division
the project involves two satellites to be launched by japanese and european agencies, as well as four by nasa. it features an estimated $2 billion u.s. price tag, he said
we need the intellectual resources of all mankind,'' butler said. ``we must have international cooperation.''
nasa has already received about 870 letters from scientific groups proposing experiments, he said. he also said soviet participation is a possibility
instruments to be used on the satellites include a synthetic aperture radar, which uses radar waves to create images that would otherwise be hidden by clouds or vegetation
another is a ``geodynamics laser ranging system'' that could detect the slightest movement along such geological features as california's san andreas fault, butler said
three members of this city's assyrian community were arrested by police after they fired guns repeatedly in a cemetery salute to a dead comrade, authorities said
the arrests occurred tuesday during the burial of charles warda, 21, who died in an auto accident last week, said police capt. clarence zanders
john cannon, an official of the montrose cemetery and crematorium on chicago's northwest side, said the three men began firing into the air as part of a makeshift salute
there was quite a bit of shooting going on, and we really didn't think it was proper,'' cannon said
zanders said the officers who were called to the scene discovered no injuries and no damage to property, but confiscated five guns
a police spokeswoman, tina vicini, said gunfire has been reported before in connection with burials in the assyrian community
modern assyrians, a christian group from present-day iraq, are said to be the descendants of the people who ruled the ancient assyrian empire before its destruction in 612 b.c. million</head>
eds: new thruout to update with india canceling tennis visit, figures on cost of uprising to israel, cabinet to meet. changes byline
india today canceled the visit of a tennis team to protest israel's handling of arab riots, and new figures showed that anti-occupation violence in the west bank and gaza strip cost israel more than $335 million
israel's 10-member inner cabinet was to meet later in the day to hear a report from prime minister yitzhak shamir on his talks in the united states
shamir was greeted tuesday by thousands of singing and dancing supporters who welcomed his steadfast refusal to accept an american peace plan
i return satisfied, especially after people tried to frighten me before i left that the visit would be a difficult one and that i would hear harsh words,'' shamir told an airport news conference. ``i'm satisfied that didn't happen.''
also tuesday, defense minister yitzhak rabin told a parliamentary committee that israel had jailed 3,000 arabs since dec. 8, including 700 since sunday, israeli newspapers said today
in an underground leaflet circulated in the gaza strip, the palestine liberation organization announced payments will be made to people who lose family members, property or jobs because of clashes with israeli soldiers
gad yacobi, minister of economy, disclosed that the violence that began dec. 8 in the occupied lands has cost israel more than $335 million in lost production, exports and added security costs, spokeswoman naama henig said today. the tally does not include losses in tourism and agriculture
if the situation continues, it will have a significant impact on israel's economy,'' she quoted yacobi as telling israeli economic writers
yacobi said there was a drop in overall production, especially in construction, of 10 percent to 20 percent a month during the last three months. this resulted in a loss of at least $75 million, he said
he put the cost for extra security at $60 million
the biggest loss was in israeli exports to the occupied lands _ reduced by $200 million thus far. israeli exports to gaza and the west bank totaled $1.15 billion last year
indian prime minister rajiv gandhi announced today that his country's davis cup team was canceling a visit to israel to protest israeli ``repression and atrocities'' against arabs in the territories
zvi meyer, secretary of the israel tennis association, said he was ``very surprised and disappointed'' by the decision. he said israel had already sold 1,500 seats for the three-day series that was to begin april 7
it was the first protest cancellation of a sporting or entertainment event as a result of the clashes in the occupied lands, although the violence has made it difficult for promoters to arrange such events
for example, an all-star tennis fund-raiser for israel's sharei tzadek hospital was canceled after officials said big name players such as chris evert would not come because of security concerns
the underground leaflet distributed in gaza said families would receive a one-time payment of $2,900 for ``martyrs'' killed in confrontations and $600 for anyone arrested. according to u.n. figures, 107 palestinians have been killed by israeli soldiers or settlers since dec. 8 in the territories israel seized in the 1967 middle east war. one israeli soldier has been killed
merchants unable to open stores because of strikes would get $1,450 in compensation from the plo, and police who resigned their jobs would get $1,450 as a first payment
israeli officials have taken steps to prevent the plo from compensating palestinians who suffered financial losses
money changers have been particularly hard hit because one such measure is a ceiling of $1,350 on the amount of money brought into israel by individuals or institutions, an official said on condition of anonymity
demonstrations subsided this afternoon in israel's occupied lands, although arab reports said a curfew was extended on deir al balah in the gaza strip after an overnight demonstration in which youths threw stones at soldiers
all of gaza is under a nightly curfew until 3 a.m
on tuesday, a palestinian motorist was ambushed and killed near the gaza strip town of khan yunis, and israeli troops shot and killed a palestinian in the west bank village of tubas
ugly is officially out in this community east of san francisco, where residents now can be sent to jail for having eyesores in their yards
not everyone is happy about the new law, which critics say will turn neighbors into enemies
the law, which goes into effect march 30, will outlaw hanging a clothesline visible from the street, leaving broken furniture or auto parts in the yard, or even maintaining a house with most of its paint peeling
provisions banning garbage cans, building materials, dirt piles, packing boxes and broken appliances in front yards are part of a self-improvement campaign by the city, city officials said
city councilman dave burton says the city has no business subjecting citizens to white-glove inspections
this is a sledgehammer approach to a problem of aesthetics,'' burton said. ``if you brought a pile of lumber to your house, they could cite you.''
city councilman paul moffatt said the law was needed to prevent public health and safety problems arising from the large number of people piling refuse in their yards and creating dangerous conditions for children in dublin, a city of 19,000 located 30 miles southeast of san francisco
we have old decaying trees where rodents can get in and we have some rabies out here,'' said moffatt
he explained a clothesline could be a hazard ``if constructed so it restricts the vision of a person taking a car around a corner so they couldn't negotiate the corner in a safe and orderly manner.''
a first violation carries a $100 fine, which increases to $500 for a third infraction before a scofflaw can be charged with a misdemeanor and put in jail. the ordinance will be enforced only when a citizen files a complaint
liberal politicians and a legal expert today criticized president p.w. botha for halting the murder trial of six soldiers charged with the killing of an activist in south-west africa
helen suzman, parliament member for the anti-apartheid progressive federal party, noted that botha's action came a week after he refused to intervene to spare ``the sharpeville six'' _ a group of blacks sentenced to hang for complicity in a 1984 mob killing of a black town councilor
despite an international clemency campaign, botha said his policy was to avoid interfering with the judicial process. last thursday, after botha's pronouncement, a judge granted a one-month stay of execution to the six in order to consider claims that a state witness committed perjury
in light of botha's refusal to intervene in the sharpeville case, mrs. suzman said she was ``astonished'' that the president ``did not allow the ordinary course of justice to be followed'' in the case of the soldiers in south-west africa
botha ordered the attorney general of the territory, commonly known as namibia, to halt prosecution under the defense act, which exempts security forces members from court action if they act ``in good faith'' in combating suspected terrorism
the six soldiers _ four officers and two enlisted men _ were accused of arranging for 50 black soldiers to disguise themselves in civilian clothes, arm themselves with spears and knives, and disrupt a political rally in 1985
the rally was sponsored by the south-west african people's organization, which seeks independence from south africa. swapo's outlawed military wing has been waging a guerrilla war since 1966
the man fatally stabbed at the rally, immanuel shifidi, was a swapo member
dirk van zyl smit, a criminology professor at the university of cape town, said botha's intervention was the worst type of executive interference because, unlike a pardon or reprieve, it occurred before a judgment had been made
dave dalling, a progressive federal member of parliament, said botha's action placed the army above the law and undermined public confidence in the judiciary
in the namibian capital, windhoek, the local bar association expressed ``shock and disbelief'' at botha's action
the labor party, which represents most of the territory's mixed-race people, said botha's ``arbitrary decision ... may give rise to further public violence, bloodshed and chaos.'' has received 3 death sentences and faces execution, sted that he faces three death sentences</note>
when eleanore rose holds a burial next week for her murdered daughter, allegedly a victim of killer ted bundy 14 years ago, the casket will contain denise's favorite dress, a rose and some photos
but there will be no remains
king county authorities, who had kept the bones of 18-year-old denise naslund as part of their investigation of the alleged serial killer, misplaced them shortly after they were found in 1974 in a wooded area in the cascade foothills east of seattle
a lawsuit filed by ms. rose and relatives against the county was settled recently out of court and details were not made public. but ms. rose said the settlement, and next wednesday's memorial, are little consolation
i can't forget the remains were lost,'' she said tuesday. ``her being murdered was bad enough. ... all those years they told me they would give the remains back.''
in 1974, police agreed to temporarily place the remains in the casket so a memorial service could be held. afterward, they were taken away by detectives, and the casket wrapped in plastic and placed in the funeral home's basement
ten years later, when ms. rose sought to have them released for burial, she learned they had mysteriously disappeared, possibly in an office move or an accidental cremation, which would violate her roman catholic beliefs
losing the remains ``is almost, to me, sacrilegious. it's almost like a crime was committed,'' she said
when the service is held at forest lawn cemetery in seattle, ms. naslund's casket will hold some of her personal effects, including a favorite floral-print dress. her mother said she plans to add a silk rose, photos of herself and her daughter, a crucifix and some letters
in one letter, county officials express their regret at losing ms. naslund's remains. another note is from ms. rose to her daughter, ``dear denise, god forgive them for what they have done. i love you, mom.''
ms. naslund, along with janice ott, disappeared on july 14, 1974. two months later, the bones of the women were found scattered in a remote area. the cause of death was not positively determined
no charges in washington were ever filed against bundy, who is on death row in florida after receiving three death sentences for the 1978 murders of two florida state university sorority sisters and the february 1978 kidnap, rape and murder of a 12-year-old lake city, fla., girl
however, bundy has been described by king county police as their prime suspect in the unsolved slayings of ms. naslund, ms. ott and six other young women in western washington in 1974
in ms. rose's seattle home, the walls of the small kitchen are crowded with photographs of her daughter, whose bedroom remains much the same as it was when she disappeared. ms. naslund's 1964 chevrolet impala is still parked outside
telemarketing, a sales strategy usually associated with business, is gaining popularity in the religious society of friends, a group not known for evangelism
in kernersville, a handful of quakers with telephones, address lists and friendly voices hope to gather a new weekly meeting
on tuesday night, they gathered at the former site of spruce pines friends meeting, a dwindling church that finally closed in november. quakers from winston-salem, kernersville, archdale and charlotte dial nightly in a four-week campaign that has yielded more than 200 requests for information since sunday
hi. this is archie creed with the new north view friends church that will be opening off piney grove road in may,'' said the church's pastor in a call to a prospective member
creed first asks if the person is actively involved in a local church. if they say yes, he thanks them for their time. if they say no, creed asks if the church can mail them a brochure
each call is ranked according to the person's response: fair, good, very good, excellent. ``first one tonight!'' exclaimed ethel holmes, a volunteer from kernersville, after she marked one response ``excellent.''
most of them are receptive, even if they attend another church,'' she said. ``i have had no hangups.''
holmes is sold on this unconventional method of evangelism
people do not respond to door-knocking real well,'' she explained. but they usually don't mind a phone call, she said
the goal is 25,000 calls, which creed hopes will produce a mailing list of 2,500 names
he expects more than 200 people at the church's first official service may 15
steve wood, pastor of battle forest friends church in northwest greensboro, is also sold on telemarketing
his congregation recently completed an 8,000-call campaign. on sunday, the 85-member congregation will celebrate its telephonic fruits at a service for new members
wood, a part-time real estate agent, got the idea from telemarketing advertisements in real estate magazines. if it works for business, he thought, why not use it in the church?
door-to-door visitation was out because it takes too much time for too few results, wood said
so far, telemarketing by quakers has been very successful, says billy britt, superintendent of the n.c. friends yearly meeting. in southern california, such campaigns produced seven new churches, he said
about one percent of those called end up joining the church, which means battle forest can expect to add about 60 people to its rolls
if other quakers object to the technique, they haven't told him about it
there has been no opposition to it,'' britt said. ``it is aimed at the unchurched. there's no high pressure.''
coastal residents were jolted awake by a moderate earthquake and aftershock today, prompting worried calls to police and radio stations, but there were no reports of injury or damage
the first shock, measuring 3.9 on the richter scale, hit at 12:42 a.m. and was centered 11 miles southeast of downtown santa barbara, said robert finn, spokesman for the seismology lab at the california institute of technology in pasadena
at 12:57 there was an aftershock in the same location with a 2.7 magnitude,'' finn said. ``these quakes weren't strong enough to do much damage, but a lot of people felt them.''
about 30 shaken sleepers telephoned santa barbara county sheriff's headquarters to confirm what they felt, said deputy larry ralston
they were just concerned and curious, or like one who wanted to know if he had been dreaming,'' ralston said
the early morning quake was centered about 75 miles northwest of downtown los angeles
a $52 million grant from the moody foundation will be used to build a towering greenhouse housing exotic plants from tropical rain forests, officials say
besides the tropical indoor gardens, there will be a 400-seat theater featuring a three-dimensional film, a plant-science center and a garden restaurant, foundation officials announced tuesday
all are part of the foundation's 142-acre, $120 million botanic garden, research and entertainment complex on galveston island
the one-acre preserve will grow inside a facility foundation officials said will be 12 to 15 stories tall. it is scheduled to open in early 1993, said e. douglas mcleod, the foundation's director of development
galveston mayor jan coggeshall said she was grateful to the foundation for the project, which is expected to attract thousands of visitors and subsequently pump more tourist dollars into the community
i think it (the project) is a symbol of galveston's future,'' ms. coggeshall said. ``it is a living part of our future on the island.''
moody gardens will have a movable viewing platform so visitors can see the gardens from different levels. there will be streams, trails, waterfalls and plants representing the tropical rainforests of asia, africa and both americas. two conservatories also are planned
not included in the $52-million phase but part of the development is a beach area called palm beach, which will feature white sand imported from orlando, fla. the sand arrived saturday and will be spread over a three-acre area later this spring
the moody foundation was established in 1942 by wealthy businessman william lewis moody jr. and his wife, libbie shearn moody, and is still controlled by family members
a judge has ordered maria desillers to turn over additional donations that she recently told officials she had received for her late son's liver transplants
all undeposited contributions must be listed and handed over to a court-appointed curator today, dade circuit judge francis j. christie said tuesday
curator karen gievers requested the order after ms. desillers said friday that she had found a ``substantial amount'' of unopened mail last november in warehouse where she stored furniture and other possessions
the carton of mail included checks and cash donated for desillers' 7-year-old son, ronnie, who died april 29 at children's hospital of pittsburgh while awaiting his fourth liver transplant
when ronnie's need for a liver transplant was publicized last year, donations were received from well-wishers throughout the country, including $1,000 from president reagan
an audit by the florida secretary of state found that ms. desillers received almost $1 million in donations, of which about $175,000 could not be accounted for
ms. desillers' lawyer said tuesday that for four months his client didn't deposit the newly found donations, which he said totaled only a few hundred dollars
she has kept everything segregated and stapled together,'' attorney harry robbins said. ``she figured if she made any more deposits it wasn't going to look good.''
the state has charged ms. desillers with using donations for her personal expenses and failing to register ronnie's fund as a charity. ms. desillers, who faces a maximum $1,000 fine, will contest the charges at a may 10 hearing
state investigators say ms. desillers withdrew at least $47,000 in donations to buy jewelry, clothing and furniture, pay rent on her miami bayfront apartment and return $5,000 loaned to her by a former boyfriend
last fall, children's hospital sued ms. desillers after she refused to pay $262,000 of the $424,300 bill that remained from her son's transplants. ms. desillers claimed the boy received poor care, which hospital officials deny
meanwhile, the dade county state attorney's office is continuing a criminal investigation into whether ms. desillers committed fraud or theft by using some of the donations for her expenses
earlier this month, christie froze the boy's estate and appointed ms. gievers to oversee the $239,287 that remained in the child's bank account
when ms. gievers learned of the undeposited funds last week, she requested that the money be turned over to her immediately. by tuesday, when she had not received the money, she filed the petition in the dade court
the money will be deposited in a restricted, interest-bearing account until the court rules how the remaining funds will be distributed, ms. gievers said
robbins has said his client did not misuse any of the donations and that she is entitled to the estate because she is the boy's natural heir
the roman catholic bishop whose diocese includes the ira stronghold of catholic west belfast said today the outlawed guerrilla organization is ``sheer evil.''
the ira poses a very grave spiritual danger to the catholic community and we must realize that and have no illusions about it,'' said bishop cahal daly in an interview with radio ulster, the british broadcasting corp.'s local northern ireland station
this is a question of sheer evil and we have got to face that evil and have no truck with it,'' he declared
daly is bishop of down and connor. the diocese includes west belfast where two british soldiers were killed saturday when they drove up to the funeral cortege for irish republican army guerrilla kevin brady
in scenes that shocked television audiences around the world, members of the catholic crowd in the funeral cortege for brady dragged the soldiers from the car, stripped them naked and beat them unconscious with iron bars before ira gunmen shot them dead
daly in a statement tuesday declared: ``ira violence is often disguised with a mask of romantic rhetoric and militaristic mock ritual. for a ghastly half-hour on saturday, the mask slipped. the real face of ira violence was shown and it was horrible to see.''
he said the crowd saturday had a right to fear that they were going to be attacked. the previous wednesday a protestant extremist killed three people and wounded 68 in an attack on an ira funeral
but let us not be deceived. this was not a momentary lapse from high ira principles and standards. people would not have taken iron bars in their hands to batter soldiers into unconsciousness if they had not taken hatred into their hearts,'' he said in tuesday's statement
daly pleaded with those who joined the ira ``for idealistic reasons and out of sense of justice'' to quit the organization
for god's sake, for ireland's sake, let them leave the organization now before still more grievous harm is done,'' he said
sean kenny, a sinn fein member of belfast city council, dismissed the statement, saying the bishop was an apologist for the british security forces. sinn fein is the ira's legal political arm
brady was one of three people killed in a gun and grenade attack at the march 16 funeral at milltown cemetery of three unarmed ira guerrillas killed by british troops in gibraltar
protestant michael stone was charged tuesday with three counts of murder in connection with the cemetery deaths and with murdering three other catholics in sniper attacks
the predominantly catholic ira is fighting to unite northern ireland with the irish republic. background. no pickup.</note>
president francois mitterrand said he will seek re-election because he can rise above france's fractious politics and keep the country together
the 71-year-old socialist announced on nationwide television tuesday that he will seek re-election next month. prior to his announcement, opinion polls put him in the lead
mitterrand told a tv interviewer he decided to run because he thinks disunity threatens ``to tear the social fabric'' of france
i saw a risk that the country might fall again into the quarrels and divisions that have hampered it so often. i want france to be united ... not be taken in hand by the spirit of intolerance, by parties who want everything, by clans, by cliques,'' he said
after mitterrand declared, michel rocard, until now the socialist party's only candidate, withdrew and gave his full support to the incumbent. the main conservative candidates are premier jacques chirac and former premier raymond barre
the first round of the elections is to be held april 24 with a run-off between the top two candidates scheduled for may 8
mitterrand led the leftist surge in may 1981 that ousted president valery giscard d'estaing and the center-right alliance that had controlled the national assembly for 23 years
the victory avenged mitterrand's defeats in the presidential elections of 1965 by charles de gaulle and 1974 by giscard d'estaing
but france's love affair with the socialists was short-lived
after five years, french voters in the march 1986 parliamentary elections returned control to the right _ creating what became known in france as ``cohabitation'' between a socialist president and a conservative premier
socialist policies had dragged mitterrand's popularity rating in public opinion polls as low as 27 percent, but under the unwanted marriage with the conservatives it soared again to a consistent 55 percent or more
that gave mitterrand the dubious honor of being, in one seven-year term, both the least and most popular chief executive in the 30 years of the fifth republic
in the beginning of his administration, mitterrand pursued costly social programs after the socialists gained power. then he reversed course, instituting austerity measures
economic troubles brought his party to power, and caused its downfall five years later. after the socialist defeat, mitterrand eased into the role of elder statesman and held himself above the day-to-day battles of governing, commenting on issues only occasionally
the french called him ``tonton,'' or uncle
mitterrand was born oct. 26, 1916, in jarnac and attended universities in paris, earning degrees in law and letters. he was drafted into the army in 1938, and shot and captured during the german invasion in 1940
mitterrand escaped from a prison camp in germany, returned to france and created a resistance network. his feud with de gaulle began when mitterrand refused to unite his resistance group with de gaulle's
it was in the resistance days that he met danielle gouze, and they married in 1944, soon after france was liberated. he held several government posts, including interior and justice minister
in the early 1970s he built the moribund socialist party into a major political force, but the union of the left he formed with the communists fell apart in 1977
not until the final days of the 1981 campaign did the two main leftist parties join forces again to defeat giscard and oust the conservatives
mitterrand shocked much of the west by bringing communists into his government, but the union lasted only three years. in 1984, the communists pulled out in a dispute over economic policy
ortho pharmaceutical corp. says it will challenge a state appellate court's decision upholding a jury's verdict that the diaphragm manufacturer was responsible for a woman's toxic shock syndrome
in a 36-page ruling tuesday, the middle-level court of appeals said there was sufficient evidence to justify a maricopa county superior court jury's $1.5 million verdict against ortho, manufacturer of the ortho all-flex diaphragm
the verdict was the first to hold a pharmaceutical manufacturer responsible for a case of toxic shock syndrome, according to the appellate court and the plaintiff's lawyer
tss is an acute and sometimes fatal illness caused by a bacterium, staphylococcus aureus, that produces a poison. the ailment is most closely associated with tampon use
the case was brought in phoenix by roberta baroldy, whose physician prescribed an ortho all-flex diaphragm in april 1982, about six weeks after the birth of her first child
ortho pharmaceutical has since issued warnings on the possibility of toxic shock syndrome, but court records show that the company had been warned by at least one doctor of a possible tss link nearly four months before mrs. baroldy's illness in july 1982 and had not publicized the warning
mrs. baroldy was hospitalized for 41 days and was ``at times comatose and near death,'' the 3-0 appellate ruling noted
mrs. baroldy's medical witnesses testified that she would have physical problems for the rest of her life as a result of the disease
we will appeal,'' ortho spokesman rich salem said tuesday at corporate headquarters in raritan, n.j. ``beyond that, we'd like a chance to actually see the opinion before we comment further.''
the company, a subsidiary of johnson &amp; johnson and has sold millions of the contraceptive devices over more than 40 years, according to court records
about 1.8 million diaphragms are sold each year in the united states, salem said, adding that he did not know ortho's share of the market
ortho's attorneys argued on appeal that the theory under which experts claimed that mrs. baroldy was stricken did not have the required ``general acceptance'' in the scientific community
they also argued that the case should have been tried using north carolina laws because mrs. baroldy was in north carolina at the time of her illness while her husband was taking parachute training at fort bragg
but the appeals court said it was satisfied that testimony from a broad cross-section of experts showed general acceptance of a link between diaphragms and tss
and the judges said arizona's product liability law was more appropriate than north carolina law because it was closer to the laws in new jersey, where ortho is headquartered, and because the baroldys, who are from the globe, ariz. area, were living in mesa at the time the suit was tried
the u.n. command today rebuked communist north korea for refusing to return the remains of u.s. soldiers killed during the korean war, officials said
the u.n. command called for return of the remains at a meeting with north korean military officials at the panmunjom truce site. u.n. officials accused north korea of aggravating tension on the korean peninsula
this irrational and inhumane action by your side on this issue is totally unacceptable and will be denounced by all fair-minded people and the community of civilized nations worldwide,'' said u.s. army col. charles coffman, according to a u.n. statement
north korea refused to return the remains of two u.s. soldiers who died during the korean war after the united states imposed sanctions against the country in january for its alleged bombing of a south korean commercial jetliner
the united states, south korea and other nations have accused north korea of bombing the airliner, killing all 115 people aboard, last nov. 29. north korea has denied involvement
a woman who flew on an early part of the flight confessed in january to being a north korean agent and said she planted a bomb on the korean air jet to disrupt the 1988 olympic games in seoul
the two americans whose remains are being sought by the u.s. have been identified as 1st lt. jack j. saunders of utah and cpl. arthur i. seaton of pennsylvania. they reportedly died in north korean prison camps in 1951
coffman, acting as secretary of the u.n. command, complained that north korea was trying to stir up tension on the korean peninsula
he also objected to repeated north korean charges that military exercises being held by u.s. and south korean forces under the name ``team spirit'' were a prelude to a nuclear attack on the north
your repetition of charges, and your repeat of your annual litany of false allegations against team spirit _ filled with abusive language, unfounded and irrelevant allegations _ obviously satisifed your propaganda purposes,'' he said
about 200,000 u.s. and south korean troops are taking part in the annual exercises between now and april. the united states keeps 40,000 troops in south korea under a mutual defense pact
the u.n. command meets periodically with north korean and chinese representatives for meetings of the military armistice commission to supervise disputes and violations of the cease-fire that ended the korean war in 1953
the war began in 1950 after north korean forces invaded the south and troops from the united states and other nations came to the assistance of the south. correct name of island to san nicolas; subs 7th graf with three grafs, ``state and federal xxx, to add background, show 1,400 refers only to california population of sea otters</note>
a $1-million-a-year program has relocated 62 sea otters to an island off southern california, but 27 of the endangered beasts have vanished without a trace
sure we're concerned,'' said jim estes, who is monitoring the program for u.s. fish and wildlife service. ``we wish we had 62 sea otters there. but we've only been at this six months. we need more time with these animals.''
in addition to 27 otters missing since aug. 8 after being moved to san nicolas island, about 60 miles off the coast, eight have died and six are known to have left the area, the state coastal commission learned tuesday
we've lost most of the adults out there,'' estes told the commission, but added, ``we have only just begun to look for animals that have dispersed from the island.''
you stand before us and tell us that you can't account for almost one-half of the population you transferred out there,'' commissioner dorrill wright responded. he said he was ``very unhappy'' about the report
the otters were the first of several groups to be airlifted over five years to the small, rocky island that was once a breeding ground of the animals, which were hunted to near extinction before the turn of the century
the california population of sea otters numbers about 1,400 and lives along a 300-mile stretch of the central california coast from morro bay to santa cruz
the airlift to san nicolas was part of an effort to establish another population center for the animals off southern california. state and federal marine biologists say the california population could be threatened with extinction if their breeding grounds are hit with an oil spill or disease
the population transfer was opposed by local fishermen, who feared that the otters would wipe out abalone, lobsters and other marketable marine life
of the eight otters that died, three perished from stress related to the transfer, three drowned in lobster traps and fishing nets, one was shot and one was found dead of unknown causes, according to the report
officials have acknowledged that at least six otters have eluded recapture and managed to swim home to monterey. another was caught off the northern los angeles county coastline and returned to its original capture site, officials said
wildlife officials hope to continue relocating sea otters to san nicolas island
we've learned a lot and we are guardedly optimistic,'' said david riley, an assistant regional director with the u.s. fish and wildlife service
carol fulton, representing friends of the sea otter, a carmel-based group that claims 4,500 members nationwide, supported the project
the issue has to be put in perspective,'' she said. ``we were losing over 100 otters a year in fishermen's gill nets within their present range.''
a pastor who opposed his congregation's decision to bar blacks from the church preschool has resigned at the request of the church's deacons
it all goes back to the integration issue. i was like a toy two children were fighting over,'' the rev. kenneth newton said about his resignation and the split among members of northside baptist church
in an unsigned letter to church members dated march 14, the deacons said they unanimously recommended that newton resign immediately. the letter said the recommendation was based on ``matters of trustworthiness that had a significant effect on the church.''
wyman lawson, chairman of the deacons, would not comment on the letter
newton, however, said monday the mistrust was mutual
the last pastor stayed here 16 months and said the deacons would not cooperate with him and left. i was able to stay here 13{ years under adverse circumstances,'' newton said
the deacons' letter said newton was offered $10,000 in severance pay. he accepted the money march 4 and resigned that day
some church members who were opposed to the deacons' action sent out a letter listing newton's accomplishments. they said when newton first came to northside in 1974, the church was $90,000 in debt
the letter said the debt has been paid along with renovations to the church, opening of the learning center for children and purchase of 7.6 acres of land and seven houses. the group also said the church's budget has increased from $60,000 to $500,000 under newton's leadership
in a secret vote last october, the congregation decided by a two-thirds majority that blacks should not be accepted by northside baptist learning center. afterward, newton attacked the decision publicly, angering some congregants
it's a clammy situation, scientists admit
a year ago, a species of tiny clams believed to come from the asian coast were discovered in san francisco bay. now, scientists say, there are millions in the muck along the bottom
it's too early to determine if the clam might displace other species in the bay, said jim carlton of the university of oregon, an authority on marine transplants
it's brand new, so the full-scale ecological consequences of the invasion probably won't be measured for several years as we see how it spreads and where,'' he said
carlton plans to send some specimens to asian scientists to determine the clam's origins
at one time, the soviet union was thought to be the clam's home because a similar mollusk was found there in the 1860s. ``we know now that's not true,'' said larry schemel of the u.s. geological survey. ``it appears right now that there's a higher probability that the clam came from china.''
one thing's certain, though, they said. there is little chance the clam will end up on menus at the city's fashionable restaurants
the maximum size is half to three-quarters of an inch, so we're not even talking about an hors d'oeuvre,'' carlton said. tanker. picks up 8th graf pvs, `salvage tugboats ...</note>
iranian gunboats attacked a cypriot freighter in the persian gulf today and set it ablaze, and iraq said a long-range missile fired by iran hit baghdad, killing and wounding civilians
the international committee of the red cross condemned the use of chemical weapons in the 7{-year-old iran-iraq war, calling it a ``new and tragic escalation'' of the conflict, and said it had taken urgent steps to end such attacks
the statement followed iranian charges that iraq killed or wounded 5,000 people in chemical weapons attacks last week on kurdish border cities
the freighter attack was iran's ninth raid on neutral commercial shipping in six days
the stricken vessel was the cypriot-flag 34,346-ton odysseas h, which had been in saudi arabia recently
gulf-based shipping executives, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the captain reported his vessel was attacked by two iranian gunboats 10 miles west of the strait of hormuz, the entry to the gulf, at 4:45 p.m. he reported a fire and requested aid
salvage tugboats rushed out in the direction given by the master
the iraqi news agency reported that the missile lobbed by iran crashed at 7:30 a.m. into a residential neighorhood, ``killing and wounding civilians and destroying property.''
the agency, monitored in cyprus, did not give an exact casualty count. it acknowledged that iraqi gunners fired a similar projectile into tehran on tuesday
two sailors were killed and nine others injured in an attack tuesday by iranian gunboats and a helicopter on the havglimt tanker, which was hauling a load of ammonia through the gylf
the vessel, operated by the oslo-based havtor co., was hit northwest of the united arab emirates
the british destroyer hms exeter sent out a gas-masked medical team to help the crew of the 38,534-ton ship, which flies the singapore flag
dubai port authority officers identified the dead crewmen only as singapore nationals. most of the injuries were due to inhalation of ammonia vapors, maritime salvage sources reported
in geneva, the international committee of the red cross issued a statement saying it had informed iran of ``its readiness to provide emergency assistance for the victims'' of chemical weapons attacks
iran has repeatedly accused iraq of using chemical weapons. iraq has denied the allegations
the use of chemical weapons, whether against military personnel or civilians, is absolutely forbidden by international law and is to be condemned at all times,'' the red cross said
it said the icrc has ``taken urgent steps to bring to an immediate end the use of chemical weapons.'' it did not elaborat
the postmaster who found a stolen claude monet painting worth $175,000 will get a pat on the back, but he won't collect the $17,500 reward because he was simply doing his job
steve reutter, spokesman for the st. paul fire &amp; marine insurance co., which paid a $175,000 claim after the theft, said postal rules prevent charles polley and other employees from collecting rewards ``for things done in the line of duty
we asked them and that's what they said,'' reutter said
i really didn't expect it,'' said polley. ``you are here on a payroll and that's the way it is.''
reutter said the company will make a ``good will'' offering to a charity in marshalltown in polley's name. the amount and charity haven't been decided, he said
the painting, ``fishing boats under the cliffs of etretat,'' was stolen from the fisher community center march 19, 1987 and was recovered this month when polley found it in a mail drop box in legrand, which is near marshalltown
polley said he has a metal detector and goes hunting for buried treasures now and then, but the monet discovery tops his list. ``i've found the gold ring,'' he said. ``that was the most valuable thing i've ever found.''
art experts say the painting is damaged but restorable. the fisher foundation, which operates the center, will keep the insurance money to build a new gallery. the insurers have said they'll probably auction the painting. study finds</head>
most employers believe they benefit when workers have good child care available, but the companies don't want to pay for it, a survey of 141 businesses concludes
nationwide, about 800 companies have developed child-care centers on or near their business, according to the survey being published in the april issue of personnel journal in costa mesa, calif. most of these are large companies or public agencies
the majority of u.s. employers are not establishing child-care centers,'' wrote the authors, toni a. campbell of san jose state university in california and david e. campbell of humboldt state university in arcata, calif
on the other hand, they wrote in the survey released tuesday, most employers surveyed thought they should be involved in family matters
the problems are money and information, the survey found
the question appears ... not to be whether employers might involve themselves, but rather how they can get involved without jeopardizing the bottom line,'' the authors wrote
certainly the focus on expense is a major issue for small businesses,'' they added
the survey found that eight of 10 companies surveyed believe productivity and the quality of the work force will improve if the organization helps employees with child-care problems
but 71 percent said they don't want to provide space at the work site, and 69 percent said they don't want to subsidize child-care programs
the researchers said many employers offer options involving work schedules to help families. flexible hours were offered by 60 percent of the companies surveyed; 71 percent offered part-time work; 24 percent had job sharing; and 71 percent gave leaves to care for a sick child
the researchers suggested that small companies could share the cost of locating and implementing a child-care program for employees. they said this could be coordinated through a local chamber of commerce or a trade group. work</head> 34, sted 35</note>
harold thomas spent harsh winter days in an open shack, then took a job in new mexico when a couple offered to improve his life. now he's back home looking for more work, and he might write a book
the former homeless man returned to chicago late tuesday after working for two months as a handyman. he said he appreciated the chance to ``see a lot of america'' but the job given by roy and ethel gilman didn't provide steady wages
the gilmans are fine people, but they didn't want to pay me,'' said thomas, weary after riding a bus from portales, n.m., a small farming community
he said he lived in a trailer and worked six days a week, fixing cars, erecting fences and other farm chores
but a man can't live on room and board alone. i want to start a family, maybe get married,'' thomas said
for nine months, thomas, 34, lived in a shack just west of downtown chicago. the gilmans read an associated press account of his plight and offered him a job in mid-january
the gilmans paid thomas room and board and deposited $300 in wages for him in a portales bank about a month ago. on monday, thomas withdrew the money and boarded a bus for chicago
he said the money was put into an account after media reports indicated he wasn't receiving a regular salary
i thought i'd get some wages,'' thomas said. ``they treated me very nice. they're nice, church-going people, but no wages
i didn't have a lot of time for things myself. when a fellow turns and sees everything negative, what's a guy to do?'' he said
thomas, wearing the clothes he received from well-wishers when he left chicago on jan. 15, said he would be living with a girlfriend at a public housing project on the north side
i don't have a job, not right off,'' he said. ``but i've got a few ideas of my own. i'm going to be looking. i've got a few dollars in my pocket to last me awhile
i'm thinking about writing a book. a lot of people look down on the homeless. i just want everyone to know people on the street aren't junk.''
mrs. gilman, 68, said thomas was treated as well as ``our own family.''
she said past news reports about wages may have contributed to thomas' departure
mrs. gilman said people who read those stories had ``been calling us from everywhere saying we've been trying to make a slave out of harold. all we did was try to help him.''
thomas said he hasn't forgotten his homeless friends, many of whom seek shelter in the wooden shack he built last year along the chicago river
i've got to see my friends,'' he said before hopping in a cab. ``we've got a lot to talk about.'' throughout to recast and incorporate additional background. no pickup.</note>
