an initial review of court documents indicates that the manufacturer of the copper-7 birth control device did not attempt to mislead federal regulators about its potential hazards, a government spokeswoman says
g.d. searle &amp; co. is being sued by women who claim use of the intrauterine device caused them to develop pelvic infections
a lawyer for one of the plaintiffs contends court documents indicate an attempt to conceal known health threats from the u.s. food and drug administration. the papers were unsealed by a judge's order
fda spokeswoman susan cruzan said tuesday that investigators met with searle officials march 16 to go over the documents
the fda has not had any reason to withdraw approval of the copper-7 iud,'' she said, adding that could be the ultimate penalty if the fda determined the company did misrepresent the product
cruzan said the fda will continue to review documents that are unsealed in the case brought by esther kociemba of melrose, who claims that the copper-7 made her infertile
her attorney, michael ciresi of minneapolis, has said the unsealed documents ``will collectively establish without a doubt that the copper-7 causes (infection) and searle knew about it but did not disclose it to doctors or to women.''
ciresi said tuesday he could not comment on cruzan's initial assessment because he does not know which documents the fda reviewed
mrs. kociemba's case against searle is scheduled to go to trial may 16 in federal court in st. paul
the copper-7 was approved for public use in 1974. from then until 1986, when searle withdrew it from the market because of mounting litigation costs, it was the most popular iud in the united states. searle recently resumed manufacturing the device to fill foreign orders
searle, which maintains that the device is safe, has won 14 of the 17 cases that have gone to court and says it has settled several hundred out of court
searle is a unit of monsanto co. of st. louis. sister</head>
tennessee williams' sister will maintain literary rights to the late playwright's documents and personal files, but harvard university may take possession of them for study, a judge has ruled
williams, whose plays included ``a streetcar named desire'' and ``cat on a hot tin roof,'' died in new york city in 1983 at 71. he willed to harvard a bundle of papers, reportedly appraised at $175,000, that include plays and other manuscripts, some unpublished
trustees for 78-year-old rose williams, who has long been institutionalized, wanted the papers given ``in trust'' so the manuscripts could be sold if she needed money. trustee john eastman of new york said miss williams' annual expenses average $200,000
harvard maintained it had the right to possession of the papers, now held in vaults by estate executor southeast bank in miami
at a hearing tuesday, one of the final steps toward distribution of the williams' estate, monroe county circuit judge helio gomez said he found no reason why the school could not take the papers
harvard attorney frank connors promised miss williams' trustees she will receive the earnings of any publication or documents with commercial value. williams' royalties totaled $3.1 million from february 1984 to august 1987, he added
we are not taking the literary rights,'' connors said. ``we are simply talking about the papers physically being there (at harvard) where scholars can see them.''
miss williams has been at the private stony lodge sanitarium in ossining, n.y., for 53 years. she underwent a lobotomy decades ago. many of williams' plays are said to reflect his feelings toward his sister and other people who are lonely or mentally disabled
the papers in question include some unpublished plays and manuscripts, said attorney jim hendrick, who represents miss william's trustees. million.</note>
democrat albert gore jr. today called on the government to ``straighten out its economic policy'' to make heavy industry more competitive worldwide
the tennessee senator, campaigning in michigan for a share of the 138 delegates at stake in saturday's caucuses, made his plea during a tour of a giant iron ore processing plant in the state's upper peninsula
gore spoke informally with some of the 700 workers at the tilden mining company facility, and then noted the plant's reduced production, which officials attributed to lowered demands
the candidate said the plant ``is competitive so long as the competition is not unfairly subsidized.''
we need to straighten out our economic policy and stop borrowing $500 million every 24 hours so that we're competitive in the world economy _ and we have to take steps to remove unfair trade barriers overseas,'' he said
gore donned a hard hat to tour the facility where iron ore is minded and rendered into small pellets. he walked amid large, whirling cylinders that grind and filter the iron and peered inside a giant rotating kiln that bakes the final product
it's an amazing place, isn't it. it's like the inside of a death star,'' gore said in apparent reference to the ``star wars'' movie trilogy
gore was seeking votes in the state's sparsely populated upper peninsula for a second day today after attacking vice president george bush and the reagan administration before high school and college audiences tuesday
he was heading to wisconsin later today to address the state legislature in madison. aiming toward wisconsin's april 5 primary, gore began airing television commercials there this week lashing out at corporate greed
gore said bush represents the choice for voters to ``continue what we're doing'' without change. denouncing that choice, he cited the iran-contra affair, u.s. support for panama strongman manuel noriega in the face of evidence of drug involvement until recently, and what he said was a general feeling of economic pessimism among america's youth
i think if we continue what we're doing now, continuing down the same path, we're headed for trouble,'' he told high school students who jammed an auditorium for an after-school rally in traverse city
he repeated those themes later in a speech to more than 1,000 students at lake superior state university in sault ste. marie
he denounced bush as lacking the ``gumption'' to disagree with president reagan's veto on the civil rights bill, which congress voted to override. gore dropped plans to campaign in wisconsin on tuesday so that he could return to washington to vote to override the veto
i was quite surprised that george bush belatedly announced he was in favor of the veto _ that surprised many people,'' gore said. ``but of course he has not been willing to disagree with president reagan on anything.''
gore campaigned in northern michigan as polls of the state's democrats, published by both detroit newspapers, showed him trailing far behind rivals jesse jackson and michael dukakis. democrat richard gephardt is also campaigning in michigan, which is a do-or-die state for his white house hopes
facing those long odds, gore has not waged an intensive michigan campaign and has aired radio but no television commercials. much of gore's michigan organization is based on the support of key state legislators, including a legislative power from the northern region, dominic jacobitti
gore largely avoided mention of his democratic rivals, however. the closest he came was saying the country needs a president ``with foreign policy experience'' _ something he has in the past charged dukakis with lacking
gore appeared before an enthusiastic audience of college students in sault ste. marie and contended, ``i am the first presidential candidate to campaign in sault ste. marie since teddy roosevelt.''
