the supreme court today dismissed a medicaid dispute between the reagan administration and california that the justices had been studying for over a year
the court said recent action by congress has made the case legally irrelevant
federal authorities had sought to limit state power to ease eligibilty for medicaid, a combined federal and state program of medical assistance to the needy
the california legislature decided in 1983 that aged and disabled medicaid recipients were unable to afford necessary medical care as well as other necessities under the program's existing income standards
so the legislature increased from $544 to $709 the income adult couples may keep each month for non-medical needs and still qualify for medicaid
federal authorities had said the amount was illegally high
in an unsigned opinion today, the high court noted that a law recently enacted by congress ``required the secretary (of health and human services) to approve the proposed california amendment, retroactively to the date of its proposal.''
the court also noted that lawyers for california and the administration ``agree that these developments have rendered the controversy moot.''
the case is bowen vs. kizer, 86-863
democrats living overseas picked a largely uncommitted delegation to attend the party's national covention this summer, although massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, the winner of a non-binding poll, picked up a fraction of a convention vote
in balloting on tuesday, the democrats abroad elected 10 delegates, each of whom will cast one-half vote at the national convention. nine of those delegates have declared themselves uncommitted, while one is pledged to dukakis
another four delegates, each of whom will cast one-half vote, will be picked later at a meeting in paris, and under party rules they initially would be uncommitted
of course we have an impact, particularly if we're uncommitted,'' sally mcnulty, chairwoman of the democratic party committee abroad, said tuesday as organizers around her began readying stacks of air mail envelopes for counting. ``we could tip the ballot.''
of the 2,385 expatriate americans voting in the non-binding part of the ballot, cast mostly by mail, dukakis got 990 votes, or 41.5 percent and jackson 347 votes or 14.5 percent, according to democrats abroad, the official organizers of the poll
in third place was andrew sundberg, a businessman living in geneva, switzerland, who campaigns for expatriate benefits. he got 304 votes, or 12.7 percent
sen. paul simon of illinois was fourth with 248 votes, or 10.4 percent, and new york gov. mario cuomo, who is not a candidate, finished fifth with 171 votes, or 7.2 percent
it was the fourth primary for expatriate democrats, who select seven national convention delegates. two other delegates are party officials
the primary gives democrats worldwide the chance to vote by mail or in person for convention delegates
a slow trickle of voters turned out through the morning tuesday at the queen elizabeth ii conference center, around the corner from the houses of parliament. but party officials were not concerned
our members would have voted already by post,'' said ms. mcnulty, who estimated that 2 million to 3 million americans live abroad
any democrat abroad was eligible to mail a ballot to the primary. officials believed the majority would come from the 18 countries with democrats abroad organizations and large american populations, including israel, france and canada
for the first time, ballots were available at embassies and consulates worldwide
republicans abroad have a similar organization but they do not hold primaries
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev today called for a transformation of the country's inefficient agricultural system led by farms owned by farmers, not by the state
gorbachev, in an address to a national congress of collective farmers at the kremlin, said the possibilities of cooperatives were a ``brilliant discovery'' of soviet founder vladimir i. lenin that have been underused by subsequent soviet leaders
we should revive co-ops not in their old, often too primitive forms, but in the form of a modern, high-standard cooperative movement,'' gorbachev said
collective farms, where members jointly own farm buildings and machinery and share in earnings, have faded in importance in recent years in favor of state farms, where farmers, like employees in a factory, receive a basic wage
there were 33,000 collective farms in the soviet union in 1970, but their number dropped to 26,300 by 1986. in that same period, the number of collective farmers dropped from 16.7 million to 12.6 million
gorbachev has been striving to persuade soviets to enter into cooperative ventures to make up for shortages in the state-run economy. since reforms instituted last year, nearly 14,000 cooperatives have sprung up to offer restaurant services, pump gas, make clothes and provide other goods and services in short supply
a draft of a new law on cooperatives published earlier this month in the soviet press specifically prohibits government interference in their affairs but also forsees a progressive tax system to catch what gorbachev has called ``money-grabbing.''
gorbachev, in remarks at the farmers congress summarized by tass, said the new law aims to ``ensure the enhancement and development of cooperative and collective-farm property (and) create legal machinery to protect cooperative democracy.''
the summary of gorbachev's speech distributed by the official soviet news agency did not give any indication whether gorbachev would move give land to individual farmers
tass said the cooperative law would be a main item of discussion at the three-day session of collective farmers. it is the first such conference since 1969
according to tass, gorbachev said it was the cooperative movement that ``helped in many ways to overcome hunger and economic dislocation in the aftermath of the civil war, mend the financial and monetary systems, and get people more closely involved with the building of a new life.''
gorbachev said his re-emphasis on cooperatives is a result of greater democracy in soviet society and ``an important lever for furthering the democratic process and combatting administration by fiat and red tape.''
soviet agriculture has been plagued by central planners who tell farms what and how much to plant, lack of incentives for farmers to work the state-owned land, inefficient production, and poor storage and transportation facilities
the 3,100 u.s. troops dispatched to honduras as a warning to neighboring nicaragua are expected to return home next monday and tuesday, pentagon officials said today
the officials, who insisted on anonymity, described the withdrawal schedule as still tentative and subject to last-minute changes, depending upon developments in the region
but we said about 10 days for exercises and that's what it should be,'' another source said
the officials noted the soldiers had been airlifted to honduras over the course of two days last week and said that same procedure would be followed for the withdrawal
four battalions _ two from the 82nd airborne division at fort bragg, n.c., and two from the 7th light infantry division at fort ord, calif. _ were airlifted to honduras on march 17 and 18 after nicaraguan soldiers crossed the honduran border in pursuit of u.s.-backed contra guerrillas
the reagan administration insisted from the beginning that the u.s. soldiers would be kept away from the scene of the fighting, but said the deployment was necessary to demonstrate america's commitment to honduras and democracy in the region. update with details from services. picks up 11th graf, `on tuesday ...' edits to tighten.</note>
police announced today they were abandoning a policy of staying away from ira funerals because five people, including two british soldiers, were killed during funerals last week
protestant activists had demanded that police reinstitute the policy of clamping tight security on ira funerals
describing the ira threat as ``deadly,'' a police statement indicated security chiefs will order heavy police and troop presence at future ira funerals
experience has shown that maintenance of the law and prevention of outrages will only be guaranteed through the firm presence of the police and army,'' a statement from the royal ulster constabulary headquarters said
the statement marked the swift collapse of a policy introduced under pressure from moderate roman catholic leaders in the hope of avoiding clashes
at the first unpoliced ira funeral march 16, a protestant guerrilla launched a firearms and grenade attack from behind a tombstone in the catholic milltown cemetery, killing three people and wounded 68
at the ira funeral saturday for one milltown victim, two british soldiers drove up to the funeral cortege in an unmarked car were brutally slain
in britain, prime minister margaret thatcher joined grieving relatives at northolt air base north of london where the bodies of the soldiers, identified as signals corpsmen, were brought home
services for derek wood, 24, and david howes, 23, of the royal corps of signals, were scheduled for today in belfast, ballynahinch and lisburn, where they were based
security forces continued to search catholic areas of west belfast for their killers. police sources said investigators were looking for as many as 30 suspects
at northolt, mrs. thatcher glanced around anxiously while the sister of one of the men sobbed as the royal corps of signal band played chopin's ``funeral march'' and a bearer carried the flag-draped coffins to hearses
in belfast, some 25,000 people, mainly protestants, gathered this afternoon at the cenotaph outside the city hall for a memorial service to the slain soldiers
british and republic of ireland government ministers said they will hold a special meeting in london on friday to discuss tougher security because of the latest outburst of violence in northern ireland
the meeting was called under an anglo-irish agreement which gives the catholic republic an advisory say in britain's running of the protestant-dominated province
on tuesday, a protestant guerrilla said he killed three people at the ira burial in milltown because he wanted to avenge ira attacks aimed at mrs. thatcher and others, prosecutors said
the guerrilla, michael stone, 33, was charged with murdering three people in the attack on the march 16 funeral of three ira guerrillas killed by british soldiers in gibraltar. stone also was charged with killing three other roman catholics in sniper attacks dating back to 1984
none of earlier victims _ a milkman, a bread delivery man and a carpenter _ had any known links to the ira
stone was ordered to remain in custody until april 8, when he is next due in court. a trial date has not yet been set
flanked by heavy security in belfast magistrates court on tuesday, stone remained silent while a police superintendent read a statement he had made about the milltown attack
i alone carried out this military operation as a retaliatory strike against provisional sinn fein, the ira, in response to the slaughter of innocents at la mon, darkley, brighton and enniskillen,'' stone told police
i would state i am a dedicated free-lance loyalist (protestant) paramilitary. no surrender.''
the four attacks stone cited in his statement span nearly 10 years from 1978 to 1987 and claimed the lives of 35 people. mrs. thatcher escaped injury in the october 1984 brighton attack
in belfast, a senior bishop whose diocese includes the tense catholic ghetto of west belfast, denounced the ira as ``sheer evil.'' it was one of the strongest attacks yet by catholic prelates, who regularly condemn the mainly catholic guerrilla organization
bishop cahal daly said the ira posed a ``grave spritual danger to the catholic community.''
the mainly catholic irish republican army wants to end british rule in northern ireland and unite the predominantly protestant province with the overwhelmingly catholic republic of ireland under socialist rule. could come monday or tuesday. picks up 6th graf, `foreign minister ...'</note>
american troops will stay in honduras to complete emergency training exercises even though honduras says its border crisis with nicaragua is over, a u.s. military spokesman here said
in washington, pentagon officials who requested anonymity said the defense department was planning to withdraw the troops on monday and tuesday
president reagan ordered 3,200 american troops to honduras last week after nicaraguan soldiers allegedly penetrated honduran territory in pursuit of u.s.-supported contra rebels
on tuesday, president jose azcona hoyo told the associated press that sandinista troops had retreated and the american military contingent ``will leave honduras very soon.''
u.s. military spokesman maj. gary hovatter on tuesday said the soldiers first will finish their training exercises
right now the plans are to make it a 10- to 14-day exercise. we have not received any directive as to when to begin redeployment,'' he said, adding the exercises were taking place tuesday at four sites
in washington, a pentagon source stressed the withdrawal schedule was still ``tentative'' and subject to change, depending upon future developments in the region
but we said about 10 days for exercises and that's what it should be,'' another source said
the officials noted the soldiers had been airlifted to honduras over the course of two days last week and said that same procedure would be followed for the withdrawal
foreign minister carlos lopez contreras on tuesday said the border tension ``has virtually disappeared'' after both the sandinistas and the contras suspended hostilities and began truce talks in southern nicaragua
some u.s. soldiers expressed frustration on tuesday that they had not been allowed to join the fighting along the border
they get you all hepped up and then there's nothing to do,'' said pfc. jose pena, 23, of scottsdale, ariz., who was rushed in last week as part of what the white house called a ``measured response'' to the crisis
most of us were hoping to get a little action,'' he said at palmerola air base, headquarters for u.s. military operations
one soldier said he came prepared for anything
they told us it was a training exercise, but if things got hot and heavy, it was time for our training to kick in,'' said spec. 4 duane mccarty, a 25-year-old helicopter mechanic from novi, mich
the deployment of the u.s. troops bolstered the american military presence in honduras to about 6,000 servicemen. the reagan administration billed it as both a show of support for azcona and a warning to the sandinistas against further actions in the border region
the united states has been carrying out joint exercises with the honduran military periodically for five years as part of the reagan administration's policy of isolating the sandinistas
nobel laureate elie wiesel, a nazi death camp survivor who lectures on the holocaust, canceled an appearance here after learning his fee would come from a grant by a conservative publisher once accused of being an agent of south africa
wiesel had been scheduled as a speaker today at the john mcgoff distinguished lecture series at northern michigan university
but mcgoff's reported links to the south african government and the university's plans to pay wiesel's fee from a $300,000 grant from mcgoff brought protests from the school's faculty
when it comes to apartheid you cannot make compromises,'' wiesel said in explaining his decision
philosophy professor james green, who led the protests, said wiesel said he would have declined to appear had he known mcgoff's money was being used to pay for his appearance
mcgoff, former chairman of the northern michigan university board of control, was accused by the securities and exchange commission of illegally using south african money to try to buy u.s. newspapers and lobby on behalf of the south african government
mcgoff has denied acting as an agent for the south african government and the charges were dismissed
mcgoff, whose telephone number in williamston is unlisted, could not be reached for comment today
green said the university faculty voted to disassociate itself from the mcgoff lecture series. friday, the faculty voted 82-62 against using $3,000 from faculty funds to finance wiesel's talk
green said faculty members asked the university for assurances that none of the mcgoff money to be used for wiesel's lecture came from south africa, but the university never provided such an assurance
jim carter, news director at the university, said today the university received word late tuesday from the harry walker agency in new york city that wiesel's appearance had been canceled
we are making no further statement to that effect,'' carter said, declining to answer questions about how the cancellation came about
wiesel said some faculty members had urged him to use the lecture as a forum to denounce apartheid, which by law and custom establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs
the 5 million south african whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
when it comes to mass humiliation, a compromise is already playing the other side's game. and what is apartheid but collective humiliation; furhtermore, it is legal humiliation,'' said wiesel. ``in south africa, humiliation is the law of the land.'' graf pvs, when the</note>
the senate foreign relations committee today defeated the first attempt by sen. jesse helms, r-n.c., to change the u.s.-soviet treaty banning medium-range nuclear missiles
the democratic-controlled panel voted 12-3 against helms' amendment, which would allow non-nuclear u.s. cruise missiles to be deployed in europe
the pact signed dec. 8 by president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev bans missiles of ranges from 300 to 3,400 miles. the prohibition includes cruise missiles, both nuclear-tipped and those armed with non-nuclear weapons
the ban covers both types of missiles because ``there's no way to verify the distinction between'' the two, said sen. alan cranston, d-calif
but helms said the ban means ``the conventional imbalance in europe will be even greater than it is now'' because nato will lose a major weapon in the cruise missile
cranston responded that the pentagon has no plans to build non-nuclear cruise missiles
the vote came on the first of 43 pending amendments or reservations, either to the treaty text or the resolution by which the senate would register its approval of the pact
of those amendments, 36 were proposed by helms, the committee's ranking republican and the chief opponent of the treaty. three more were offered by sen. larry pressler, r-s.d., who has also been critical of the pact
sen. claiborne pell, d-r.i., the chairman of the committee, told his colleagues that he intends ``to oppose all reservations, conditions, etc.,'' with the possible exception of amendments designed to solve a long-running fight between the reagan administration and congress over treaty intepretation
helms said today the committee shouldn't be ``a rubber stamp'' for the administration, which has urged approval of the treaty without changes
both democratic and republican leaders predict overwhelming ratification when the treaty reaches the senate floor and say only 10 or 12 senators are likely to vote against it. ratification requires a two-thirds vote of the 100-member senate
i don't intend to obstruct'' the committee's work on the treaty, helms told his colleagues tuesday, but he added, ``i'm concerned that we're about to rush to judgment.''
given the large number of amendments, pell said the panel now ``seems very unlikely'' to meet its original goal of finishing work by friday
sen. richard lugar, r-ind., told helms, ``if you don't have the votes and you simply try to overload it with amendments, that isn't fair.''
most of helms' amendments are designed to improve what he says are compliance verification problems and clear up ambiguities
the majority of helms' proposals would amend the ratification resolution, which would not require new negotiations with the soviet union
any change made by the senate in the actual text of the treaty would have to be accepted by the soviet union, and administration officials have urged the senate to avoid so-called ``killer amendments'' that would cause the soviets to reject new talks
the treaty requires the elimination of nuclear-armed missiles with a range of 300 miles to 3,400 miles and includes on-site inspection provisions among its verification system, which is the most intrusive in arms control history
the foreign relations committee heard endorsements of the pact tuesday from two other committees, intelligence and armed services, which had also looked at the treaty during the past two months
but the congressional debate over the treaty has been clouded by the reopening of a long fight between the democratic-controlled congress and the white house
the complicated legal fight involves the question of whether an administration has the legal right to unilaterally change how the united states interprets a treaty. reagan asserts the administration has such a right, but sen. sam nunn, d-ga., chairman of the armed services committee, and other legislators have disagreed
the fight involves the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty, but it has spilled over into the debate on the intermediate-range nuclear forces treaty, nunn told the foreign relations committee
nunn said letters written by white house counsel arthur b. culvahouse jr. effectively undercut previous assurances from secretary of state george p. shultz that administration testimony on the new pact is ``authoritative.''
nunn said culvahouse asserted that some administration responses may be less authoritative than others
culvahouse suggested that the testimony of a secretary of state may be more authoritative than that of other administration witnesses or responses in writing to questions by members of congress, nunn said
culvahouse has since issued a second letter asserting that his original remarks were not inconsistent with the shultz statement. but nunn said he finds that unacceptable
nunn said the new letter ``puts the shultz statement in the trashcan, saying that certain testimony is not to be taken seriously.''
the dispute should be resolved by the full senate instead of seeking another letter from the administration, even from the president, said nunn
sen. alan cranston, d-calif., said the dispute ``is the major stumbling block and could create grave perils if we don't resolve it.''
six israeli warplanes today rocketed palestinian guerrilla bases on the outskirts of this southern port city
thick black smoke billowed from the stricken targets southeast of sidon, 25 miles south of beirut, as the fighter-bombers struck shortly after 4 p.m., lebanese police said
the israeli military said the targets were buildings used by guerrillas for storing weapons and equipment. it said the buildings were also used as garages for the guerrillas' vehicles
there were no immediate figures on casualties. police said several ambulances raced with sirens wailing from sidon to pick up victims
the israeli announcement did not identify which guerrilla group had been attacked. israel radio's arabic service quoted beirut radio stations as saying the targets belonged to yasser arafat's fatah guerrillas and lebanese moslem militias
the army said that all the planes returned safely to their bases and that the pilots reported that the targets were destroyed
the army said israeli planes also destroyed a vehicle equipped with anti-aircraft guns
police said the planes fired at least 25 rockets in five runs on guerrilla bases in a cluster of villages near sidon's ein el-hilweh refugee camp
they said the pilots released air balloons to deflect heat-seeking sam-7 missiles unleashed by guerrillas
the air strike was the second against the palestinians in a week and the fourth this year. thirty-one people were killed and 43 wounded in the three previous israeli air raids this year
consumer prices, restrained by lower food and energy costs, rose a modest 0.2 percent in february, the government said today in a report that shows inflation remains tame
food prices fell 0.3 percent after rising 0.3 percent in january. energy costs, which had fallen 0.7 percent in the preceding month, fell 0.6 percent last month
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater hailed the report, and one showing that the nation's gross national product had risen 4.8 percent in the last quarter of 1987, as ``more good news on the economic front. ... the economy is doing well. the reagan miracle holds.''
so far this year, consumer prices have been increasing at a rate of 3.2 percent. that compares to the moderate 4.4 percent rate for all of 1987 and the scant 1.1 percent 1986 increase
some economists suggested that last month's moderate food and energy cost hikes may be masking hefty increases for other goods and services
subtracting these two volatile categories, however, the index for all other goods and services also advanced 0.2 percent in february after a 0.5 percent increase in january, when prices overall rose 0.3 percent
a restrained consumer price index had been expected since the labor department reported that the companion producer price index, also restrained by moderating energy and food prices, had dipped 0.2 percent in february
the department gave these other specifics on february retail price activity:
_grocery store prices fell 0.6 percent after a 0.2 percent rise in the previous month; restaurant meals were up 0.3 percent, the same as in january
pacing the drop in food prices was a 4.0 percent fall in the costs of fruits and vegetables, more than offsetting 0.4 percent rise for meats, poultry and fish
_gasoline prices fell 1.7 percent, down for the third month in a row. gasoline prices had fallen 1.7 percent in december and 1.6 percent in january
_heating oil prices were up 0.6 percent while the cost of natural gas and electricity rose 0.5 percent
_new automobile prices rose 0.3 percent
_clothing prices fell 0.3 percent
_alchoholic beverage prices rose 0.9 percent
last month's 0.2 percent gain was equivalent to an annual inflation rate of 2.1 percent
the february increase left the overall index at 116.0, meaning that a hypothetical selection of goods costing $100 during a 1982-84 base period would have cost $116.00 last month
unlike other figures in the report, the overall index is not adjusted for seasonal fluctuations
the labor department recently changed its base period. had the former computation been used, the february consumer price index would have been 347.4 compared to a 1967 base of 100
that means that the same selection of goods would have cost $13.00 more last month than in february 1987, when the cpi was 334.4
unexpectedly brisk economic activity is raising some economists' concerns that inflation may pick up in the months ahead, particularly as import prices rise further under pressure from a dollar that is now 50 percent weaker against key foreign currencies than it was three years ago
a weaker dollar makes imports more expensive. higher prices, particularly for japanese and european products, have been noticed on store shelves in recent months as a result of these exchange-rate movements
this is good for the u.s. trade deficit, because as imports get more expensive u.s. goods become cheaper and more competitive overseas. but analysts have long warned that any sustained increase in import prices could fuel overall higher inflation
adding to worries about inflation was the february unemployment report, showing that the jobless rate fell to 5.7 percent, the best performance since l979
as unemployment declines below a certain level, pressure builds for higher wages to fill vacant jobs. economists disagree on the exact level
federal reserve board chairman alan greenspan told congress last week that he felt that inflation could be rekindled if unemployment fell another 0.5 percentage points
i don't think inflation will be a problem probably for the whole year, but the bond markets are worried,'' said michael k. evans, president of a private economic consulting service. up 3rd graf pvs, mackay said.</note>
the reagan administration and house speaker jim wright said today reports of progress at cease-fire talks in nicaragua are encouraging, and democratic leaders said agreement there likely would trigger a new package of strictly ``humanitarian'' aid for the contra rebels
we want to be cautious but we are encouraged (by the talks),'' said white house spokesman marlin fitzwater. ``they do seem to be making progress,'' he said, adding that was ``somewhat surprising'' in view of previous actions by the sandinistas
we hope these talks succeed,'' fitzwater said
it is my earnest hope that we can obtain a bipartisan agreement on humanitarian aid so that the bill can be scheduled quickly,'' wright, d-texas, told reporters. ``that is the best way to encourage the peacemakers in central america.''
house majority whip tony coelho, d-calif., said such a bill could be approved next week if the cease-fire talks, in their third day in sapoa, nicaragua, bear fruit, and if aid would be consistent with whatever agreement is reached by the contras and the managua government
senate majority leader robert byrd, d-w.va., said it was time that there be ``a ceasefire between the congress and the white house'' on the issue, but said he had no plans to bring an aid bill before the senate
wright indicated that an aid proposal being advanced by rep. buddy mackay, d-fla., one of the ``swing'' votes on the contra issue, would likely be acceptable to house leaders
mackay said he and other centrist house members who have traditionally determined the outcome on the polarized issue of aid to the rebels were left skittish by last week's incursion of nicaraguan troops into neighboring honduras in an effort to attack contra supply camps
it had an impact on all of us,'' mackay said in an interview tuesday. the sandinista military action on the eve of renewed cease-fire talks with the contras was a reminder that ``relying on their good faith is just not realistic,'' mackay added
all we are trying to say is that leaving the situation as it is is unacceptable,'' he said
the compromise bill, still being drafted tuesday, was similar to a package put together last week by senate backers of the rebels. it contained a one-year, $48 million infusion of ``humanitarian'' aid, to include food, clothing, shelter and medicine. it also would authorize the central intelligence agency to deliver existing supplies of weapons
but in contrast to the senate version, mackay's would permit president reagan to call for an expedited vote on new aid for the rebels if peace talks break down, but not to dictate the terms of the aid package. it would be up to congress to decide what kind of aid to send, he said
mackay said he expected to formally introduce the package this week and hoped to have about half a dozen other moderates join him
he said the effort is not intended to be a challenge to house speaker jim wright, d-texas. republicans have accused wright of using his scheduling powers to bottle up any aid bill that goes beyond a strictly humanitarian package democrats offered earlier this month, but which was defeated
president reagan on tuesday appealed to house republicans in a closed-door meeting to unite behind a new aid bill, but did not specify which provisions he would support
we are determined to get continued assistance to the resistance, and if we stick together, this time we'll make it,'' reagan told the lawmakers, according to a white house transcript. he also said democrats would be to blame if the contras ``are extinguished'' by the leftist nicaraguan government
democrats insisted the republicans were responsible for the narrow house defeat of a package of strictly ``humanitarian'' aid on march 3
what we're seeing is a public relations campaign here,'' said rep. tony coelho, d-calif. ``the republicans are very nervous about it because the finger's pointed right at them.''
a poll published in today's editions of the washington post found that 40 percent of the people surveyed support aid to the contras, while 56 percent oppose it. the support figure in the washington post-abc news poll is the highest since 43 percent on july 15, 1987, a day after lt. col. oliver north, the indicted former white house aide, testified before a congressional committee
the survey, completed monday, also found 55 percent to 43 percent disapproval of reagan's decision to send the troops to honduras. pollsters interviewed 1,007 randomly chosen adults in the continental united states by telephone. the poll had a margin of error of 4 points
the rebels released a television advertisement to begin airing this week that makes a direct appeal to u.s. viewers for contributions
your congress abandoned us,'' ernesto palazio, a washington lobbyist for the rebels, says somberly in the spot. ``we have nowhere to turn but to individual americans like you.''
the spot, which asks for money for ``medicine, blankets and food for our families and children,'' was to begin running this week in washington, charlotte, n.c., and wright's home town of fort worth, texas
the chief of security for a medellin newspaper that has fought drug trafficking was shot and killed today and his young daughter was wounded, police said
el colombiano security chief, jorge alberto stefan gomez, was leaving his house with his wife and child when several gunmen in parked cars opened fire with pistols and submachine guns
investigators said stefan's wife was not injured and that they did not know who was behind the attack
on tuesday, troops trying to arrest an alleged drug kingpin tripped a sophisticated alarm system at a country estate and the man got away
the army said pablo escobar gaviria escaped after a shootout in which one man, thought to be one of escobar's bodyguards, was injured
escobar, wanted in the united states on drug charges, is an alleged leader of the notorious medellin drug cartel and reportedly a billionaire
the u.s. drug enforcement administration says the cartel is responsible for 80 percent of the cocaine that reaches the united states
at least 25 of escobar's heaviy armed bodyguards were arrested after the clash and 13 vehicles, various firearms, ammunition, communications equipment and documents seized, the army said in a communique
escobar's wife, maria victoria, and her sister were arrested elsewhere in medellin carrying ``several documents of interest,'' the army said
escobar was indicted in 1986 on federal drug charges in the united states. last month, another u.s. drug indictment named him along with panamanian strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega and 14 others
colombia's justice ministry in january ordered the arrest of escobar and others named as cartel leaders for extradition to the united states
since then no cartel leader has been arrested
the newspaper el colombiano has urged the colombian government to pursue its war on drug traffickers. medellin, the cocaine capital of colombia, is where many drug traffickers live. it is also the site of cocaine processing plants
on march 10 two bombs were thrown from a speeding car at the newspaper's offices. a guard threw the bombs into the street and a passer-by was killed
last november gunmen shot up the home of el colombiano's publisher, juan gomez martinez. the gunmen apparently were trying to kidnap gomez to get the government to suspend extraditions of colombians to the united states
drug traffickers have killed a justice minister, an attorney general, 21 judges, two newspaper editors and scores of policemen and soldiers in the last four years
president reagan will travel to richmond, va., to tour a reynolds metals plant next monday, speak to employees and attend a republican party fund-raiser, the white house said today
chief spokesman marlin fitzwater said reagan will fly to richmond for the series of events, inlcuding a speech to the reynolds employees
fitzwater said reynolds is a good example of a company that has had ``success as an exporter'' and reagan would emphasize in his talk the emergence of an international economy and the u.s. role in it
aside from his appearance at the reynolds headquarters, reagan also will attend a reception for major donors to the virginia republican party at the hyatt richmond hotel nearby
reagan will be in the city about 2{ hours before returning to the white house
an avalanche that plunged down on a helicopter skiing expedition left one skier dead, but an expedition guide was rescued after being buried under snow for nearly 90 minutes, authorities said
pandora chapman, 26, of davis, calif., died in avalanches on sale mountain near this southeastern british columbia community tuesday, said coroner sam olynyk
it was the second fatality this year involving selkirk tangiers heli-skiing, based in golden, british columbia
guide erik suchovs of revelstoke skied ahead of his party and was buried by an avalanche
the three skiers skied down to locate him and another avalanche came down behind them,'' olynyk said. chapman was buried, and the other two skiers were partly buried
suchovs was uncovered by searchers using emergency radio locators. according to queen victoria hospital administrator jim vaillancourt, suchovs was in good shape and was treated and released
the two surviving skiers, a california man and a woman from revelstoke, were also treated and released
jim bay, an avalanche technician with the highways ministry, said the avalanche occurred because ``basically, the snow of the past three or four days didn't bond to the surface.''
since 1972, 29 people have died while heli-skiing in british columbia. heli-skiers are taken to areas of deep powder snow accessible mainly by helicopter, allowing them to ski untouched areas
alma archer fox, a well-known authority on fashion, style and taste during her career as a syndicated columnist with the new york mirror, has died. she was 89
the galesburg native, who died tuesday, was a 1919 graduate of knox college in galesburg and landed her first fashion job in los angeles where she designed custom-made cadillacs
ms. fox moved to new york in 1924 where she ran a charm school on fifth avenue and became a columnist. highlights of her career included interviewing adolf hitler, drinking with ernest hemingway in paris and sailing south of france with james joyce
in 1937, at the height of her popularity, ms. fox was featured in a full-page ad in the saturday evening post promoting chrysler automobiles and proclaiming her ``one of the world's great authorities on style and smartness.''
she was editor of the women's section of the new york mirror and her column on fashion and style was syndicated by the united press association to more than 1,100 newspapers
ms. fox was married to broadway composer harry archer and later to t. edward fox. she returned to galesburg in 1959 following her second husband's death and wrote a weekly column for the galesburg post until her retirement in 1983
ms. fox, who died of pneumonia in a nursing home, is survived by two nephews.  up 9th graf, `the indictment ...' ^by wendy mitman</note>
a man whose ex-wife went to jail rather than let him see their children surrendered to authorities today after being indicted on a charge of sexually assaulting his daughter
mark russell murabito, 33, of derry, was awaiting arraignment in rockingham county superior court after turning himself in to the county sheriff
a grand jury indicted murabito on a charge of felonious sexual assault against his daughter, now 5 years old, county attorney carleton eldredge said tuesday
eldredge said the indictment was ``based upon a course of conduct'' since march 1987, when a superior court judge found no evidence to back jesse murabito's allegations that her husband molested their daughter
eldredge did not elaborate on the indictment. as a condition of bail, eldredge said he will ask that murabito be barred from seeing his children
in his 19-page divorce decree last march, judge douglas gray admonished both parents to stop ``tearing (the children) to pieces,'' and granted murabito unsupervised visitation with the girl and her brother, now 3{
murabito's lawyer, raymond kellett, said tuesday his client will plead innocent to any such charges. ``it is evident that (mrs. murabito) will do anything and everything to keep the children from mr. murabito,'' kellett said
mrs. murabito said tuesday the case ``is not murabito versus murabito. this is the state of new hampshire versus mr. murabito.'' she declined further comment
the indictment is a turning point in mrs. murabito's nearly two-year struggle to convince the courts and child welfare officials that her ex-husband was molesting their daughter
gray could not be reached for comment tuesday evening; there was no home telephone listing in new hampshire under his name
in february 1987, gray jailed mrs. murabito, now 39, after she hid the children in defiance of a court order to let her husband see the children during supervised visits
a week later, he released her after she agreed to allow supervised visits pending a hearing
in the subsequent order of march 20, 1987, in which murabito was granted unsupervised visits, gray said mrs. murabito and experts she called as witnesses during a seven-day hearing had failed to prove allegations that murabito sexually abused the daughter after mrs. murabito sought a divorce in late 1985
of course the possibility exists that the court is wrong, but that possibility exists in any judicial fact-finding process,'' gray wrote, but to uphold the abuse allegations ``would be to engage in blatant speculation.''
gray said mrs. murabito's chief witness, the children's psychiatrist since spring 1986, based many of her assertions on hearsay. mrs. murabito had said she contacted the psychiatrist when she noticed the children were losing sleep and weight and becoming irritable
gray cited an evaluation of the children by a court-appointed psychologist as ``by far the more clinically neutral and detached.''
the psychologist found no evidence of sexual abuse and said actions by the father that had been construed by others as abuse could be interpreted otherwise
the reagan administration today condemned the reported use of chemical weapons by iraq that iran says killed or wounded 5,000 people in kurdish border cities last week
we condemn the use of chemical warfare and the gas use by anybody, anywhere, anytime,'' said white house spokesman marlin fitzwater
referring to television broadcasts, fitzwater said, ``i saw _ everyone in the administration saw _ the same reports you saw last night. they were horrible, outrageous, disgusting and should serve as a reminder to all countries of why chemical warfare should be banned.''
asked if the united states would convey its reaction to baghdad, he said, ``our views are known ... to all governments.''
meanwhile, the international committee of the red cross also condemned the use of chemical weapons in the 7{-year-old iran-iraq war, calling it a ``new and tragic escalation'' of the conflict, and said it had taken urgent steps to end such attacks. addressing aremenian demands. picks up 2nd graf, `alexander ogorodnikov ...' edits to tighten.</note>
the soviet government today ignored armenian demands for annexation of a predominantly armenian section of a neighboring republic and called for efforts to improve social and economic conditions in the area
a session of the presidium of the national supreme soviet, called after carefully orchestrated appeals by 13 soviet republics, made no reference to the armenian demands
the resolution today appeared to be a definitive response from the kremlin leadership to the demands regarding the nagorno-karabakh region of the republic of azerbaijan
armenian activists want the region united with armenia
the presidium ordered the soviet council of ministers to ``work out all measures directed at deciding the immediate economic and social-cultural development of the nagorno-karabakh autonomous region.''
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev and other top leaders participated in the meeting. it called on officials of armenian and azerbaijan to bring to ``strict accountability those who with their actions destabilized the situation.''
that statement appeared to indicate authorities would take action not only against those who have been arrested for violence in ethnic rioting that killed at least 32 people, but also armenian activists
earlier, a moscow dissident said soviet authorities had sent back to armenia an activist who had been giving foreign journalists information about the ethnic unrest between aremanians and azerbaijanis
alexander ogorodnikov, a former political prisoner, said armenian nationalist paryur arikyan was put on a plane for yerevan, the armenian capital, at 1:30 a.m
he said calls to armenian activists in yerevan today indicated that arikyan had arrived from moscow
another dissident source, tamara grigoryants, told the associated press on tuesday that police arrested arikyan in central moscow after he met with a western television journalist
thousands of armenians protested last month for approval to annex nagorno-karabakh
on feb. 28 rioting broke out in sumgait, a city of azerbaijan, in which officials say 32 people were killed
armenian activists say at least 78 armenians were killed by azerbaijanis in sumgait
arikyan, who said he spent 17 years in jail for armenian nationalist activities, arrived in moscow from yerevan last week and held news conferences for foreign journalists at ogorodnikov's apartment
he said saturday that officials had confiscated his internal passport, so he had traveled to moscow via soviet georgia and the russian city of tula to escape detection
the tass news agency, meanwhile, announced the governments of 13 soviet republics had addressed the violence in the republics of armenia and azerbaijan
tass said the supreme soviets of kazakhstan, lithuania, moldavia, latvia, kirghizia, tadzhikistan, turkmenia and estonia passed resolutions calling for ``discretion and composure, and at the same time for issuing a decisive rebuff to any illegitimate actions.''
that followed a tass report tuesday that the russian federation, and the republics of ukraine, byelorussia, georgia and uzbekistan had passed similar resolutions and urged the national supreme soviet to take action
such concerted action by those 13 republics, equal under the soviet constitution to armenia and azerbaijan, was very unusual and almost certainly orchestrated by communist party authorities
the government calls for action also came as the communist party newspaper pravda and the government newspaper, izvestia, ran articles sharply criticizing armenian activists
pravda's article monday charging that the annexation campaign had a ``clear anti-socialist spirit'' sparked a protest in yerevan. the pravda journalist whose name was one of three attached to the article disassociated himself from it in a telegram to the paper's editor
a fugitive wanted in the poisoning death of a las vegas beauty contest winner was arrested here, authorities said today
murray police sgt. bill brusik said steven paul mack was taken into custody about 10 p.m. tuesday after police stopped him in his car about half a mile from his home in this salt lake city suburb
mack, a convicted forger and burglar who served two prison terms and was paroled in 1985, was being held without bail today in salt lake county jail on a felony homicide warrant issued in sacramento, calif
brusik said sacramento detectives were expected to arrive today to question mack and begin extradition proceedings
mack, 39, is sought for questioning in the february 1987 slaying of karen grace winslett, 21, of carmichael, calif. winslett won the title of miss english leather in las vegas, nev., shortly before disappearing feb. 19
her decomposed body was found 12 days later hidden under the rear hatchback door of her sports car, parked behind a sacramento motel
sacramento detectives said she died of a large dose of percodan, a pain killer for which winslett had no prescription. she had no health problems, was not suicidal and had no background of drug abuse, authorities said
detectives concluded she had been poisoned, and said mack was linked to the crime by physical and other evidence they would not detail
sacramento police also said mack is a suspect in a similar slaying of a 19-year-old annette huddle in marion county, ohio
brusik said police discovered mack's identity during an unrelated forgery investigation involving sean paul lanier, the name mack purportedly used for the four or five months he had been living in murray
the senate refused today to limit debate on a bill that would require the government to individually warn thousands of workers each year that they face a high risk of cancer and other diseases from exposure to dangerous chemicals and other substances in their jobs
in a key test vote, democratic supporters of the house-passed legislation could muster only 33 of the 60 senate votes necessary to limit debate on the measure to 30 hours before an up-or-down vote on its passage
sen. howard metzenbaum, d-ohio, the primary senate author of the legislation, offered today to accept amendments expanding exemptions for small businesses and farms in an effort to pick up more support in anticipation of another vote scheduled friday on cutting off debate
the bill's proponents had filed motions to limit the debate as soon the measure was brought to the senate floor on tuesday after republican and business opponents made it clear they would try to prevent a vote on the bill itself through the use of a filibuster
ending a filibuster requires 60 votes while final passage of a bill requires only a simple majority, or 51 votes if all 100 senators are present
sen. orrin hatch, r-utah, the leader of the opponents, said metzenbaum's willingness ``to whittle the bill down until he gets engouh votes to pass it'' demonstrates the problems with the legislation
if it's good enough for one, it's good enough for all,'' hatch said. ``the overwhelming majority of the business community opposes this bill.'' business groups that support it, hatch said, ``have worked out exemptions for themselves to the exclusion of everybody else.''
among the business supporters of the bill are the chemical manufacturers association, the american electronics association and dozens of the nation's largest companies, including general electric, ibm and atlantic richfield. most already have their own worker notification programs
opponents include the reagan administration, the national association of manufacturers and the u.s. chamber of commerce
the bill would establish an agency in the department of health and human services to determine which workers are most at risk. the national institute of occupational safety and health would then be required to send individual notices to between 100,000 and 300,000 of them every year and employers would be required to provide medical monitoring programs for them
the national association of manufacturers and other opponents claim that the monitoring programs and the possibility of subsequent lawsuits by workers and former workers against their employers could cost businesses up to $6 billion a year
here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout the nation
march 17
roswell (n.m.) daily record on u.s. involvement in central america:
liberal congressmen are obsessively fond of comparing u.s. involvement in central america with what later developed into the vietnam war
the trouble is, their comparison is with the wrong war
double-dealing by nicaragua's sandinista government along with house leaders' blindness to the reality of the central american conflict is more reminiscent of the preliminaries to world war ii
like the sandinistas now, nazi germany claimed it supported peace, while working feverishly for war and conquest
the united states is not facing ``another vietnam'' by giving assistance to its contra allies, it faces far worse if it doesn't
march 19
the kennebec journal, augusta, maine, on sending u.s. troops into honduras:
keeping the contras in the field, if not in nicaragua, seems to be the basis for the $48 million emergency aid package introduced ... (march 18) in congress. only two weeks ago congress couldn't even agree on a $30 million ``humanitarian'' aid bill
the sandinista raid (into honduras) will probably turn around that vote in short order
daniel ortega has a history of snatching diplomatic defeat from the jaws of victory. after a previous contra aid vote, he flew off to moscow; this time he decided on military action. ..
but president reagan won't get a free ride. just by dispatching 3,200 troops to honduras, 100 miles from the war zone, he ignited what may be the largest anti-war protests since vietnam. ..
march 16
nashville (tenn.) banner on the hostages in lebanon:
in vivid contrast to the situation in 1980 when 52 american hostages were being held in iran, little is heard these days about the hostages being held in lebanon
the hostages are rarely allowed to communicate with the outside world, and their captors, believed to be moslem fundamentalists, rarely come out of the shadows
the hostages in iran were freed after 444 days. but one of the lebanon hostages _ associated press newsman terry anderson _ has now been held for a full three years. ..
anderson isn't the only victim of lebanese kidnappers. but he is the longest held of about two dozen westerners missing in beirut
and he was there because his job was to tell u.s. newspaper readers what was happening in that tortured country
march 18
westerly (r.i.) sun on toy guns that look real:
handguns, both fake and real ones, are sources of concern in what still seems to be a trigger-happy society ... given the shocking homicide rate in this supposedly law-respecting country
san francisco's city supervisors, following the lead of los angeles, have just banned the sale of toy guns not easily distinguishable from those they imitate
san francisco's action came after police, fearing for their lives when a mentally retarded boy pointed a real-looking pistol at them, shot and killed the boy. ..
there is no justification for the manufacturers to continue putting on the market accurate toy replicas of lethal weapons
it is folly ... to tolerate the manufacture and sale of toys that can easily be mistaken for real weapons, sometimes with tragic consequences
march 21
tulsa (okla.) world on irs penalties:
a horror story about the internal revenue service assessing a $400 penalty against a small businessman who paid two cents less than he owed has rightly outraged the public
but the nation's chief tax collector, irs commissioner lawrence b. gibbs, offers a different perspective, one that clearly shows congress to be the source of a lot of the troubles between the irs and taxpayers
the tax code now includes 154 statutory penalties, he told congressional investigators, noting that congress has changed the tax code seven times in the last 10 years and enacted ``a seemingly endless array of ad hoc penalties.''
gibbs, in trying to carry out an unpopular job, knows that the whole system depends on public confidence ... and that wholesale stupidness on the part of congress is quickly eroding that confidence
it's enough to make one sympathize with the irs
march 16
east oregonian, pendleton, ore., on running for president:
it's time teacher-researchers, voter organizations and citizens in general tried to figure out why so many of the brightest americans are refusing to run for office..
politics and politicians have picked up rotten reputations. that stems partly from the watergate era, the trauma of the vietnam era and various investigations and charges against public officials
and it results in part from journalists' digging, reporting and commentary on those cases
lots of potentially strong public officials want to avoid putting themselves and their families in the glare of publicity
march 18
the seattle post-intelligencer on iran-contra indictments:
the indictments of the principals in the iran-contra affair are heartening evidence that the judicial system is working properly
this is a country based on the rule of law. democracy cannot survive if it accommodates those who put themselves above the law. corruption in government, even for an avowed noble purpose, cannot be tolerated
that's why those charged should stand trial to have their guilt or innocence determined. ..
it should be kept in mind in the months ahead that at issue here is not the political question of what ought to be the proper role of the united states in nicaragua. the question is whether these men broke the law
obtaining a judicial answer to this question is important for the spiritual health of the country, which depends on the faith of its citizens in the rule of law
march 21
the baltimore sun on iran-contra pardons:
shredders, obstruction of justice, contempt for routine governmental and political processes, lots of money, colorful characters, white house involvement, special prosecutor, multiple indictments. ..
if it all sounds familiar, that's because it is. the iran-contra affair is a repeat in many ways of the watergate scandal of the 1970s. ..
just as in watergate, the question of pardons is central to the outcome of this drama
as a general rule, we don't believe pardons ought to be granted or even discussed before guilt or innocence has been established in the courts. but the general rule doesn't apply here. the question of pardons needs some public discussion
the guilt or innocence of adm. john poindexter, lt. col. oliver north, general richard secord and albert hakim probably cannot be decided until after president reagan leaves office. ..
reagan should not pardon these men before trial, even though he sympathizes with them and had a lot to do with their troubles
march 18
the record, hackensack, n.j., on sending u.s. troops into honduras:
president reagan's emergency airlift of 3,200 troops in response to a supposed nicaraguan incursion into honduras is an example of an administration driven to desperation as a result of its inability to win additional aid for the contras
at best, the airlift is a splashy way of stampeding congress into voting the rebels additional military aid. if so, it would seem to run counter to the prevailing viewpoint of most americans as well as congress
the plain fact is that the white house's nicaraguan policy has failed, the victim of scandals, ineptitude and miscalculation, and it will take more than a war scare to bring it back to life
instead of a military drive, this seemed to be a time for holding the line, and reducing to a minimun the chances of added hostilities
march 17
charleston (w.va.) daily mail on mandatory use of seat belts:
the (west virginia) legislature has made the use of seat belts mandatory. it's the wrong idea, done the wrong way for the wrong reason
yes, everyone should wear seat belts when driving. but it is outrageous to have government decree such behavior
first, there's the approach itself. lawmakers are using another one of those rankling $25 fines to get their way
a more appropriate method would be to lower the amount of damages that juries award injured parties who were not wearing seat belts when they were involved in an accident
the motive was also wrong. lawmakers were pushed to pass the bill on grounds that it would help stop the u.s. department of transportation from requiring air bags on cars
ironically, west virginia's law contains exemptions which keep it from complying with the federal criteria for such laws
the state's new seat belt law may make lawmakers feel good. but as a practical piece of legislation, it's a dismal failure
march 18
marietta (ga.) daily journal on aid to the contras:
there is no joy in being able to say ``we told you so'' regarding aid to the nicaraguan contras when the criminal misjudgment of congress may cost us thousands of american lives
when the vote on military aid for the contra rebels fighting to overthrow the illegal marxist government in nicaragua came up last month, we argued that daniel ortega's recent peaceful overtures were merely for show, and that if congress cut off military assistance to the rebels, ortega would quickly resume his warring ways and attempt to wipe out the relatively defenseless rebels
the sandinistas have now begun to do just that
amazingly, many liberals in congress have refused to recognize that the man who they thought was their friend, ortega, has sold them down the river
they cannot see that they have been used as pawns by an avowed communist who exploited their weaknesses to achieve a military advantage
march 17
owatonna (minn.) people's press on the iran-contra indictments:
since the iran-contra scandal broke nearly one and a half years ago, president reagan has declined to answer questions about the possibilities of pardons, should those involved be convicted of crimes
while reagan's reaction to the indictments (issued last week against former national security adviser john poindexer, lt. col. oliver north, retired air force maj. gen. richard secord and businessman albert hakim) and questions about the possibilities of pardons are of immediate concern, so, too, are the thoughts of those seeking election to the office of the presidency
if reagan delays a decision on pardons, which he may grant prior to any convictions, the next person elected president of this nation may well face the decision
the indictments and the possibility of pardons have heightened the importance of the iran-contra scandal as a campaign issue
now more than ever, the american public needs some answers from the candidates, including vice president george bush
march 20
observer-reporter, washington, pa., on money for the poor:
if the united states took all the money spent each year on anti-poverty programs _ about $130 billion _ and divided it by the number of americans categorized by government as poor _ about 32 million, each poor person would receive over $4,000; each family of four over $16,000
even if we subtracted a reasonable amount for administrative costs, there would still be more than enough to lift all welfare families above the poverty-income threshold _ $11,202 for a family of four in 1986
march 18
the riverside (calif.) press-enterprise on the situation in panama:
the reagan administration cuts off aid and payment of canal fees to panama, and suddenly the rule of strongman manuel noriega is being challenged, openly and violently, in the streets by his own people
there is a temptation to say that the white house finally found the right button to push to get a rebellion started, but ... that interpretation is too simplistic by far. ..
the banks of panama have been closed for days, they aren't expected to reopen soon. a canal fee payment, due (last) week from the united states, is not in the mail. that's a $6.5 million shortfall right there. ..
it's a lot, but a ruler who had the support of his people could weather that much and more. but the fact is, the first demonstrations against the noriega regime occurred in panama city's streets last summer. ..
in the year of costa rica president oscar arias' nobel peace prize for his regional peace plan, there is even less of that commodity in central america than usual. ..
as for the people of panama, they can concentrate on the one problem at hand _ and it looks increasingly as if they aim to do that, for as long as it takes
march 22
st. louis post-dispatch on the balance of trade:
for america to seek an actual trade surplus is probably unwise
if the united states were to run a surplus, most of its trading partners would have to run deficits, and the majority of these nations' economies are neither large enough nor rich enough to afford them
while the u.s. economy continues to grow, even if slowly, europe's economies remain largely stagnant
perhaps japan could survive a trade deficit for a time, but south korea, hong kong, taiwan and singapore _ known as the four asian ``tigers'' _ could not, for the same reasons as the europeans. `the stumbling ...' inserts x grafs after 12th graf, `in other . ..,' to update with comment from white house. picks up 13th graf, `the sandinista ...' edits to tighten.</note>
sandinista and contra rebel negotiators resumed their cease-fire talks today closer than ever to reaching agreement on steps to end nicaragua's six-year war
but, as the two sides entered the third session of talks, the state-run voice of nicaragua radio reported a contra violation of the truce agreed on for the talks' duration
the broadcast said the u.s.-backed rebels ambushed an army truck near mulukuku in the northern province of matagalpa at 2 p.m. tuesday, killing two soldiers
bosco matamoros, a spokesman for the rebels, told reporters that ``there could be isolated cases, but there is a clear will from both sides to respect that decision (for a truce).''
a defense ministry spokesman in managua, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said, ``we have no information about (the report), but we will see if we can confirm it.''
the main stumbling blocks facing the third round of talks appeared to center on the mechanics of how the contras would lay down their arms and be granted amnesty. on tuesday, both sides exchanged proposals that agree on major points
defense minister humberto ortega, who heads the government delegation, said today that he was optimistic there would be success in today's talks
tuesday, he said he expected a ``concrete agreement'' to emerge from the discussions. but sources close to the talks cautioned that they could still stall on final details. one source said the talks could continue beyond today
it is like a boxing match,'' a sandinista official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said tuesday. ``they were tense (monday) and they had some sparring (tuesday).''
adolfo calero, political leader of the u.s.-supported contras, described the second round of talks as ``direct and frank.''
the two sides stood far apart at the start of the talks, which opened monday at this border post 90 miles south of managua and which represented the government and rebel leaders' first face-to-face meeting in nicaragua. a battlefield truce that began monday appeared to be holding
in other developments, a pentagon source said today american troops are expected to return home monday and tuesday following emergency training exercises in honduras
and white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said u.s. troops should begin their withdrawal ``over the weekend.''
fitzwater also expressed cautious optimism about the talks
they do seem to be making progress,'' he said, adding that it was ``somewhat surprising'' in view of previous actions by the sandinistas
the sandinista proposal, outlined by deputy foreign minister victor hugo tinoco on tuesday, calls for a truce of up to 90 days during which the contras would lay down their weapons and join a ``national reconciliation dialogue.''
for every rebel who stops fighting, the government would release a political prisoner the sandinistas consider eligible for release. the government is holding an estimated 3,300 political prisoners
contrary to previous sandinista demands, tinoco said rebels who put down their arms would be free from prosecution without applying for amnesty and could take part in nicaraguan political life
they would be permitted to operate uncensored newspapers, magazines and radio stations, but television would remain a government monopoly. many press liberties were barred for almost six years under a state-of-emergency decree
the contra proposal calls for a 45-day cease-fire and would provide for zones to be set up for the estimated 10,000 contra combatants to gather while a permanent truce is negotiated
it does not mention when the rebels would be willing to give up their arms
the proposal calls for total amnesty, return of political exiles, full press freedoms, a suspension of the military draft during the truce and incorporation of contra representatives into the national dialogue process
the sandinistas called for an international commission to verify an end to hostilities, which the government says have claimed 26,500 lives since 1981
the sandinistas, according to sources who demanded anonymity, also want the contras to be more specific about a final cease-fire. the government also would not be expected to give in readily to the contra demand for suspending the draft during a truce or for an immediate, total amnesty
a national dialogue as well as the cease-fire are included in the regional peace plan signed aug. 7 by the presidents of nicaragua, el salvador, costa rica, guatemla and honduras
that plan also calls for greater democracy and an end to foreign aid to insurgents and the use of one country's territory for attacks on another
a teen-ager was given a suspended death sentence and six classmates received prison terms ranging from two years to life for the stabbing death of a college student, an official newspaper reported tuesday
the beijing daily said the seven, all 17- and 18-year-old students from a technical school, were convicted monday of involvement in the dec. 2 slaying of zhang han, a student from beijing normal university
the report said the seven ran out of their dormitory and attacked zhang and others with bricks and knives after hearing people outside shouting insulting remarks. it was not clear if zhang was among the shouters
dong qiufei, identified as the assailant who stabbed zhang, received a death sentence with a two-year reprieve. that means the sentence will be changed to life imprisonment if he shows a good attitude in the next two years
long kaiyuan, who had a criminal record for thefts, was convicted of hooliganism and sentenced to life in prison. the other five received terms ranging from two to 10 years
zhang was among three college students murdered in brawls in december
land reform, the issue that helped trigger a 1973 military coup, has disappeared from the country's political agenda as effectively as the horse-drawn plow from the fields
experts say the country's ranks of landless peasants remain swollen and may be worse off than they were a decade or two ago. but social and economic changes have dulled their once-fierce thirst for their own acre to till
the loss of priority is evident in declarations by civilian politicians pressing for an end to the 14-year-old military government of president augusto pinochet. no longer do they cry out for expropriation of large land holdings for distribution among the poor _ a call that once chilled the blood of wealthy farmers and ranchers
a recent 91-page proposal by six opposition groups for a transitional government to restore democracy contained not a word on the issue. ``there will be no land reform'' during any such transition, patricio aylwin, president of the christian democratic party, told reporters
the young are calling for a well-paid job rather than for land,'' said emiliano ortega, a santiago-based agronomist and social scientists. ``they remember the experience of their fathers, who lost their land.''
the issue of land reform began sweeping latin america in the 1950s and 1960. in chile it reached its peak under the government of president salvador allende, a marxist elected in 1970. his adminstration expropriated about 16 million acres for distribution among 60,000 peasant families. some farms were directly seized by leftist groups
the upheaval helped trigger a 1973 coup that installed pinochet, commander of the army and a fierce anti-communist
pinochet quickly gave back more than half the expropriated land to its original owners or new farming companies, and tens of thousands of peasants were booted off their newly acquired plots. powerful peasant organizations, often aligned with the political left, were dismantled
a free-market economic program was launched, stressing agricultural exports. to compete in world markets, farmers were pushed to modernize with costly tractors and other machinery, fertilizers and insecticides. many made the expensive switch from traditional crops such as wheat and corn to more profitable products, especially fruit
the result has been an extraordinary agricultural boom, with production up by about half overall and annual exports soaring from about $20 million in the early 1970s to more than $500 million now
but the peasants found themselves without a secure role. the land reform efforts and ensuing modernization destroyed the traditional ``hacienda'' system, under which peasants worked as tenant farmers or farmhands with free housing. in addition, many peasants who did receive land found competition too costly and sold their plots
tens of thousands turned to seasonal and migrant labor, working eight to 16 hours a day for a monthly salary equivalent to less than $100, said solidarity, a church-sponsored magazine on human rights and issues. ``the peasant became just another laborer.''
ortega said that as a result of the changes, the peasant of the 1980s is more interested in his paycheck and working conditions than in being given land he can't afford to cultivate
there's been a very strong cultural change and a strong change in labor relations,'' he said. ``it's not going to be like in the past.''
before, peasants lived for generations on the land. now they don't, they don't live within the farms. thus, they don't identify themselves as much with a piece of land.''
ortega estimated the number of seasonal farm laborers at about 300,000 and said they will represent a powerful political force if given the opportunity to organize
people outraged over a protest group's announced plan to burn a puppy to demonstrate the brutality of war in nicaragua today flooded a radio station and the county humane society with calls
the dane county humane society office logged at least 30 phone calls in the first hour it was open from people opposing plans announced tuesday by david read, founder of the nihilist workers party, an animal shelter official said
the whole thing is we want to put people in touch with the worst feelings they've ever had,'' said read, 26, a university of wisconsin-madison philosophy student. ``i think this is really brilliant because it will hit a raw nerve with people.''
we're going to prevent it as best we can,'' mary collins, shelter manager, said today
humane society officials were meeting with the state humane officer to see what could be done and were recording the names and addresses of callers ``in case we need bodies to protest his protest,'' collins said
read's telephone number was busy this morning. collins said shelter officials had been giving it to callers, suggesting they contact read
some of the callers had suggested read set himself on fire, she said. callers to wiva-fm in madison suggested read should either burn himself or go fight in the war himself instead of torturing a puppy.police said harming the animal could lead to an arrest
shelter officials cannot confiscate the animal, even if they knew where it was, on the basis of a threat to burn it next week, collins said
read said war has become normal in our society and he wants to demonstrate its brutality by dousing the puppy with gasoline and burning it next tuesday on campus. if police or spectators try to stop the effort, read said, it will kill the puppy somewhere else
read said he fully expects to be arrested and jailed and to be criticized
we're going to be recruiting a lit of a goon squad for protection,'' read said. ``let's face it, people are going to try to stop us.''
he said the 10-week-old dog, which he described as a mutt, was being held at an undisclosed location outside madison
read said he and a friend organized the nihilist workers party in madison in 1986 to spread the doctrine of nihilism, a belief that existing social, political and economic institutions must be destroyed in order to make way for new institutions. read</head>
the education department on wednesday released a booklet with tips for parents who want to help their children read but may not know the best way to go about it
the surest prevention of illiteracy is making sure kids know how to read,'' chester e. finn jr., assistant education secretary for research and improvement, said in unveiling the 29-page booklet
and children's first and most important teachers are their parents. we want to help parents who want to help their children to read,'' he said
the booklet, ``becoming a nation of readers: what parents can do,'' begins by noting that reading is a skill that continues to improve with practice. then, starting with parents of preschoolers, the booklet offers suggestions for things parents can do to encourage their children to read
the education department's first tip to parents of young children is to read aloud to them. ``when adults read aloud, children quickly learn that a book is a wonderful thing,'' the booklet notes
for parents of children in kindergarten and first grade the booklet suggests parents continue to read aloud with their children, take their children on trips to the library or bookstores and listen to their children read. the booklet also recommends that parents ``place reasonable limits on tv viewing.''
and for parents of children in higher grades, the booklet suggests parents set aside a time and place at home for studying. it also recommends parents keep close tabs on their children's progress and encourage reading for fun
for some families, plainly this booklet is not necessary,'' finn said. ``but it's a useful book for parents who have the impulse and don't know how to go about it.''
the reading booklet, which is being printed by the lexington, mass.-based d.c. heath and co. textbook publishers, can be obtained by sending 50 cents to: ``what parents can do,'' consumer information center, pueblo, colo. 81009. numerous school districts and the american federation of teachers also are printing copies
newspapers likened government press restrictions to those of the soviet union and said wednesday the closure of a militant newspaper for blacks endangers all south african news media
the closing of the new nation is ``a chilling reminder of the lengths to which the government is ready to go in its attempts to impose thought countrol,'' the star of johannesburg said in an editorial
after this, no other newspaper is safe,'' south africa's largest daily declared
home minister stoffel botha, who has censorship powers under the emergency in effect since june 12, 1986, issued a decree tuesday prohibiting publication of the new nation for three months
the weekly tabloid is financed by the roman catholic church. its editor, zwelakhe sisulu, has been in detention for 15 months
botha also warned a monthly cape town community paper, grassroots, that it faces closure or prior censorship if it continues publishing ``subversive propaganda.''
grassroots was the eighth paper to receive a warning, the first step in the closure process, and the new nation was the first to be shut down
an editorial in the cape times said:
if the newspapers continue on traditional lines in spite of such warnings, will they share the fate of new nation? the censorship system seeks to achieve a compliant press on pravda-like lines, rather than a wholesale closure of publications, which would be embarassing and inconvenient
if it is really felt that newspapers are fomenting revolution, why not charge them in the courts? there are laws enough.''
business day, a conservative johannesburg daily, declared:
the decision to close new nation for three months confirms what has been plain for some time: south africa can no longer claim to have a free press and in this respect, as in others, it has left the ranks of civilized nations
in the past it was possible to argue that the press was restricted, but free, and even to make self-flattering comparisons with the british official secrets act. this is no longer so
it seems idle to protest at the closing of a newspaper when that newspaper's editor, zwelakhe sisulu, has been in detention without trial for more than a year. government's opponents _ or those it deems opponents _ are locked away indefinitely for crimes which cannot be defined in the law, and are punished without a chance to rebut the charges against them
the decision to suppress new nation rests on the minister's opinion that the newspaper propagated communism, but neither the minister nor the law can define the crime for which the newspaper is punished. radical newspapers will be circulated ... as they are in the soviet union, from hand to hand.''
a pro-government daily, the citizen, took a different view
newspapers still report most of the news that is fit to print, and where reporting is restricted, they still, in the main, give a fair picture of what is happening,'' it said. ``but south africa is in a state of emergency. the press is subjected to stringent restrictions.''
the citzen also said, however, that court proceedings would have been better than botha's action, which was taken ``on the recommendations of a faceless panel of so-called experts exercising judgments that are personal, based on no specific criteria or guidelines, and cannot be tested in a court of law.''
a radio program which bills itself as the ``voice of indian america'' is fighting to survive as the only nationally broadcast native american news program, its founder says
first person radio'' is heard on 35 stations in 13 states, down from 52 stations in 26 states, said laura waterman wittstock. and financial troubles for public radio have clouded the program's future, she said
we're sort of passengers in a sinking ship, so to speak, because the indian-owned radio stations are in equally distressed situations,'' wittstock said recently
the half-hour weekly news and commentary program is produced by migizi communications, an 11-year-old, non-profit organization based in minneapolis. migizi is ojibwe for eagle
the eagle symbolizes messages, and also it's a symbol of high standard,'' wittstock said. ``we wanted to have the highest standards of indian journalism, to train more indians into journalism and to develop a national news service.''
and the show enables indians around the country to feel a part of a community. in southern alabama, it serves 1,859 members of the poarch band of creek indians
we're the only reservation in alabama. the cultural exchange is really important,'' said dale gehman, a creek indian who is general manager of wasg-am in atmore, ala. ``i don't know what we'd do without it.''
alaska public radio offers separate stories about indians which are distributed by national public radio, but not in the format of a regular broadcast program, according to npr
correspondents in new mexico and idaho regularly file stories to give ``first person radio'' a national flavor, wittstock said. but affiliated stations have been unable to offer many stories because they are also struggling and have little time left over to make contributions, she said
the '80s have been disastrous for radio _ not just indian radio,'' she said, adding that interest in sponsoring minority radio programs has lost favor to shows with mass appeal
so why do wittstock and dale means, the show's program adviser, struggle to keep ``first person radio'' on the air?
i feel there is a market for indian programming, but nobody is doing it,'' said means, brother of former american indian movement leader russell means. dale means helped start kili-fm on the pine ridge indian reservation in south dakota that went on the air in 1983 to mark the 10th anniversary of the wounded knee occupation
early on, kili and migizi, which received promotional support from the american indian movement, were criticized within the indian community because of that association, means said
it wasn't an aim podium, so to speak. that's one of the good things about the radio station,'' he said. ``on occasion, it had some critical comments about aim itself.''
but the issue no longer arises, wittstock said. ``we've proven ourselves.''
before ``first person radio'' began in the late 1970s, wittstock said, ``you might get a little snippet about a demonstration, or a little snippet about a murder, or somebody going to jail for 99 years or something like that. that isn't indian news.''
recent news stories have included coverage of federal college loan problems for navajo students, an ongoing land claims dispute on the white earth indian reservation in northern minnesota, and a law requiring labeling to distinguish wild rice harvested by indians from the paddy-grown variety
training young journalists is an important goal for wittstock, 50, the last director of the defunct american indian press association, which distributed articles to about 100 indian newspapers nationwide
she and means, 46, run after-school programs for students interested in learning about communications, and have trained 50 college students over the years
water officials facing what could be the state's second-driest year ever have declared an emergency shortage and warned 1.1 million customers that water rationing may be ordered for homes and businesses
the east bay municipal utility district stopped short of imposing emergency restrictions but voted yesterday to approve a $300,000 campaign to teach the public water conservation methods
we don't want to make this a draconian thing, but we do want to save a lot of water,'' district general manager jerome gilbert said at the board of director's meeting tuesday
the board will meet again april 13 to consider rationing but is already divided over whether to allow more water in the warmer areas such as the san ramon valley
directors from berkeley and richmond argued it would be unfair if affluent suburbs such as san ramon receive an extra share of water for their sprawling lawns and gardens
water officials said studies show rain and snow runoff from the mokelumne river basin, the district's major water source, is estimated at 180,000 feet, 24 percent of normal
this year has the potential to be the second-driest year ever,'' said ted way, chief engineer
officials stopped short of declaring a drought for the district east of san francisco, but said river runoff from snow melt will average 60 percent of normal between april and july statewide
a nearly 2-year-old lawsuit that accuses several iran-contra figures of collaborating with colombian drug lords is under attack by the defendants who call the complaint ``legal terrorism.''
the lawsuit, filed in may 1986 several months before the iran-contra affair was exposed publicly, names some of the people in the private network that lt. col. oliver l. north formed to help the nicaraguan contras
the lawsuit has attracted widespread attention, and the christic institute, a liberal policy group representing the plaintiffs, has used it as a vehicle to raise money
daniel sheehan, the christic's chief counsel, has traveled around the country speaking about the suit, which was filed by martha honey and tony avirgan, two american reporters based in costa rica
the allegations in the civil lawsuit _ set for trial june 26 in federal court in miami _ are significantly different and much broader than the issues raised by lawrence walsh, the independent counsel in the iran-contra case
last week, a federal grand jury indicted four men on charges of conspiring to defraud the u.s. government in the program to sell weapons to iran and divert the proceeds to the contras
they are john m. poindexter, the former national security adviser; north, poindexter's one-time aide; and richard v. secord and albert hakim, two arms dealers who helped north run the iran-contra program
secord and hakim are among the 29 defendants in the miami lawsuit, which does not cite any u.s. government officials. central to the lawsuit is the claim that the defendants conspired to traffic in drugs and plot assassinations in central america and elsewhere
lawyers for both sides expect the trial to proceed despite walsh's criminal indictments
this case is going to trial,'' said thomas spencer, an attorney for retired gen. john singlaub, one of the defendants in the lawsuit
honey and avirgan are represented by attorneys for the christic institute, a liberal policy group based in the nation's capital
i think they (the plaintiffs) are desperately looking for a way to get out of the lawsuit,'' spencer said. ``they have come to the conclusion there is no basis for their case.''
peter dykstra, a spokesman for the washington-based institute, rejected spencer's claim. ``we want a trial _ why else would we be doing this?'' he said
spencer and other defense lawyers have waged a concerted effort to discredit the lawsuit. among other things, they have obtained affidavits from some of the christic's sources, contradicting information in the lawsuit
judge james lawrence king ordered the institute to reveal its sources
secord, meantime, has filed a $5 million slander suit against eugene wheaton, one of the institute's principal ources. wheaton's lawyer, robert thompson, said his client has not responded to the lawsuit
at the heart of the honey-avirgan lawsuit is the allegation that ``a secret team'' headed by former cia official theodore shackley worked over two decades to manage a covert, shadow government funded with drug profits. there has never been independent confirmation of the charge
shackley has waged a personal publicity campaign to defend himself and vowed to seek reprisals through the legal system
in an article in the journal of defense &amp; diplomacy, shackley described the plaintiffs as ``practitioners of character assassination through legal terrorism...''
the christic institute stands by its charges, and sheehan says he is developing more information that implicates the defendants. but many of the institute's theories will not be tested in court because king has limited testimony in the case to events between 1983 and 1986
specifically, avirgan and honey seek damages of $22 million to compensate avirgan for injuries he suffered inside nicaragua at a bombing at a may 1986 press conference held by former contra leader, eden pastora. three reporters died in the bombing
the lawsuit claims the defendants, who include known colombian drug smugglers pablo escobar and jorge ochoa, conspired to:
_ kill pastora because he would not cooperate with other contra rebels
_ smuggle cocaine into the united states to finance contra operations
_ assassinate a u.s. ambassador in costa rica in order to claim a bounty
the special congressional committees that investigated the iran-contra case last summer did not deal specifically with allegations raised in the lawsuit
but a senate panel chaired by sen. john kerry, d-mass., is looking into reports of drug-dealing by the contras. the rebels have denied they trafficked in narcotics
the iran-contra committees, however, heard public testimony from glenn robinette, a former cia security specialist who said secord paid him thousands of dollars to investigate the lawsuit in 1986
over the past several months, the institute has conducted depositions of witnesses, many of whom have refused to talk, citing their fifth amendment right to remain silent
spencer said the lawsuit has cost singlaub $150,000 in legal fees so far, and that could double. the institute has budgeted $3 million to cover operational expenses 1988, with 90 percent of the money expected to be spent on the lawsuit
a bone marrow transplant researcher was named wednesday as recipient of the $50,000 bristol-myers award for distinguished achievement in cancer research
george santos, professor of oncology and medicine at the johns hopkins university school of medicine in baltimore, will receive the prize at a luncheon may 4 in new york
bone marrow transplants are used to treat leukemia
santos was among the first researchers to realize the importance of suppressing the immune system with drugs in bone marrow transplants, to avoid a potentially fatal complication known as graft-versus-host disease, said e. donnall thomas, director of the fred hutchinson cancer research center and a member of the award committee
in the disease, immune system cells from the donated marrow attack the recipient's tissue as foreign
santos said he and colleagues are now studying use of marrow transplants as part of treatment of cancers of the breast, ovary and colon. the research involves using higher-than-usual doses of chemotherapy to kill cancer cells, then doing transplants to restore marrow destroyed as a side effect
another line of research is using the drug thalidomide in fighting graft-versus-host disease, he said. animal studies are encouraging, he said in a statement
thalidomide is best known for causing birth defects when taken by pregnant women as a sleeping pill in the 1950s. but apart from that, scientists say, it has far fewer side effects than cyclosporine, another suppressor of the immune system that can damage the kidneys
two iraqi jetfighters inadvertently violated turkish airspace when they bombed kurdish guerrillas in a joint security zone along the border, it was reported wednesday
the semi-official anatolia news agency said tuesday's air raid caused panic in villages in southeast turkey, a few miles from the border with iraq. it said the iraqi warplanes bombed kurdish guerrillas fighting for an autonomous homeland
it was not known if there were any causualties
an estimated 19 million kurds seeking independence live in the area where the borders of iran, turkey and iraq meet
turkey and iraq have an agreement granting rights to each other to operate in a 6-mile-wide joint security zone along the common frontier
turkish military units also have been fighting kurdish guerrillas over the past four years. turkish warplanes staged two air raids against kurdish rebel hideouts in the joint security zone in the past two years
