state republican party chairman ray shamie said today he will not challenge sen. edward m. kennedy this year. instead, longtime shamie aide joseph malone will run against the veteran democrat
shamie, a retired walpole millionaire, told a news conference he had decided, despite pleas from president reagan and other national party officials, to remain state party chairman
among other things, shamie said he was concerned about giving up a chairmanship won only last year to run what most observers agree is an uphill battle to unseat kennedy, who will be seeking his fifth full term
shamie, 67, endorsed malone, saying that none of the other republicans who expressed interest in challenging kennedy would be serious candidates
malone, 33, of waltham, has been a close aide to shamie since 1982, when shamie emerged by mounting a credible challenge to kennedy. currently, malone is executive director of the republican party under shamie
a graduate of harvard college in 1978, malone has helped operate a family trucking business and also is a partner in family real estate holdings
i have devoted 10 years of my life working to help bring back a two-party system to massachusetts,'' malone said in an interview. ``it's important that we have a strong, aggressive campaign in massachusetts.''
the top gop party brass was concerned that a weak challenge to kennedy would leave him free to roam the country helping other democratic campaigns, including the presidential race
but state rep. john macgovern said shamie, ``did not like being used by other people like a battering ram. he did not want to run. you're just banging yourself up to keep ted kennedy busy.''
malone is a virtual unknown in massachusetts except in political circles. he is well off from his family business interests but said he is not a millionaire
shamie spent $1.8 million against kennedy in 1982 when he lost 61 percent to 38 percent. he spent a record $2.3 million in 1984 against john kerry for senate in a race kerry won 55 percent to 45 percent
police on the lookout for terrorist attacks at the capitol report a 50 percent decline in seizures of handguns and rifles last year but a sharp increase in canisters of chemical sprays that visitors carry for self-protection
figures supplied by senior police officials appeared to contradict an earlier claim by house sergeant-at-arms jack russ that weapons seizures rose by a startling 147 percent at the capitol last year
members of a house appropriations subcommittee said russ left the impression at a recent hearing that many of the 1,162 confiscated weapons were guns. russ cited the figure in arguing for an $18.5 million plan to tighten security on the house side of the capitol
but capitol police chief frank kerrigan said in a subsequent interview that all 1,162 actually were canisters of mace, tear gas and other non-lethal chemical sprays, some in lipstick-style containers, that women carry to immobilize would-be attackers. the same seizures totaled 470 the previous year
tear gas and other chemical sprays are illegal in the district of columbia, including the capitol grounds. the capitol police classify them as weapons subject to seizure and destruction
kerrigan said chemical sprays accounted for the vast majority of the actual total of the 1,270 weapons confiscated at the capitol last year, a 125 percent increase over 1986. the police said gun seizures actually declined to 14 from 28 the previous year
the balance included knives, explosive liquids, clubs, blackjacks and various exotic weapons, plus non-lethal ``stun guns,'' which use an electrical jolt to render victims temporarily harmless
asked about kerrigan's details, russ said he must have misinterpreted the figures he received from the capitol police. senior members of the house panel that heard russ' testimony discounted suggestions that he might have given misleading figures in an attempt to gain support for his security plan
but rep. vic fazio, d-calif., the subcommittee chairman, said house members responsible for capitol security intend to take a much closer look at the situation, in consultation with the senate, before any decisions are made
fazio said he has heard conflicting arguments over the need for stricter anti-terrorist measures. ``we won't be stampeded,'' he said
i don't think jack was trying to mislead us, but it does raise a question,'' said rep. john t. myers, r-ind., a panel member
rep. jerry lewis of california, the subcommitee's ranking republican, agreed with fazio's go-slow approach
they're pushing very hard to increase security everywhere up here,'' lewis said. ``we must protect ourselves in this modern age of terrorism, but i tend to resist any unnecessary steps that would hinder the public's access to the capitol.''
kerrigan said the sharply higher number of weapons seizures probably reflected improved use of metal detectors in the capitol building and six nearby office buildings, better training of police officers and more thorough searches of visitors, rather than any increase in the number of visitors with criminal intent
russ said many of the visitors who carry firearms have out-of-state gun permits but are unaware that the permits are invalid on the capitol grounds
kerrigan said 63 people were prosecuted at the capitol last year on illegal-weapons charges, compared with 50 people in 1986. transition. picks up 10th graf pvs ``the feud...''</note>
the general assembly voted overwhemingly today to condemn the u.s. move to close the palestine liberation organization's u.n. mission
the assembly voted 148-2 to deplore the u.s. action and urge it to abide by the international u.n. headquarters treaty, which allows foreign missions to operate. the united states and israel voted against the resolution
general assembly resolutions are not legally binding, but carry moral weight
the vote came one day after the u.s. justice department filed a lawsuit seeking to close the plo mission and freeze its funds, in accordance with an anti-terrorist law
u.s. ambassador herbert s. okun, the deputy permanent representative, said the justice department was obliged by law to enforce the anti-terrorist legislation, which would close the mission
but he said the united states would take no further steps to close the mission until a court has ruled on the u.s. lawsuit filed in u.s. district court in manhattan
the plo envoy, zehdi labib terzi, told the assembly that the united states claims to be proud to play host to the united nations. then he shouted:
what pride to you have in throwing your guests out?
is this the message the u.s. delegation wants to bring to the world? that guests have no respect, the united nations has no respect, international law has no respect? ..
this is not gunboat policy any more. we are living in a stage where the human approach, where obligations are respected,'' said terzi. he said the plo will fight the u.s. lawsuit
of the united states, terzi said: ``is this the country which claims to be the bastion of freedom and democracy ... afraid to permit the voice of the palestinians?''
israeli ambassador johanan bein, the deputy permanent representative, told the assembly that the plo has been ``the principal terrorist organization of our time'' and it rejects the central u.n. principle of peaceful settlement of disputes
on tuesday, the plo accused the united states of engaging in ``financial terrorism'' by seeking a court order to close the mission and force the plo to transfer its bank funds out of the united states
the closure of the mission is required under the 1987 anti-terrorism act, which found the plo and its affiliates were a terrorist organization responsible for numerous violent incidents, including the murder of an american citizen during the hijacking of the cruise ship achille lauro in 1985
the feud over the future of the plo's mission on east 65th street has created a crisis in u.s.-u.n. relations
secretary of state george p. shultz also has called the law ``a very bad piece of legislation'' which unnecessarily glorifies the plo
terzi has said he will have to be dragged away from the plo mission and that if forced to move, it will be to the united nations on international territory, out of reach of u.s. marshals
in 1973, plo chief yasser arafat spent a night at the united nations because he could not stay on u.s. territory
nobody was surprised when president francois mitterrand finally announced he would seek re-election, but many were stunned by the pugnacity of his words and his version of charles de gaulle's ``me or chaos'' alternative
the 71-year-old socialist president declared his candidacy in a television interview tuesday night, waiting until five weeks before the first round of voting to end months of speculation
mitterrand had said he preferred to step down but would run for a second seven-year term if ``exceptional circumstances'' warranted it. he said tuesday that after listening to the speeches of other candidates, he was convinced france is in danger
i see a risk that the country might fall into the quarrels and division that so often have undermined it,'' he said. ``i want france to be united. and it will not be if it is taken in hand by intolerant minds, by parties who want everything, by clans, by gangs. ...there must be civil peace in france.''
though he named no names, the president's remarks were aimed at his two main opponents, conservative premier jacques chirac and former centrist premier raymond barre
typical of the reaction in the conservative press wednesday, gerard badel wrote in le parisien: ``the chief of state has, in sum, confronted the french people with the choice that he had so often reproached gen. de gaulle for: me or chaos.''
alain juppe, spokesman for chirac's government, said mitterrand ``goes to war against perils that do not exist.''
if there is really danger, one wonders why mr. mitterrand waited so long to say so. in reality, all that is pure fabrication,'' juppe said
french presidential elections are run in two rounds. the first, april 24, pits mitterrand against chirac, barre and a handful of minor candidates. if, as expected, nobody wins a majority, a runoff will be held may 8 between the top two vote-getters
for the past year, the polls have indicated that mitterrand will win the second round handily, no matter who his opponent is. but he could slip now that he has had to abandon his strictly presidential role
chirac remarked on what he called mitterrand's ``language of rare violence and sectarianism that risked setting the french against one another.'' the stakes, he said, are clear: ``on one side, there is the socialist party that wants to retake power and institute socialist policies ... on the other is the (conservative parliamentary) majority that has governed for two years in calm and union.''
barre said he doubted mitterrand could unite the country, adding that since the president's election in 1981 he has been ``the president of one fraction of the french population against another.''
the reality is that since the mid-1980s, french politics have moved toward the center. the gulf between the left and right has narrowed to the point where it is difficult to distinguish the two
without an overriding issue, the campaign has evolved into one of personalities
there is chirac, 55, the hard-driving, almost frenetic, political bulldozer, and currently the leading rightist; barre, 63, the thoughtful economics professor, who is more toward the center; and mitterrand, who in the two years since the right ousted the socialists from control of the national assembly, has become the sage father figure
the vocabulary is the same. each has presented himself as the only man capable of uniting the french
few differences exist in foreign policy and defense. even unemployment, now at 10.4 percent, has not emerged as a battleground. both right and left have tried and failed to come to grips with it
in his announcement, mitterrand presented no program, saying only that he would get to it later
since ``cohabitation'' between the socialist president and the conservative premier was forced on french politics by the 1986 legislative elections, mitterrand has profited the most. he has taken pains to distance himself from the socialist party, which he founded and led for years, and is trying to appear as a man above parties
the ailing leader of at least 150,000 pakistani refugees began a fast wednesday to demand that islamabad take back the refugees stranded here since 1971
if the pakistan government does not respond favorably to our request for early return to our country, hundreds and thousands of our brothers and sisters will be on fast unto death,'' said nasim khan, 64, who began his fast outside the national press club
khan suffered a heart attack two weeks ago. he told the associated press, ``it's better to die struggling to go back to our homeland than live in vice, hunger and disease ridden camps in an alien country.''
khan and the others were stranded in 1971 when bangladesh, formerly east pakistan, became an independent country after a liberation struggle and a war between india and pakistan
by 1973, 174,000 refugees returned to pakistan, but the repatriation ended abruptly when funds ran out, stranding 250,000 people. about 100,000 are believed to have returned since, but the rest remain in refugee camps in bangladesh
bangladesh foreign secretary nazrul islam told reporters wednesday that his government has renewed a longstanding request to pakistan to make arrangement for the return of the refugees
islam said pakistan has agreed in principle to take back the refugees. but a pakistani diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said sufficient funds for the transfer still were lacking. moslem charitable organizations have been asked for help in raising the money
as khan began his fast, hundreds of other refugees held a silent march on a nearby street
nasim khan bazlul huda, 19, said, ``i will burn myself to death soon if pakistan does not announce a timetable for our repatriation.''
islam said that dhaka and islamabad had approached a number of countries and world organizations to raise enough money for a repatriation of refugees
four years ago, the stranded pakistanis planned a march to their homeland, but border guards crushed it. colter said...</note>
gov. evan mecham's former chief of staff testified today there was no effort to cover up an $80,000 loan from the governor's protocol fund to mecham's auto dealership
i just forgot or failed'' to record the check in the fund's checkbook register, former chief of staff jim colter told the senate
colter also told prosecutor william french that mecham had called his home on tuesday and left a message on the answering machine ``that i had done a good job, or something to that effect'' in his earlier testimony
meanwhile, the senate voted 25-4 today to drop the longer schedule it had adopted in an effort to speed up the impeachment trial. prosecution and defense lawyers complained the eight hours of testimony tuesday left them too little time for preparation, and lawmakers agreed to return to a six-hour schedule
voting against the shorter schedule were republican sens. carl kunasek, bob usdane, tony west and peter kay
the senate is now hearing testimony on the second impeachment charge, which accused mecham of misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to mecham pontiac
there was certainly no effort to cover up'' the loan, colter testified today
colter testified tuesday that he warned the governor it would be ``politically unwise'' to borrow the money, but mecham instructed him to write the check anyway
you certainly were not anxious that the general public be aware of this loan, were you?'' french asked today
no, i did not broadcast it,'' colter replied
the former chief of staff acknowledged that he did not shop around for better interest rates before processing the loan to mecham pontiac, but added, ``as far as i'm concerned (the loan) was a good investment of the money.''
it had ``nothing to do with the governor's personal use,'' colter said
however, democratic sen. jones osborn questioned whether it would be a subsidy to mecham pontiac to loan it money if the interest rate were lower than the dealership would have had to pay to a bank
colter said mecham also asked him not to record a document securing the loan, although colter did not know why. he testified, however, that he did not think any law had been broken ``or i would have objected.''
the protocol fund, created with fund-raising revenues from mecham's inauguration, is intended to be used for state ceremonial gifts
the prosecution contends the fund is public money and therefore the loan was illegal, while the defense says the money can be used as mecham sees fit, except to repay his campaign expenses
however, the first two witnesses to testify on the charge said they were shocked when they heard that mecham had loaned the funds to his auto dealership
i was very surprised and disappointed and saddened,'' said warner lee, a former state attorney general who advised the mecham inaugural committee. ``i thought that it was a very awkward thing politically to have done.''
i personally was shocked and initially felt betrayed,'' said deputy maricopa county attorney howard schwartz, who helped draft an agreement for use of funds raised by mecham's inaugural committee
in an interview tuesday on ktar radio, mecham said he considered the protocol fund to be ``private association money ... not state money.''
he acknowledged he was told ``it was politically not a wise thing to do, but i wasn't thinking of that.'' the governor said he could have borrowed the money from other sources, but decided on the protocol fund so it would earn the 9 percent interest being paid by mecham pontiac
mecham, the first u.s. governor to be impeached in six decades, also said if he is exonerated, he will do a better job as governor
they'll probably say this is another one of those gaffes, but a lot of the rats have come out of their holes that's been after me, and now we know a lot more who they are,'' mecham said. ``quite frankly, i'll be a lot wiser governor from here on out.''
if he is allowed to resume his job, mecham said, he will fire department of public safety director ralph milstead, one of the chief accusers in his senate trial
a senate conviction, mecham said, ``will certainly not be on the basis of evidence and on that we'll go and appeal it of course ... probably direct to the u.s. supreme court.''
earlier tuesday, the senate finished hearing testimony on the first impeachment charge _ that mecham tried to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official against a former top mecham aide
after heated debate, a motion to vote on the first count immediately was dropped after it became clear most senators wanted to hear testimony on all three charges first
the third charge accuses the governor of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan. a two-thirds vote of the 30-member senate is required to convict mecham and remove him from office
meanwhile, a lawyer defending mecham at his april 21 criminal trial on six felony counts related to the $350,000 loan sought dismissal of the charges. the lawyer, michael scott, said the governor has been singled out for prosecution because he is unpopular
the judge did not rule on the motion. mecham also faces a may 17 recall election. ld-writethru and expands throughout</note>
state republican party chairman ray shamie said today he will not challenge sen. edward m. kennedy this year. instead, longtime shamie aide joseph malone will run against the veteran democrat
shamie, a retired walpole millionaire, told a news conference he had decided, despite pleas from president reagan and other national party officials, to remain state party chairman
among other things, shamie said he was concerned about giving up a chairmanship won only last year to run what most observers agree is an uphill battle to unseat kennedy, who will be seeking his fifth full term
shamie, 67, endorsed malone, saying that none of the other republicans who expressed interest in challenging kennedy would be serious candidates
malone, 33, of waltham, has been a close aide to shamie since 1982, when shamie emerged by mounting a credible challenge to kennedy. currently, malone is executive director of the republican party under shamie
a graduate of harvard college in 1978, malone has helped operate a family trucking business and also is a partner in family real estate holdings
i have devoted 10 years of my life working to help bring back a two-party system to massachusetts,'' malone said in an interview. ``it's important that we have a strong, aggressive campaign in massachusetts.''
the top gop party brass was concerned that a weak challenge to kennedy would leave him free to roam the country helping other democratic campaigns, including the presidential race
but state rep. john macgovern said shamie, ``did not like being used by other people like a battering ram. he did not want to run. you're just banging yourself up to keep ted kennedy busy.''
malone is a virtual unknown in massachusetts except in political circles. he is well off from his family business interests but said he is not a millionaire
shamie spent $1.8 million against kennedy in 1982 when he lost 61 percent to 38 percent. he spent a record $2.3 million in 1984 against john kerry for senate in a race kerry won 55 percent to 45 percent
a physicist reported wednesday the discovery of a new superconducting compound that he believes may work at minus 100 degrees fahrenheit, potentially setting a new temperature record for superconductivity
the compound, made of lanthanum, copper and oxygen, forms crystal structures that are relatively pure examples of the basic copper-oxygen lattice found in all the new superconductors, said stuart wolf, who reported the development along with colleagues from the naval research labortatory
because of their relative purity they may be able to attain superconductivity at higher temperatures than other materials, he said
the compound now appears to become superconducting at above 280 degrees below zero fahrenheit, but that could go to minus 100 degrees fahrenheit or higher, he aid
the substance can be made only at temperatures of 2,700 degrees fahrenheit and at pressures 65,000 times those of the atmosphere, but it can then be cooled and studied at normal temperatures and pressures, he said
allen hermann of the university of arkansas reported that he has now achieved superconductivity at a temperature of 234 degrees below zero fahrenheit with a superconductor he discovered late last year
ibm scientists had been the first to push hermann's new superconductor to that temperature, even before hermann himself could do it, demonstrating how rapidly research is spreading and advancing
when hermann and his arkansas collaborator zhengzhi sheng announced the discovery of the material, ``within two days we had confirmation around the world,'' he said _ almost before the ink was dry on his laboratory notebooks
for physicists, who are accustomed to working in exotic realms, minus 234 degress fahrenheit is warm. previous superconductors had operated at no higher than minus 418 degrees fahrenheit
no one can yet be sure how much higher temperatures will go, but many are optimistic that temperatures will continue to climb. ``i think we have simply uncovered the tip of the iceberg,'' said hermann
the so-called high-temperature superconductors that have set physics ablaze offer the promise of dramatically cheaper electricity generation, transmission and storage, faster and smaller computers and 300-mile-an-hour magnetically levitated trains
but initial enthusiasm for those applications is now somewhat lower, as each discovery raises as many questions as it answers, physicists said
we don't want to promise too much to society,'' said robert cava of bell laboratories. ``but the promise exists.''
the latest batch of reports came at an unscheduled session held tuesday night during a meeting of the american physical society
the meeting, convened by researchers eager to swap their latest findings, followed by one year the ``woodstock of physics'' in new york, at which the first reports of the new superconductivity were presented to scientists in a session that continued until the wee hours of the morning
physicists in new orleans discussed new experiments with two superconductors first reported earlier this year _ the thallium-containing compound found by hermann and sheng and another containing bismuth, which was first reported by hiroshi maeda and colleagues in japan
fears the new superconductors would be unable to carry currents large enough for practical applications have diminished, the researchers said
it has now been shown that the materials are potentially capable of carrying huge amounts of current, and researchers reported that they have devised ways of making them that bring them closer to their theoretical current-carrying capacity
theoretical physicists are still trying to figure out how the new superconductors work, but the availability now of four distinct superconductors has made some aspects of their operation clearer
all the superconductors include sheets of copper and oxygen, suggesting that these sheets are critical. furthermore, the materials that operate at higher temperatures have these copper oxide sheets, as they're called, layered in twos and threes
physicists are now trying to make compounds with the copper oxide layers grouped in fours, on the hunch those materials will have even higher operating temperatures
here are the latest major developments in central america:
nicaragua:
sapoa, nicaragua _ negotiators for the sandinistas and contra rebels resumed their truce talks today after exchanging proposals that for the first time agree on major points. the proposals, put forth on the second day of talks tuesday, call for an extended cease-fire, amnesty and release of political prisoners. among obstacles still to be worked out are how the contras will lay down their arms and be granted amnesty
the state-run voice of nicaragua today reported a violation of the truce agreed on during the peace talks. the radio said the contras ambushed an army truck tuesday, killing two soldiers. a defense ministry spokesman said the ministry had no information about the report
washington _ the reagan administration and house speaker jim wright called reports of progress at cease-fire talks in nicaragua encouraging. democratic leaders said agreement there likely would trigger a new package of humanitarian aid for the contra rebels
president reagan is seeking to revive his stalled effort to aid the contras. the last aid package ran out feb. 29
honduras:
palmerola air base, honduras _ honduras says its border crisis with nicaragua is over, but u.s. military officials say american troops sent as a response will stay on to complete emergency training exercises. in washington, pentagon officials say the american troops will return monday and tuesday
panama:
panama city _ a general strike aimed at ousting gen. manuel antonio noriega was in its third day today. it closed an estimated 90 percent of offices and industries on tuesday, and food is running low. on tuesday, noriega again rejected a u.s. call for him to surrender power and go into exile
washington _ reagan administration officials say they've tried to encourage noriega to leave panama by offering to fly him into exile along with family and friends. noriega told two high-levle u.s. envoys who visited him last week that he was not willing to accept any arrangement that involves leaving panama. firms</head>
a trial lawyers' group has sharply criticized members of two prominent law firms for concealing evidence from families who sued their clients over water pollution alleged to have caused six cancer deaths
in documents filed with a federal appeals court, the massachusetts academy of trial attorneys said the conduct of attorneys representing beatrice foods co. and the owner of a woburn tannery threatened to undermine the judicial system by encouraging lawyers to flout court rules
the court must support those who abide by the rules and expose those who bend them to their own advantage,'' the academy said in a brief filed to support the request by eight woburn families for a new trial in their suit against beatrice and the john j. riley co. tannery
a wrongdoer should be unable to take comfort or benefit in a judgment obtained by cheating,'' the academy said in the brief filed tuesday with the 1st u.s. circuit court of appeals
the lawyers' group singled out beatrice attorney jerome facher of the law firm of hale &amp; dorr for its harshest criticism
the concealment of information through misrepresentation and misconduct was accomplished by the lead attorney for the defendant,'' the academy said. ``as a senior member of the bar, he commands respect and attention. how the court determines the appropriateness of his conduct will not go unnoticed.''
without naming her, the academy also lambasted mary ryan of the law firm nutter, mcclennen &amp; fish, the attorney for riley, which bought the tannery from beatrice. the families blame the tannery for polluting the town's water supply
neither facher nor ryan returned telephone calls wednesday from the associated press
the academy frequently files briefs in cases involving complex and controversial legal issues. it did not specify requested sanctions against the lawyers
the filing with the appeals court followed u.s. district judge walter jay skinner's decision in january denying the families a new trial
their original suit contended four parties were responsible for the pollution, beatrice and riley, w.r. grace co., and unifirst, a uniform supply company. unifirst settled prior to trial and w.r. grace settled for a reported $8 million halfway through the trial. skinner dismissed the portion of the suit against beatrice and the tannery
the families asked for a new trial after their attorney learned of a 1983 report that was not disclosed by facher or ryan. the report said it was possible that dumping on the tannery property contributed to groundwater pollution near two town wells
skinner ruled that facher and ryan were aware of the report but failed to disclose it to the families. but the judge refused to order a new trial, saying he did not think the report would have affected the outcome of the case and that the families failed to prove the concealment was deliberate
the families' attorney, jan schlichtmann, and the academy said skinner applied the wrong standard in deciding the issue, saying that he was wrong to speculate that the report would not have led to evidence favorable to the claim that pollution on the tannery property seeped into the town's water supply
