president saddam hussein has dismissed the ministers of light industry and heavy industry from his cabinet and replaced them with the army officer who supervises the manufacture of iraq's military hardware
a presidential decree issued tuesday night and published wednesday by government newspapers said heavy industry minister abdul-tawab mulahuwaish and light industry minister hatem abdul-rashid were relieved of their duties
it did not say what prompted their dismissal, but added that col. hussein kamil has been appointed minister of industry and minerals
government sources said the cabinet reshuffle is designed to merge the two ministries and give the military industry a boost
kamil, a career military man, has been heading the war industry committee that supervises the manufacture of military equipment
iraq says it is making some of its own ammunition and weapons, including long-range missiles
more than 100 missiles have been fired at the iranian capital, tehran, since feb. 29 in a missile duel by the nations
while the iraqis say these were homemade, western military analysts believe they are soviet-built, surface-to-surface scud-bs that the iraqis have equipped with boosters to increase their range. policy</head> to update with comment from dukakis campaign.</note>
republican presidential contender bob dole on wednesday accused michael dukakis and the rest of the democratic white house hopefuls of a ``failure of nerve as well as a failure of vision'' in responding to the soviet-backed regime in nicaragua
the call to defend the freedom of nicaragua, which should be easy for them to answer, instead produces endless foot-shuffling and sophistry,'' dole said in a speech that made little mention of his own presidential candidacy and avoided even a single reference to gop front-runner george bush
dole said the issue of the sandinista government in nicaragua is ``as symbolic for our time as hitler's brazen aggression was for an earlier generation.''
he warned that failure to confront it might eventually lead to communist governments in costa rica, panama or even mexico as the sandinistas strengthen their grip at home and begin supporting guerilla movements elsewhere
what will the democrats say then?,'' he asked in a speech that marked the beginning of an effort to lay out his views on a variety of issues. the kansas senator is far, far behind bush in the race for delegates to the republican national convention, and is widely viewed as a candidate for withdrawal after the wisconsin primary on april 5
in his speech to the center for strategic and international studies, dole addressed an issue that has divided republican candidates _ who favor military support for the contras fighting the nicaraguan government _ from the democrats who oppose it
he turned his fire on massachusets gov. dukakis, the other democratic presidential hopefuls and the ``democratic left.''
dole said dukakis ``says that the monroe doctrine, which has defined america's security in its own neighborhood for some 200 years, is `obsolete.' he says that this country ... has no choice but to tolerate the existence of soviet client states wherever subversion might install them.''
broadening his attack, dole added, ``today, all the democratic party presidential candidates sound themes similar to the `dukakis doctrine' for latin america .... instead of joining president reagan in challenging the thieves, they have found ways to rationalize the loss of liberty in nicaragua.''
dole's charges brought a sarcastic reply from dukakis' communications director, leslie dach
i guess bob dole is taking after michael dukakis because he's accomplishing what bob dole can't _ beating george bush in the polls,'' dach said
dole said democrats are guilty of an attitude that says ``america must not be too forceful'' that stems from the belief that america, rather than the soviet union, poses a threat to peace
perverse but pervasive, this attitude has enveloped the democratic side of the primary campaign like nerve gas,'' he said
dole cited anti-communist stands taken by democratic presidents harry truman and john f. kennedy, but said the party has abandoned its heritage
the question (among democrats) has become whether we should bear any burden at all? will the liberal democrats pay even a small price, one reckoned in american money rather than american lives?'' he said
dole said, ``what we see on the democratic side of this presidential campaign is a failure of nerve as well as a failure of vision.''
he added, ``today we stand and watch as nicaragua slowly twists in the wind and the fate of the americas begins to tilt.'' ^by harry f. rosenthal</byline>
the club lady in illinois never knew what a flap she caused when she wrote the president of the united states asking to use air force one as a party room for the ``spectacular event'' she had to plan
frankly, we can't think of anything which would be more thrilling,'' she wrote to richard nixon, who was president then. ``you can land on our property, seven secluded acres.''
the letter, which has rested all these years in a file folder, was only one document out of 400,000 that were opened to public view for the first time tuesday by the national archives. but while hundreds of people begged for a ride on the presidential plane, it was the only one that asked to use it for something other than transportation
her answer came directly from ralph d. albertazzie, an air force colonel, who was the president's pilot
landing air force one on seven acres of ground would certainly be a spectacular event in itself!'' albertazzie wrote. ``i can only say for reasons far too numerous to enumerate: no.''
according to the records, that didn't sit too well with gen. james d. hughes, who was nixon's military aide. in a note, he chewed out the colonel for making light of ``a sincere effort on the part of the writer to score a million in one shot for her club.'' a chastened albertazzie replied, ``i've goofed,'' and a white house functionary wrapped up the whole thing with a note ``for obvious reasons, please keep this in your restricted file.''
a ride on the president's airplane, a blue and silver boeing 707 with ``the united states of america'' lettered boldly across each side, is the ultimate status symbol and a lot of americans want one
dear mr. president,'' one letter began. ``my nephew will be leaving shortly to start his three years as a law student at georgetown school of law in washington, d.c
with some of his money he purchased quite an expensive stereo with speakers and we are quite reluctant to ship, mail or whatever this item. is it permissible in any way for this stereo and speakers to be transported on air force one when you return to washington from your sojourn in california?''
no
i see you are flying to california and i wonder if i can hitch a ride,'' a young man wrote. ``i'm going there to see a girl i haven't seen in 14 months. i'm a small guy and i won't take up much space. all i'll have is a small suitcase and my guitar.''
no
correspondence and memos about air force one _ renamed ``the spirit of '76'' for a time in the nixon tenure _ fill a half-dozen thick file folders in the national archives. such requests undoubtedly come to every president
if politicians wanted to be seen on air force one _ and they did, desperately _ the white house reciprocated by using rides as a political tool
it is a prized thing to ride on air force one and we intend to keep it that way,'' said presidential appointments secretary dwight chapin in chewing out political adviser murray chotiner for inviting a congressman
no one is allowed to place a guest on the president's aircraft without prior approval of the president,'' chapin wrote
chapin also asked another presidential assistant for a memo ``detailing the responsibilities and duties of the hand-holder when he travels on air force one.'' hand-holders, chapin explained, are people carried on the plane ``for the purpose of massaging vips.''
another time, chapin complained to hughes that the wife of white house chief of staff h.r. haldeman ``was placed in a three-abreast seating area whereas there was a forward compartment with sundry military personnel in two-abreast and more comfortable seating.''
the pleasures of riding air force one were more image than comfort. a dozen memos complained about lousy food. others griped about the temperature in the cabin being too cold. in one, chapin groused that meals used to be served with crystal glasses and china and ``now, plastic seems to be the in-thing.''
there also was a curious memo from chotiner to chapin. he asked for a ride ``in the event the president has a plane going to california for his niece's wedding.'' a handwritten notation, signed only ``c,'' said, ``tell him the president isn't going _ but not to tell don nixon.''
whether chotiner got his ride or not isn't indicated. but nixon did attend the wedding of his brother's daughter, lawrene, and kissed the bride
the reagan administration said wednesday it would be premature to impose new economic sanctions on haiti because the new government of president leslie manigat ``has shown a determination to move haiti in a democratic direction.''
while the administration is not prepared to seek a lifting of sanctions imposed on haiti after election violence late last year, new incentives may be in order as the caribbean nation makes steps toward developing democratic institutions, said richard holwill, deputy assistant secretary of state for inter-american affairs
if we hope to play a constructive role in haiti ... we will be obliged to consider incentives as well as sanctions, and be willing to judge progress by specific interim milestones,'' holwill told a house foreign affairs subcommittee
we should not expect perfection before we offer assistance,'' he said
several members of congress have introduced legislation to impose a series of trade sanctions on haiti unless a more democratically elected government is installed. the sanctions include revocation of haiti's lucrative sugar quota and suspension of other trade preferences
but holwill said the legislation would be counterproductive. ``the haitian people..., not we, should determine the fate of the manigat government,'' he said. ``they now appear willing to give that government a chance.''
the administration last nov. 29 suspended all direct aid to haiti's government, leaving in place only humanitarian assistance operated through private organizations
the move cost haiti some $60 million in economic aid and about $2 million in military aid in the current fiscal year, the state department estimates, while about $36 million in humanitarian aid continues to flow
an unemployed streetsweeper who burned himself to death in a car near prime minister margaret thatcher's residence took his life in a ``futile gesture,'' a coroner said wednesday
westminster coroner paul knapman made the remark after an inquest ruled that derek bainbridge's death feb. 16 was a suicide
bainbridge, 40, who lived in worksop in central england, had been depressed about his inability to find work a year after leaving his job as a streetsweeper
i am quite satisfied he has taken his life in a rather dramatic but futile gesture,'' knapman said
on wednesday, bainbridge's brother visited mrs. thatcher's residence and presented a photograph of derek inscribed with the words from his suicide note, ``too young to retire ... too old to live.''
we are not a political family,'' said joseph bainbridge. ``but we want mrs. thatcher to see the man who died at the end of her road.''
unemployment in britain was 9.1 percent in february, down from 9.2 percent in january and 11 percent in february last year
congressional supporters will seek about $100 million in 1989 funding for the superconducting super collider project, around a third the amount requested by president reagan, rep. carl pursell, r-mich., said wednesday
pursell and house members from five other states hoping to win the project met to map strategy for pushing appropriations through congress
the $4.4 billion physics research center has been attacked by congressional critics, who argue the massive project would siphon away money needed by research in other areas
the energy department is expected to decide in november where to build the super collider
in his 1989 budget, reagan proposed spending $363 million on the facility.
congressional supporters of the project, however, are considering funding ``somewhere around the bottom of $100 million plus,'' pursell said after the private meeting. ``we have not fixed on exact figures.''
the house members also discussed target dates in their drive to ensure the project survives congressional budget cuts
as long as we've got good support from the leadership, we're sure we can get through the budget process,'' pursell said
the project proponents, members of an ad hoc task force, will meet soon with house speaker jim wright, d-texas, and minority leader robert michel, r-ill., to discuss appropriations for the facility, pursell said
the super collider, involving a 53-mile-circumference particle accelerator, will produce 4,000 jobs and have an annual operating budget of $279 million
physicists have said the project is necessary to gain a greater understanding of the physical structure of the universe
besides michigan, states that remain in the running for the project are arizona, colorado, illinois, north carolina, tennessee and texas
arizona was unrepresented at wednesday's meeting, pursell said
frank e. terpil, a fugitive former cia agent turned gunrunner, went to cuban four years ago and works for that country's intelligence service, a cuban defector says
maj. florentino aspillaga lombard, in an interview with the washington times published on wednesday, said terpil has helped the cuban dgi intelligence agency recruit americans and conduct counterintelligence operations
aspillaga, a career employee of the dgi until he defected to the united states last june, also said nicaragua's sandinista government is under the ``complete control'' of cuban leader fidel castro
at the time of his defection, which took place in vienna, austria, aspillaga was the head of the dgi in czechoslovakia
aspillaga said terpil ``travels with a cuban passport and was with me in czechoslovakia.'' the cuban said he hoped to bring terpil with him to vienna, but cuban intelligence officers blocked terpil from leaving the east bloc
terpil, a fugitive since 1980, was convicted in absentia in may 1981 of conspiring to sell machine guns to undercover agents posing as south american revolutionaries. he was sentenced to 53 years in prison
terpil and former cia agent edwin wilson were also charged with selling explosives to libyan leader moammar khadafy. wilson was convicted and sentenced in the case
after fleeing the united states, terpil was reported living in lebanon
the justice department spokesman john russell said he had no information about terpil's activities
bessie heard, who endowed her hometown with a wildlife sanctuary and natural science museum, has died, a museum spokesman said wednesday. she was 101
more than 40,000 visitors each year come to the heard natural science museum and wildlife sanctuary, which miss heard endowed in 1964. it includes more than five miles of nature trails, said steve runnels, the museum's director of development
the non-profit museum and sanctuary are funded by the bessie heard foundation, membership dues, tuition fees, gift shop sales and contributions
at the heart of the museum was ``miss bessie,'' as she was known for most of her life
miss heard died tuesday night at home, runnels said
she was born may 26, 1886, the eldest of five daughters. her father, john spencer heard, spent four years in the confederate army and then opened a general store in mckinney, north of dallas, with his brother
miss heard attended mary baldwin college in staunton, va., but spent most of her life in mckinney
survivors include two cousins. a funeral was scheduled friday
a man accused of making millions by selling worthless mail-order cures for ills from impotency to baldness to obesity has been banished from living and working in florida
mitchell friedlander, the 38-year-old owner of robertson-taylor co., entered pleas of no contest tuesday to 13 charges of operating a scheme to defraud
in return for his pleas, broward county circuit judge mel grossman, gave him a suspended one-year jail term, put him on probation for five years and barred him from doing business or living in florida
grossman withheld adjudication in the case, meaning friedlander will have no criminal record if he complies with probation terms. if he forms a corporation, owns retail outlets or warehouses, or obtains a mail drop in florida, he can be sent to prison
friedlander's mail-order company, which had 400,000 customers and grossed millions in sales, began operating from a fort lauderdale office in early 1984, police and his lawyer, william richey, said
through ads in national magazines, it offered pills and lotions to cure baldness, turn fat to muscle, relieve stress, increase breast size, dissolve cellulite, cure impotency, and provide the ``ultimate orgasmic experience.''
three months after the business opened, police began investigating customer complaints. in july 1985, police charged friedlander with 43 counts of racketeering, scheming to defraud, misleading advertising and cheating
six weeks later, he was charged with 70 new counts of fraud and grand theft after police searched his office
friedlander's no contest plea, which is not an admission of guilt, was prompted after grossman ruled that none of the evidence gathered during the search would be admissible at trial. the ruling wiped out 70 charges
the plea came as jury selection was beginning for trial
today, friedlander lives in atlanta, in debt, according to richey. workers</head>
washington _ federal collective-bargaining laws should take precedence over state laws protecting union employees who are fired for filing workers' compensation claims, a lawyer told the supreme court on wednesday
giving states the authority to govern union contracts ``would be a threat to collective bargaining,'' said charles c. jackson, a chicago attorney representing the norge division of magic chef inc
federal laws regulating collective bargaining agreements provide for arbitration to resolve unfair labor practices
but the lawyer for an illinois woman fired by norge said federal law never was intended to thwart state statutes prohibiting retaliatory firings
if this were (not) true, all states' rights could be channeled away by arbitration,'' lawyer paul alan levy contended
the supreme court agreed to weigh both arguments before ruling _ probably in july _ in the case of jonna lingle, who was fired in late 1984 from her job at herrin, ill
the woman had notified norge that she was injured on the job and asked the company, under the state workers' compensation law, to pay her medical bills. norge fired mrs. lingle a week later, contending she filed a false claim
however, her union contract contained a provision protecting workers from dismissal without just cause, and the union filed a grievance the day she was fired
an arbitrator ruled the firing violated the just-cause provision and ordered her reinstatement. but before the ruling was issued, mrs. lingle filed a lawsuit contending the dismissal was contrary to illinois law
the relief available through the courts was greater than what she could receive through arbitration, which did not include punitive damages and compensation for lost overtime
a u.s. district court judge threw out her lawsuit, ruling that the state law was pre-empted by the arbitration remedy available under federal labor law, and the 7th u.s. circuit court upheld the dismissal in june 1987
levy asked the supreme court to overturn the lower-court rulings
the right of action is available to both union and non-union employees alike,'' levy argued. ``if there is any state cause of action that is independent of a labor agreement, lingle's case ought to be one of them.''
but jackson said congress gave states authority to supercede federal law only on health and safety issues and said the power does not extend to rules against retaliatory firings
if independent state laws were enacted that flew in the teeth of a labor contract, they were pre-empted,'' he said. ``mrs. lingle's claim is exactly what arbitration is all about. this is why we have collective bargaining agreements.''
a brief filed on mrs. lingle's behalf by the state and local legal center in washington said 21 states and the district of columbia have laws protecting workers filing workers' compensation claims
it identified the states as california, connecticut, hawaii, illinois, louisiana, maine, massachusetts, minnesota, missouri, montana, new jersey, new york, north carolina, ohio, oklahoma, oregon, south carolina, texas, virginia, washington and wisconsin
bonnie blair, the olympic speed-skating champion, dispensed some blunt advice wednesday for girls whose boyfriends don't want them to be athletic:
tell them to go jump in the lake,'' said blair, who took the gold medal in the 500-meter race and bronze at 1,000 meters in calgary. ``maybe they're not worth having around.''
blair spoke at the city hall launch of a drive by the women's sports foundation to encourage girls to take part in a new athletic program at city high schools
