at times tearful during a news conference here wednesday, miss hepburn said she was moved not only by the ``ravages of the famine on the children'' but also by efforts being made by volunteers
the country suffers from two grave injustices,'' she said. ``one is man-made _ they get too little aid. and the other from god _ they get too little water. but i plan to talk to him.''
miss hepburn, recently named a special ambassador for the u.s. committee for unicef, will go to several american cities to help raise $22 million for the united nations children's fund
poet allen ginsberg says the reagan administration has spawned an era of ``troglodytes and fundamentalists,'' with the ``moral minority trying to control what the majority hears.''
speaking to a university of maine audience tuesday, ginsberg railed against a recent federal communications commission ruling that material judged to be indecent can be broadcast only between midnight and 6 a.m
the ruling has a ``chilling effect'' on broadcast programs of art and literature and ``reduces the listening radio public to the level of children,'' ginsberg said
the ruling stemmed from fcc action last november against three radio stations in california and pennsylvania, one of which scrapped plans to air part of ginsberg's controversial epic poem ``howl.''
actor-singer kris kristofferson denounced american policy in central america after returning from a visit to nicaragua
speaking to reporters at los angeles international airport tuesday, kristofferson, 51, said, ``i'm so sick of hearing the lies that are being told by our government and even by the so-called friends of nicaragua.''
kristofferson claimed the u.s. government had lied about nicaragua's recent incursion into neighboring honduras in an attack against american-backed contra rebels based there
he also lashed out at the american news media, saying he wished network television cameras would show the popular support in nicaragua for the sandinista government
nobel laureate elie wiesel canceled an appearance here after learning his fee would come from a grant by a conservative publisher once accused of being a south african agent
the nazi concentration camp survivor had been scheduled as a speaker today at the john mcgoff distinguished lecture series at northern michigan university
but mcgoff's alleged links to the south african government and the university's plan to pay wiesel's fee from a $300,000 grant from mcgoff brought protests from the school's faculty
when it comes to apartheid you cannot make compromises,'' wiesel said in explaining his decision. and dukakis. adds byline. no pickup.</note>
new jersey sen. bill bradley today endorsed the presidential bid of michael dukakis, calling the massachusetts governor the democrat's best hope against republican front-runner george bush in november
today i endorse michael dukakis for president of the united states,'' bradley said with the democratic hopeful by his side. ``i do so because among the candidates of both parties, he would make the best president. and among the democratic candidates, he is the one who can beat george bush.''
bradley, often mentioned as a possible dark-horse nominee if the democratic convention is deadlocked, said dukakis can defeat the vice president ``because he is tenacious, innovative, resilient and disciplined.''
and he has the personal depth and life experience that embodies the promise of america,'' he said
dukakis, who is expected to draw strong support in the state's june 7 primary election with the endorsement, welcomed bradley's decision
this is a very important endorsement because it comes from one of the most respected and one of the most accomplished public figures in america today.''
bradley made the sought-after endorsement in an old railroad terminal at liberty state park, in the shadow of the statue of liberty. the terminal, now a museum, was used at the turn of the century by immigrants who came through ellis island
dukakis' parents came through the new york entry point in 1913
bradley, a second-term senator, has declined repeated calls to enter the presidential race himself. a former rhodes scholar and pro-basketball star who is viewed as one of the democratic party's rising stars, bradley has said he is not ready to seek the presidency. dukakis; picks up 7th graf pvs, bgng: gephardt hammered...</note>
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis today picked up the endorsement of new jersey sen. bill bradley, once mentioned as a possible rival for the democratic presidential nomination
the endorsement came as dukakis' campaign was under attack from democratic and republican presidential candidates on issues ranging from trade to central america
bradley, who for months has fended off suggestions that he would enter the presidential race if no front-runner emerged, today called dukakis the ``candidate who can beat george bush.''
he can beat george bush because he is tenacious, innovative, resilient and disciplined and he has the personal depth and life experience tht embodies the promise of america,'' bradley said
dukakis, who appeared with bradley at a new jersey park, said the endorsement came from ``one of the most respected and one of tghe most accompliched pubblic figures in america today.''
meanwhile, democratic presidential contender richard gephardt today accused dukakis of talking tough on trade to entice michigan voters
bush, too, came under fire for supporting president reagan's veto of a major civil rights bill
gephardt, who has staked out michigan's caucuses on saturday to revive his battered presidential campaign, issued a statement today accusing dukakis of trying ``to have it both ways.''
he may talk tough on trade in michigan, but everywhere else he has opposed tough legislation,'' gephardt's statement said
and sen. bob dole, a candidate for the republican nomination, also attacked dukakis today for failing to stand up to soviet-backed subversion in central america
he says that the monroe doctrine, which has defined america's security in its own neighborhood for some 200 years, is `obsolete,''' dole said of dukakis. ``he said this country ... has no choice but to tolerate the existence of soviet client states wherever subversion might install them.''
gephardt hammered away at dukakis as a new poll suggested he trailed the massachusetts governor by a 2-1 margin in michigan, which holds democratic caucuses on saturday
according to the survey, dukakis had 35 percent; jesse jackson 29 percent; gephardt 17 percent; sen. albert gore jr. 6 percent and sen. paul simon 5 percent, with 9 percent undecided, detroit television station wjbk said tuesday night. the telephone poll of 400 democratic or independent voters, with a margin of error of 5 percentage points, was taken over the weekend
gephardt, who has made trade a campaign centerpiece, questioned the sincerity of dukakis' support for senate trade legislation, calling it a ``political ploy'' to win workers' votes in michigan
who is for a tough trade policy? who is going to be for a tough trade policy after michigan?'' gephardt asked. ``dick gephardt is. ... mike dukakis hasn't been, isn't and won't be.''
but the dukakis campaign countered with a tape-recorded interview in which dukakis praised the senate trade measure as long ago as last year
i think the senate bill, which is very, very different from the gephardt amendment, is sound policy. i would have voted for it,'' the governor told the des moines register on july 11
the dukakis camp also hinted that if gephardt keeps up the accusations, it will strike back. a dukakis aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said: ``our gun is loaded and ready if any salvos are fired at us.''
dukakis collected endorsements from connecticut gov. william o'neill and sen. christopher dodd on tuesday, a week before the state's primary. o'neill said he expected dukakis, who has won in every new england state so far, would do ``extremely well.''
meanwhile, a survey published in today's washington post suggested dukakis was the only democrat who could outpoll bush. fifty percent said they would vote for dukakis in an election held today and 45 percent said bush. the newspaper said the survey, conducted with abc news, had a margin of error of 4 percentage points
bush was the chief target of democrat gore, who faulted him for lacking the ``gumption'' to break with reagan over the president's veto of a civil rights bill, which congress overrode tuesday
gore interrupted his campaigning to fly back to washington and vote for the override, as did fellow democrat simon
when push comes to shove the vice president never disagrees with president reagan,'' gore said in traverse city, mich. ``he really has not carved out an identity of his own in this election.''
simon hailed the civil rights measure and attacked the white house for trying to quash it
it's another indication of the insensitivity of the administration to women, to people with disabilities, to minorities,'' simon said
jackson used the occasion to blast both reagan and bush
when you have a president who vetoes a civil rights act and a vice president who suports him, there's a leadership gap in washington,'' he told an audience at benton harbor high school in michigan
too many lives (were) lost in the struggle for civil rights to stand on the sideline while those policies are abandoned,'' said jackson, a onetime associate of slain civil rights leader martin luther king jr
bush announced on the eve of the veto vote that he supported the president, although he said he agreed with the main thrust of the bill. new jersey gov. thomas kean, who had endorsed bush just hours before the vice president sided with reagan, said tuesday it was time for bush to start speaking his mind
the vice president in this instance should have said publicly the way he felt. he said instead that he was going to be loyal to the president,'' kean said
bush wasn't the only one put on the spot by the veto override. bob dole, who did not vote on tuesday, said if he were casting the deciding vote he would have sided with the president. but he indicated tuesday night on cnn's ``larry king live'' that otherwise, he would have voted for the override
dole stressed he's not conceding the nomination _ yet _ but said he wouldn't mind if his wife, elizabeth, ended up on a ticket with bush
it would be all right with me,'' he said. ``i'd probably get a car and driver out of it.''
mrs. dole stepped down as transportation secretary to campaign for her husband
the government reported wednesday that the u.s. economy performed even better than previously thought from october through december, growing at a robust 4.8 percent rate which further eased fears of a recession triggered by the october stock market collapse
the commerce department said the increase in the gross national product, the total output of goods and services, was the fastest advance in almost two years and represented an upward revision from last month, when the gnp gain was put at a slightly lower 4.5 percent
especially encouraging to economists was the upward revision in particular sectors. the new gnp report said that both consumer spending and business investment were not as weak as previously feared and u.s. export sales were even stronger than originally reported
when the fourth quarter gnp report was first released, many economists expressed concern because the bulk of the growth came from production of unsold goods which was occurring at the same time that consumer spending was falling sharply
many analysts worried that this overhang of excess business inventories would cause a big drop in factory production and job layoffs at a time when consumers were already worried about the impact of the huge 508-point drop in the stock market which occurred on oct. 19
some analysts even forecast that a recession would start in early 1988, caused by weak consumer spending and falling industrial production
but the economic evidence so far this year shows those worries were overstated. many analysts, while still looking for significantly slower growth than last year, are now predicting the economy will get through this presidential election year without a downturn
one thing is clear _ the economy has shrugged off oct. 19 pretty well,'' said donald straszheim, chief economist for merrill lynch. ``we will not have a recession in 1988.''
the brighter economic outlook is certain to cheer republicans campaigning to hold onto the white house. president reagan, speaking to a group of business executives wednesday, boasted that the country is now in the midst of its longest peacetime economic recovery with the percentage of the labor force at work at an all-time high
with the new revisions, the economy during 1987 grew 4 percent, almost double the 2.2 percent increase turned in during 1986 and the best showing since 1984. this figure measures growth from the fourth quarter. averaging all the quarters, the gnp grew 2.9 percent in 1987, identical to 1986
the administration is forecasting gnp growth of 2.4 percent this year, with almost half of that gain expected to come from a further rise in export sales
private economists, whose original forecasts were well below that estimate, have been busy revising their own projections upward
william dunkelberg, dean of the business school at temple university, said he believed many private economists are still underestimating economic strength, citing the february unemployment report, which showed the jobless rate dropping to an 8{ year low of 5.7 percent
i think the economy is going to look a lot stronger in the first half of the year than people have been predicting,'' he said. ``we see tremendous strength in the export side of the economy.''
the 4.8 percent gnp growth in the fourth quarter followed growth of 4.3 percent in the july-september quarter and was the fastest quarterly growth rate since an increase of 5.4 percent in the first three months of 1986
the rapid growth occurred without a pick-up in inflation. a price index tied to the gnp rose at an annual rate of 3.6 percent in the fourth quarter, little changed from a 3.4 percent third quarter increase
in a second report, the commerce department said u.s. corporations' after-tax profits rose 1.6 percent in the fourth quarter, closing out a year in which business profits shot up 8.4 percent, reflecting the boom in export sales that boosted the fortunes of american manufacturing companies
the state council on the arts, under fire for funding homosexual-oriented art projects, espouses freedom of expression and not points of view, chairwoman kitty carlisle hart said wednesday
the process is like democracy,'' the actress told a joint legislative committee hearing. ``it may not be perfect, but it's the best thing we've got.''
hart was summoned before the assembly and senate arts committees following a new york post report last week that the council had provided $7,200 to help pay for a photographic exhibit on transvestism sponsored by the national gay and lesbian task force fund for human dignity
other council grants went to create an archive on gay and lesbian writers and to fund a feminist magazine with an emphasis on writing by lesbians
hart, who complained of being put on the ``hot seat,'' said the council supports a variety of groups in the name of artistic expression
we fund art,'' she said. ``we are neutral as far as anyone else is concerned. we don't fund anyone's point of view.''
about 100 spectators watched the hearing, with the majority applauding lawmakers who defended hart's viewpoint
assemblyman philip healy said the arts council should show ``delicacy and discretion'' in how it spends taxpayers' money. he said he sees ``an element of propaganda creeping in'' with some of the programs funded
to have only one side portrayed on any level, be it the war in nicaragua or lesbians, shows a lack of judgment,'' healy said. ``i don't know if this was an overt act or a mistake. i hope it's a mistake.''
fellow republican assemblyman frank talomie said the arts council should have a greater system of checks and balances to ensure proper funding decisions
i think there's a concern regarding the public's best interests and the taxpayers' dollar ... that we have to go back and justify to our constituents,'' he said
hart said each funding request is reviewed by the arts council staff and a ``peer group committee'' before it is approved or turned down by the 20-member council. council members are appointed by the governor and serve without salary
mary hays, the council's executive director, said the council funded 3,633 different programs last year from 6,000 requests
i defy you to find any prejudice or imbalance in what we do,'' she said
the environmental protection agency will not use data from a nazi poison-gas experiment on prisoners of war and will study whether such data should ever be used, an agency official said wednesday
the decision was prompted by a letter to epa administrator lee m. thomas from 20 agency employees, many of them scientists, asking that the issue be studied and the report in which the data appeared be put on hold
we don't need this kind of data,'' was thomas' response, according to craig deremer, an assistant to the administrator
the gas is phosgene, used as a weapon in world war i and used today in the production of other chemicals. there is a wealth of data from animal experiments and other human exposure
deremer said thomas was ordering a study of the issue, probably by the agency's risk assessment forum, an interoffice group that tries to forge common policies in epa's programs
this has not been nailed down yet,'' deremer said wednesday
epa has listed phosgene, which forms hydrochloric acid in the lungs, among the most toxic 406 chemicals that communities should consider in disaster planning
small quantities can be deadly since effects may take three or four hours to appear. the occupational safety and health administration permits exposure of only 0.1 part per million over an eight-hour shift and says 2 ppm represents ``imminent danger to life or health.''
the agency is considering whether to add phosgene to the airborne chemicals it regulates, and as part of that work asked a consultant to ``validate some computer models,'' deremer said. it was the consultants' report that prompted the letter to thomas
the report of the consultant, icf-clement inc., referred to the findings of a french military court which tried those responsible for exposing french prisoners to phosgene, according to one of the signers of the letter who saw the report, microbiologist morris levin
levin said he believed the consultant found the court report in its own research, but deremer said he understood epa officials had called it to the attention of icf-clement when they discussed the work to be performed
the icf-clement vice president in charge did not immediately return two telephone calls wednesday
some have suggested that such data, if scientifically sound, and verifiable, should be used if some `good' to humans can result,'' the letter to thomas said. ``others feel that to use such data debases us all as a society, gives such experiments legitimacy and implicitly encourages others, perhaps in less exacting societies, to perform unethical human `experiments.'''
his own view, levin said, had changed in discussions in the group of 20 from acceptance of use to the belief that such findings should never be used. the use of radiation data by epa and others from the u.s. nuclear bombing of hiroshima and nagasaki, japan, in 1945 is ``not in the same category, but close,'' levin said
the german phosgene results, he said, are ``useless. they had no proper controls (an untested group used for comparisons) and no idea what the dose was until halfway through. if anyone had brought us those results from mice, we would have said, `do it over.'''
a former army captain who was paraguay's most famed political prisoner fled virtual house arrest wednesday with the help of two opposition leaders and sought asylum in the colombian embassy residence
colombian ambassador vicente ramirez emiliani told the associated press a diplomatic note had been sent to the paraguayan foreign ministry advising that napoleon ortigoza had taken refuge in the residence and asked for political asylum
the colombian government will proceed to study the situation,'' he said, adding that he did not know how long that might take
hermes rafael saguier, a leader of the opposition authentic radical liberal party, said he and attorney felino amarilla went to see ortigoza, 56, at the home where he has been held under armed guard since completing a 25-year prison sentence for his involvement in a 1962 slaying and an alleged plot against president alfredo stroessner
at first the guards wouldn't let us in or let ortigoza out,'' saguier said by telephone from the embassy residence
then we asked ortigoza if he was prepared to recover his freedom and he said `yes,' and we forced our way past the guards and put him in a car and drove him to the residence of the colombian ambassador,'' saguier said
the last thing we heard were three or four shots,'' saguier added. ``i can't tell you for sure because we were too scared to listen.''
saguier said no one was injured
the opposition leader, whose party is a frequent critic of the 34-year-old stroessner government, said the colombian residence was chosen because it is only a block and a half from where ortigoza was confined
half a dozen armed police blocked the entrance to the embassy residence
ortigoza was released from an asuncion prison on dec. 19 and confined in a hotel in san estanislao, 135 miles northeast of asuncion. on feb. 9, he was taken to asuncion and confined under guard in a house belonging to his invalid mother
saguier said he and amarilla decided to remove ortigoza from the home after attorney general clotildo jimenez benitez told reporters tuesday that the ortigoza case was closed and the former captain was ``in complete freedom.''
questioned about the presence of armed guards at the house, the attorney general said they had been there to protect ortigoza and not restrict him
ortigoza was sentenced to 25 years in prison in 1962 after he confessed to having participated in the slaying of army cadet alberto benitez. also convicted in the case was sgt. guillermo ovando, who was freed in 1984 after spending 21 years behind bars
the former captain, who never was allowed to appear in court in his own defense, maintains his confession was obtained under torture
paraguayan human rights leaders have said ortigoza's imprisonment was meant by the government to serve as a lesson to those who might conspire against stroessner's authoritarian rule
the police van's megaphone issued a strange warning to the crowd of over 100 people hovering around the manhattan exit from the queens midtown tunnel early wednesday
do yourself a favor and don't touch the cages.''
up from under the river came ringling bros. and barnum &amp; bailey circus' annual three-mile parade of animals as the big top moved into madison square garden for a six-week run
the caged lions and tigers came first, 14 of them in two strands of cages linked together and pulled by trucks
living things in manhattan that are not people, and are not cockroaches!'' yelled amy slaton, a 30-year-old art critic. ``this is the happiest night of my life.''
the crowd roared as the 19 elephants walked out of the tunnel. the cry went up, ``wooo-oooo! elephants! elephants! aaaall right!''
richard dunne, a 37-year-old lawyer from baltimore, bought his seat atop one of the elephants in a charity auction
it was like a gigantic horse,'' dunne said. ``it's so fresh for new york. everyone is smiling and happy, even the cops were happy.''
after the elephants came 15 horses, five zebras and six camels
inevitably, the rear was brought up by a department of sanitation street sweeper
a former new yorker living here was astonished when a denver policeman showed up at his front door, apologized and ripped up a four-point traffic citation he had issued just a day earlier
in new york, this just doesn't happen. i couldn't believe it,'' said joe milotta, 34
but the action by patrolman glen miller, an eight-year veteran, didn't surprise deputy chief cliff stanley
he has, on more than one occasion, admitted his mistakes,'' stanley said. ``police officers are human and we do admit our mistakes. in fact, we encourage it.''
miller said he mistook milotta's car for a similar vehicle that used an emergeny lane to avoid morning rush-hour traffic on march 9
rush county farmer andy ariens has a built-in barometer so accurate it has earned him a countywide reputation as an ace weather prognosticator
i told trudy before we got married, `now, there's something you need to understand about me,''' said ariens, 56. `` `whenever there's a storm on the way, i'll go off to bed and i'll just sleep right through it. i may sleep all afternoon and all night long if you let me.'''
ariens also reads the winds and watches the behavior of animals and insects to predict mother nature's plans. he said if he sees an ant cover its hole or if cows refuse to graze, he knows it is going to rain
neighbors say ariens has a 90 percent accuracy rate. he correctly predicted the ice storm that coated central indiana march 3
so what's his forecast?
in two weeks, we'll have above-normal temperatures, say around the first of april,'' ariens said recently. ``it'll be a wetter spring than last year, so planting season should be a little later.''
the last two weeks of spring will be quite cool with below normal temperatures, he added
an avalanche hit a group of skiers in the stubai valley of tyrol province on wednesday, killing one person and injuring six others, authorities said
the victims were part of a 17-member swiss ski group. the injured were flown by helicopter to an innsbruck clinic
a group of austrian army soldiers who happened to be near the accident site dug out the people buried by the snowslide
the men wore firefighting gear, and a fire truck was parked on the street, but the ``firefighters'' served a search warrant and made an arrest on drug charges
the men were deputies disguised to trick occupants of the house into opening the door. it worked, but it made fire officials angry
orange county fire chief john hunt said he didn't know one of his subordinates had lent the truck, and he said he would not permit a recurrence
people could become suspicious that firefighters are really police, and real firefighters could come under fire,'' he said
and hunt's boss, deputy county administrator phil brown, said tuesday that nobody told the deputy sheriffs they could use the coats, hats and boots firefighters wear
police officials disagreed
we're not at all upset about the way we did this. we got two stolen guns and some drugs off the street,'' said sheriff's spokesman randy means
i don't think there is any threat to firefighter safety,'' said sheriff's sgt. mike foreman. ``this was the safest way to execute the search warrant. it involved us not having to make any forced entry.''
the head of the 427-member firefighters' union, jerry polk, said he wouldn't object in some situations, such as those involving hostages
let's say there was a kid in there and the police needed a decoy to get in. that is within the realm of reasonable judgment,'' polk said. ``but going into the criminal community is a daily occurrence the police world deals with. to intermingle the fire department, which has no protection, well, that's not a very smart move.''
deputies arrested sammie battle, 66, on a charge of possession of cocaine. they said they found less than a fifth of an ounce of rock cocaine. also seized were two stolen guns. battle was released on bond
mikhail s. gorbachev called for greater freedom for collective farmers and other cooperatives wednesday to rejuvenate the soviet union's struggling agricultural sector and enable the nation to feed itself
gorbachev called the possibilities of cooperatives a ``brilliant discovery'' of soviet founder vladimir i. lenin that had been underused, and even despised, by subsequent rulers
we should revive co-ops not in their old, often too-primitive forms, but in the form of a modern, high-standard cooperative movement extensively integrated ... with government-run enterprises and organizations,'' he said, speaking at the first national congress of collective farmers to be held since 1969
the soviet leader's remarks opening the three-day session in the kremlin were carried by the official tass news agency and broadcast on state-run tv
collective farms, where members of a cooperative jointly own farm buildings and machinery and share in earnings, have faded in recent decades in favor of state farms, where workers, like employees in a factory, have traditionally received a basic wage
there were 33,000 collective farms, or ``kolkhozes,'' in the soviet union in 1970, but their number dropped to 26,300 by 1986. in that same period, the number of collective farmers dropped from 16.7 million to 12.6 million
gorbachev has been striving to persuade soviets to enter into cooperative ventures to make up for shortages in the state-run economy. under reforms instituted last year, nearly 14,000 cooperatives have sprung up to offer restaurant services, pump gas, make clothes and provide other goods and services in short supply
starting in the late 1920s, when josef v. stalin was soviet leader, cooperatives were liquidated and kolkhozes were transformed into state-owned farms. a taste for giant state-run enterprises was accompanied by bans on private farm plots, gorbachev said
the consequences of such an attitude to kolkhozes, to cooperatives as a whole, are well-known,'' he said. ``to it must be laid the delayed solution of the food problem, the deficit and narrowness of an assortment of many consumer goods, the limited nature of the service sector.''
soviet agriculture has been plagued for decades by central planners who tell farms what and how much to plant, lack of incentives for farmers to work the state-owned land, inefficient production, and poor storage and transportation facilities
gorbachev said grain harvests, meat production and milk supplies are improving, but the soviet union still is forced to spend millions of dollars of its hard currency every year for imported grain
a wider role for kolkhozes and co-op ventures should help the country become self-sufficient in foodstuffs, gorbachev said
by breeding the feeling of ownership, initiative and enterprise, co-ops are able to render substantial help in solving the food problem, in increasing the output of good-quality consumer goods,'' gorbachev said
to define the widened prerogatives and responsibilities now envisioned for cooperatives, a draft law was published this month in the press that prohibits government interference in their affairs
gorbachev said the new law aims to ``ensure the enhancement and development of cooperative and collective-farm property (and) create legal machinery to protect cooperative democracy.''
he said, however, that the land farmed by kolkhoz members would continue to belong to the state. the law also foresees a progressive tax system to catch what gorbachev has called ``money-grabbing.''
his re-emphasis on cooperatives is a result of greater democracy in soviet society and ``an important lever for furthering the democratic process and combatting administration by fiat and red tape,'' he said
gorbachev, the son of a south russian peasant, was the communist party official responsible for agriculture before becoming the party's general secretary in march 1985
he said it was essential to increase the growth rate of grain harvests by at least 50 percent and to begin harvesting from 260 million to 280 million tons of grain annually under the next five-year economic plan, in 1990-95
grain harvests for the past two years have been about 210 million tons, well above figures for the previous several years but below the government targets of about 240 million tons, which western experts regard as unrealistic
he also stressed the importance of the small individual plots whose produce soviet farmers are allowed to sell for themselves, and called for steps to help people manage them
gorbachev said the ruling politburo had decided to hold a special meeting of the central committee, the party's policy-making body, to consider national agricultural policy
reforms enacted last year permit the farms to sell directly to shops and restaurants up to 30 percent of the fruits and vegetables planners require them to produce. excess production can be sold at farmers' markets, where prices are not controlled, or to state stores
aix-en-provence, france (ap) _ a criminal court wednesday ordered prison terms or fines for three men convicted of attacking several amateur swiss football players during a brawl in may
marco bagarri, 27, was sentenced to 18 months in prison, with 16 months suspended, according to court officials. guy distanti, 35, was given an eight-month suspended sentence and fined $890. distanti's brother, alexandre, 38, was given a one-month suspended sentence and an equal fine
the men were involved in a fight during a football match in the southern city of fos-sur-mer in which several footballers from the swiss canton of vaud were injured. update with bradley endorsement, comments from senator and dukakis.</note>
michael dukakis, fighting to establish himself as the democratic presidential front-runner, picked up a key endorsement wednesday but also came under fire from rival richard gephardt for his trade views and from republican bob dole for a ``failure of vision'' on foreign policy
new jersey sen. bill bradley, once mentioned as a possible candidate for the democratic nomination, announced his support for dukakis at an old railroad terminal in jersey city, n.j
among the candidates of both parties, he would make the best president. and among the democratic candidates he is the one who can beat george bush,'' bradley said with the candidate by his side
the senator said dukakis can defeat the vice president in november ``because he is tenacious, innovative, resilient and disciplined.''
dukakis, who is expected to draw strong support in the state's june 7 primary election with the endorsement, called bradley's decision ``a very important endorsement because it comes from one of the most respected and one of the most accomplished public figures in america today.''
dole, setting aside his attacks on republican rival george bush, focused on the democrats in general and dukakis in particular in a foreign policy speech at the center for strategic and international studies in washington
after the speech, dole flew to hartford, conn., to address the state legislature, but before he landed, top connecticut gop officials announced their backing of bush for the presidential nomination
bush and dukakis were heavily favored to win most of the delegates at stake next tuesday when connecticut holds its presidential primary
in his washington speech, dole said dukakis ``says that the monroe doctrine, which has defined america's security in its own neighborhood for some 200 years, is `obsolete.' he said this country ... has no choice but to tolerate the existence of soviet client states wherever subversion might install them.''
the kansas senator went on to say that ``what we see on democratic side of this presidential campaign is a failure of nerve as well as a failure of vision.''
michigan, which holds democratic caucuses on saturday, was the next major battleground for dukakis and his rivals, and gephardt was hammering away at the massachusetts governor for allegedly waffling on trade
the gephardt campaign produced a sheaf of dukakis quotes opposing trade legislation and used them to support the missouri congressman's contention that dukakis' support for senate trade legislation was a ``political ploy'' to win workers' votes in michigan
the president of the united states today has all the authority he needs to do something about those unfair trade practices,'' gephardt quoted dukakis as saying during a debate last august in iowa. ``we don't need more laws or more amendments.''
campaigning in michigan, gephardt asked, ``who is for a tough trade policy? who is going to be for a tough trade policy after michigan? dick gephardt is. ... mike dukakis hasn't been, isn't and won't be.''
the dukakis campaign produced a tape-recorded interview in which dukakis praised the senate trade measure as long ago as last year
i think the senate bill, which is very, very different from the gephardt amendment, is sound policy. i would have voted for it,'' the governor told the des moines register on july 11
a new michigan poll commissioned by detroit television station wjbk said dukakis was leading in the state with 35 percent support. jesse jackson had 29 percent; gephardt 17 percent; sen. albert gore jr. 6 percent and sen. paul simon 5 percent, with 9 percent undecided
connecticut gop state chairman robert s. poliner announced his support for bush, saying, ``among republicans i believe george bush has the best chance of winning the presidency in 1988.''
i'm sure that a connecticut ticket led by george bush and (u.s. sen.) lowell weicker will be strongly supported by many independents and democrats as well as most republicans, and will give connecticut republicans a chance to increase our numbers in congress and in the state legislature,'' poliner added, predicting that bush would take 25 of the 35 connecticut delegates at stake in next week's primary
a poll published wednesday by the hartford courant showed bush favored by 64 percent of likely gop voters, while his nearest rival, dole, is the choice of 20 percent. the margin of error for the random sampling of 432 likely republican voters was 5.5 percent
gore also talked about trade as he toured a giant iron ore processing plant in ishpeming, mich. and said, ``we have to take steps to remove unfair trade barriers overseas.''
in london, democrats living overseas picked a largely uncommitted delegation to the party's national convention. dukakis, who won a non-binding preference poll, picked up a fraction of a delegate
democrats abroad send 22 delegates to the convention, where they will cast nine votes. nine of those delegates were uncommitted, one was backing dukakis
corporations' after-tax profits shot up 8.4 percent in 1987, the best performance in three years, as american manufacturers benefited from the weaker dollar, the government reported wednesday
the commerce department said after-tax profits rose to $137.4 billion last year, the first increase since a 12 percent rise in 1984
in 1985, corporate profits plunged 12.3 percent and they dipped another 1 percent in 1986 as the widening trade deficit cut into sales by american manufacturing firms
u.s. companies have been enjoying an export boom this past year as declines in the dollar made american products competitive again on overseas markets
for u.s. manufacturing, 1987 was a turnaround year. exports rose and american companies benefited tremendously from previous cost-cutting measures,'' said allen sinai, chief economist for the boston co
analysts said the rise in profits was particularly significant because it occurred at the same time corporate taxes were being boosted substantially by the landmark 1986 tax overhaul law
sinai predicted further gains in corporate profits in 1988, estimating they should rise by between 6 percent and 7 percent
we will see continued increases in corporate profits until the start of the next recession,'' he said
the report said the dividends corporations paid to stockholders rose along with their improved profit picture, increasing 8.1 percent to $93.8 billion. this followed a 6.8 percent increase in dividends paid out in 1986
for the fourth quarter, after-tax profits rose 1.6 percent at a quarterly rate following a 5.5 percent increase in the third quarter
corporate leaders on wednesday described the nightmares of doing business with federal agencies that refuse to pay their bills on time, and pleaded with congress to crack down on washington's bureaucratic deadbeats
small businesses cannot afford to carry any customer for an indefinite period of time, even if it is the u.s. government,'' joseph a. schaedel of the national federation of independent business told a house hearing
kenton pattie of the international communications industries association said the defense department was more than 19 months late paying its $1,424.15 bill to a small virginia supplier, and didn't pay the delinquent penalty required by law
worse, he said, an alabama company waited nearly two years before the air force paid the $8,833 due for some playground equipment, after sen. howell heflin, d-ala., was enlisted to exert pressure
when the air force check finally arrived, the company was cheated out of $648.21 in interest penalties
one contractor, frustrated after waiting three months for the navy to pay for a shipment of steel pipe, drove a truck to the main gate at the philadelphia naval shipyard and told guards: ``we want it back!'' the navy returned the goods, pattie said
an august 1986 report by the general accounting office, the investigative arm of congress, estimated that 24 percent of all federal agency bills were unpaid for more than 30 days
members of a house government operations subcommittee listened sympathetically as other legislators and witnesses for small businesses, industrial contractors and trade associations urged congress to close loopholes in the 1982 prompt payment act, which requires the federal government to pay its bills within 30 days
the witnesses endorsed amendments, which the senate approved unanimously last october, that would provide a stricter statutory definition of when a federal agency receives an invoice, which triggers the 30-day time clock for payment
the senate bill also would set a five-day limit for an agency to accept or reject a supplier's goods or services; eliminate a 15-day grace period for payment of late penalties; require automatic payment of penalties with a double penalty if not paid within 10 days; and prohibit agencies from taking an early-payment discount after payment is due
raymond s. wittig of the u.s. chamber of commerce said the government's late payment of bills causes the most damage to small businesses, which lack large capital funds and depend heavily on cash flow to finance their operations
they often do not have the resources to battle the federal bureaucracy over late or incorrect payments,'' wittig said. ``as a result, small businesses concentrate on selling to customers who pay on time.''
he added: ``if the government does not pay on time, all taxpayers and citizens are injured because fewer businesses choose to sell to the government. this decreased competition raises the costs of goods and services purchased by the government.'' recipients ^for release at 6 p.m. est, time set by source</head>
scientists have triggered disease-fighting defenses in bone marrow transplant recipients with an experimental procedure, a scientist said wednesday
the recipients had their immune system defenses raised against poisons that are produced by tetanus and diphtheria bacteria, showing they benefited from vaccines given marrow donors a week before the marrow was harvested, said albert donnenberg of johns hopkins university in baltimore
those diseases are not particular problems in marrow recipients, but the experiment suggests that a similar process might one day protect against potentially lethal fungal and viral infections that do appear in recipients, he said
recipients had to be immunized within 35 days of their marrow transplants, or else the transferred immunity was lost, he said
donnenberg described results to science writers at a seminar sponsored by the american cancer society
marrow transplants are performed in cases where radiation or chemotherapy for cancer is powerful enough to destroy a patient's own marrow. bone marrow produces the white blood cells of the immune system, as well as red blood cells and platelets
the experiment included 38 recipients who got marrow from immunized donors that was then treated with a technique designed to prevent graft-versus-host disease. this is a potentially fatal complication in which immune system cells from transplanted marrow attack the recipient's body
the technique uses a centrifuge to strip the marrow of about 99 percent of the white blood cells called lymphocytes that cause graft-versus-host disease
the experiment, designed to look for side effects rather than effectiveness, found the technique did little to reduce the incidence of the disease. but it did appear to reduce the number of moderate to severe cases in comparison to standard experience with non-treated marrow, donnenberg said
the transfer of vaccine effects from donor to recipient occurred because the processing of the marrow enriched it, in the lymphocytes remaining, with a ``memory'' for the vaccine, donnenberg said
such transfer has been shown before, said david golde, chief of hematology and oncology at the university of california, los angeles, school of medicine
a key research problem now is how to retain some disease-fighting capability in marrow recipients but not enough to trigger graft-versus-host disease, he said in a telephone interview
another study reported at the meeting found that cancer patients whose marrow had been destroyed by therapy regained marrow function after injections of their own blood cells
such injections may allow aggressive cancer treatment in patients who cannot get marrow transplants or store some of their own marrow for use after cancer treatment, said margaret kessinger of the university of nebraska college of medicine in omaha
marrow transplant experts said the technique's near-term usefulness would be limited, but that it may have potential for wider use
kessinger said the experimental technique begins with extracting white blood cells from a patient's blood
the goal is to harvest a kind of cell called the pluripotent stem cell, which essentially replaces lost bone marrow
kessinger described a study of 26 patients who went through that procedure and received the injections of blood cells, rather than marrow, after cancer therapy
in comparison to 83 patients whose marrow had been harvested by conventional means and later returned, the experimental group first showed white cells in the blood three days sooner, for an average of eight days after the procedure, she said
both groups took the same amount of time to recover other marrow function, she said
the world's only coon dog graveyard may need the help of some patrol hounds to keep vandals at bay
caretakers of the key underwood coon dog memorial graveyard in northwest alabama say vandals have damaged the unique tombstones and littered the tourist attraction with beer and soda cans, the florence timesdaily reported sunday
it used to happen just once in a while,'' william o. bolton of russellville, secretary-treasurer of the tennessee valley coon hunters association, told the newspaper. ``but it's been happening more frequently lately.''
underwood started the graveyard when he buried his coon dog troop on the 10-acre site in 1937. many of the graves are marked with elaborate epitaphs, stones with statues of dogs or wooden crosses
i just think some people are jealous for some reason,'' said bolton. ``i think they go out there and drink beer and smoke pot, and i guess they want to do something bad before they leave.''
erecting a tall fence around the graveyard, as some people have suggested, is not a solution because it would discourage visitors, he said
the kremlin on wednesday rejected demands by armenians who want to control an area of neighboring azerbaijan, and it threatened to crack down on armenian activists who cause further ethnic unrest
the presidium of the supreme soviet, the country's highest executive body, did not directly address armenian demands to annex the nagorno-karabakh region of azerbaijan. but it made it clear that the government would not bend to pressure to change internal borders
at least 32 people were killed in riots after armenians demanded that the predominantly armenian section of azerbaijan be united with armenia. aremenians are mostly christian while the azeris are mostly moslem
in what appeared to be the soviet union's definitive statement on the territorial dispute, the presidium ordered government ministries to make efforts to improve ``the economic, social and cultural development of the nagorno-karabakh autonomous region.''
armenian activists have said such efforts would not meet their demands
the meeting, attended by soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev, president andrei a. gromyko and other senior officials, was held after carefully orchestrated appeals by 13 soviet other republics
a statement carried by the tass news agency said it was ``intolerable'' to use pressure to ``resolve complicated national-territorial issues.''
such actions can lead to ``unpredictable consequences,'' tass said
armenians held a series of large protests in february to demand that nagorno-karabakh, which is three-quarters armenian, be annexed from azerbaijan. ethnic rioting broke out in the azerbaijani city of sumgait on feb. 28, and officials said 32 people were killed
armenian activists put the death toll at 78 armenians, killed by azerbaijanis. most armenians are christian, while azerbaijanis are predominantly shiite moslem
the soviet officials condemned violence that caused loss of life and also called on armenian and azerbaijani officials to ``bring to strict account those who by their actions destabilize the situation.''
that statement appeared to indicate an impending crackdown on armenian activists and on those arrested for taking part in violence
in early february, the policy-making communist party central committee turned down an appeal by armenians to annex nagorno-karabakh. but gorbachev promised in a feb. 26 speech that the region's problems would be considered when the central committee meets to discuss problems between the soviet union's nationalities
as recently as march 17, communist party officials in nagorno-karabakh appealed for permission to join the armenian republic
before the government's decision wednesday, armenian activists had been planning a meeting for march 26 to determine their course of action
wednesday's pronouncement was seen as an attempt to discourage further protests
the presidium said armenian and azerbaijani officials must speak out against any ``nationalistic or extremist manifestation,'' protect the rights of citizens of all nationalities. it ordered armenia, azerbaijan, the national prosecutor's office and the interior ministry to ensure order
the soviet leadership also demanded that armenian and azerbaijani officials drastically improve their political and education work to ensure that riots do not happen again
the presidium's pronouncement came at a time when the official press had started to sharply criticize armenian activists
the activists said 7,000 people turned out in yerevan on monday to protest an article by the communist party daily newspaper pravda that said the annexation campaign had a ``clear anti-socialist spirit.''
y. arakyelan, an armenian correspondent whose name was one of three attached to the article, later disassociated himself from it
at a news conference sponsored by the soviet foreign ministry, yulian bromley, director of the soviet union's institute of ethnic studies, indicated that top government and party officials soon would establish an apparatus for handling differences between soviet republics after many years of pretending they did not exist
but he and the institute's deputy director, solomon bruk, said transferring territory from one republic to another would not help gorbachev's effort to restructure soviet society. bruk said economic development rather than ethnic differences would be a more likely reason for any changes in internal borders
earlier wednesday moscow authorities sent home an armenian activist who had been providing foreign journalists with information about the unrest
alexander ogorodnikov, a moscow religious activist, said paryur arikyan was put on a plane for yerevan, the armenian capital
while the sandinistas and contras worked wednesday on a cease-fire and journalists waited for scraps of information, the sleepy village of sapoa stayed sleepy
tight security segregated the international press corps of about 150 journalists and most the 2,000 residents of this town about 90 miles from managua on the costa rican border
the delegations met in the main customs house at the border crossing, the only building big enough for the talks
covering the negotiations, which began monday, has meant hours of waiting punctuated by frenzied activity. whenever negotiators leave the customs house, cross the blacktop road and mount a makeshift stage, photographers shove and push for position as writers grab for pens and notebooks
otherwise, the press waits in the constant wind blowing off lake managua, said to harbor the world's only freshwater sharks
some reporters meandered down to the lake. others went to san juan del sur to work on their tans. one slept in a hammock tied to a utility pole
but most passed the time chatting, reading, writing or sipping beer bought with u.s. dollars, costa rican colones or nicaraguan cordobas from a snack bar the government set up in a storage room
another room held the phones for international calls the government had installed for the talks. payment _ in u.s. dollars _ had to be on the spot
the contra delegation is staying in liberia, costa rica, about 37 miles miles away
they arrive each day in a pale green schoolbus with smoked windows accompanied by costa rican and sandinista security agents and with contra fighters in u.s.-made fatigues flanking the leader of the delegation, alfredo cesar
nicaragua's state-run radio sandino, which is heard here, refers to the contras as the ``delegation of the u.s. government.'' radio impacto, a u.s.-financed station in costa rica that broadcasts the contra point of view, can also be picked up in sapoa
the sandinista delegation, headed by defense minister humberto ortega, arrives in four-wheel drive vehicles with motorcycle escorts. the sandinistas are staying in san juan del sur, a beach town on the pacific ocean about 10 miles away
one report said phone lines there were cut as a security measure
sandinista security has been tight along the panamerican highway, but the border crossing itself has stayed open throughout the talks
journalists are searched by state security agents and issued credentials each day at a site about a mile away, then bused to the scene of the talks, a complex of customs buildings next to the village
most of the area is closed to reporters, roped off by security agents. the governnment set up a covered press area outdoors, across a road from the customs house
japan and the nato allies are doing more to ensure the free world's security than they get credit for, but the administration will continue to press them to assume a larger share of the burden, defense secretary frank c. carlucci said wednesday
in a 14-page report requested by congress, carlucci said, ``i intend to follow up personally on this issue and to reiterate at every opportunity the need for progress in improving both allied defense capabilities and the equity with which the roles, risks and burdens of the alliance are shared.''
carlucci, while promising a more extensive report later this spring, said it appeared that japan and eight european countries might have increased their defense spending by 3 percent or more in 1987 _ matching the nato goal
he identified the eight as greece, italy, luxembourg, norway, spain, turkey, france and portugal
only greece, however, appears to be allocating as much of its gross national product to defense as the united states ``and there are substantial variations in the performance among the individual allies,'' carlucci wrote
while some are doing at least their fair share, others are making a contribution that can best be characterized as mixed, and a few are doing far less than their fair share,'' he continued
progress to date has likewise been mixed, with the good performers generally making the greatest improvements in their defense postures while the others fall further behind.''
