it did not say what form the aid should take or whether it would be forthcoming
iran claims the rebellion is inspired by islam, but observers say opposition to israeli occupation is the chief motivation
authorities have reopened hueco tanks to rock climbers, ending a three-week moratorium that gave rangers time to remove bolts climbers hammered into the rock to aid tricky maneuvers
park officials had feared the bolts might have destroyed ancient indian rock paintings, but said they found no damage
hours after the moratorium was lifted friday, park rangers were fielding calls from as far as europe
hueco tanks is one of two good winter-climbing spots in the united states,'' david cottom, spokesman for the texas parks and wildlife department, said wednesday. ``the world climbing community is tight-knit; you wouldn't believe how fast word gets around.''
officials closed the 860-acre park about 35 miles east of el paso to climbers after rangers discovered the steel bolts they said had been placed mostly by european visitors. some climbers had even used epoxy to create handholds and footholds on the sheer rock faces
climbers often embed bolts into rock to secure safety ropes. most climbers use bolts only to halt falls and consider it cheating to use them as handholds or footholds
a lot of (bolts) are for safety, but these aren't for safety,'' said ranger bob parker, pointing at three bolts in the face of a 30-foot-high boulder. ``bolts like these are for acrobatics. that's what we disagree with.''
rangers removed 23 bolts and epoxy handholds, and filled the holes with brown epoxy to blend in with the rock, parker said
drilling bolts is banned at hueco tanks, though rangers have decided to leave bolts necessary for safety on the many established routes
and park officials plan to call a conference of climbers next month or next winter to discuss the ethics of bolting _ a hot topic in climbing circles
parker said he hoped the moratorium and the conference will get climbers to police themselves and report illegal bolting
park officials want to make sure everyone follows the rules because the sport is growing fast at hueco tanks, cottom said. several hundred climbers from the americas, europe and asia traveled to hueco tanks this winter. a few years ago, most of the park's climbers were from texas and new mexico
hueco tanks and joshua tree national monument, east of los angeles, are the most popular north american winter climbing sites
a judge sentenced 10 people to death by hanging for murdering a left-wing politician and his son three years ago, news reports said wednesday
judge kazi golam rasul passed the sentence at narail, 60 miles west of dhaka, on tuesday
the convicts, who will be hanged unless they appeal to higher court, were found guilty of killing eklasuddin ahmed and his 22-year-old son, tutu, in june 1985
ahmed was a local leader of a left-wing baksal party
a spokesman for the baksal party said in dhaka on wednesday that the convicts were former supporters of the governing jatiya party
spokesman abdur razzak said that the killing of ahmed was politically motivated to eliminate rivals
an assistant state prosecutor has been suspended with pay following claims that she led police on a 90-mph car chase and was naked from the waist down when stopped
assistant state attorney jan bamping, 32, was charged with fleeing to elude an officer and improper passing, both misdemeanors, the bradenton herald reported wednesday
police reports cited by the herald said bradenton beach patrolman ron robertson stopped bamping and fellow assistant state attorney jerry blevins, 27, a passenger in the car and owner of the vehicle, at about 1:45 a.m. sunday after a 1{-mile chase
robertson said bamping had been drinking, but he didn't order her from the car to take a roadside sobriety test because she was naked from the waist down. he said he could see she had ``a tattoo on the inside of her leg.''
robertson said that when he asked ms. bamping why she was partially nude, she became upset and answered that it's ``not against the law to drive nude.''
ms. bamping could not be reached by phone wednesday for comment
blevins was fully clothed, robertson said. he was not charged and the herald reported there was no indication he was disciplined
police reports also said ms. bamping and blevins tried to use their positions as prosecutors to intimidate robertson, but blevins denied that
i don't think we did anything improper as far as using this office,'' blevins told the herald
chief assistant state atorney mack futch said he will request that gov. bob martinez appoint a special prosecutor to handle ms. bamping's case
ms. bamping was scheduled to appear in traffic court may 11. statement from fatah-revolutionary council. picks up 5th graf pvs bgng, a base ...</note>
israeli fighter-bombers blasted palestinian and moslem guerrilla bases on the outskirts of sidon on wednesday, destroying at least six in israel's second anti-guerrilla air strike in a week
police said four skyhawks and eight phantom f-4s roared in at 4:05 p.m. and staged eight dive-bombing and rocketing runs in a one-hour raid
at least five bases manned by guerrillas of terrorist mastermind abu nidal's fatah-revolutionary council went up in flames in the villages of bekesta, majdelyoun and salhiyeh near sidon's ein el-hilweh refugee camp, police said
one rocket struck a guerrilla arms depot in bekesta, setting off a two-hour chain of ammunition explosions that demolished the building, police said
in a military communique fatah-revolutionary council claimed the jets raided only ``one of the organization's positions.'' it vowed to ``severely strike back against the zionist enemy's arrogance and barbarism ... at the adequate time and venue.''
the attacks left a number of our heroic fighters martyred or wounded. we will announce specific figures in a later communique,'' the statement said. ``this crime will be added to the black record of the zionist enemy.''
a base of the moscow-oriented democratic front for the liberation of palestine also was destroyed as the jets fired 25 rockets and dozens of delayed-action bombs in the area, police reported
they said the warplanes also hit sidon's power plant, plunging the city into darkness. sidon residents watched the raid from balconies
guerrillas cordoned off the stricken targets after the raid, preventing police and reporters from getting a casualty figure. however, police said two boys aged five and 10 were rushed to sidon's hammoud hospital from bekesta
israel radio's hebrew broadcast said explosions in sidon prevented red cross vehicles from reaching the bombed areas. it said residents of sidon and its palestinian refugee camps closed their stores and rushed in panic to bomb shelters
a communique from the democratic front for the liberation of palestine said an unspecified number of lebanese civilians were injured in the raid
the escalation of the enemy's aggression reflects the deepening crisis engulfing israel as a result of the continuous palestinian uprising in the occupied west bank and gaza strip,'' said the communique, released in beirut
it described the raid as ``the first fruit'' of israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir's recent visit to washington
the israeli command said its planes destroyed buildings used by guerrillas for storing military hardware and vehicles
police said israeli gunboats cruised off sidon, 25 miles south of beirut, during and after the raid. it was israel's fourth into lebanon this year
the israelis said all planes returned safely to their bases and that the pilots reported accurate hits
sidon police said the israeli pilots released air balloons that deflected waves of heat-seeking sam-7 missiles shoulder-fired by guerrillas
a communique issued by the popular liberation army militia of sidon's sunni moslem nasserite leader, mustafa saad, said its positions east of the city were also hit by the israeli jets
it charged the air attack was aimed at breaking the ``lebanese-palestinian nationalist alliance.''
saad's militia, which has controlled sidon since the 1975 outbreak of lebanon's civil war, has been allied with yasser arafat's palestine liberation organization and maintained close ties with abu nidal's group, which opposes arafat
thirty-one people were killed and 43 wounded in the previous israeli air raids on lebanon this year
the supreme court was urged wednesday to allow states to place strict new regulations on professional organizations that solicit contributions for charities
attorney general lacy h. thornburg of north carolina said the rules his state seeks to impose would not violate free-speech rights
professional fund-raisers ``are keeping too much'' of the money, he said. ``we want it to go back to the charities.''
but charitable groups said if the north carolina plan were adopted nationwide it would severely threaten their ability to raise money
the north carolina regulations, invalidated by a lower court, force fund-raisers to tell prospective contributors what percentage of the money the solicitors raised over the past 12 months had been used for expenses and the fund-raisers' fees
the law also could limit the fees paid by charities to the professional fund-raisers. a licensing provision of the statute presumes that in most cases if more than 35 percent of donations goes for the solicitor's fee, that is unreasonable
errol copilevitz, an attorney representing professional fund-raisers and charities, said the law ``creates a real and present danger of censorship.''
i'm telling you professional representatives will not make their services available if this regulation is allowed to stand,'' he said
copilevitz particularly challenged the requirement that solicitors tell a prospective contributor at the outset how much money goes for expenses. that could cripple fund-raising over the phone, he said
by the time the solicitor provides that information he ``will have received a dial tone,'' copilevitz said, adding, ``high costs are not a measure of fraud or the worth of a charity.''
the north carolina law, enacted in 1985, was designed to prevent fraud and assure that most of the money goes to charities and not fund-raising costs
u.s. district judge earl britt declared the law unconstitutional in 1986
britt said that without the help of professional solicitors, many charities might be unable to communicate their views and goals
the judge also said that requiring a solicitor to disclose his track record for the past 12 months ``is not relevant to the particular solicitation campaign he is involved with at the time.''
during an hour of supreme court arguments wednesday, the justices briskly questioned lawyers for both sides. the court is expected to announce a decision by july
chief justice william h. rehnquist compared north carolina's law to a state regulation that sets a maximum price on theater tickets
copilevitz said that would be permissible if the purpose was to make artistic performance more widely available
but when justice antonin scalia asked whether a state could place a ceiling on the cost of a renting a hall for a political rally, copilevitz said that would be unconstitutional
justice thurgood marshall questioned the authority of states to tell charities how to allocate their resources
could you stop them from throwing away their money?'' he said
thornburg said the charities need such protection. he said a survey by north carolina officials showed that from 1980 through 1984 the five largest professional fund-raisers in the state spent approximately 80 percent of the money they raised on expenses and their fees
the supreme court in 1980 and 1984 barred states from limiting the amount of money charities spend on fund-raising. thornburg argued that those rulings do not preclude the type of regulation north carolina seeks to impose
many states require fund-raisers to disclose to regulatory agencies how much is spent on expenses
but copilevitz said north carolina's plan goes far beyond that
he is representing the national federation of the blind, the optimist club and professional fund-raisers. other charities have joined in urging the court to declare the north carolina law unconstitutional
the case is riley vs. national federal of the blind, 87-328
portugal has asked the united states to equip its air force with f-16 fighter-bombers to compensate for a shortfall in u.s. funds for the use of a strategic air base, a government official said wednesday
the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said lisbon was seeking substantial u.s. help in modernizing its armed forces
the military assistance would offset cuts made by the u.s. congress in aid paid for use of the mid-atlantic lajes air base
prime minister anibal cavaco silva last month formally requested a review of the defense agreement under which the united states uses the submarine-warfare and refuelling base on the azores archipelago because of falling u.s. aid to portugal
the request for the f-16s, described as the world's finest fighter-bombers, was presented to a u.s. military delegation that visited lisbon march 1-5, the official said
he refused to specify how many f-16s portugal is seeking but indicated the number requested in the first phase of negotiations could approach 50. washington officials are studying the proposals, he added
the official said portugal also sought hawk missiles, combat helicopters, sophisticated radar equipment, armored personnel carriers and m-60 combat vehicles from the united states
portugal's request for f-16s comes after neighboring spain asked the united states withdraw 74 f-16s from an air base outside madrid. there was no indication of where portugal would station the planes if they were supplied
cavaco silva called for a review of the defense agreement after congressional cuts caused u.s. aid to portugal to fall from $208 million in 1985 to $117 million this year
defense secretary frank carlucci visited lisbon to try to soothe portuguese dissatisfaction. the two countries agreed to set up a joint task force to examine the posssibilities of supplying portugal with surplus u.s. military equipment to make up for the shortfall in financial assistence
apparently portugal rejected the offer
we wanted to take the initiative by informing the united states of the equipment we need instead of being presented with a list of available surplus material that we can choose from,'' said the government official
he said the proposals for u.s military equipment supplies were based on portugal's needs to modernize its armed forces so that it could adequately fulfill its defensive role within the north atlantic treaty organization
opposition parties on wednesday said the government must not cover up the growing scandal involving alleged corruption by the brother of former president chun doo-hwan
the opposition alleged that corruption by chun's relatives and the saemaul development movement was widespread
saemaul, or new community, which claims a membership of more than 5 million community leaders, was formed in 1971 to improve rural and urban living standards
we warn the government against minimizing, covering up or whitewashing the scandal,'' said park young-sook, acting president of the party for peace and democracy. the rival opposition reunification democratic party also called for an independent parliamentary probe
kim tae-ryong, rdp spokesman, also demanded an investigation into the ilhae foundation, a semi-official think tank established by chun
the government is investigating charges that saemaul, while headed by chun's younger brother, embezzled millions of dollars, sold patronage and forced donations
the former president, who is on a private visit to the united states, installed his brother, kyung-hwan, as saemaul head. chun kyung-hwan resigned in 1987 after being linked to gangsters locked in a bloody power struggle
many political observers contend the saemaul probe stemmed from a power game between president roh tae-woo and chun, with roh's supporters working to reduce the former president's power
roh, a former general picked by chun to succeed him, is widely thought to be building popular support by proving corruption under chun. roh has promised reforms since he won the country's first democratic election last december
the new government faces an unavoidable challenge ... the burdensome legacy of the old government,'' don-a ilbo, an influential seoul newspaper, said in a commentary
newspapers said the saemaul probe could be roh's efforts to distance himself from chun, who tried to retain power. but governing party officials fear the growing scandal would erode their chances in national assembly elections in april
the prosecutor general's office said wednesday it had questioned about 50 government and saemaul officials about allegations of fraud, embezzlement and influence peddling
the prosecutors said saemaul was found to have diverted some of an estimated $130 million in funds to profit-oriented projects, land speculation and other irregular activities. warships</head>
a house subcommittee has quietly voted to delete funding for the trident submarine in next year's budget and use that $1.4 billion to build two aegis destroyers instead, lawmakers disclosed wednesday
rep. sam gejdenson, d-conn., said the house armed services seapower subcommittee voted in a closed session tuesday to cut out all trident funding for fiscal 1989, a move pushed by rep. charles e. bennett, d-fla
bennett, chairman of the subcommittee, is opposing an administration plan to sell two aegis ddg-51 destroyers to japan, fearing that the united states would lose technology secrets
under the funding plan approved by the subcommittee, the government would order five aegis warships in 1989. the administration had requested three. the two extra ships would be deployed in japan under u.s. control, protecting japanese security interests while keeping the aegis technology under wraps
gejdenson, whose district includes the electric boat shipyard, the division of general dynamics corp. that builds tridents, sought to play down tuesday's vote
while i am clearly disappointed by the decision of the seapower subcommittee, the subcommittee's decision is only the first step in a lengthy and complex budget process,'' gejdenson said
the congressman, who is not a member of the armed services committee, noted that the seapower panel deleted funding for the trident two years ago, but funding was later restored by congress
gejdenson said he was confident trident funding would be restored again
but bennett said in a telephone interview that he would fight to keep the trident out and the two extra aegis ships in. he said the program, which traditionally calls for one new trident each year, would be continued in the 1990 budget
a critical test comes next week when the full committee takes up the defense budget
electric boat is the sole builder of the 18,750-ton submarine, which is armed with 24 long-range, multi-warhead missiles. the subs are built at the company's yards in groton, conn., and north kingstown, r.i
the 8,300-ton aegis destroyer, equipped with 90 missiles, is being built by bath iron works in bath, maine, and the ingalls shipbuilding in pascagoula, miss
a study of last year's wheat quality showed that 76 percent of the hard red winter wheat samples graded no. 1 or no. 2, compared with 70 percent in 1986, the agriculture department said wednesday
for hard red spring wheat, 75 percent graded no. 1, compared with 70 percent in 1986, the department's federal grain inspection service said
the annual survey involved 12,739 wheat samples from the 1987 crop, said w. kirk miller, administrator of the agency. the samples were taken during the first four weeks following local harvests around the country
the democratic party's chances in november would suffer if a non-candidate such as new york gov. mario cuomo won the presidential nomination after a deadlocked national convention, a top party official said wednesday
it would be a difficult situation and there would be increasingly bad feelings, lynn cutler, vice chairman of the democratic national committee, said at a news conference. ``to the general electorate it might not make any difference at all, but to the people who have to go out and win the election ... i think it would be very tough.''
cuomo has said much the same thing, but has refused to rule out accepting a draft if the convention is deadlocked. he has also declined, as yet, to endorse any of the democratic candidates
he's fully aware of the power of his endorsement and what it means,'' ms. cutler said. ``it makes a national statement. without question i think it would have a big impact in a place like california where there's a great deal of affection for the governor.''
lenora fulani says her presidential campaign gives blacks and other minorities someplace to go when, she predicts, jesse jackson is denied the democratic nomination
ms. fulani, 37, of new york, candidate of the new alliance party, says she is the first black woman presidential candidate to qualify for federal election matching funds
she said her campaign will give jackson leverage at the democratic national convention this summer
they're going to know he's sitting there with an ace up his sleeve. and that ace is a well-orchestrated, viable third-party road,'' she said. ``what i'm building in this country for jackson is something to broker with.''
ms. fulani said she will give up her campaign if jackson wins the democratic nomination in july. but she said that is unlikely because ``he is too black and too progressive'' and the democrats will pick ``a white moderate, conservative of pseudo-liberal.''
she was in tulsa on tuesday to boost her petition campaign for a place on oklahoma's ballot
mayor edward i. koch predicted wednesday that george bush will be the next president _ unless the democrats turn to new york gov. mario cuomo or bush puts ``both feet in his mouth.''
he predicted the democratic ticket will be massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and tennessee sen. albert gore
as i perceive it now, i think we will have a very tough time,'' said koch, a democrat. he said bush, as evidenced by his many defeats of sen. robert dole in the republican primaries, was drawing strength from president reagan's popularity
but koch said he thought bush was ``capable of putting both feet in his mouth'' and added, ``maybe we'll be lucky.''
as for the democrats, he said, ``i hope at the convention we'll turn to mario cuomo. he (would make) a most articulate candiate, charismatic.''
but if that doesn't happen,'' he said, ``i expect the candidates will be dukakis and gore.''
mayor tom bradley has decided not to endorse any presidential candidate in the june primary, despite pressure to back jesse jackson
i have been asked by every democratic presidential campaign to support their candidate,'' bradley, a democrat, said in a statement tuesday. ``i have told each of those campaigns exactly the same thing. i am not going to be involved in the democratic primaries in 1988.''
jackson backers said the mayor's decision could cost him some black support in next year's election, when he will run for an unprecedented fifth term as mayor of the nation's second-largest city
tom takes a chance by not supporting jesse,'' said businessman bondie gambrell, a local jackson supporter and one of bradley's biggest financial backers
here are the key points in truce proposals by nicaragua's sandinista government and the contra rebels:
sandinistas
a cease-fire of up to 90 days during which the contras would lay down their weapons and join a ``national reconciliation dialogue.''
for every rebel who stops fighting, the government would free a political prisoner considered eligible for release. nicaragua has an estimated 3,300 such prisoners
rebels who put down their arms would be free from prosecution without applying for amnesty and could take part in political life. they would be permitted to operate uncensored newspapers, magazines and radio stations, but television would remain a government monopoly
contras
a 45-day truce, with zones where rebel fighters could await negotiation of a permanent truce, keeping their weapons. there is no mention of when the rebels would give up their arms
total amnesty including release of all political prisoners, return of political exiles, full press freedom, suspension of the military draft and inclusion of contras in the sandinista dialogue with the domestic opposition
verification
the sandinistas propose an international commission to verify an end to hostilities. the contras suggest a commission run by cardinal miguel obando y bravo, roman catholic archbishop of managua, and joao baena soares, secretary-general of the organization of american states
officials have declared a water shortage emergency in the communities east of san francisco and are warning they may ration water to 1.1 million customers for the first time in a decade
if a voluntary conservation plan approved by the east bay municipal utility district on tuesday fails, the agency may impose water restrictions of up to 25 percent for homes and businesses in the burgeoning alameda and contra costa counties from may through september
rationing measures under consideration include refusing water hookups to new housing developments, and restricting new or expanded landscaping, car washing and street washing. swimming pools could not be filled after a certain date and lawns could be watered just two days a week
the proposed conservation measures would be the most severe steps taken by the district since the 1977 drought, when water customers were charged up to 10 times the normal rate for excessive water use, district spokesman gayle montgomery said wednesday
we don't want to make this a draconian thing, but we do want to save a lot of water,'' said district general manager jerome gilbert, at a packed, four-hour public hearing tuesday
from oct. 1 to march 1, precipitation was 85 percent of normal statewide, water officials said. that means there's much less snow in the mountains ready to melt and flow into rivers and reservoirs this spring
state water resources department engineers said last week that river runoffs from snow melt will average below 60 percent of normal between april and july statewide, even if spring rainfall is normal. if rainfall stays sparse, the situation will be even worse
at least one farm irrigation district has already declared a drought emergency and cut back water allotments to its farmers
the turlock irrigation district, which serves central valley farmers in southern stanislaus to northern merced counties, said farmers will be allotted only about one-fourth their typical water amount this year
without question, we are in a drought situation,'' said district general manager ernest geddes. ``even with normal precipitation for the remainder of the spring, the tuolumne river runoff will total no more than 50 percent of the historical average.''
in the east bay municipal utility district, gilbert said reservoirs that are half-full now could be one-quarter full by september unless there are major storms during the next two months
runoff this year is the second-lowest year on record in our area and follows a year that was the fourth-worst,'' said ted way, the district's chief engineer. he predicted this year's dry conditions will become as severe as those in 1977
if the dry spells continued into a third year, the effect would be ``devastating,'' said montgomery
san francisco, marin and santa clara counties face possible water shortages next year, but are in better shape than alameda and contra costa because they have more water sources and have received more storms
at a meeting in sacramento last week, state water experts considered whether to declare a drought for the state as a whole, deciding to take a wait-and-see approach for the time being
every day without a storm, the picture gets worse,'' said jack pardee, a snowpack survey engineer with the state water resources department
but maurice roos, chief of the department's water supply branch, said declaration of a drought is premature because even though river runoff from the mountains is substantially below average, storage in reservoirs is only slightly below normal in most parts of the state
water officials aren't the only ones worried about the dry weather. fire officials say it could be the sign of an early and dangerous fire season. during the grim fire season last year, lightning-spawned blazes blackened nearly a million acres of mostly forest lands in california
this is very similar to the weather pattern we saw last year at this time,'' said maryn pitt, assistant director of the state department of forestry. ``it will only further distress the watershed, and to date already this year we've had 520 fires over 448 acres. our 90-day forecast (for rain) is below normal through may.''
east bay water district directors will consider specific rationing proposals april 13, and judging from tuesday's hearing the issue threatens to set suburban residents against city dwellers
i think we should share the pain,'' said sandy skaggs, water board president and a resident of an affluent development in san ramon, where suburbanites take their lawns seriously
but danville mayor beverly lane, whose lawn died in the 1977 drought, agreed with landscapers that the area could suffer layoffs and financial losses if new landscaping was restricted or valuable grasslands allowed to die
we are the hot weather part of the district,'' lane said tuesday during four hours of spirited debate by more than 100 city leaders and landscaping and gardening industry representatives. ``our needs are different than the cooler parts of the district.''
in a move some analysts called risky, northwest airlines announced wednesday it will become the first major u.s. airline to ban smoking on all domestic flights except those to and from hawaii
the ban by the minneapolis-based carrier, the nation's fifth-largest airline, also covers some foreign routes. it goes beyond federal regulations that go into effect next month for domestic flights lasting two hours or less
the stringent non-smoking policy appears to be aimed at attracting new passengers but could backfire and cost the carrier some traffic, some analysts believe
it does run the risk of some loss of business,'' said james v. cammisa, the publisher of travel industry indicators, a new york-based newsletter. ``i guess they (northwest officials) really stuck their neck out.''
wall street seemed unimpressed by northwest's smoke-free innovation. the airline's stock closed on the new york stock exchange at $45.75 per share, down 12{ cents from tuesday
the northwest ban is ``somewhat contentious from a marketing point of view,'' said robert joedicke, an airline analyst for shearson lehman hutton inc. ``if there is a danger, why try to be a leader?''
it is fairly unlikely that the other big u.s. airlines would match northwest's policy, creating a financial risk for the carrier, some observers believe
but northwest says the prohibition is a response to its passengers' and employees' requests. a.b. ``sky'' magary, northwest's executive vice president for marketing, told a news conference in new york that while the policy is not without risk, ``we believe more non-smokers will switch to northwest than smokers will leave.''
he cited a northwest study showing that nine out of 10 passengers prefer to sit in the no-smoking section of a plane. more surprisingly, about 30 percent of smokers express the desire for smoke-free flights, according to the survey
the new policy, called ``northwest clears the air,'' will take effect on april 23 _ the same day as the less restrictive federal law. it will apply to flights within the contiguous 48 states as well as flights to and from alaska, mexico, canada, jamaica and the cayman islands
northwest flights to and from hawaii and overseas will continue to offer smoking sections because those flights ``carry a greater proportion of foreign passengers who feel differently about the issue,'' the airline said in a statement
we still have competitors that are handing out cigars to passengers on board,'' magary said
about 30 percent of northwest's domestic flights last more than two hours, and could have kept their smoking sections under the new federal regulations. the longest flights covered by the smoking ban are four or five hours, according to the airline
under those rules, passengers who insist on lighting up will face civil fines of as much as $1,000, and passengers who tamper with smoke alarms in airplane lavatories will be liable for as much as $2,000 in penalties
air canada, which banned smoking on some flights between canada and the united states last april, said it has gained customers as a result of its no-smoking policy. ``it's been very successful,'' said steve pisni, a spokesman for the carrier
northwest's announcement drew praise from several quarters, including officials of the american cancer society, the american lung association and the u.s. surgeon general's office, who participated in the news conference with magary
rep. richard durbin, d-ill., the prime sponsor of the new federal non-smoking law, also hailed northwest's move. he said he is sending letters to all the other major u.s. carriers, urging them to follow northwest's lead
this action by northwest just proves what we've been saying all along: cleaning up the air in airplanes is a good business decision and a good health decision,'' durbin said
some travel agents also praised the new policy, saying many of their customers have been pressing for a tougher stance
i think it's a good move ... because the public is the one that wants it,'' said jack bloch, owner of jb's world travel in new york. proposal</head> pvs bgng: ``for the ...</note>
the house approved with rare bipartisanship wednesday a $1.1 trillion budget that would tighten domestic and military spending but boost high-profile items including aids research, education, the space program and the war on drugs
the fiscal 1989 plan, which follows the outlines of last fall's budget summit between president reagan and congressional leaders, was approved 319 to 102. a majority of both democrats and republicans voted in favor of the package
the house brushed aside criticism from reagan's budget director, who said the plan used accounting gimmicks to stay within the prearranged spending limits. it also rejected three alternative budget proposals
many members conceded they were putting off tough deficit-reduction decisions until next year, but republicans and democrats praised the plan and spent much of the debate reveling about the absence of acrimony
we've got a miracle,'' said house speaker jim wright, d-texas
for the first time in many many years, we've seen a budget resolution out before cherry blossom time or autumn leaves,'' said rep. silvio conte, r-mass
lawmakers had far less to haggle over than in past years. the totals for military, foreign aid and domestic spending were predetermined by last fall's summit between reagan and congressional leaders. the tax increases envisioned in the summit, $14 billion for fiscal 1989, were enacted in december
using the president's own optimistic economic estimates, the budget claimed a $134 billion deficit, which is within the limits of the gramm-rudman budget balancing law
like reagan's plan, the house budget would not touch social security. the lawmakers rejected a cut in medicare the administration said was needed. they also refused to go along with reagan's plan to eliminate some domestic development and mass transit programs
instead, the election-year plan would give most federal agencies a little more money to spend than in the current year, but not enough to keep pace with inflation
in addition, the agencies would be required to find enough savings to absorb half of a 3 percent pay raise for federal employees. reagan had proposed a 4.3 percent pay boost for the militay and 2 percent for civilian workers, but the house made them equally 3 percent
in selected areas, spending was increased. the budget authorizes $1.5 billion for aids research _ a little more than reagan proposed _ and it would increase space and science spending, though not as much as the president asked
the $134 billion deficit figure for the year beginning oct. 1 was about $5 billion above the president's mark, largely because reagan wanted to sell more government assets. the deficit in fiscal 1987 was $150.4 billion. the administration estimates it will go down to $146.7 billion this year
the house budget claimed to hit exactly the limits in the budget summit pact for cash outlays and for budget authority _ the legal obligations by agencies for spending that could stretch over more than one fiscal year
the pact included: $299.5 billion in budget authority and $294.0 billion in outlays for the military; $148.1 billion in budget authority and $169.2 billion in outlays for annually appropriated domestic programs; and $18.1 billion in budget authority and $16.1 billion in outlays on foreign aid
in crafting the budget, the house budget committee ran into difficulty meeting the limits on domestic spending authority. in the end, the panel reclassified about $3.7 billion in spending authority out from under the categories covered by the agreement
james c. miller iii, director of the white house office of management and budget, said in a letter he was ``disturbed'' by the accounting shift. in addition, he said there appeared to be ``deliberate underfunding of certain programs that would require a supplemental appropriation next year.''
rep. william h. gray iii, d-pa., chairman of the budget committee, said he considered miller's letter a sign that the administration would keep working with congress to control spending. he called the dispute a ``scorekeeping issue'' that would be resolved later
the budget technique could lead to higher spending allowances when the fiscal blueprint is translated later into actual pending bills. several lawmakers said that while the budget was in the spirit of the bipartisan ``summit,'' it also avoided any tough belt-tightening in an election year
this budget is in a real sense a delay budget,'' said rep. charles schumer, d-n.y
next year is going to be the real problem,'' said rep. amory houghton, r-n.y
the house approval of the budget was far earlier than in past years, but it was still unlikely that congress would meet its april 15 deadline for final approval of a budget resolution
senate majority leader robert c. byrd, d-w.va., said wednesday he did not expect full senate action on the budget before the second week of april. director</head>
eugene o'neill's classic ``desire under the elms'' played to a sold-out audience on a moscow stage wednesday night, the first play directed by an american in the soviet union
mark lamos, 42, artistic director of the hartford stage co. of connecticut, received a standing ovation after the opening performance of o'neill's 1924 play about the struggle for dominance between father and son on a 19th-century new england farm
lamos had to confront linguistic and cultural barriers in bringing the play before a soviet audience
the 870 people at the performance applauded politely in rhythm for the soviet actors, and then rose to applaud energetically for lamos
the director, wearing a dappled blazer and red tie, was given an ornately painted samovar and bouquet of flowers. he plucked one out and presented it to the lead actress, nina popova, who was still in tears from the final wrenching scene
the feeling of great personality is missing,'' alexander aronov, who writes for the youth newspaper moskovsky komsomolets, said in an interview
he said he believed lamos strayed from o'neill's conception, although the actors' movements and attire seemed more american than previous soviet performances of the play he had seen
lamos said he believed his version was closer to o'neill's because the original russian translation was too poetic and smooth. he said during a break in a rehearsal tuesday that he tried to tone down what he called the overemotional and unnatural style of the actors
several soviets in the audience said they found the language in lamos' version too crude
aronov said part of the blame should be placed on the actors of moscow's pushkin theater, with the exception of ms. popova
o'neill and tennessee williams are the best known and best loved american playwrights in the soviet union. lamos said soviets know little about other american playwrights, especially more contemporary ones whose work he prefers, and was unhappy with the choice of ``desire under the elms'' for his direction
the exposition of the play is a bit crudely done,'' lamos said
the play was chosen by the pushkin theater's artistic director, yuri yeremin, as an appropriate way to celebrate the centennial of o'neill's 1888 birth
desire under the elms'' was the first play performed in the pushkin theater in 1926 and has become a standard in the soviet repertoire
lamos was invited to stage the play in moscow after he met a group of soviet theater directors in new york last summer
another american, nagle jackson of the mccarter theater in princeton, n.j., is directing a production of ``the glass menagerie'' by williams that is scheduled to open later this year at leningrad's gorky theater. two other americans are scheduled to direct plays in moscow in the fall
lamos relied on a soviet interpreter to communicate with the all-soviet cast and crew
language difficulties seemed especially severe when he was first reviewing the script with the actors and came across the phrase ``to pull the wool over his eyes,'' he recalled
when lamos explained that the phrase meant to fool someone, the actors came up with a russian equivalent _ which translates into ``he has noodles on his ears.''
the american didn't believe the expression was appropriate, but he said one participant chimed in: ``let me put it this way, mark, we've had noodles over our ears in this country for 70 years.'' slayings linked to stone to six total, sted nine; picks up 10th graf pvs: the royal ...</note>
police on wednesday said they were abandoning their policy of staying away from ira funerals, following the slayings of five people _ including two british soldiers _ at rites last week
prime minister margaret thatcher joined grieving relatives at northolt air base near london as the bodies of two british soldiers arrived home and were lifted from a transport plane to the strains of chopin's ``funeral march.''
mrs. thatcher's appearance marked the first time a prime minister had watched the coffins of soldiers brought home from northern ireland in the nearly 20 years since britain deployed troops in the province
in central belfast, police mounted heavy patrols at the cenotaph as 25,000 people turned out for an emotional service for the soldiers
the two corporals were dragged from their unmarked car, beaten, stripped and shot after they drove up to an irish republican army funeral on saturday. no police had been assigned to the funeral
a british army spokesman said that a security patrol ordered to intervene after an army helicopter reported disturbances at saturday's funeral arrived ``within three minutes of the shots having been fired'' at the british soldiers
at another unpoliced ira funeral in belfast on march 16, a protestant fired shots and hurled hand grenades at mourners, killing three people and wounding 68
the no-police policy was implemented at the march 16 funeral when three ira guerrillas shot by british commandos in gibraltar were buried. moderate roman catholic leaders had urged police to stay away to avoid clashes with mourners
michael stone, a protestant guerrilla, is accused of killing three people and wounding 68 at the funeral. he told police he was on a mission of revenge against the ira and was charged with those three killings and three other sectarian slayings in the past four years
the royal ulster constabulary, the province's police force, announced wednesday that security chiefs will resume their presence at the funerals of ira members
experience has shown that maintenance of th law and prevention of outrages will only be guaranteed through the firm presence of the police and army,'' a police statement said
sinn fein, the outlawed ira's legal political front, sinn fein, condemned the police decision
any return to the violence of saturation tactics at funerals will only ensure confrontation,'' said sinn fein vice president martin mcguinness. ``all we want is to be allowed to bury our dead with dignity and peace.''
at northolt, mrs. thatcher stood with the families of royal signals corp corporals derek wood, 24, and david howes, 23, as a hercules transport landed with the coffins
the prime minister, who presence underscored national outrage over the killings, glanced around anxiously as wood's mother and sister sobbed when the army band struck up and a bearer party carried the flag-draped coffins slowly toward hearses
since 1969, 563 british soldiers have been among the nearly 2,700 people killed in the sectarian violence in northern ireland. of the soldiers killed, 391 have been from mainland britain and 172 from the locally recruited ulster defense regiment
in another development, britain's two television networks gave police untransmitted video footage of the rampage at saturday's funeral after they were threatened with prosecution
the networks had initially refused to yield the footage, saying it would endanger the lives of their crews
earlier, the catholic bishop whose diocese includes west belfast denounced the ira as ``sheer evil'' in one of the strongest attacks yet by a prelate on the guerrilla organization
ira violence is often disguised with a mask of romantic rhetoric and militaristic mock ritual,'' said bishop cahal daly. ``for a ghastly half-hour on saturday, the mask slipped. the real face of ira violence was shown and it was horrible to see.''
the ira is fighting to unite northern ireland with the catholic republic of ireland under a leftist administration. edits to tighten</note>
the senate foreign relations committee cleared the way wednesday for an early vote to endorse the new arms reduction treaty with the soviet union after a series of lopsided tallies against amendments proposed by the pact's chief opponent, sen. jesse helms
helms, r-n.c., had introduced a series of 36 amendments to the accord. but he agreed to press for substantive action on just four of them after republican and democratic senators accused him of obstruction and deliberately engineering a series of delays
committee chairman claiborne pell, r-r.i., announced the panel will vote next tuesday afternoon on reporting the treaty to the senate floor with a favorable recommendation
pell had promised to keep the committee in lengthy session to dispose of the helms amendments, none of which had attracted more than three votes among the 19 committee members
helms's reversal of course came after a morning session of the panel in which sen. richard lugar, r-ind., complained: ``we're just in a delay, stall situation which i find disagreeable.''
if you don't have the votes and just try to overload it with amendments, that isn't fair,'' lugar said shortly before the committee defeated the first of the helms amendments, 12-3
i don't know what is the magical effect of racing to get this thing reported'' to the senate floor, helms said at that point
meanwhile, pell and several other key committee members said the last major factor complicating senate consideration of the new agreement banning u.s. and soviet medium-range missiles is the dispute between congress and the reagan administration over the interpretation of treaties
sen. sam nunn, d-ga., chairman of the senate armed services committee, seeks to add language to the treaty text declaring the senate's understanding that administration testimony about the contents and impact of the accord is authoritative and binding
the dispute stems from the administration's earlier reinterpretation of the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty to permit the deployment of a star wars missile defense system which most arms control treaty experts believed had been effectively banned
senate majority leader robert c. byrd, d-w.va., told the senate on wednesday he has concluded it will be essential to attach a reservation or understanding to the pact spelling out the senate's position
byrd said that while there have been exchanges of letters on how the treaty should be interpreted, ``this matter is not going to be resolved, in my judgment, by any exchange of letters, because a future administration can say ... `we don't agree with that interpretation at all.'''
the initial 12-3 committee vote rejected a helms amendment which would have changed the treaty to permit the united states to deploy a ground-launched cruise missile armed with conventional and not nuclear explosives
only sens. larry pressler, r-s.d., and frank murkowski, r-alaska, joined helms in supporting the amendment
adopting the amendment would mean reopening negotiations with the soviets, sen. alan cranston, d-calif., said. ``and that would mean we would plainly not get a treaty anytime soon. so this can fairly be labled as a killer amendment.''
he said conventionally armed cruise missiles were included in the pact because it is impossible to differentiate them from identical weapons armed with nuclear warheads
with the conventionally armed missiles excluded, the treaty would not be verifiable, cranston said
but helms said the ban means ``the conventional imbalance in europe will be even greater than it is now'' because nato will lose a major weapon in the cruise missile
however, helms later relented, the tuesday vote was set, and the committee overwhelmingly rejected three amendments, all of which were described by opponents as having the potential to kill the treaty by forcing the reopening of negotiations with the soviets
an amendment by sen. larry pressler, r-s.d ., which would have delayed implementation of the treaty until negotiations reduced soviet surperiority in conventional arms in europe also was rejected, 15-2
both democratic and republican leaders predict overwhelming ratification when the treaty reaches the senate floor and say only 10 or 12 members of the 100-member senate are likely to vote to reject it. ratification requires a two-thirds vote. subs last graf with 3 grafs background and additional quotes.</note>
the house ethics committee wednesday sharply rebuked rep. charles rose, d-n.c., after concluding he improperly borrowed funds from his campaign and then failed to publicly report the transactions
finding ``clear and convincing evidence'' of house rules violations, the committee also said rose wrongly pledged a certificate of deposit from his campaign as collateral on a personal loan; and failed to report liabilities to financial institutions on his financial reports, filed publicly by all lawmakers
the panel, formally the committee on standards of official conduct, wrote rose that his behavior was ``deserving of reproach.'' but the committee concluded there should be no punishment by the full house because the eight-term lawmaker has tried to rectify his mistakes
the committee recognizes and takes into consideration the fact that all funds borrowed were replaced in full without the insistence of this committee, and that this action was taken by you prior to this committee beginning a preliminary inquiry,'' rose was told in the letter, signed by panel chairman julian c. dixon, d-calif., and ranking republican floyd d. spence of south carolina
furthermore, the committee recognizes that the campaign certificate of deposit in question is no longer encumbered, due to restrictions placed on it in connection with your personal financial dealings.''
rose said he was ``very happy that the committee found that no further action was warranted, other than the letter to me.'' he said he did not expect the situation to hamper his future re-election bids, and that the committee's decision not to take tougher action demonstrated it considered his mistakes technical in nature
i'm happy that it's behind me, i'm satisfied with the result and i'm glad i can move on to total concentration on what the people elected me to do,'' he said in an interview. ``my head is high.''
a house rule restricts the use of campaign funds to bona fide campaign purposes. the committee called the requirement ``crucial to maintaining public confidence in the fund-raising system governing house members
the use of your campaign funds, as alleged and proved, is entirely inconsistent with this principle,'' the committee letter said
the panel said the personal benefit rose received in each instance of borrowing, and the lower interest rate received from use of the certificate of deposit, ``are the kinds of abuses'' house rules were designed to prevent
for this reason, the committee instructs that you refrain from any future campaign borrowings and-or use of campaign assets as collateral,'' the committee said
rose said he was disappointed the committee did not accept his contention that money he took from his campaign amounted to repayment of loans. he said he apologized for signing his name to the certificate of deposit, contending he hadn't known doing so violated house rules
rose, 48, was first elected to the house in 1972. the state republican party first raised allegations about rose's finances in 1986. but rose easily won election to an eighth term in the house, where he is chairman of the agriculture subcommittee on tobacco and peanuts
i rather expect that the republicans will be angry that the committee gave me the lightest possible action they can give,'' he said
the new president of a moderate group of southern baptists said wednesday the organization has no intention of forming a separate denomination, but he acknowledged it appears headed in that direction
the rev. john thomason of jackson, miss., was elected president tuesday of the 25,000-member southern baptist alliance, a group of moderates formed in response to fundamentalist control of the 14.7 million-member southern baptist convention
the alliance, which was formed more than a year ago, concluded its annual meeting here wednesday
while both factions generally are conservative, they disagree on key issues, including ordination of women and biblical inerrancy, the view held by fundamentalists that the bible is the literal truth
the fundamentalists have gained control of the sbc hierarchy through nine years of electing their presidential candidates
during the next year, thomason said in an interview, he will ``keep pressing the concern of the alliance, to continue sounding the word about our threatened heritage.''
while some have accused the alliance of being the nucleus for a denomination, thomason said: ``we are not a fringe group, we are not an avant garde faction of the southern baptist convention. the great majority of sba members are denominational loyalists.''
thomason acknowledged that the alliance may appear to be headed toward denominational status because of its publishing activities and its discussions concerning the possible need for a new seminary or divinity school
whenever we take specific steps like that, we are acting independently of the institutions of the southern baptist convention and that gives the appearance of independence, but it is not our desire to forge a permanent split with the sbc,'' thomason said
he said the alliance has to be an ``advocate for groups and causes we feel are disenfranchised. ... if this means acting independently of the existing agencies and channels of sbc life, then for the time being, we are willing to do that.''
fundamentalists, who oppose ordination of women, say the bible is without factual error in historical, scientific and religious areas. moderates maintain there is room for interpretation, especially in non-religious areas
before fundamentalists gained control of the sbc, thomason said, there was no ``creedal litmus test'' for appointees. if the practice continues, ``one by one, we will see our institutions succumb to creedalism,'' thomason said
fundamentalists have clear control of southeastern baptist theological seminary in wake forest, n.c. and the home mission board in atlanta
r. randall lolley resigned last year as president of southeastern rather than carry out the board's order that only biblical inerrantists be hired as professors. the home mission board has refused to help pay women ministers
thomason is pastor of the 561-member northminster baptist church, the third church to join the alliance after its formation in february 1987. the alliance includes 40 churches in 11 states
britain's two television networks on wednesday gave police unbroadcast videotapes of a mob attack leading up to the killing of two british soldiers at an ira funeral procession in northern ireland
the british broadcasting corp. and independent television news had refused earlier to comply with police demands for the film, on grounds that doing so would endanger their crews in the british province
on wednesday night, however, the bbc in belfast said it gave police a 49-second videotape from the funeral
an irish republican army mob at the procession dragged the two soldiers from a car saturday and beat them with iron bars. the soldiers were hauled away and later found shot to death nearby
an announcement from itn said the commercial network also gave police untransmitted footage from the funeral in belfast, the provincial capital
having considered our legal position, we have complied,'' itn said. ``the principle of withholding our untransmitted material remains important to us, but itn's policy is to observe the law.''
bbc director michael checkland said the network relinquished the footage in ``response to a legal requirement'' after plainclothes officers visited its belfast office
the bbc has never set itself above the law,'' checkland said. ``in dealing with this matter, we have been concerned with the difficult and dangerous position of our crews in northern ireland. i very much hope ... the bbc's future newsgathering in the province will not be damaged.''
both networks had shown the mob attack, but not the killings, in their regular newscasts. the royal ulster constabulary, the provincial police, demanded untransmitted film to assist its investigation
network spokesmen said their untransmitted tapes did not show the soldiers being shot to death and would be of little help, but police demanded the material under britain's antiterrorist legislation
officials of bbc, itn and the irish network rte had said they would not release footage that had not been broadcast unless a court ordered it. rte said wednesday the police had not yet made a formal request
all the networks said terrorists had threatened the lives of employees who covered the funeral, and argued that crews covering future violence would not be safe if they were thought to be cooperating with police
prime minister margaret thatcher rejected the networks' argument that they must maintain an impartial stance in their coverage of violence
either one is on the side of justice or on the side of terrorism,'' she told parliament on tuesday
i believe everyone, the media included, has a bounden duty to do everything they can to see that those who perpetrated the terrible crimes we all saw on tv, which disgusted the whole world, are brought to justice.''
a witness at abbas hamadi's kidnap trial testified wednesday that hamadi confided to a friend that he was involved in abducting one of two west germans kidnapped in lebanon
the lebanese-born defendant is accused in the separate kidnappings of the two germans in january 1987 in a bid to force the bonn government to release his brother, mohammed hamadi, who is charged with hijacking a twa airliner
el saheli, who was hired by west german investigators to listen in on abbas hamadi's wiretapped telephone calls after the abductions, testified that abbas hamadi acknowledged at least one kidnapping
saheli said a lebanese friend asked abbas hamadi in one telephone conversation whether he helped kidnap businessman rudolf cordes
he answered `yes,''' said saheli
but defense attorney eckhardt hild told the court his client was ``only bragging to make himself look good'' in the eyes of his lebanese friends in west germany
in other testimony wednesday, abbas hamadi said two members of the extremist pro-iranian hezbollah group prevented him from boarding a plane leaving beirut just before cordes was kidnapped on jan. 17, 1987
hamadi said an employee of beirut airport, whom he identified as ``l. ham rachan,'' could verify he was forced to miss his flight to europe
the 29-year-old defendant did not indicate what he thought hezbollah's motives might have been
west german investigators suspect hezbollah was involved in the kidnappings and that hamadi had links to the group
abbas hamadi returned to west germany from lebanon on jan. 26, 1987, and was arrested at frankfurt airport
since his trial began on jan. 5, abbas hamadi has appealed for the release of cordes, and has denied any role in the kidnappings
west german engineer alfred schmidt, abducted in beirut on jan. 20, 1987, was released in september
mohammed hamadi, 23, was arrested at frankfurt on jan. 13, 1987, carrying liquid explosives and forged identification documents
west germany has refused a u.s. extradition request for the younger hamadi, but has charged him in connection with the june 1985 hijacking of a twa airliner in which 39 people were held hostage 17 days and a u.s. navy diver was killed
mohammed hamadi is being held in a frankfurt prison pending trial. abbas hamadi's trial is to resume on april 5 and a decision is expected by april 19. picks up 6th pvs bgng, `panama is ...'</note>
a u.s. diplomat was given 48 hours to leave panama on wednesday, the third day of a general strike that has virtually shut down the country but not loosened gen. manuel antonio noriega's grip on power. david miller, an economics counselor, was the second american diplomat ordered out by the foreign ministry, which gaveno reason for its decision
in washington, the state department said wednesday night it would ignore the order because the united states considers the government that issued it illegitimate. it gave the same reason for rejecting the previous order against terence kneebone, head of the u.s. information service in panama, who remains in the country
panama is out of cash because washington cut off the supply of u.s. dollars, the panamanian national currency, in its effort to drive noriega into exile. federal grand juries in florida indicted noriega last month on narcotics and money laundering charges
a u.s. medical batallion truck returning from maneuvers with a dozen soldiers was surrounded and stopped by national police after straying onto a city highway wednesday afternoon
the truck and men were held for an hour at the roadside, then taken to fort amador, a panamanian base with a u.s. liason
a panamanian soldier outside the military police office where the americans were taken would not allow reporters inside and said the incident was being handled as an administrative process. under u.s.-panama treaties, such military trucks are prohibited outside the former canal zone
the panama canal operated normally, as it has through weeks of protest against noriega, who holds the real power in panama through his position as commander of the 15,000 soldiers and police. officials say the daily average of 35 ships has been passing through the waterway throughout the months of unrest here
some opposition leaders were frustrated wednesday that the strike had not loosened noriega's grip on the bankrupt nation
we're well aware of the situation, that gen. noriega appears unmoved by all the human suffering,'' jose mulino, an attorney, told a news conference. ``we'll be considering new strategies. i'm not sure what it will take.''
mulino is prominent in the national civic crusade, an alliance of about 200 professional, business, labor and other groups formed last june to lead the campaign against noriega
he and other opposition leaders vowed to continue the strike
in a clear attempt to dramatize its cause, the alliance sponsored a roman catholic funeral mass on wednesday for a young private security guard killed by a shotgun blast during riots rioting last saturday
the site of the mass, the church of christ the king, was not the dead man's parish but has been the scene of several clashes between noriega's opponents and supporters
after hearing the victim eulogized as a ``young man who died for patriotism,'' more than 100 people stood at the church entrance and chanted ``justice!'' and ``noriega, your end is near!''
about 300 people, including several directors of the civic crusade, attended the mass, along with more than 100 journalists
there was no disturbance
officials of the panamanian committee for human rights say alcibiades vasquez, 24, was killed by a pro-government paramilitary squad
his death was the first in a nearly a month of often violent civil unrest that began after president eric arturo delvalle tried to fire noriega on feb. 25 and was dismissed the next day. the united states still recognizes delvalle, who is in hiding in panama
churches throughout panama have started soup kitchens to feed the destitute. the catholic welfare agency caritas said it is feeding 6,000 families in poor neighborhoods around the capital with donated supplies
civic crusade leaders joined delvalle in appealing for donations of food from abroad through the catholic church or international relief agencies
i am very concerned and fear for the health and lives of many panamanians,'' delvalle said in a videotaped message from his place of hiding
he has not appeared in public since the legislature dismissed him on orders from noriega
another leading opposition figure, ricardo arias calderon, is expected to try to enter the country thursday after four weeks of forced exile in miami
arias, head of the christian democratic party and a presidential aspirant, was denied entry when he returned from a business trip on the day delvalle was ousted
hundreds of party faithful are expected at the panama city airport. several central american legislators plan to accompany him as a guarantee of safety
panama's economy, already hampered by a $4.8 billion foreign debt, started disintegrating when delvalle's dismissal caused a run on the banks. they were closed in early march and the cash shortage was aggravated by u.s. economic sanctions
a judge has dismissed one of two drug charges against john zaccaro jr., the son of 1984 vice presidential candidate geraldine ferraro
district judge francis mccaffrey ruled monday there is insufficient evidence to support a charge of possession of cocaine with intent to sell
mccaffrey also said defense attorneys cannot claim at trial that zaccaro was a victim of selective prosecution because it does not relate to guilt or innocence
zaccaro was arrested in 1986 in a raid of his home and car while attending middlebury college. his trial on a charge of sale of a regulated drug is scheduled to begin april 4
mccaffrey in 1986 had ruled inadmissible eight grams of cocaine and records of drug transactions seized by police from zaccaro's car. the judge said at the time that the search warrant was based on insufficient evidence
addison county state's attorney john quinn argued he could prove the possession charge based on the observations of undercover state trooper laura manning
but mccaffrey disagreed, saying, ``there is no evidence ... to show that the other packets observed by manning contained cocaine.''
egypt warned wednesday it will consider any israeli attack on saudi arabia's new intermediate-range missile launchers an attack on egypt itself. other arab nations issued similar warnings
egypt, the only arab state that has diplomatic relations with israel, accused the jewish state of violating international laws by demanding that saudi arabia remove the missiles, which are capable of carrying nuclear warheads and of reaching israel
in amman, chairman sharifuddin pir zadeh of the organization of islamic conference said the group also would support saudi arabia. his statement echoed similar declarations of support by syria and jordan, which said they would consider any attack on saudi arabia an attack on them
they pledged to help the saudis militarily if necessary
i am sending a cable to king fahd supporting his moslem kingdom and our saudi brothers against the israeli threats,'' pir zadeh said
pir zadeh was in the jordanian capital for a meeting of foreign ministers of the islamic conference. he said conference members would support the saudis ``morally and, if necessary, militarily.''
saudi arabia recently acquired chinese css-2 missiles, which have a range of 2,200 miles. they are capable of being fitted with nuclear warheads, but the saudis have denied this will be done
prime minister yitzhak shamir of israel said tuesday that his country and the united states were ``making efforts to deal with . .. (the) grave development.'' he did not elaborate
israel radio on sunday quoted a close shamir aide, yossi ben aharon as saying israel had a reputation of not waiting until potential dangers became actual ones, apparently a reference to israel's 1981 air raid against a nuclear reactor under construction in iraq. shamir said ben aharon denied making the statement
egypt warned it will deal with any israeli attack on saudi missile launchers ``strongly and with firmness.''
official cairo television broadcast the warning, attributed to a responsible source, as the first item of the main evening newscast. it was later carried by the middle east news agency
egypt reiterates that it considers any attack on saudi arabia an attack on itself which must be dealt with strongly and with firmness and the offender will have to bear the responsiblity for this attack,'' the source was quoted as saying
in the year's first defense spending vote, a house subcommittee decided wednesday to cut deeply into president reagan's budget request for his star wars anti-missile research project, according to congressional sources
the armed services research and development subcommittee also increased spending for the midgetman nuclear-tipped missile and sharply reduced the planned budget for deploying mx atomic weapons aboard trains, said the sources, who spoke only on condition of anonymity
the committee met behind closed doors to make the decisions
the votes by the subcommittee were the first step in the lengthy congressional budgeting process. the full armed services committee will later consider its subcommittee actions before sending the pentagon budget bill to the floor of the full house. the same procedure will also be followed in the senate
the overall pentagon budget for the 1989 fiscal year will be $299 billion, a figure set by the white house and congress last december during negotiations aimed at reducing the federal budget deficit
reagan had sought $4.5 billion in pentagon spending for star wars, known formally as the strategic defense initiative
but the subcommittee approved a $3.7 billion figure, which would be an increase of only 3 percent over the current star wars budget, the sources said
the fight over the midgetman and the mx involves a pair of nuclear-tipped weapons which have been at the heart of a long-running dispute between the reagan administration and the democratic-controlled congress
congressional democrats support the single warhead midgetman while the air force wants to build more than the 50 of the 10-warhead mx weapons allowed by congress. the second 50 mx weapons would be based, two each, aboard 25 trains that would be housed on western military bases until a crisis
reagan had wanted $1 billion for the two programs, including $800 million for study of the rail-basing plan, while the budget contained $200 million for midgetman. that latter total was enough to keep the program alive until the president who succeeds reagan can make a final decision on the dispute, according to defense secretary frank c. carlucci
as it worked through the budget, the subcommittee rejected a republican-backed plan to spend $650 million for mx railroad basing plans and another $350 million for midgetman, according to the sources
then, the panel turned down a democratic-proposed plan to spend $500 million for midgetman and nothing for the mx
finally, the panel agreed to split the $1 billion figure, giving $500 million for research into each weapon
president reagan marked the fifth anniversary of his plan for a star wars missile defense system on wednesday by asserting that the high-tech program is an incentive to u.s.-soviet arms control efforts
in a written statement issued the same day he announced a date for his fourth summit with soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev, reagan lauded the missile shield proposal, known formally as the strategic defense initiative, as ``vital to our future security.''
we must recognize that we live in an imperfect, often violent world, one in which ballistic missile technology is proliferating despite our efforts to prevent this,'' reagan said. ``we would be doing a grave and dangerous disservice to future generations if we assumed that national leaders everywhere, for all time, will be both peaceful and rational.''
the president warned, as he has many times, that the soviets ``not only are ahead of us in ballistic missiles, but also are deeply engaged in their own sdi-like program. if they are allowed to keep their near-monopoly in defenses, we will be left without an effective means to protect our cherished freedoms in the future.''
the president announced his proposal for the missile shield defense program on march 23, 1983
i put forward the vision of ... a future free from the threat of the most dangerous weapon mankind has invented: fast-flying ballistic missiles,'' reagan recalled in his statement
reagan, who has staunchly defended the plan despite soviet efforts to curb it and congressional efforts to cut its funding, said it had ``provided a valuable incentive for the soviets to return to the bargaining table and to negotiate seriously over strategic arms reductions.''
and as we move toward lower levels of offense, it will be all the more important to have an effective defense,'' reagan argued
the president has repeatedly insisted, however, that he will not use sdi as a bargaining chip in negotiations with the soviets
reagan, following an oval office meeting with soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze, announced he will go to moscow from may 29 to june 2 for his fourth meeting with gorbachev
the highlight of the summitt was intended to be the signing of a treaty to slash the superpowers' long-range strategic weapons, but reagan has suggested that the agreement will not be ready due to time limitations
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said the issue of sdi did not come up in wednesday's meetings between u.s. and soviet officials at the white house
in his statement, reagan said the high-tech program now faces problems that ``are largely political.''
congress has cut funds for the program every year, reagan said, asserting this has put the program ``one to two years'' behind schedule
capitol hill slashed reagan's 1988 request for the program from $5.6 billion to $3.9 billion. he is seeking $4.6 billion in 1989
in the year's first defense spending vote, a house subcommittee decided wednesday to cut deeply into reagan's budget request for star wars, approving $3.7 billion, which would be an increase of only 3 percent over the current star wars budget, according to congressional sources speaking on condition of anonymity. the request will later go to the full house armed services committee, and later to the full house. 8-9 pvs, bgng: ``one amendment ...''; picks up 10th graf pvs: ``a similar ...''</note>
senate republicans succeeded wednesday in delaying any votes on a bill to require the government to warn millions of workers they risk cancer and other diseases from job exposure to hazardous substances
democratic supporters of the ``high risk occupational disease notificiation and prevention act'' were unable to break off lengthy orations by opponents led by sen. orrin hatch, r-utah, aimed a preventing a vote on the bill
in a key test vote, the bill's chief author, sen. howard metzenbaum, d-ohio, was able to muster only 33 of the 60 senate votes necessary to limit further debate to 30 hours
the legislation is aimed at what the national institute of occupational safety and health says are the one in every four americans who have been exposed to carcinogens or other hazardous substances on the job, most of them unware of it
metzenbaum and other supporters of the bill on wednesday put together what he said were ``weakening amendments'' aimed at diminishing opposition from farmers and small businesses before making another attempt to limit debate on thursday
hatch, however, prevented votes on the amendments, as well, holding control of the sente floor for hours, but saying he might allow their consideration on thursday
i don't consider this a filibuster,'' hatch said. ``a filibuster is reading from the phone book. this is a discussion that is very necessary. this bill could cost taxpayers and consumers millions or billions of dollars.''
later wednesday, sen. edward m. kennedy, d-mass., chairman of the senate labor and human resources committee, substituted the bill entirely with a new version including several weakening amendments on which hatch had been blocking action
the new version effectively exempts companies with less than 50 workers and farms from having to continue to pay wages and benefits for up to a year to workers ordered off the job because of the danger continued hazardous exposure would raise for them
it also puts restrictions on what information from the program that workers and former workers could use in pursuing liability suits against employers and places a $250 ceiling on the medical monitoring expenses that companies would have to pay for each covered worker
do we have a `for sale' sign on the legislation so that you keep watering it down until you get enough votes to pass it?'' hatch asked rhetorically, calling kennedy's action a ``reprehensible tactic.''
democrats admitted that kennedy's parliamentary maneuver, although allowed by senate rules, could be used to keep repubicans from offering amendments of their own. but they maintained that was not the intent
democratic leader robert c. byrd acknowledged the ``unfairness that has been circumstantially brought about ... with no malicious intent.''
because of that, byrd said that on thursday he would vote against his own motion that was part of a second attempt to bring an end to the republican delaying tactics
metzenbaum, attempting to salvage the measure in what appears to be a swell of opposition to it, said he would urge fellow supporters to also vote against putting a limit on the gop delay tactics
a similar bill was passed by the house on a 225-186, largely party-line vote last october despite vehement opposition from the reagan administration
unions have been seeking the legislation for the past four years, contending the administration effectively had ``defanged'' the occupational safety and health administration from protecting workers from hazards
over the past two years, metzenbaum had succeeded in winning support for the bill from several trade groups and corporations, including the chemical manufacturers association, the american electronics association, ibm, general electric, occidental petroleum and w.r. grace and co
but hundreds of other business groups, led by the national association of manufacturers and the u.s. chamber of commerce, remained opposed to the measure in any form
jerry jasinowki, the nam's chief economist, called the legislation a ``ticking time bomb'' that could subject employers up to billions of dollars in lawsuits each year from workers and former workers that the government identifies as being at risk to occupational diseases
the bill would set up a panel of seven scientists in the department of health and human services to identify hazards and the groups at risk from exposure to them
the national institute of occupational safety and health would then be required to send individual notices to between 100,000 and 300,000 individuals every year, and employers would be required to provide medical monitoring programs for each. weapons use and raise references to claims. picks up 10th graf pvs bgng, `the kuwaiti-bound... subs bottom three grafs, ``the netherlands ..' with 1 to trim.</note>
iran accused iraq on wednesday of using poison gas against civilians and warned it might retaliate with its own chemical weapons, and the united states urged a u.n. security council protest
the international committee of the red cross called the use of chemical weapons a ``new and tragic escalation'' in the 7{-year-old war between iran and iraq
also wednesday, iranian gunboats attacked a cypriot freighter in the persian gulf, leaving it in flames, and iran fired six missiles into iraqi cities
iraq claimed a number of civilians were killed or wounded by an iranian missile fired into iraq's capital, baghdad
iranian prime minister hussein musavi claimed iraqi troops killed 5,000 iraqi kurds with poison gas last week after their home villages and towns were ``liberated'' by iranian troops fighting with the autonomy-seeking kurds. he called the use of poison gas ``one of the greatest crimes of the middle east.''
it depends on international measures taken to stop these iraqi crimes,'' musavi was quoted as saying by iran's official islamic republic news agency, monitored in cyprus
western journalists who toured the affected area in northeast iraq and the hospitals where victims were taken corroborated the claims
iran's war information minister kamal kharazi said iran may retaliate with its own chemical weapons if the u.n. security council does not condemn iraq for its use of such weapons
iraq has denied using chemical weapons
the international committee of the red cross said in geneva that it had taken urgent steps to end such attacks and had informed iran ``of its readiness to provide emergency assistance for the victims.''
in washington, the state department urged the u.n. security council to mount an international protest
this incident appears to be a particularly grave violation of the 1925 geneva protocol against chemical warfare,'' said spokesman charles e. redman. he said there was also evidence iran may have fired chemical artillery shells against iraq
we call upon iran and iraq to desist immediately from any further use of chemical weapons, which are an offense to civilization and humanity,'' redman said
refering to film footage on american television showing victims of the alleged attacks, white house spokesman marlin fitzwater told reporters: ``we condemn the use of chemical warfare and gas use by anybody, anywhere at any time
i saw, everyone in the administration saw, the same reports you saw last night. they were horrible, outrageous, disgusting and should serve as a reminder to all countries of why chemical warfare should be banned.''
the kuwaiti-bound cypriot freighter, identified as the 34,346-ton odysseas h, was struck about 10 miles west of the strait of hormuz as it entered the gulf with a shipment of barley from tarragona, spain
the master issued a distress call at 4:45 p.m., saying two gunboats had raided his vessel and set it ablaze, according to gulf-based shipping executives who spoke on condition of anonymity
two salvage tugboats that rushed to the scene brought the flames under control by nightfall, and there were no reported injuries. the extent of damage to the cargo was not immediately known
about the same time and in the same vicinity, an iranian frigate challenged the saudi abha, a 42,600-ton vessel laden with motor vehicles for saudi arabia. the vessel, which flies the singapore flag, is operated by the national shipping co. of riyadh
the sources said that the saudi abha was told to wait for an iranian boarding party to check the cargo
interception of commercial vessels sailing through the strait of hormuz, the sole entryway to the gulf, is common practice by iranian gunboats looking for iraqi-bound cargo to confiscate
iran has struck nine vessels in the last week
the iraqi news agency reported that the latest missile lobbed by iran at baghdad crashed at 7:30 a.m. into a residential neighorhood, ``killing and wounding civilians and destroying property.''
it said iraqi gunners fired a similar projectile into tehran on tuesday
the iranian news agency said five other misiles were fired at ``economic and military centers'' in the iraqi towns of basra and karnaqin
iraq has fired more than 100 missiles against iran and iran has fired more than 60 at iraq this month
the netherlands announced that it is planning to withdraw one of its two mine hunters from the western european force protecting commercial shipping in the gulf. diplomatic sources cited assessments by western security analysts that the mine threat has diminished
a little-known, 33-year-old gop leader will run against edward m. kennedy in the fall for the senate seat kennedy has held without serious challenge since 1962, the republican state chairman said wednesday
joseph malone of waltham, executive director of the massachusetts gop, will challenge kennedy, said party chairman ray shamie, who himself declined a request from president reagan last week that he take on kennedy a second time
the kennedy campaign insisted the five-term democrat will ``take nothing for granted,'' and will wage a statewide grassroots campaign
in washington, b.j. cooper, a deputy white house press secretary, said the white house had no comment on shamie's decision
shamie aide charles manning said that malone represented a new generation of republicans and that as a catholic of italian descent, malone would be a departure from the yankee-protestant line of new england republicans
malone will have neither the name recognition nor the cash of shamie, who sold a high tech business three years ago for more than $60 million
kennedy, 56, was first elected for an interim term from 1962 to 1964, filling the seat once held by his brother john. he went on to victories against a succession of old-line republicans like george cabot lodge and josiah spaulding
a 1978 graduate of harvard college, malone has helped operate a family trucking business and also is a partner in family real estate holdings
i have devoted 10 years of my life working to help bring back a two-party system to massachusetts,'' malone said in an interview. ``it's important that we have a strong, aggressive campaign in massachusetts.''
state democratic party chairman chester atkins said malone is too closely tied to shamie to present himself as a ``new generation'' republican
if the people wouldn't accept the real thing in ray shamie, it will be even harder still for them to accept his understudy,'' he said
shamie, 67, launched his political career in 1982 by investing $1.8 million, mostly of his own money, in a kennedy challenge. while he lost in a landslide _ 61 percent to 38 percent _ it was also the best finish by a republican against kennedy
students at west virginia university who passed on to caterpillar co. confidential information gathered during a class exercise acted on their own, after grades were issued, dean said wednesday
the wall street journal reported tuesday that professor terry wilson, who did consulting work for caterpillar, had students gather information on rival heavy-equipment businesses as part of a class exercise
several current or former wvu graduate students told the journal they then released the information to two caterpillar dealers. the students charged they felt pressure to do so, in part because of wilson's connection to caterpillar
we were worried about getting through the course,'' mark wheatley told the journal. wheatley no longer attends the university and is not listed in the morgantown telephone directory
whatever the students might have done, was done after their grades were issued, said cyril m. logar, dean of wvu's college of business and economics. ``what their grade was based on was all legitimate,'' he said
wheatley and some other students in wilson's marketing class were assigned to do work for the two caterpillar dealerships _ h.o. penn machinery co. in armonk, n.y., and yancey bros. in atlanta _ last spring as part of a project designed to give them practical experience
at the two dealerships' direction, the graduate students obtained inventory and sales volume reports on those dealers' competitors, according to the newspaper
during the survey, those in the class identified themselves only as university students, not mentioning their link to the caterpillar dealers, and promised that information would remain confidential, the journal reported
but that promise was broken, students said, and former student herman flinder, who has since returned to his home in norway, likened the work to ``spying.''
wilson did not return phone calls to his home and office wednesday. the professor told the journal the exercise was good for students but added that he will no longer assign similar projects
spokesmen for both equipment dealers denied asking the students to do anything unethical
it was my understanding that the information would be made available to all the participants,'' said goodloe yancy iv, general manager of yancy bros. ``there are situational ethics involved. at no time were any of the students told to compromise their personal ethics
they chose whatever path they chose,'' he said
milton long, marketing manager for h.o. penn, said he never asked for or received the names of competitors used in the study
logar said that wilson, who is on sababatical, would be told to boost the emphasis on ethics in the curriculum
heavy snow and wind gusting to 89 mph chilled the northwest on wednesday, while the mercury in michigan and ohio hit record highs and most of the rest of the nation had sunny skies
eighteen inches of snow fell overnight across stevens pass in the oregon cascades, and a heavy snow warning remained in effect in the northern cascades of oregon during the afternoon. advisories for snow also were posted in the washington cascades and olympic mountains, as well as the southern cascades of oregon
as the storm system moved eastward, a winter storm warning was posted for wednesday night and thursday in the northern and central mountains of colorado
gusts were clocked at 89 mph in reno, nev., in the morning, but no serious damage was reported. in idaho, winds gusted to 58 miles at twin falls and 54 mph at idaho falls, and thunderstorms and hail also were reported
gale warnings extended along the northern pacific coast through the afternoon
warnings or advisories for high winds were posted from the sierra nevadas of california and much of inland southern california, to parts of washington, nevada, arizona, wyoming and colorado
it was springtime in michigan and seemed like summer in ohio. the temperature at lansing, mich., hit 69, tying the record for the date, while in alpena, mich., the thermometer hit 61, breaking the record by one degree
in southeastern ohio, chesapeake reported 79 degrees. the 73-degree mark in toledo broke a record of 72 set in 1945
rain and occasional thunderstorms continued over the pacific northwest into the afternoon, with snow showers in the idaho panhandle and western wyoming
showers and thunderstorms also extended over western louisiana. afternoon skies were sunny in much of the remainder of the nation
there were no reports of measurable snowfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. est. heavier rainfall during the period included 0.37 inch at newport, ore., and olympia, wash
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 31 degrees at limestone, maine, to 87 degrees at palm springs, calif. the early-morning low for the nation was 3 degrees above zero at montpelier, vt
the forecast for thursday called for snow in the rockies. rain, possibly including severe thunderstorms, was predicted across the plains and much of the missouri, mississippi and ohio valleys, stretching as far as alabama. there will also be rain in northern maine and the northern pacific coast
high temperatures will be in the upper 30s and 40s in the upper great lakes and mississippi valley, the dakotas, the rockies, and northern maine; in the 50s and 60s from southern maine across maryland, the lower great lakes region, the central mississippi valley, middle plains and the northern half of the pacific coast; the low 80s in western florida and from western louisiana across to southern arizona, and in the 70s in most of the rest of the nation. evening. picks up 3rd graf pvs, `the jurors ...'</note>
the jury in the ``preppie murder'' trial of a man accused of strangling a teen-ager during sex in central park deliberated a seventh day wednesday, rehearing testimony about the autopsy on the woman
the jury was interested in the internal injuries revealed by the autopsy performed by dr. maria alandy, associate medical examiner in new york city. she testified about injuries to jennifer levin's mouth, neck, head and internal organs
the jury deliberated until early evening and will return thursday morning
the jurors apparently were trying to discern how badly miss levin, 18, was beaten and how much physical force it would take to cause the injuries. a day earlier, their request focused on how long miss levin had to be choked to produce pinpoint hemorrhaging on her eyelids
the prosecution contends robert chambers punched miss levin before strangling her in a rage. the defense contends the death was accidentally caused when he yanked her backward during rough sex, as chambers said in a videotaped statement to police
after the reading of the testimony, jurors spent several minutes sitting in the jury box speaking with one another before returning to deliberations, which is highly unusual
chambers, 21, is accused of second-degree murder in the death of miss levin on aug. 26, 1986
the jury, which got the case last thursday, could also convict chambers of the lesser crimes of first- or second-degree manslaughter or criminally negligent homicide
the commerce department said wednesday that safeway stores inc. has agreed to pay a $995,000 penalty to settle anti-boycott violations in saudi arabia and kuwait last year
undersecretary paul freedenberg said the sum was ``the largest civil fine in the department's 10-year enforcement of federal anti-boycott laws.'' under the department order, safeway has 20 days to pay the fine
the anti-boycott provisions of the export administration act were designed to keep u.s. firms from participation in foreign boycotts the u.s. government does not sanction
the supermarket chain was charged in july 1987 with multiple violations in connection with operations of supermarkets in saudi arabia and kuwait, including refusing to do business with u.s. suppliers on a saudi arabia boycott list and using a ``whitelist'' of approved suppliers from which it offered products for sale to arab supermarkets
safeway was also accused of furnishing prohibited information to kuwait about its business relationships with israel and furnishing prohibited information about its affiliations with charitable and fraternal organizations which support israel
safeway neither admitted or denied the allegations but agreed to pay the civil fine in a settlement march 14, the commerce department said
had the case gone to trial, and the supermarket chain found guilty on all counts, safeway could have received an administrative sanction and a civil fine of $4.5 million, the department said
a safeway spokesman did not immediately return a reporter's phone calls seeking comment
gold rose $1.13 an ounce thursday, opening at $453.19. it closed wednesday at $452.06
u.s. district judge walter l. nixon of mississippi reported to federal prison wednesday to begin serving a five-year sentence for perjury
nixon, 59, is the second federal judge convicted of crimes while in office. he has refused to step down and continues to draw his $89,500 annual salary
last week, house judiciary chairman peter w. rodino jr., d-n.j., introduced a resolution to impeach him
nixon was convicted in 1986 of lying to a grand jury investigating whether he tried to influence a local drug case involving the son of man with whom he had business dealings. he was sentenced to two concurrent five-year terms
the u.s. supreme court on jan. 19 refused to review nixon's appeal
the first federal judge convicted in office, harry e. claiborne of nevada, was impeached and removed 1{ years ago. he was convicted of tax evasion
at least two rockets were fired from a bazooka at the u.s. embassy wednesday night, police said
the rockets were launched from outside the front of the diplomatic mission by two men from a distance of about 55 yards, police said
there was no immediate information about damage or injuries at the embassy, which is in downtown bogota
richard pyle of the associated press is a member of the pentagon media pool in the persian gulf
the iraqi air force has begun using a second type of soviet-built bomber on its forays against iranian oil shipping in the persian gulf, u.s. naval officers said wednesday
the supersonic tu-22, a twin-jet aircraft known in nato's military lexicon as blinder, apparently carries only iron bombs instead of the air-to-surface missiles that are on iraq's other attack aircraft in the gulf
the u.s. officers, who spoke on condition of not being identified, also said blinders operating over the gulf fly at about 450 mph. that is faster than other iraqi warplanes but less than the aircraft's top speed of 900 mph
one officer said it was possible that the blinders were flying training missions to prepare for regular action against iranian tankers
this guided-missile frigate observed several of the soviet bombers in action during a recent 14-day assignment in the northern gulf
the officers wouldn't indicate whether the flights began before or after a visit to baghdad by an american military delegation last month. the meeting was set up to discuss the problem of iraqi aircraft flying down the gulf in a manner that appeared to pose a threat to u.s. warships
the talks were known to have dealt with flights by iraq's french-built f-1 mirages and soviet-made t-16 badgers, both of which are armed with anti-ship missiles
many u.s. officers have expressed concern that the flight patterns of the iraqi aircraft could lead to another mistaken attack such as that which devastated the frigate stark last may 17, killing 37 of its crew
as the roberts sailed toward the strait of hormuz on tuesday, an iraqi warplane ventured further ``down the pipe'' than usual _ posing no threat. but far enough for a call from the ship's combat information center to interrupt the skipper's dinner
the plane veered eastward toward iran before it reached the point at which cmdr. paul x. rinn said he would have ordered a precautionary increase in alert status
on wednesday, the roberts went to what rinn called a ``modified condition zebra,'' an upgrading of damage-control precautions, when it entered waters about 20 miles from abu musa, a small island that iran uses as a base for gunboat attacks on gulf shipping
u.s. military sources in washington say iran has recently begun installing launch platforms for its chinese-made silkworm anti-ship missiles on the island
rinn, a native new yorker who now lives in summerville, s.c., told members of a pentagon news media poll that there has been no change in navy procedures around abu musa, and there was no evidence of the silkworms having been placed on the island
we've always been careful around abu musa because it's a base for the iranian speedboats,'' he said
iranian gunboats, on the lookout for war-related materials bound for archenemy iraq, were heard conducting their usual challenges of commercial vessels as to their cargoes and destinations
a major rebel group appears ready to sign a peace agreement drafted during a week of talks in northern uganda, the government newspaper and sources said wednesday
ugandan soldiers and the rebel uganda people's democratic army have observed a cease-fire since negotiations began last thursday at gulu, a town 170 miles north of kampala, the government paper new vision reported
we are coming out fully to join the government,'' said mike kilama, chief rebel negotiator. ``we are coming to join hands with the nra to work and rebuild our nation.''
uganda's army is called the national resistance army, the name yoweri museveni gave it during a five-year bush war that gained him the presidency two years ago
a proposal drafted in the negotiations says the army will accept rebels who are found not to have taken part in atrocities under previous regimes, sources reported
reports from the sources and in new vision said the agreement excludes politicians. among them are otema allimadi, who was prime minister under former president milton obote and directed the rebel army from london
new vision said the peace agreement was to be signed within days and the rebels were assembling at lukome, 8 miles north of gulu
they consist almost entirely of soldiers from the previous national army, which museveni's forces drove into southern sudan at the end of the civil war. the rebel army began its insurgency in august 1986
rebel spokesmen say there are 7,000 insurgents, but the government puts the strength at 3,000. more than half a dozen rebel groups operate in uganda, but the uganda people's democratic army is the most professional
museveni declared a six-month amnesty in which rebels would be allowed to surrender. it expires at the end of march, and museveni said tuesday he was reluctant to extend it. pvs, `india protested ...' minor editing throughout to conform.</note>
troops detained hundreds of arabs in a huge crackdown to contain four months of unrest in the occupied lands, and israeli jets bombed palestinian guerrilla bases in south lebanon wednesday for the second time in a week
overnight raids which went into wednesday morning were israel's latest strategy for ending a rebellion which, by u.n. count, has killed 107 arabs and one israeli soldier
arab reports said about 500 palestinians were rounded up. defense minister yitzhak rabin said 3,000 have been detained since riots began dec. 8 in the west bank and gaza strip
israeli troops in gaza shot and wounded an arab protester in jabaliya refugee camp, shifa hospital officials said. they said another arab from deir al balah camp was badly hurt with beating injuries to his head
the number of major demonstrations and clashes has fallen dramatically in recent days and rabin credited israel's tough policies of mass arrests and economic sanctions
the phenomenon of large violent demonstrations has been substantially reduced ... as a result of the general activity of the army, the security forces, the riot police,'' rabin told officers on a tour of gaza. ``we feel a certain tiredness among the (arab) population.''
prime minister yitzhak shamir said simply restoring quiet was not enough
no doubt, it is possible to turn the situation back to normal and even a better one,'' shamir said wednesday on israel television. ``but i think it's not enough today to restore order and normal life. we have to prepare ground so this does not repeat itself.''
there are things to be done to prevent the return of these dangerous events,'' he said, without elaborating
nearly all the 107 palestinians killed died by israeli army gunfire or beatings. the israeli soldier was shot to death by an arab last weekend
india protested israel's handling of the arab rebellion by canceling a match in israel by its davis cup tennis team scheduled for next month. it was the first such cancellation of a sports or entertainment event
gad yacobi, israel's economy minister, said the violence and strikes have cost israel more than $335 million in lost production, exports and added security expenses. he said the figure did not include losses to tourism and agriculture
in the air raid, israeli pilots destroyed buildings used by guerrillas to store weapons and equipment near sidon, a port in south lebanon, the military said. it was the fourth israeli air raid in lebanon this year
the army did not identify a guerrilla group, but beirut radio stations said the warehouses belonged to yasser arafat's palestinian guerrilla group fatah and lebanese moslem militias
shamir reported to the 10-member inner cabinet on his talks in washington. a minister who attended said shamir had found no signs the united states would yield to israeli requests for changes in its middle east peace proposals, which involve trading territory for peace
the army said it might allow israelis to volunteer for three to six months of paid reserve duty in addition to annual compulsory duty. last week, the army increased the compulsory tour from 42 days to 50
according to the arab-run palestinie press service and arabic daily al quds, soldiers detained about 500 palestinians overnight, including 200 from hebron and the nearby west bank village of dura
palestinian witnesses said the army sealed off villages and refugee camps after midnight, then went from house to house with lists of names. the arab news agency said 80 people were arrested in attil, 12 miles north of nablus
army spokesmen confirmed mass arrests overnight but would not give numbers
an israeli official said rabin told a parliamentary committee israel has jailed 3,000 arabs since dec. 8, including 700 since sunday
he said, on condition of anonymity, that 1,000 more arabs had been arrested and released. the official also confirmed a report in the daily haaretz that the army planned to put 300 arabs under administrative detention, meaning they could be jailed for up to six months without trial
a palestine liberation organization leaflet circulated in the gaza strip said payments will be made to arabs who lose family members, property or jobs because of clashes with israeli soldiers
it cited $2,900 for ``martyrs'' killed fighting soldiers, $600 for anyone arrested and $1,450 for a merchant unable to open his store because of a strike. arab policemen who resigned would get $1,450 as a first payment, the leaflet said
israel had imposed rules limiting the flow of money into the territories in an attempt to prevent such compensation and other plo financing of the rebellion
a house subcommittee has decided against seeking perjury charges against the chairman of the nation's largest meatpacker for testifying falsely last year that only one set of injury records was kept at its dakota city, neb., packinghouse
rep. tom lantos, d-calif., chairman of the house government operations committee's subcommittee on employment and housing, said that although the testimony by ibp corp. chairman robert peterson was misleading, the panel will not ask the justice department to prosecute him
peterson, testifying before the panel last may, denied charges from the united food and commercial workers union that the company was keeping two sets of injury logs _ one for internal use and the other to be shown to government inspectors _ at its dakota city plant
afterwards, the company sent the subcommittee a 28-page statement again denying there were two sets of records. later, however, peterson wrote lantos a letter saying that he had learned that two sets of logs were in fact kept
at a subsequent hearing last september, ibp officials said their earlier testimony was based on misunderstandings between the plant's medical director and a vice president of the company
while some of the explanations offered by top ibp officials strained credibility or were incongruent and raised serious questions, there is insufficient evidence to warrant referring the matter to the justice department for perjury proceedings,'' lantos said tuesday
he made the statement in presenting the subcommittee's report on the occupational safety and health administration's handling of the ibp case to the full 39-member government operations committee
committee officials said they expect that report to be released within the next two weeks
ibp, then a subsidiary of occidental petroleum co., and the ufcw were engaged in a bitter lockout turned strike at the dakota city plant during the subcommittee's first hearing
as the result of proddings from the union, osha initiated a thorough inspection of the plant and subsequently fined ibp more than $2 million for a series of health, safety and record violations
at the time, it was the largest fine ever levied by osha. ibp has contested the osha charges and is appealing the fine
texts for an afghan peace settlement have been sent to lawyers for finishing touches but there still is no agreement on two essential issues, sources close to the geneva negotiations said wednesday
the sources said one question still open was whether the current afghan government or another would oversee implementation of the deal. the other is the future of aid to afghanistan from the soviet union, which now has an estimated 115,000 soldiers in the country helping fight moslem insurgents
moscow and its communist allies in kabul say both issues are outside the scope of the geneva talks and raising them with a third country _ pakistan in this case _ would constitute interference in afghanistan's internal affairs
diego cordovez, the u.n. mediator, was said to be confident a third problem could be resolved by compromise language. that problem arose last week when abdul wakil, the afghan foreign minister, accused pakistan at a news conference of creating new ``complications'' by reviving an old border dispute
it concerns the durand line, a boundary between afghanistan and british india agreed upon in 1893. it was accepted by pakistan after independence in 1947, but afghanistan claimed an area south of the line
pakistan's chief negotiator in geneva, acting foreign minister zain noorani, told reporters on the same day wakil made his allegations that his delegation ``never raised any question as to the pakistani-afghan border.''
he said the border was a ``non-issue'' and pakistan accepts the passage in the agreements requiring the parties ``to refrain from violations of the existing internationally recognized boundary between the two countries.''
pakistan acts as spokesman for the afghan guerrillas. fund</head> including accountant saying dealership was in deep trouble, picking up 8th graf pvs, `donna carlson...'. deletes 12th graf pvs, `asked by...'., and last 3 grafs to tighten.</note>
gov. evan mecham's auto dealership would have been overdrawn and unable to meet its payroll if he hadn't borrowed $80,000 from a state fund, an accountant testified at mecham's impeachment trial wednesday
the testimony contradicted mecham's claim that he didn't need the money and that he borrowed it in july solely to help the state earn higher interest than it was receiving on the money
an accountant hired by the prosecution to analyze the financial records of mecham's company indicated the money was badly needed
unless these funds had been paid from the protocol fund, mecham pontiac would have had an overdraft the following wednesday in excess of $60,000,'' said randall sorensen, referring to the payday following the loan
the senate is investigating allegations mecham misused the funds, which were raised by his inaugural committee but transferred to the protocol fund because of a state law barring use of such contributions to pay campaign debts
sorensen took the stand after former mecham chief of staff james colter acknowledged he filled mecham's request for the $80,000 loan to his car dealership without checking the company's financial condition
when sen. manuel pena suggested to colter, who left the mecham administration in the fall, that mecham pontiac was overencumbered when the loan was taken, colter said: ``if that's so, it's a bummer deal. but it was repaid, so i guess it wasn't a bummer deal.''
prosecutor paul eckstein noted that mecham testified before the house that his company did not need the money to pay the bank for overdue loans on cars
however, sorensen said mecham pontiac paid first interstate bank $81,309 owed for six cars on july 17, 1987 _ the same day that the $80,000 loan was received
on cross-examination, mecham's lawyer, jerris leonard, suggested that the mecham car dealership had assets that could have been converted to cash when needed. but sorensen said he saw no records indicating such assets
leonard also said the dealership had a net worth of $4.25 million. but sorensen said some of the figures he saw indicated otherwise. he did not elaborate
prosecutors had said they would show that mecham pontiac was in deep financial trouble and ``desperately needed the loan'' to survive
in his statement tuesday, leonard said of mecham's loan: ``the governor is going to tell you he did it for one purpose and one purpose only, to try to improve the earnings of the fund.''
the governor's lawyers had objected vehemently to testimony about the dealership's financial condition but were overruled
before the trial recessed for the day, former arizona attorney general jack lasoto testified that he analyzed state laws relating to the mecham loan and found it was improper
he said it was clear that money placed in the governor's protocol fund became public money intended for promoting arizona's image
also wednesday, mecham's former legislative aide testified she quit because she was worried that ``people could possibly go to jail'' if the loan was discovered
donna carlson, who was the subject of an alleged death threat investigated earlier in the trial, testified she and other mecham staffers believed the fund could be used only to ``promote the interests of the state of arizona.''
in addition to charges of obstructing the investigation of an alleged threat against ms. carlson and of misusing state funds, mecham is accused in the impeachment trial of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan
ms. carlson described a conversation with colter late last summer which she said involved both loans
mr. colter was extremely upset,'' said ms. carlson. ``he said, `i don't think the governor understands the magnitude of the debt.' ... he said, `i had to loan him $80,000 out of the protocol fund.'''
i believe i came out of my chair,'' ms. carlson said. ``i made a remark ... that people could possibly go to jail for something like that.''
witnesses have said that ms. carlson was the subject of an alleged death threat just before she was called to testify before a grand jury about mecham's campaign finances
the first-term republican governor also faces an april 21 criminal trial on felony charges of concealing the campaign loan. mecham, the first u.s. governor to face an impeachment trial in six decades, also faces a recall election may 17
during intensive quizzing by senators, colter insisted he never tried to cover up the protocol fund loan to the dealership even though it was never recorded in the fund's check register
i'm a poor record-keeper,'' he said
an ominous warming of the atmosphere and depletion of earth's protective ozone shield have given urgency to plans by nasa, japan and europe to launch four satellites to study the planet's ecological system
the project ``will bring about a revolution in our understanding of the earth as a whole system,'' said dixon butler, project scientist for the national aeronautics and space administration, which plans to spend more than $2 billion on its share
instruments planned for the first satellite include a laser to measure movement along faults such as the san andreas in california; radar that can by peer through clouds and vegetation, and devices to measure wind speed and direction, air temperature and humidity
officials said the polar-orbiting satellites could improve weather forecasts by allowing meteorologists to study developing weather patterns worldwide
other instruments also are scheduled to be placed on the space station, which is set for operation in the mid-1990s, but the eos is being designed so it will work even if the space station is delayed
the program recently moved into high gear because of ominous changes in the earth's atmosphere, butler said tuesday, speaking via satellite to scientists at nasa centers across the country, including the jet propulsion laboratory in pasadena
the four satellites will operate for 15 years, and one of their tasks will be to monitor the greenhouse effect, in which earth's temperature is gradually rising because of increased carbon dioxide in the atmosphere, butler said from nasa's goddard space flight center in greenbelt, md
the satellites also will keep track of depletion of earth's protective ozone layer, he said
scientists fear the greenhouse effect may cause crop failures and raise sea levels, threating threaten coastal cities. loss of high-altitude ozone will let more harmful solar ultraviolet rays reach earth, increasing skin cancer and possibly killing microscopic ocean organisms that are at the bottom of the food chain, scientists say
nasa plans to launch its first eos satellite, a 60-foot-long spacecraft carrying 20 instruments, in 1995, followed by the launch of a european space agency satellite in 1997. nasa's second satellite could lift off in 1997, followed by a 1998 launch for the fourth satellite, which would be japanese
butler said the soviet union, which has many satellites in polar orbit, also may participate
nasa is asking for $20 million in next year's budget to determine what instruments should be placed on the satellites, then will seek money in 1991 to build the equipment, nasa spokesman charles redmond said
satellites in polar orbit circle earth from north to south, allowing onboard instruments to study the whole planet as it rotates
customs agents seized $1 million worth of caviar in three states and arrested two men on charges of importing the delicacy in violation of an embargo on iranian goods, authorities said wednesday
about 3,400 pounds of iranian caviar were flown into miami in counterfeit russian caviar tins and repacked in iranian tins, said customs service spokesman michael sheehan
gerald stein, 49, of new york city and patrick bachelier, 38, of miami were charged with violating a 1987 presidential ban on imports from iran
the caviar was seized march 15 at caspian caviar co. in miami, iron gate caviar co. in new york city and epicurean international inc. in rockville, md., sheehan said
the caviar was in fact falsely labeled in western europe in order to circumvent the embargo,'' sheehan said. ``after the cavier was released by customs, bachelier would transfer the caviar into iranian tins, which he had imported separately.''
bachelier, who owns caspian caviar, said wednesday, ``i'm innocent. it's a mistake.''
he said he imported some iranian caviar under a permit issued to a person he declined to identify. the rest of the caviar was genuine russian caviar, he said
stein is president of iron gate products, a wholesaler, and is author of ``caviar! caviar! caviar!'' a published report last year said his company supplies macy's department stores
telephone calls to iron gate products went unanswered wednesday
stein is scheduled for an appearance in federal court in miami on april 5 and bachelier was arraigned march 16. they face up to 16 years in prison and $150,000 fines if convicted
the legislature's chief abortion foe said the odds of a rape victim getting pregnant are ``one in millions and millions and millions'' because the trauma causes a ``certain secretion'' that kills sperm
doctors specializing in reproduction dismissed the claim, made by republican rep. stephen freind, as nonsense
freind, who made the assertion during an interview on a hanover radio station earlier this month, said tuesday he stands by the claim and will provide medical documentation to support it in about a week
gov. robert p. casey has said he will sign a bill that requires victims of rape or incest to report the crimes to be eligible for government funding of abortions
in a debate with barry steinhardt of the philadelphia branch of the american civil liberties union, freind said, ``it is almost but not quite impossible to become pregnant on the basis of rape. the odds are one in millions and millions and millions. and there is a physical reason for that
rape, obviously, is a traumatic experience,'' he said. ``when that traumatic experience is undergone, a woman secretes a certain secretion, which has a tendency to kill sperm.''
there's no basis for that. that's nonsense,'' dr. richard depp, chairman of the department of obstetrics and gynecology at thomas jefferson university in philadelphia
dr. luigi mastroianni jr., director of the division of human reproduction at the hospital of the university of pennsylvania in philadelphia, said tuesday: ``boy. if i could find out what that (secretion) was, i'd use it as a contraceptive.''
mastroianni, a past president of the american fertility society, said: ``there is no such secretion.''
he said freind's statements ``reflect a lack of concern for women who have been victimized by rape'' by dismissing the act as not having consequence
freind has been trying for years to get strong anti-abortion laws through the legislature
most americans believe president reagan should not have sent troops to honduras last week, according to a cbs news-new york times poll released wednesday
thirty-five percent of the participants in the survey conducted between friday and tuesday said the troops should have been sent, 52 percent said they should not have been, and 13 percent said they did not know
the poll asked respondents if they were more concerned about the united states getting into a war in honduras or about a communist takeover in the area
it found that 53 percent were more worried about getting into a war and 37 percent about a communist takeover, while 4 percent said the factors were equal and 2 percent said they were worried about neither. four percent said they did not know
when asked if president reagan should pardon oliver north if he is convicted of theft, fraud and conspiracy charges in the iran-contra affair, 43 percent said yes, 43 percent said no and 14 percent said they did not know
the poll also found that 48 percent of those interviewed did not think the united states should be giving military aid to the contras while 39 percent said the aid should be given and 13 percent said they did not know
when asked if vice president george bush is hiding something the public ought to know about the iran-contra matter, 51 percent said he is, 28 percent said he is not and 21 percent said they did not know
a total of 1,654 people were interviewed for the poll, which has a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percent
president jose sarney on wednesday hailed the decision to keep the presidential system of government, but some brazilians wondered how long sarney himself would be be allowed to keep the office
lawmakers writing a new constitution ended a year of political uncertaintly tuesday by deciding to have a president, rather than a prime minister, as chief of government
it's a victory for the nation. it is not a personal victory,'' said sarney, who has complained that uncertainty about the country's political direction was a factor in brazil's economic and social ills
sarney told reporters, ``this decision was better for the country. congress understood that.''
lawmakers decided 344-212 to have a presidential system of government. legislators who argued in favor of parliamentarism said a prime minister was a modern alternative and a protection from military leaders, who have made it clear they favor a presidential system
sarney said parliamentarism ``would bring chaos and threaten democracy,'' an indirect reference to possible government intervention by the military
lawmakers also voted a five-year term for the presidential office, another victory for sarney
but whether sarney can serve that long should be known in about a month, when lawmakers are to vote on the remaining length of sarney's tenure
his term likely will be the last item voted on by the 559 legislators rewriting an authoritarian constitution. the present constitution was handed down without a vote in 1969 by a military junta that seized power in a 1964 coup. brazilians haven't voted for president since 1960
the country's leftist faction and most brazilians, according to polls, would like to see sarney's term reduced by one year, from five to four
but some brazilians said trimming a year off sarney's term is harder now, after congress voted to give the office of president a five-year term
it would be hateful to have other presidents with five years and reduce sarney's to four,'' said communications minister antonio carlos magalhaes
the lawmakers' vote was preceded by heavy lobbying by sarney and his supporters
jornal do brasil, the influential daily of rio de janeiro, condemned the ``methods used'' to obtain victory and criticized sarney for not keeping a promise to step down in four years
the intervention of the government was obscene,'' said rep. ronaldo cezar coelho of the brazilian democratic movement party
indirectly elected in an electoral college election, sarney was running mate on a liberal ticket headed by tancredo neves. neves died before taking office and sarney became president in march 1985
as former leader of the military-backed party, sarney was a compromise candidate to appease the outgoing generals
the neves-sarney team was to be a transitional marriage to smoothly lead south america's largest country to democracy. but under three years of sarney, brazil has had its highest inflation rate in history
authorities outlawed an independent students union at warsaw university on the grounds that it threatened to stir unrest and engage in anti-state activities, organizers of the group said wednesday
members of the organizing committee of the warsaw university independent students union, known by its polish initials nzs, said they would defy the ban and organize a rally next week to protest delays in dormitory renovations
the ban, dated monday, was signed by the city's socio-administrative department, which has the power to decide the legality of organizations established by citizens
student union activists announced at a march 8 campus rally, attended by about 2,000 students, that they were giving up underground activities to work openly for more academic freedoms and to protect students' material interests
the banning order said the program of the nzs chapter shows the student union's ``intention is to undertake activities which could cause a threat to the peace and public order.''
a copy of the order was made available to western reporters wednesday
student activists have campaigned at several major universities this year for communist authorities to legalize the independent students union, which was officially registered in february 1981 but outlawed a year later after the martial law crackdown on the solidarity free trade union movement
about 1,500 warsaw university students have joined the warsaw university nzs chapter since march 8, said andrzej papierz, a history student and union organizer
