_ ``sarafina!,'' a south african musical about high school students in a black township. cort, 239-6200, same number as telecharge. available
_ ``starlight express,'' an andrew lloyd webber-trevor nunn roller-skating extravaganza about a train race across the united states. gershwin, 586-6510. teletron. available
_ ``the gospel at colonus,'' a gospel version of a greek classic by sophocles. lunt-fontanne, 575-9200. teletron. ticketron. available
_ ``the nerd,'' a comedy by larry shue, author of ``the foreigner,'' about the limits of friendship. helen hayes, 944-9450. teletron. ticketron. available. closes april 9
_ ``the phantom of the opera,'' the lavish andrew lloyd webber musical about a deformed composer who haunts the paris opera house and the young soprano he loves. majestic, 239-6290, same number as telecharge. difficult. florida suit; and to recast to clarify that both man and wife died in crash. picks up 5th graf pvs, `we don't...'. adds 4 grafs with detail on second case.</note>
the death of an ibm executive in a 1985 airplane crash deprived him of more than $6 million in earnings, according to a federal jury that awarded $7.95 million to the estates of the man and his wife
attorneys for delta air lines immediately moved to set aside the verdict, delivered monday night after five hours of deliberations in the case brought by the estate of philip d. estridge, 47, of new canaan, conn., and his wife, mary ann, who also died in the crash
tuesday, another ibm executive who lost a daughter in the crash, and claimed his career was damaged by his emotional reaction to that loss, won a $3.5 million damage judgment against delta in a case that was tried in west palm beach, fla. the flight originated in fort lauderdale
attorney lee kreindler, who represented the estridge estate, said the sum awarded in the new york case was a record for compensatory damages in a wrongful-death suit. the breakdown was $6.25 million for estridge's loss of earning; $750,000 for loss of enjoyment of life; and $100,000 for mental anguish
for the estate of mrs. estridge, the jury awarded $750,000 for loss of enjoyment of life; and $100,000 for mental anguish. the couple's three daughters had sought $25 million for estridge and $5 million for mrs. estridge
we don't think anything could have happened any better, and we're definitely relieved it's over,'' said evelyn eubanks, one of the daughters. ``it doesn't make it better, but it helps us to live with it.''
estridge, who received much of the credit for moving ibm into the personal computer market, and his wife were among 137 people killed when a lockheed l-1011 crashed on approach at dallas-fort worth international airport on aug. 2, 1985
ibm chairman and chief executive john f. akers testified at the trial that there was ``a strong possibility'' estridge would have become one of the company's six senior executives
those executives make an average of $350,000 per year, with an additional $150,000 per year in ibm stock which cannot be sold until retirement. shortly before his death, estridge was named overseer of ibm's worldwide manufacturing operations at a yearly salary of $240,000
akers also testified there was a competitive market for computer executives and estridge could have moved to another company offering more money
although the trial was held in new york city, the award was reached under the law of estridge's home state of connecticut to allow for the salary projection figures, kreindler said
delta lawyer john sabetta declined to comment on the award, but asked u.s. district judge john e. sprizzo to set the jury award aside shortly after it was announced. legal briefs on that motion are due may 21
delta spokesman bill berry referred calls to the company's insurance carrier, u.s. aviation underwriters, and had no other comment. a u.s. aviation spokesman, bob albert, was in a meeting and unavailable to comment
in the florida case, a federal jury deliberated less than two hours before awarding dennis and gayle zarnt of boca raton $3.5 million for the death of their 15-year-old daughter, julie, who coincidentally was aboard the same flight as the estridges
ibm executives testified in videotaped depositions that the girl's death left zarnt, a member of the management team responsible for the introduction of the original ibm-pc, an emotional ``basket case'' unable to continue what had been an outstanding career
delta attorney howard barwick, who had argued to the jury that an award of about $500,000 would be adequate, declined to comment on the verdict. the zarnts' attorney, robert m. montgomery jr., said he expected delta would appeal. he had sought $5 million in damages
much of ibm's development of the personal computer was done at boca raton, and the estridges had formerly lived there
higher postage rates, including a 25-cent charge for first-class letters, will take effect april 3, the postal service says
the new rates, announced tuesday, reflect higher costs of delivering mail, said john l. griesemer, chairman of the postal service board of governors
the board set the effective date for the sweeping series of new rates recommended by the independent postal rate commission earlier this month. rates were last changed in february 1985, when the price of a first-class stamp rose to 22 cents from 20 cents
dissident stockholders dropped their opposition to texaco inc.'s financial reorganization plan as a federal judge opened a hearing on whether to implement the proposal
texaco, the nation's third largest oil company, announced tuesday that the plan was overwhelmingly supported in a vote by shareholders. some 96 percent of the 181 million shares voted backed the plan, which would allow the company to emerge from bankruptcy court protection
u.s. bankruptcy court judge howard schwartzberg heard comments on the plan from various parties, and recessed the hearing until today
campeau corp. has sweetened its bid for federated department stores inc. and proposed a friendly merger with the retailer
campeau raised its two-tier, all-cash offer to approximately $73 a share, or $6.53 billion, on tuesday from $68 a share, or $6.18 billion
at the same time, campeau extended the deadline for expiration of its offer until midnight est april 4, when a competing $6.3 billion tender offer by r.h. macy &amp; co. inc. that federated has accepted is also due to expire
american stores co. has offered $1.72 billion to acquire lucky stores inc. of california in a deal that would create one of the nation's largest supermarket and discount drug chains
the $45-per-share bid announced tuesday for lucky stores came some 16 months after lucky derailed a hostile takeover attempt by new york investor asher edelman
the latest unsolicited offer sent lucky's stock soaring by $14.50 a share to $46.37{ on the new york stock exchange
black &amp; decker corp. has withdrawn its $77-a-share bid for american standard inc., halting the bidding war over the plumbing giant
tuesday's action permits a $78-a-share leveraged buyout of american standard, spearheaded by kelso &amp; co. and valued at $2.45 billion, to go forward
under the agreement, kelso will pay black &amp; decker $25 million for withdrawing its bid, as soon as kelso begins purchasing stock under its tender offer or acquires at least 20 percent of american standard's shares in any other transaction
koppers co. has rejected a revised cash tender offer of $56 a share, or about $1.6 billion, from a takeover company formed by britain's brian beazer and the u.s. investment firm shearson lehman hutton inc
koppers chairman charles r. pullin said tuesday that the koppers' board believes remaining independent ``is a superior alternative to accepting'' the revised offer from beazer's bns inc
entertainer merv griffin has raised his bid for hotel and casino operator resorts international inc. by $70 million to $295 million
the new offer disclosed tuesday is for $45.73 per share, more than twice the $22 per share that his rival bidder, real estate tycoon donald trump, is proposing to pay for the portion of the company he doesn't already own
trump, who is resorts' chairman, controls 88 percent of the company's voting power. trump's lawyer, jack nusbaum, said tuesday that trump would be willing to withdraw his own offer for resorts under certain conditions
orders to u.s. factories for major durable goods fell 1.8 percent in february, the government says
but analysts said tuesday that the second consecutive monthly decline in durable goods orders _ which matched the 1.8 percent decline in january _ had not shaken their belief that manufacturing will be a bright spot in the economy this year
federal fuel-economy standards will cause thousands of traffic deaths next year by discouraging the use of safer, larger cars, two researchers say
a study released tuesday by robert w. crandall of the brookings institution in washington and john d. graham of the harvard school of public health in boston said fuel-economy regulation ``inevitably leads to smaller, lighter cars that are inherently less safe'' than bigger cars
meanwhile, the transportation department told congress that passenger cars sold in the united states got 28.2 miles per gallon last year overall, up 0.2 miles per gallon from the previous year
three zeros may mean nothing by themselves, but leaving them off the end of a number may cost the nation's largest insurer about $11 million
prudential insurance co. of america is offering the payment to settle claims resulting from a clerical error in which a lien it held was listed as worth $92,885 instead of $92,885,000
u.s. bankruptcy judge howard buschman iii heard closing arguments on the proposed settlement tuesday and is expected to rule within several days
eight states have filed suit accusing dozens of insurance companies of conspiring to create the liability insurance crisis, making coverage unavailable or too costly for many governments and businesses
texas attorney general jim mattox said tuesday that the suits alleged that eight american property and casualty insurance companies, along with other industry representatives, plotted to create the liability insurance crisis beginning around 1984
david ostwald, a vice president of the insurance services office, which is named in the suit, called the charges ``unfounded and meritless.''
the stock market finished narrowly mixed tuesday as the dow jones average of 30 industrials fell 0.99 point to 2,066.15
bond prices were narrowly mixed and short-term interest rates edged up
the dollar finished mixed against most major currencies
platinum future prices surged, petroleum futures prices finished mostly higher, wheat and soybean futures prices rose but corn slipped
energy futures prices have turned mixed in moderate trading, with crude oil falling sharply on the final day of trading in the april contract
on the new york mercantile exchange, contracts for april delivery of west texas intemediate, the benchmark u.s. crude, settled at $16.09 per 42-gallon barrel tuesday, down 40 cents from monday. the contract had fallen 9 cents on monday
traders attributed the decline largely to technical factors stemming from the imminent expiration of the april contract, which traded for the last time on tuesday. the may contract for wti rose 6 cents to $16.37 a barrel
among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale heating oil closed up 0.75 cent at 46.15 cents per gallon, after rising 0.35 cent monday. unleaded gasoline, which increased 0.12 cent on monday, gained 0.21 cent to 46.32 cents a gallon on tuesday
richard redoglia, a trader for merrill lynch energy futures, said prices were supported by speculation that a pending weekly report from the american petroleum institute would show a reduction in crude oil stock levels
he said the market generally ignored the cancellation of a tuesday news conference by rilwanu lukman, president of the organization of petroleum exporting countries, that was expected to have focused on stabilizing sagging oil prices
no one expected him to say anything of great importance anyway,'' redoglia said
down but not out of its battle for federated department stores inc., campeau corp. has launched a counterattack: a sweetened buyout offer and a proposal for a friendly merger
campeau's move on tuesday appeared to give it back the edge it recently lost to r.h. macy &amp; co. inc. in the high-stakes campaign to acquire the cincinnati-based retailer
campeau raised its two-step, all-cash offer to approximately $73 a share, or $6.53 billion, from $68 a share, or $6.18 billion. under the new offer, campeau said it would pay $82 each for 70.5 million federated shares and $37 for the remainder of federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares in a subsequent merger
campeau also extended the expiration of its offer to midnight est april 4, when macy's competing $6.3 billion offer is to expire
campeau, a toronto-based developer, also proposed to federated's board of directors an alternate friendly merger under which it would pay $73 a share for 70.5 million shares in a tender offer and $73 for the remaining shares following the merger
federated has agreed to merge with macy, which is offering $77.35 a share in cash for 70.43 million federated shares, for a total of $5.4 billion. macy would exchange shares in the merged company and issue convertible debt securities for the remainder of federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares
federated stock was up $2.37{ to $69.25 a share in new york stock exchange composite trading tuesday. campeau announced its sweetened offer an hour before the end of the session
campeau had been expected to sweeten its offer or propose a friendly deal after the company lost two rounds in court to invalidate federated's ``poison pill'' takeover defense
campeau contended its bid could not go forward while the pill was in effect, leaving macy with the upper hand following the court rulings
the defense makes a takeover prohibitively expensive by allowing federated shareholders to buy more of the company's stock at a steep discount
it was not immediately clear how a simultaneous expiration of both offers would affect the application of the pill, over which federated has sole discretion
that's not something we can really comment on at this point,'' said jim sluzewski, a federated spokesman
nancy raeside, a campeau spokeswoman, said the company would continue its legal battle to strike down the defense
on monday, a federal judge rebuffed campeau's proposal that he remove the pill in exchange for campeau extending its tender offer to expire simultaneously with macy's offer
u.s. district judge leonard sand said the pill would remain in place at least until federated makes a final recommendation to its shareholders, ms. raeside said. on friday, sand denied campeau's request to invalidate the pill
before sand's ruling, analysts had given campeau's all-cash offer the edge over macy's cash-and-stock bid. but campeau appeared to regain the advantage with its sweetened offer, said edward johnson, an analyst with prescott ball &amp; turben inc
johnson said federated shareholders likely would jump to take advantage of the higher price in the first stage of campeau's offer. ``it puts campeau's bid ahead and leaves the ball up to macy's,'' he said
macy had no immediate comment on campeau's move, said maureen milano, a spokeswoman for the retailer
federated spokesman sluzewski said if the federated board received a revised offer from campeau, the directors would consider it. he said the board was scheduled to meet this week, but would not confirm that the revised offer would be on the agenda
in a letter to the federated board, campeau proposed that a campeau-federated merger be structured along lines similar to the retailer's agreement with macy
campeau said it also would continue fighting federated's agreement to pay macy millions of dollars in fees if the macy-federated deal falls through
lucky stores inc., a takeover target for the second time in two years, is highly regarded in the supermarket industry for its quality management and shrewd marketing practices
the company is on a roll,'' analyst jonathan ziegler of sutro &amp; co. inc. said tuesday after american stores co. made an unsolicited $45 a share, $1.72 billion buyout that sent lucky's stock soaring
i think american wants lucky's management as much they want a stronger foothold in california,'' ziegler said
lucky said from its headquarters in dublin, 30 miles east of san francisco, that it was not prepared to comment on the surprise offer
but investors reacted quickly, sending lucky's stock climbing $14.50 a share to $46.37{ tuesday in heavy trading on the new york stock exchange. the rise above american stores' offer could indicate speculators believe the bids will go even higher _ some analysts say $50 a share is not out of the question
if successful, the acquisition by salt lake city-based american stores would create the nation's largest supermarket chain
lucky stores, the nation's no. 6 grocery retailer, has 480 stores and had $6.4 billion in 1987 sales. american stores, the third biggest, has 1,600 stores and $14.1 billion in sales
the bid for lucky came just over a year after takeover strategist asher edelman formally dropped a hostile takeover attempt, in return for the company's agreement to $2.8 million of his legal costs
lucky thwarted edelman partly by selling off non-grocery divisions and adopting anti-takeover measures that make it difficult but not impossible for an unwanted suitor to grab the company
a lot of people were looking to see how the restructured lucky's would wind up,'' said ron rotter, an analyst for morgan, olmstead, kennedy &amp; gardner in los angeles
they're seeing a very healthy company that got out of its one link, the midwest, and is left with very strong market shares in much of the country,'' he said
in its defensive restructuring, lucky stores closed its popular gemco department stores and sold other non-grocery divisions, shedding thousands of employees in the process
industry observers say the slimming gave company management the impetus to make long-needed structural changes that have been beneficial in the long run
the ``poison pill'' anti-takeover measure adopted during the edelman battle clash limits the voting power of any shareholder who acquires more than 10 percent of lucky's stock
today, the company is a major force in the discount supermarket business. its main competitors are oakland-based safeway _ the nation's largest grocery chain _ in northern california and von's and ralph's in southern california
the one thing that makes them (lucky's) successful is they have a clearly defined identity as the every-day, low-price leader,'' said rotter. ``even the competition will admit that they are the king at that
other stores are constantly shifting what their identity is,'' rotter said
if successful, american stores is expected to merge its weaker alpha beta grocery chain in california with lucky's stores, according to ziegler
i think it makes a lot of sense for american stores, and lucky's management would get a chance to shake up alpha beta,'' he said
if the dublin-based chain fights the bid, its might attempt a leveraged buyout or to seek a ``white knight'' friendly suitor to make a more attractive offer. but lucky stores, which had been exploring a possible acquisition of ralph's and further expansion in the food retailing business, may not be able to stand on its own through a second takeover battle, analysts said
until tuesday, the company's stock had been creeping up gradually since the october stock market crash. it stood at $35 a share last oct. 1, then fell to $21 before recovering to the levels it held before the american stores offer. stock</head>
in an unexpected twist, real estate developer donald trump has offered to end his bid for resorts international inc. and back a rival offer by entertainer merv griffin _ but only if griffin agrees only to seek stock with lesser voting rights than that owned by trump
mr. trump's position is quite simple,'' his attorney, jack nusbaum of new york said tuesday. ``if mr. griffin wishes to buy the (other) stock and become mr. trump's silent partner, god bless him.''
griffin _ who raised his cash offer for resorts by $70 million to $295 million on tuesday _ quickly rejected trump's proposal as ``ludicrous,'' said spokesman mark gill
we are trying to buy the entire company,'' gill quoted griffin as saying. ``we aren't interested in fooling around with portions or in sparring on the board with mr. trump.''
trump, who is resorts' chairman, controls 88 percent of the company's voting power by owning nearly all of its 752,000 class b common shares, which have 100 votes each
the company also has 5.7 million class a common shares with one vote each. trump owns none of those shares
nusbaum said if griffin amended his offer to seek only the class a stock, trump would withdraw his bid and recommend that shareholders accept griffin's
griffin on raised his cash bid for all of the company's stock to $45.73 per share, from his initial offer of $35 per share made last week
trump is offering $22 per share for the resorts stock he doesn't already own, principally its class a shares
resorts' class a stock price jumped $3.62{ to $32.25 on tuesday. that is up from $21.87{ before griffin began his overtures
the entertainer's privately-held investment concern, griffin co., said it decided to boost its offer after spending the weekend studying resorts appraisal documents released late friday by trump, a new york-based real estate developer
those documents show a $1.3 billion appraisal of resorts properties, including a when-completed value for its luxurious but troubled taj mahal hotel-casino in atlantic city, n.j
resorts, which is based on north miami, fla., has operations in new jersey and the bahamas
the documents also say the appraiser would be willing to support a $550 million bank mortgage loan secured by resorts. that is the amount trump has said will be needed to complete the taj mahal, whose estimated total price has ballooned to $938.5 million currently from $535 million four years ago
a $500 million suit griffin filed monday in new york federal court accused trump of failing to disclose ``material facts,'' including the $1.3 billion appraisal, to resorts shareholders in making his offer. it also accused trump and resorts directors of breaching fiduciary duty by refusing to consider the griffin offer
because griffin's offer is contingent on getting the backing of trump and trump has repeatedly said he won't agree to that condition, resorts' board has declined to pursue griffin's proposal, saying it is moot
griffin's offer also hinges on trump agreeing to terminate a five-year management contract worth an estimated $100 million to operate resorts' properties. trump also has spurned that condition
the justice department says it will sue real estate developer donald trump for allegedly violating federal notification provisions in his purchases of stock in holiday corp. and bally manufacturing corp
at the request of the federal trade commission, the department said it will file a lawsuit accusing trump of violating the hart-scott-rodino act fro aug. 22 through nov. 9, 1986 when he bought stock in memphis, tenn.-based holiday without complying with reporting and waiting-period requirements
the suit also will accuse trump, an operator of hotels and casinos, of violating the act from nov. 13, 1986 through jan. 22, 1987 when he bought stock in bally without complying with the law's requirements
discussions are under way to determine if a settlement can be reached, the department said in a statement issued tuesday
the act imposes notification and waiting requirements on companies and people over a certain size that are contemplating mergers or purchases of stocks or assets
the law is intended to improve antitrust enforcement by ensuring advance notice to the government of significant mergers and similar transactions
trump sought control of bally, a chicago-based hotel and amusements company, in 1987 but ended the attempt after bally agreed to buy 2.6 million shares back from him
holiday disclosed in september 1986, amid unconfirmed takeover rumors, that trump had purchased between 2 percent and 5 percent of its stock. holiday later underwent a recapitalization and adopted a ``poison pill'' takeover defense to thwart potential suitors
separately, the justice department said it will sue wickes companies inc. of santa monica, calif., accusing the company of violating the hart-scott-rodino act in its purchase of stock in the owens-corning fiberglass corp. of toledo, ohio in late 1986
but the department will file a proposed consent decree under which wickes, which sells lumber and other building materials, would pay $300,000 to settle the matter
sanford c. sigoloff, wickes chairman and chief executive officer, issued a statement saying his company did not believe it violated the disclosure requirements but settled the matter to avoid litigation costs
sigoloff also contended wickes had filed under the law in connection with the stock purchase and the ftc initially had cleared the filing
this settlement involves a long-standing technical dispute between the ftc and the investment community over the use of option agreements under the hart-scott-rodino rules,'' sigoloff stated
in a third case, the department said it will accuse roxboro investments ltd. and a subsidiary, first city financial corp. ltd., both of vancouver, british columbia, and three officers of the companies, with violating the hart-scott-rodino act. they will be accused based on their purchase in early 1986 of stock in ashland oil inc. of russell, ky
the three officers are samuel belzberg, president of roxboro and first city, and hyman belzberg and william belzberg, vice presidents of the two companies
the complaint will accuse the two companies and the three officers of violating the act from feb. 19 through april 2, 1986 when they bought ashland stock without complying with some of the law's requirements
first city attorneys issued a statement late tuesday saying they had been discussing a settlement with the department and believed a final agreement would be reached soon. trade</head>
japanese construction companies have proposed a meeting with their u.s. counterparts to help defuse tension over a construction trade issue causing serious friction between their respective governments, according to industry officials
officials of the japan federation of construction contractors said tuesday it sent a letter proposing the meeting in response to an unofficial approach recently made by the international engineering and construction industries council (iecic) in the united states
the japanese move came following last week's breakdown in negotiations over the u.s. demand that japan allow u.s. companies to participate in various construction projects in japan
the united states has given japan two weeks in which to come up with a satisfactory response, or face retaliation
last week, the japanese government advised u.s. commerce secretary william verity that it was ``working hard in order to present a further substantive offer'' and a fresh round of talks was expected to start in washington this week
according to officials of the construction federation, the letter noted the dispute has been escalating and the two nations' differing viewpoints may have arisen from a ``perception gap.'' the two trade rganizations should hold a private-sector meeting and find the ways of cooperating to defuse the tension, the letter stated
officials said construction companies in other countries had strong interest in gaining access to the japanese market, where projects worth more than 50 trillion yen _ about $393 billion at current exchange rates _ are undertaken annually
the federation last may established a special office to handle queries from other countries on legal and other procedures for taking part in construction projects in japan, and reportedly received more than 30 queries
hostile suitor black &amp; decker corp. has dropped its bid for american standard inc., allowing the target company's $2.45 billion leveraged buyout to go forward
black &amp; decker's announcement tuesday that it would drop its months-long pursuit of american standard followed a bizarre turn of events that halted trading in the company's stock for several hours for no apparent reason
american standard agreed last week to a $78 a share leveraged buyout led by the investment firm kelso &amp; co., thwarting the rival $77 a share, $2.4 billion bid from black &amp; decker
under the agreement reached tuesday with american standard, the towson-based tool and appliance manufacturer withdrew its hostile tender offer and agreed not to purchase american standard stock until kelso had an opportunity to pursue the leveragd buyout
kelso will pay black &amp; decker $25 million for withdrawing its bid, and black &amp; decker reserved the right to mount another takeover of american standard if kelso terminated its offer or failed to acquire shares by may 2
seventy-seven (dollars) was our top price,'' said barbara lucas, a black &amp; decker spokeswoman. ms. lucas also said black &amp; decker initially had thought kelso would be unable to finance its proposal, but tht apparently was not the case
an american standard spokeswoman said the company had no comment on the agreement
earlier tuesday, the new york stock exchange halted trading in black &amp; decker and american standard shares for three hours in anticipation of an announcement by black &amp; decker that never materialized
nyse vice president richard torrenzano said black &amp; decker ``initiated a call'' to the exchange and ``shared with us information concerning the american standard bid which materially could affect the price of their stock.''
but after trading was halted at 10:46 a.m. est, several conversations took place between black &amp; decker and exchange officials before it was determined that no announcement was forthcoming
the exchange also conferred with american standard, ``who advised us that it knows of no reason why trading in its stock should not resume,'' torrenzano said. the exchange resumed trading trading in both stocks at 1:43 p.m. est
the stock exchange most often halts trading when announcements that could affect a company's stock price are anticipated. typically, however, trading is only suspended for about 30 minutes while news is being disseminated, torrenzano said
it was unclear immediately whether the unusual turn of events would provoke an investigation by market regulators such as the securities and exchange commission
on the day, american standard shares dipped 12{ cents to $76.62{ per share on the nyse. black &amp; decker rose 37{ cents to $20 a share
black &amp; decker made its initial offer of $56 a share in late january, and sweetened it several times in response to rejections by american standard
american standard, a new york-based plumbing and air conditioning equipment maker, several weeks ago proposed a defensive recapitalization aimed at making the company a more expensive takeover target by loading it up with new debt
wall street analyst cornelius v. sewell said the buyout led by kelso would leave american standard with a ``some very heavy debt.''
they will presumably have a negative book value,'' said sewell, of argus research corp. in new york
sewell speculated that american standard was likely to sell its transportation products division, valued at about $600 million, to help pay off buyout costs
koppers co. has spurned a sweetened $1.6 billion cash buyout offer from british investor brian beazer and the investment firm shearson lehman hutton inc. and said it still was pursuing alternative plans to remain independent
the board continues to believe that the company remaining independent is a superior alternative to accepting your offer,'' chairman charles r. pullin told beazer in a letter released tuesday by koppers
the beazer-shearson group raised its offer on sunday to $56 per share from $45 per share for the pittsburgh construction materials, paving services and chemicals company
pullin also declined beazer's invitation to negotiate a friendly merger
koppers stock declined 50 cents to $57 a share tuesday on the new york stock exchange
koppers announced earlier it was considering a recapitalization plan that might include a special cash dividend to shareholders, along with equity interest in the recapitalized company. such a program would make koppers a more expensive takeover target because of the debt it would incur to make the cash payment to shareholders
koppers said two major banks, which it declined to identify, have offered to arrange $1.125 billion in credit to fund the recapitalization
koppers has also said it might sell all or part of the building materials and paving services businesses sought by beazer
the british investor has indicated he might settle for just those parts of koppers. previously, he said he would sell the chemicals operations if bns succeeded in the hostile tender offer it launched march 3
bns holds 1.6 million, or 7.3 percent, of koppers' outstanding common shares
ailing first republicbank corp. may have to divest itself of some of its banks to become more attractive to investors, experts say
first republicbank, weakened by a run on deposits and recent multimillion-dollar losses, received a $1 billion injection of capital last week from the federal deposit insurance corp
but because it could take as much as $5 billion to rescue the nation's 13th-largest bank holding company, banking regulators are considering selling first republicbank's individual operations as a marketing alternative
fdic chairman l. william seidman said such a move ``certainly is an option.''
no spokesman for firstrepublic bank was available tuesday to comment on the idea
the first thing you think of is splitting the company into bite-size morsels,'' said james sexton, a former fdic director of supervision who is a consultant at bracewell &amp; patterson, an austin, texas law firm
the holding company's banks in major markets could be packaged together or in regional or in statewide combinations, analysts said. the holding company has banks in dallas, austin, houston and san antonio
it's a very large bank for someone else to acquire,'' said tanya azarchs, a banking analyst with new york-based standard &amp; poor's corp. ``i don't see anyone on the scene that's willing to do that.''
although the breakup of the holding company could make it more accessible to investors, some argue it would be better if the company remained intact
these banks are intertwined, having common management, borrowers and computer systems,'' sexton said. ``breaking off chunks presents some tough administrative problems.''
the bank holding company already is consolidating some of its banks, which could make a breakup more difficult. first republicbank already has cut the number of banks from 103 to 73, and plans to consolidate until only 40 banks are left
first republicbank reported a 1987 loss of $656.8 million, $3.92 billion in problem assets and had deposit outflows of more than $2 billion this year. its assets total about $33.2 billion
the dollar fell against most major currencies in quiet early trading in europe today. gold prices rose
in tokyo, where the business day ends as europe's begins, the dollar closed at 127.15 yen, up 0.08 yen from tuesday's close. but later, in london, the dollar was quoted lower at 126.92 yen
the trading was quiet in the absence of market-affecting news and notable movements among participants,'' said ken iiya of the bank of tokyo in japan
other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late tuesday's rates, included: 1.6928 west german marks, down from 1.6935; 1.3940 swiss francs, down from 1.4015; 5.7540 french francs, unchanged; 1.9003 dutch guilders, down from 1.9015; 1,252.90 italian lire, down from 1,253.25; and 1.2455 canadian dollars, down from 1.2468
in london, the dollar also fell against the the british pound which was quoted at $1.8357, more expensive than $1.8300 late tuesday
gold opened in london at a bid price of $449.60 a troy ounce, compared with late tuesday's $448.75. at mid-morning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $450
in zurich, the bid price was $449.75 at noon, up from $448.50 late tuesday
earlier, in hong kong, gold rose 19 cents an ounce to close at $452.06 bid
silver was quoted in london today at a bid price of $6.48 a troy ounce, up from late tuesday's $6.46
the dollar, which fell sharply against the japanese yen tuesday, recovered slightly today, while stock prices also rebounded moderately in tokyo trading
after opening at 126.91 yen, the dollar edged up and closed at 127.15 yen, the day's high, up 0.08 yen from the close of 127.07 yen on tuesday, when the dollar fell 1.28 yen
the trading was quiet in the absence of market-affecting news and notable movements among participants,'' said ken iiya of the bank of tokyo
the market also was nervous about possible intervention by the bank of japan to support the dollar, he said
japan's central bank reportedly bought dollars to prop up the sagging u.s. currency when it fell to near 126.90 yen tuesday, traders said
the prevalent market view is that the dollar lacks strength, iiya said
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei average of 225 selected issues, a 123.51-point loser tuesday, gained 52.48 points, or 0.2 percent, closing at 25,895.23
the afternoon trading was not active as corporate investors took a cautious attitude, waiting for any market-affecting news, such as the u.s. consumer price index for february, which will be released later in the evening,'' said toshihisa haruumi of wako securities
most buy orders centered around large-capital issues, such as steels and heavy electricals, and they boosted the overall volume of trading, he said
the volume of first section trading today was a heavy 1.5 billion shares, up from 1.1 billion shares tuesday
besides major heavy industries, chemicals and papers were popular. shipbuilding issues, pulps and many issues of securities companies and banks also rose
here is a rundown of the historical cost of mailing a first-class letter in the united states
in the first half of the 19th century the cost of sending a single sheet of paper 40 miles or less was between 6 cents and 8 cents, with the cost rising by distance. letters going 400 miles and over cost 25 cents to send, per sheet of paper
by the middle of that century postage stamps were introduced, along with standard rates regardless of distance traveled. these started at 2 cents per half-ounce in 1863, rising to 3 cents in 1883
in 1885, the current first-class standard based on one-ounce was started. the one-ounce rates since then have been:
july 1, 1885: 2 cents
nov. 3, 1917: 3 cents
july 1, 1919: 2 cents
july 6, 1932: 3 cents
aug. 1, 1958: 4 cents
jan. 7, 1963: 5 cents
jan. 7, 1968: 6 cents
may 16, 1971: 8 cents
march 2, 1974: 10 cents
dec. 31, 1975: 13 cents
may 29, 1978: 15 cents
march 22, 1981: 18 cents
nov. 1, 1981: 20 cents
feb. 17, 1985: 22 cents
when the new postage rates take effect april 3, americans will be using special ``e'' stamps on an interim basis
the stamps were printed bearing the letter e, instead of the amount of postage, because the new first-class rate was not known in time for printing of the millions of stamps needed for a new rate to take effect
the e stamps will represent 25 cents postage
in addition some post offices should have supplies of the 25-cent stamp featuring the portrait of adventure writer jack london, which was introduced last year
and most offices have supplies of 1-cent, 2-cent and 3-cent stamps to combine with current 22-cent stamps to reach the new quarter rate
undenominated stamps have been used four times in the past, although the basic design of the stamp has changed
the a, b, c and d stamps all showed the head of an eagle, each in a different color
the e stamp carries a multi-colored space-based image of the planet with the word earth printed beneath
the stamp also carries the notation ``domestic'' since it can be used only for mail within the country. mail traveling to other nations requires stanps that show their denomination
here are some examples of the new postage rates, scheduled to take effect april 3
_letter or bill payment: 25 cents, up from 22 cents. (first class, one ounce)
_monthly bank statement: 65 cents, up from 56 cents. (first class, three ounces)
_bill from department store: 21 cents, up from 18 cents. (first class, presorted by 5-digit zip code)
_credit card bill: 20.5 cents, up from 17.5 cents. (first class, presorted by 9-digit zip code)
_high speed business mail, $8.75, down from $10.75. (express mail, 8 ounces)
_weekly news magazine, 14.2 cents, up from 12 cents. (second class, 7 ounces)
_selective advertising, 16.7 cents, up from 12.5 cents. (third class, presorted, two ounces)
_volume advertising, 10.1 cents, up from 8.3 cents. (third class, sorted by letter carrier route, two ounces)
_christmas gift: $5.92, up from $5.32. (parcel post, 7 pounds, distant zone)
_book club package: $1.95, up from $1.44. (book rate, four pounds)
_legal signature: $1.75, up from $1.45. (certified mail with return receipt)
_collect on delivery ($40 value item): $2.50, up from $1.80
despite the impending increase in u.s. postage rates, mailing a first-class letter in this country remains among the lowest in the industrialized world
here is a list of postage rates for foreign nations, supplied by the u.s. postal service, with the cost in u.s. funds
_ italy, 48.5 cents
_ west germany, 47.6 cents
_ japan, 46.9 cents
_ austria, 42.3 cents
_ norway, 42.2 cents
_ netherlands, 39.8 cents
_ france, 38.8 cents
_ belgium, 37.1 cents
_ switzerland, 36.8 cents
_ sweden, 36.5 cents
_ united kingdom, 31.8 cents
_ canada, 28.9 cents
_ australia, 26.4 cents
