stock prices were lower at midday wednesday, depressed by continued lack of trading volume and concern about a further rise in the value of the pound
the financial times-stock exchange 100-stock index was down 7.0 points, or 0.4 percent, at 1,828.4
volume was light at 221.2 million shares, compared with 211.7 million at the same time tuesday
the pound's rise was ``holding everything back,'' one dealer said, adding that many investors were waiting to see if the bank of england would take further steps to halt the currency's rise. the central bank cleared the way last week for a half-point cut in commercial banks' base lending rate to 8.5 percent. 3rd graf pvs, the new rates.</note>
the price of a stamp will rise to a quarter on april 3, the first hike in 38 months and one the postmaster general said today he hopes will hold for at least that long
we hope we will go that long or longer the next time'' postmaster general anthony frank said on cbs-tv's ``this morning'' show
frank said the biggest reaction to the higher rates has come from major business mailers who will face the largest increase, and this could affect the amount of so-called ``junk '' mail sent out
i think there could be a little more space in your mailbox over the next few months,'' frank said
most noticeable to the public, of course, is the new first-class quarter rate, but the overall hikes affect many other areas too including mailing bills, books and magazines and other items
the new rates, for example, would add about $1.15 to the annual cost of mailing a weekly newsmagazine to one home. utilities, credit card companies and department stores will have to spend about 36 cents more, annually, to bill one customer. the cost of an average book club mailing will rise by about 50 cents
the increases are needed to avoid deficits for the agency that could reach $5 billion in 1989, postal officials said tuesday in announcing the april 3 rate hike. the last rate increase was in february 1985, and the postal service lost more than $220 million last year
the new 25-cent letter rate is part of a broad series of rate changes affecting all types of mail
these are the first adjustments in general postage rates in more than three years. they reflect the higher costs the postal service is experiencing,'' said john n. griesemer, chairman of the agency's board of governors
the postal service is required to break even _ over time _ by the 1970 law that made it an independent federal agency and ended the taxpayer subsidy for the mail
frank said post offices across the country will expand window service during the next two weeks to help customers cope with the changes
but while service is being expanded temporarily to help during the changeover, recently imposed reductions in post office hours and services are not related to the rate increases and are likely to remain in effect. those cutbacks result from congressional action in december, while these rate hikes have been in the works for nearly a year
facing the biggest increase will be the so-called ``junk'' mail, third-class advertising material that the independent postal rate commission concluded wasn't paying its fair share
advertising mail prices will increase 24.9 percent, compared to hikes of 18.1 percent for newspapers and magazines and 14.7 percent for items sent by individuals
the new 25-cent first class price means that sending a one-ounce letter will take about the same bite from the average budget as in 1932. adjusted for inflation, the 3-cent postage rate introduced in 1932 would amount to 25.5 cents today
the price for each additional ounce of mail will rise from 17 cents to 20 cents. the cost to mail a post card will increase from 14 cents to 15 cents
for mail going outside the country the rate will be 45 cents per half-ounce to most areas. for mail to mexico the rate is the same as in the united states, while sending a letter to canada will cost 30 cents per ounce
the agency did cut, from 7 cents to 5 cents, the minimum charge for a business using pre-paid envelopes that allow consumers to reply without a stamp. that, officials said, may encourage more businesses to offer the service
the postal rate commission said it determined that third-class advertising mail was responsible for more postal service costs than it was paying, and thus should have a larger increase
the minimum rate for third class mail will jump from 12.5 cents to 16.7 cents and the per pound rate will rise from 38 cents to 48 cents
for non-profit advertising mail the minimum rate will increase from 8.5 cents to 8.7 cents
second class mail, newspapers and magazines for the most part, face overall increases of just over 18 percent
newspapers sent within the county will rise to 9.8 cents per pound and 3.4 to 5.9 cents per piece. the current rate is 9.1 cents per pound and 3.1 to 4.9 cents per item
a new $8.75 rate for the highly competitive express overnight mail was set for packages of 8 ounces or less
a special, nondenominated ``e'' stamp has been prepared for use when the new rates take effect
because the agency had no way of knowing what rate would be recommended, it had the e stamps printed for use at whatever the rate turned out to be. the same procedure was used the last four times rates were raised. report on corporate profits. picks up 5th graf pvs, in its ...</note>
the u.s. economy grew at a brisk 4.8 percent annual rate in the final three months of 1987 while february consumer prices were modestly higher, indicating that inflation was under control, the government reported today
the commerce department said the gross national product, the broadest measure of economic health, grew from october to december at the fastest clip in about two years
it was the second upward revision in gnp growth. a month ago the government put gnp growth at 4.5 percent, up from a 4.2 percent original estimate made in january immediately after the quarter ended
today's revisions showed more strength than previously believed in such key sectors as consumer spending, business investment and u.s. exports
in a second report, the department said u.s. corporations' after-tax profits rose 1.6 percent in the fourth quarter, the poorest showing since profits fell 3.7 percent in the first quarter of 1987. profits were up 5.5 percent in the third quarter
in its report on inflation, the labor department said that last month's consumer prices rose a modest 0.2 percent due to lower food and energy costs
food prices fell 0.3 percent after rising 0.3 percent in january. energy costs, which had fallen 0.7 percent in the preceding month, fell 0.6 percent last month
so far this year, consumer prices have been increasing at a rate of 3.2 percent. that compares to the moderate 4.4 percent rate for all of 1987 and the scant 1.1 percent 1986 increase
on tuesday, the commerce department said that orders to u.s. factories for durable goods _ items expected to last at least three years _ fell 1.8 percent in february to a seasonally adjusted $111.4 billion, following an identical decline in january
in other economic news on tuesday, the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 0.99 point to 2,066.15; the dollar was mixed against other major currencies; and bond prices were little changed in light trading
february marked the first time since the spring of 1986 that durable goods orders declined for two consecutive months
but some economists maintained that manufacturing companies still were enjoying good business because the weaker dollar has boosted export demand
cynthia latta, an economist with data resources inc., said that while new orders fell in february the total backlog of unfilled orders rose 0.7 percent, the 12th consecutive monthly increase
this backlog suggests that factories can keep humming along for a while even though new orders dropped,'' she said
still, analysts said, the back-to-back declines showed businesses were cutting back on orders in the early part of 1988 in an effort to get control of bulging inventories. inventories swelled at the end of 1987 while consumer demand fell
lucky stores inc.'s stock soared $14.50 a share tuesday after the major california supermarket chain received a $1.74 billion tender offer from american stores co
if american stores' $45-a-share bid is successful, it would create the nation's largest grocery store chain. in heavy trading on the new york stock exchange, lucky's stock surged to close at $46.375 a share. american stores stock fell $2.62{ a share to $57.87{
officials at lucky's headquarters in dublin, calif., would not discuss the offer except to say company bylaws contain a ``poison pill'' anti-takeover provision, which limits the voting power of any shareholder who acquires more than 10 percent of lucky's stock
company officials noted in a statement that the limited voting rights provision, which expires dec. 22, may not be waived by the company's board
lucky, the nation's sixth largest grocery retailer, has 480 stores while american stores, the third biggest, has 1,600 stores
in a letter to lucky stores chairman john m. lillie, american stores chairman l.s. skaggs said he would combine american's alpha beta stores with lucky's operation under the lucky name
the letter, released tuesday, praised lucky's management and marketing strategies and invited lucky executives to stay on if the deal is completed. lucky's headquarters also would remain at dublin, skaggs said
officials at salt lake city-based american stores would not provide further details of their unsolicited offer and had no comment beyond a brief press release, said senior vice president michael miller
recent rumors have suggested that american stores itself may be a takeover target, according to an analyst here who said his company has extensive dealings with the company
under that scenario, the bid for lucky could be a defensive move to make an acquisition of american stores prohibitively expensive, said the analyst, who spoke on condition of anonymity
if american stores doesn't get this acquisition, it puts the spotlight on them. they may be more open to takeover than before,'' he said
analysts agreed the lucky-american stores combination makes sense
susan c. schmierer, a retail analyst with prudential-bache securities inc., noted that the two companies operate in the same general geographic areas and that both want to increase their presence in california
i don't see any reason why it couldn't go through, given the right kind of management finesse by american,'' she said
the bid for lucky comes 16 months after takeover strategist asher edelman formally dropped his hostile bid for the company in return for lucky's agreement to pay $2.8 million of his legal costs
lucky thwarted edelman partly by selling off non-grocery divisions and adopting anti-takeover measures that make it more difficult for an unwanted suitor to acquire the company
american stores' most recent acquisition occurred in 1984 when it took over jewel companies inc., a chicago-based grocery, drug and convenience store chain, for $1.1 billion
the acquisition expanded american stores' operations from just over 1,000 retail outlets to 1,700 stores in 40 states and boosted sales to about $15 billion a year
the company is organized into three divisions. the skaggs division operates supermarkets in the western united states; american superstores runs stores in the midwest and the east; and osco drug stores operates stores nationwide, according to value line investment survey
store names include acme, jewel, star, buttrey, skaggs, skaggs alpha beta and osco drug stores
lucky, with annual sales of about $7 billion, operates about 480 supermarkets and food centers in the west, midwest and southwest, principally in california and arizona
stocks opened mixed this morning in light trading, which brokers called a reflection of the uncertainty that has pervaded the market following the post-crash highs reached last week
the dow jones averge of 30 industrials, which barely budged in slack trading tuesday, rose 0.33 point to 2,066.48 by 10 a.m. on wall street
among broader market indicators, the new york stock exchange composite index of all listed issues rose 0.13 to 151.65. the american stock exchange's market value index rose 0.56 to 299.36
gaining stocks outnumbered losers by a 5-to-4 margin on the nyse, with 548 up, 422 down and 480 unchanged. volume totaled 23.65 million shares after the first half hour
on tuesday, the dow jones industrial average fell 0.99 point to 2,066.15
gaining issues narrowly outnumbered declines in composite nyse trading, with 765 up, 736 down and 481 unchanged. volume on the big board totaled 142.0 million shares, vs. the 1987 low of 128.83 million shares traded monday. title.</note>
many banks seem more willing to lend money to poor countries abroad than to take a chance on redeveloping poor neighborhoods in their own area, community representatives are telling congress
we're saying, `look ... you lend billions of dollars across the border and you can't lend to our community that is on this side of the border,''' said tony reyes, mayor of san luis, ariz., a town of 2,000 near mexico
i don't think that is fair,'' he told the senate banking committee, which is reviewing compliance with the community reinvestment act of 1977
the law requires banks to lend in their depositors' neighborhoods and prohibits ``redlining,'' the practice of denying loans to an entire neighborhood based on the race or economic class of its residents
it gives regulators the authority to block banks with poor records from opening new branches or merging with other institutions
redlining hasn't disappeared,'' sen. william proxmire, the committee chairman, said tuesday. ``neighborhoods are still starving for credit. too many bankers still think the grass is greener elsewhere.''
he noted that an estimated $5 billion in loans have been made in poor neighborhoods as a result of the act, but said, ``that $5 billion pledged to developing neighborhoods is peanuts compared to the $100 billion loaned to developing countries.''
despite a rating system by regulators that gives the vast majority of banks high marks for their anti-redlining efforts, the actual performance of most is poor, said gale cincotta, executive director of the national training and information center, a chicago community group
hundreds of census tracts in low-income america did not receive a penny in mortgage loans,'' she said
proxmire, d-wis., said that 97 percent of all lenders pass community reinvestment act reviews with flying colors and only eight of 40,000 applications from banks seeking to merge or expand have been denied in the past 10 years
how is it that so many neighborhoods are continuing to fail, while so many lending institutions are continuing to pass?'' he asked. ``this record ... raises questions about whether the examination process has succeeded.''
allen j. fishbein, general counsel of the center for community change, a washington organization that provides training for neighborhood groups, said progress in enforcing the law during the late 70s has ``been virtually undone as a result of agency indifference over the past five or six years.''
ms. cincotta complained that bank examiners, in effect, rely on community groups to enforce the law for them by filing complaints
she said that although examiners are well trained at judging the financial soundness of a bank, many are poorly schooled in judging a bank's fair housing or equal opportunity record
jane uebelhoer, legislative representative of acorn (association of community organizations for reform now), said congress should revamp the regulators' rating system so that banks with poor records get poor marks
the committee, which is reviewing enforcement of the act with an eye toward possibly toughening it, planned a second session today to hear from federal bank regulators
the house banking committee has discussed attaching provisions strengthening the community revinvestment act to legislation primarily aimed at granting banks new investment powers
the senate committee has already passed its version of that bill but could go along with the house provisions if senators are convinced by testimony this week that changes are needed. housing notes</head>
the supreme court ruled today that short-term notes used to finance public housing projects are not exempt from federal estate taxes
the 8-0 ruling was a victory for the reagan administration, which said more than $260 million in federal tax revenue was at stake
the dispute stems in part from a 1937 law congress enacted to stimulate local financing of housing projects. the act allowed public housing agencies to issue tax-free obligations called ``project notes.''
for some 47 years, it was assumed the law exempted the notes from federal income tax but not from federal estate tax
but a federal judge in illinois ruled in 1984 that the notes were exempt from estate taxes as well. the decision touched off widepsread efforts to market project notes and prompted those who had paid estate taxes on the notes to seek refunds from the government
within months of the illinois ruling, congress enacted the deficit reduction act of 1984 that included a provision making the project notes subject to estate, gift and inheritance taxes
the law took effect on june 19, 1984
heirs to people who died before that date said the law cannot be applied retroactively and they sought refunds from the government for estate taxes they paid on project notes
but today the supreme court said the project notes have been subject to the estate tax all along, even if the 1937 law did not make that explicitly clear
justice william j. brennan, in his opinion for the court, said the 1937 act was designed to exempt the project notes ``only from the normal tax'' _ that is federal income tax and surtaxes that were in effect at the time
exemptions from taxation are not to be implied. they must be unambiguously proved,'' brennan said. ``on the rare occasions when congress exempted property from estate taxation it has generally adverted explicitly to that tax rather than generically to `all taxation.'''
he said it would not make sense for congress to grant special exemptions to the project notes without stating it explicitly since the purpose of such an exemption would be to attract investors
if congress really wanted to create an especially broad tax exemption for project notes ... one would expect it to do so notoriously enough to attract investors, not surreptitiously enough to evade detection for half a century,'' brennan said
he added that today's ruling made it unnecessary for the justices to decide whether the 1984 budget reduction law chould be applied retroactively
the ruling reverses lower court decisions granting estate exemptions to project notes
justice anthony m. kennedy did not take part in the ruling
the case is u.s. vs. crocker national bank, 86-1521
after-tax corporate profits shot up 8.4 percent in 1987, a sharp rebound from the previous year when profits declined, the government said today
the commerce department said that after-tax profits rose to $137.4 billion last year, an increase of $10.6 billion from 1986, when profits had actually fallen by 1 percent
analysts credited the turnaround in profits in part to the weaker dollar, which has boosted sales of american products on overseas markets. in addition, they said that labor wage demands remained subdued during the year
the increase in profits for 1987 was outstanding, especially when you consider that corporate taxes were substantially hiked during the year because of the tax reform act,'' said allen sinai, chief economist of the boston co
particularly, for u.s. manufacturing, 1987 was a turnaround year,'' sinai said. ``exports rose and american companies benefited tremendously from previous cost-cutting measures.''
sinai predicted further gains in corporate profits in 1988 but he said the rate of increase would slow somewhat
some of that slowdown was evident in the fourth quarter with after-tax profits rising 1.6 percent following a 5.5 percent gain in the third quarter
