northwest airlines said today it will ban smoking on all of its domestic flights except to and from hawaii, making it the first major u.s. airline to mandate a smoke-free travel environment in the air
the restrictions will begin on april 23, the same day a federal law is to go into effect banning smoking on all domestic flights of two hours or less
northwest noted in a statement that its program goes ``significantly beyond'' the requirements of the new law
in addition to flights within the contiguous 48 states, the program, dubbed ``northwest clears the air,'' will apply to flights to and from alaska, mexico, canada, jamaica and the cayman islands
flights to hawaii and ovrseas will continue to offer smoking sections because those flights ``carry a greater proportion of foreign passengers who feel differently about the issue,'' the airline said in a statement
a.b. magary, the airline's executive vice president for marketing, said a majority of passengers on international flights are foreign and are ``not yet culturally ready to move in this direction.''
he said the ban ``is a response to our customers' and employees' requests.'' a northwest study showed that nine out of 10 passengers prefer to sit in the no-smoking section of a plane
magary said, however, that the airline is not going ``macrobiotic.'' the ban ``does not imply some broader-scale effort to rid the united states of cigarettes,'' he said
northwest said it will offer refunds to passengers who purchased tickets before today and who have been assigned seats in the smoking section if they decline to fly because of the new policy
travel agents on tuesday complimented northwest on its plans
we're hearing from our customers that it's time to go more toward banning,'' said jay harrington, regional president of uniglobe, a national chain of travel agency franchises. ``we think it's inevitable it will be banned on all aircraft.''
in the short run, he said, northwest might lose some customers who smoke heavily, but generally, passengers choose flights on the basis of convenience and price
air canada, which banned smoking on some flights between canada and the united states, said it gained customers as a result of its no-smoking policy
northwest would have had to eliminate smoking on many of its flights anyway because about 80 percent of all u.s. flights last two hours or less
by extending the ban to all flights, northwest could be avoiding confusion expected to result from the new law. for example, it was not clear how the law would apply to flights that are scheduled to take under two hours but are delayed
more important, northwest could be saving itself some costs. airlines must install and maintain filters that are difficult and costly to clean, and they spend additional money on air conditioning to recirculate fresh air
the new law, part of a spending bill signed by president reagan in december, is a compromise version of no-smoking bills that the house and senate passed earlier. the federal ban will last for two years. smoking cigars and pipes already is prohibited on airlines
under the new law, passengers who insist on lighting up will face civil fines of as much as $1,000, and passengers who tamper with smoke alarms in airplane lavatories will be liable for as much as $2,000 in penalties
northwest airlines said it would launch an advertising campaign to promote the program on saturday
attending northwest's press conference were representatives of the u.s. surgeon general's office, the american cancer society, the american heart association and the american lung association
james swamley, managing director of the american lung association, credited northwest with ``jetting ahead of the industry.''
separately, singapore airlines unveiled plans to introduce the first no-smoking commercial flights in southeast asia next month
four of the 14 daily shuttle flights between singapore and kuala lumpur, the capital of neighboring malaysia, will bar smoking starting april 4, said a news release from the government-controlled carrier. the trip takes about 45 minutes
grain and soybean futures prices opened mixed to slightly higher today on the chicago board of trade
one analyst called traders ``gun-shy.'' that proved an accurate description as soybeans opened strongly, but then turned surprisingly calm
traders said there was a lack of follow-through buying after contract highs were set tuesday for new-crop months in soybeans
wheat, meanwhile, was firm on talk of export business with india and the soviet union
on the open, wheat was 1{ cents to 2\ cents higher, with the contract for may delivery at $3.09 a bushel; corn was unchanged to { cent higher, with may at $2.07 a bushel; oats were \ cent lower, with may at $1.69} a bushel; and soybeans were } cent lower to 1 cent higher, with may at $6.44 a bushel
livestock and meat futures prices were mostly lower at the chicago mercantile exchange
live cattle opened .40 cent lower to .02 cent higher, with april at 74.05 cents a pound; feeder cattle .05 cent to .25 cent lower, with march at 82.30 cents a pound; live hogs were .55 cent lower to .25 cent higher, with april at 46.02 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .38 cent lower to .50 cent higher, with march at 55.45 cents a pound. plan. subs 13th graf pvs, despite the, with omb letter sent. house vote not expected until early evening; top prospects uncertain.</note>
the house showed bipartisan support today for a $1.1 trillion fiscal 1989 budget that averts deep cuts in domestic programs and glosses over a failure to comply fully with congress' deficit-reduction agreement with president reagan
debate began on the plan approved last week by the house budget committee with a procedural vote that was adopted without a roll call _ unheard-of during the recent years of pitched budget battles
we've got a miracle,'' said house speaker jim wright, d-texas, expecting easy passage later in the day
this degree of bipartisanship in developing a budget resolution is truly unprecedented,'' said rep. delbert l. latta of ohio, senior republican on the budget committee
the plan would leave a deficit of about $134 billion in the spending year beginning oct. 1 and would stay within the limits of the gramm-rudman budget-balancing law. the deficit would be about $5 billion higher than with reagan's budget, mostly because the president proposed to sell off more government assets
the lawmakers' election-year plan would freeze or slightly trim most domestic agencies. it would spend $1.5 billion on aids research _ a little more than reagan proposed _ but not boost the space program as much as the president asked. it rejects his plans to cancel aid to mass transit and other popular domestic subsidies
as in the president's plan, the government's total cash outlays on the military, foreign aid and certain domestic programs would be held to levels set last fall when the president and congressional leaders held a budget ``summit.''
however, that agreement also contained limits for budget authority _ the legal obligations by agencies for spending that could stretch over more than one fiscal year. the house plan would violate the agreement if it weren't for some accounting wizardry
to avoid breaking the limit on budget authority, the house budget committee shifted about $4 billion in the domestic budget, mostly ongoing agriculture credit expenses, outside of the categories controlled by the summit pact
the accounting change made room for the kind of budget lawmakers support _ one that would not terminate urban and rural development programs and other items the president sought to end
in its report to the house, the budget committee said the technical changes were the only way it could find to hit the budget marks for both outlays and budget authority
it is not our intention that this (budget authority) adjustment not result in higher outlays in fy 1989 than the $169.2 billion (domestic) ... allowed under the summit cap,'' the committee said
rep. william h. gray iii, d-pa., chairman of the committee, said he believed it stayed within the budget pact. ``the outlay is what you're really going to be judged by,'' he said
despite the committee language, the budget technique could lead to higher spending allowances when the fiscal blueprint is translated later into actual spending bills. the president's office of management and budget send a letter to congress critical of the approach and promising to monitor spending closely as the budget is implemented
house action on the budget today was the earliest in years, as democratic leaders were keeping to their vow to put fiscal affairs on schedule this year
members of the senate budget committee have begun private meetings on their version. the two chambers must agree on identical budgets by april 15 to meet their deadline
the budget resolution is a guideline for congress' fiscal legislation, and it does not require the president's signature
with the accounting changes, the house budget would hit exactly the limits in the budget summit pact. those are $299.5 billion in budget authority and $294.0 billion in outlays for the military; $148.1 billion in budget authority and $169.2 billion in outlays for annually-appropriated domestic programs; and $18.1 billion in budget authority and $16.1 billion in outlays on foreign aid
the summit agreement also included $14 billion in new taxes for fiscal 1989. those levies were enacted last december, and congress plans no further increases this year
the gramm-rudman law mandates a deficit of $136 billion in fiscal 1989 as an interim step toward a balanced budget by fiscal 1993. neither the house plan nor reagan's met that mark without relying on selling government assets _ which aren't counted under gramm-rudman
however, both plans would be within $10 billion of the goal, keeping below the threshold at which the law would mandate automatic, across-the-board spending cuts
those estimates are based on the white house assumptions for economic growth and government performance next year. estimates by the non-partisan congressional budget office, which are less optimistic, show the deficit some $35 billion higher. ^by vivian marino</byline>
richard and stephanie hack have not only picked out where their two small children will be attending college after the turn of the century _ they've already paid their tuition in full
the bethel park, pa., couple bought that peace of mind for about $10,000 through a ``tuition-futures'' program that had been offered for about three years at duquesne university, their alma mater
other young families may wish they had it so easy as they watch tuition increases outpace inflation. the cost of some private colleges, for instance, now comes close to the median price of a single-family home _ around $80,000
financial advisers and educators agree the only way to stay out of the poor house, yet provide a college-bound child with a good education, is to develop a strategic plan as early as possible
people need to save for a university just as they buy a house,'' said richard f. rosser, president of the national association of independent colleges and universities
it was for that reason that duquesne, a small roman catholic univeristy near pittsburgh, developed its tuition-futures plan in 1985, a program mrs hack believes will benefit her children, melissa, 5, and brian, 4. about a half-dozen other schools established similar programs, but some of them, as duquesne did last week, have stopped taking new applicants due to unexpectedly high tuition increases and falling interest rates on bonds, the schools' main investment vehicle
aside from the obvious drawbacks _ what if a grown child doesn't want to go to college or to the one already paid for _ the program seemed like a good deal. at duquesne, for instance, the family of a 1-year-old eligible to go to college in 2005 would have paid a lump sum of around $8,600 last fall to cover projected four-year tuition of $102,600. the older the child, though, the higher the cost
most investment advisers say a family could almost do the same on their own by investing bit by bit in savings bonds or certificates of deposits, although they wouldn't have the same tax benefits enjoyed by the schools
since duquesne's trendsetting program, numerous programs and proposals have emerged
in washington, several bills are pending to set up tax-free savings accounts resembling individual retirement accounts to finance education. president reagan supports a tax-exempt savings bond program
six states _ michigan, indiana, florida, maine, tennessee and wyoming _ have passed laws establishing prepayment tuitition plans, according to the education commission of the states. (the internal revenue service just ruled the michigan education trust had to pay federal taxes on earnings, but individual investors wouldn't have additional tax liabilities
california, illinois, missouri, new jersey, new york, ohio, oregon, pennsylvania, south carolina, texas and west virgina have similar legislation pending, it said. and illinois and north carolina have passed special savings bond plans, it said
on the commercial side of things, there's the college savings bank. the princeton, n.j., institution's main line of business is to sell certificates of deposit with interest rates changing annually to keep pace with rising college costs
keeping track of what's available to students and families in the way of investment plans, financial aid or scholarships is often half the battle as college-sponsored programs come and go, new laws evolve from state to state, or congress and the internal revenue service get involved
there's just so much change going on,'' said john b. cox, a spokesman for the national association of college and university business officers. the non-profit group, based in washington, d.c., publishes ``alternative approaches to tuition financing,'' available to the general public for $15. many other guidebooks also are available in book stores and colleges
cox suggests that parents start out by selecting a few prospective colleges, then contacting the financial aid departments of each to see what programs the schools have or might be considering
here's a thumbnail look at some of the many programs being offered, according to nacubo and other sources:
_prepayment plans. students have the option at some colleges and universities of paying for all four years up front, thus avoiding future tuition increases. about 50 institutions offer this program, including a number of ivy league schools like brown university, cornell university, and yale university
_delayed prepayment or installation plans. a number of colleges and universities allow tuition payments to be made in equal amounts or installments during a semester or year. some institutions require a down payment of as much as 50 percent
_tuition gift certificates. sold by a handful of colleges, including two-year schools, these certificates may be bought for a designated number of credit hours or other tuition unit. some are transferable but most cannot be cashed in
_interstate tuition plans. at least two regional consortiums _ on the west coast and in new england _ offer some students a chance to go to college out of state for slightly higher than the residential rate. the program is only limited to participating states and institutions. one of the groups, western interstate commission for higher education, also arranges for state-subsidized tuition across state borders
_loan programs. besides commercial banks and thrifts, a number of colleges and universities loan money directly to families or students, although most are intended to pick up where federally guaranteed student loans leave off. several states, such as massachusetts, connecticut, maryland and new york, also provide student loans
_others. work study programs and scholarships are available to a broad range of students. several research services will even help track down obscure scholarships for a fee
