the government delivered two welcome pieces of economic news on wednesday: consumer prices rose just 0.2 percent in february and the economy in late 1987 expanded at the liveliest pace in nearly two years
falling energy and food prices in february helped restrain the rise in the labor department's consumer price index after a 0.3 percent increase in january
for the first two months of the year, prices increased at an annual rate of 3.2 percent _ much better than last year's moderate 4.4 percent inflation
in a separate report, the commerce department said the u.s. economy grew at a brisk 4.8 percent annual pace in the final three months of last year. it was the second upward revision in the fourth-quarter gnp, estimated a month ago at 4.5 percent and in january at 4.2 percent
the department said better-than-expected performance in exports, consumer spending and business investment led to the latest revision, which pushed growth for the year to a rate of 4 percent, compared with 2.2 percent growth in 1986. it was the biggest annual increase since a 5.1 percent rise in 1984
the 4.8 percent fourth-quarter growth followed a 4.3 percent growth in the july-september quarter and was the fastest quarterly growth rate since an increase of 5.4 percent in the first three months of 1986
recent economic reports have shown an economy that rebounded quickly from last october's stock market collapse. analysts see little likelihood of an election-year recession
one of the best kept secrets in economic circles these days is that the reagan administration is going to end with a bang, not a whimper, as the economy makes a successful transition to an export-led economy,'' president reagan said in a speech to the american business conference
meanwhile, his spokesman, marlin fitzwater, hailed wednesday's reports: ``inflation remains under control, the economy is doing well, the reagan miracle holds.''
food prices fell 0.3 percent in february, erasing a 0.3 percent gain in january. fruits and vegetables led the way with a 4 percent tumble. lettuce prices, which more than doubled at the end of 1987, dropped 25.1 percent in february
energy prices fell 0.6 percent, with falling gasoline prices more than offsetting increases in household fuels
at-the-pump gasoline prices fell 1.7 percent in february, the third consecutive decline. gasoline prices have fallen 5.9 percent in six months
heating oil and other household fuels were up 0.6 percent; natural gas and electricity prices rose 0.5 percent
there is at this point no indication of any major widespread acceleration of inflation,'' said lawrence chimerine, chairman of the wefa group, a philadelphia-area economic forecasting service
competition in retailing contributed to the favorable inflation performance, chimerine said. ``stores have been holding down price increases.''
items other than food and energy were up a modest 0.2 percent in february
still, there remained pockets of inflation, particularly in service industries. medical care services were up 0.7 percent in february, while ``other services'' rose 0.6 percent
there are some chronic price problems in the economy,'' said sandra shaber, senior economist for the futures group, a washington management consultanting firm. ``these increases in health care are not going to go away.''
but if we continue to get a break on food and energy prices, that certainly is good news,'' she added
however, allen sinai, chief economist for the boston co., said the ``big issue is whether these good results we are getting so far this year are transitory or permanent. food and energy price declines are reversible almost any time.''
in other february price movements:
_new automobile prices rose 0.3 percent
_clothing prices fell 0.3 percent
_alcoholic beverage prices rose 0.9 percent
last month's seasonally adjusted 0.2 percent gain in the cpi was equivalent to a compounded annual inflation rate of 2.1 percent, labor department analysts said
the february increase left the overall index at 116.0, meaning that a hypothetical selection of goods costing $100 during a 1982-84 base period would have cost $116.00 last month
unlike other figures in the report, the overall index is not adjusted for seasonal fluctuations
the labor department recently changed its base period. had the former computation been used, the february consumer price index would have been 347.4 compared with a 1967 base of 100
that means the same selection of goods would have cost $13.00 more last month than in february 1987, when the cpi was 334.4
in two other economic reports:
_the commerce department said after-tax corporate profits shot up 8.4 percent in 1987 to $137.4 billion after declining the year before. analysts credited the turnaround in profits to the weaker dollar, which has boosted u.s. sales overseas, and to subdued labor wage demands
_the labor department said americans' average weekly earnings, after discounting for inflation, edged up 0.2 percent in february. it was the second monthly advance, matching an identical 0.2 percent january increase, but it still left americans' inflation-adjusted earnings 0.7 percent below where they were a year ago
stocks muddled through a third straight day of sluggish trading wednesday with no clear direction, and most of the action was confined to another surge of takeover speculation
some traders said the market's confusion reflected conflicting signals about the economy. others attributed the market's malaise to resilient investor reluctance to aggressively buy stocks in the aftermath of the october crash
it's really not a newsworthy day,'' said william king, head trader at nikko securities international inc. in new york
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, which fell 0.99 point tuesday, moved within a narrow range and closed 1.49 higher at 2,067.64
gainers outnumbered losers by about 3-to-2 on the new york stock exchange, with 925 up, 593 down and 448 unchanged
big board volume totaled 167.37 million shares, against 142 million in the previous session
the nyse's composite index rose 0.30 to 151.82
at the american stock exchange, the market value index rose 1.61 to 300.41
bankamerica corp., whose stock jumped 6 percent in active trading wednesday, denied rumors that it may be the target of a takeover by a japanese bank
bankamerica stock closed up 62.5 cents at $11.125 a share in heavy new york stock exchange trading
dan dorfman, appearing on cnn's ``moneyline'' program tuesday night, said he had heard a rumor that a japanese bank may be interested in acquiring part of all of bankamerica
bankamerica said in a statement from its headquarters in san francisco that there was ``no basis for the rumors.''
dorfman said wednesday from his office at usa today, where he works as a columnist, that he ``emphasized the word rumor'' and mentioned the rumor to explain the heavy dealing in bankamerica stock on tuesday
analysts quickly disputed the claim
it's unlikely,'' said mark alpert, an analyst with bear, stearns &amp; co. ``there have been plenty of opportunities in the past for japanese banks to take a position in bankamerica, and nothing has occurred
it doesn't mean it can't happen, but it's unlikely,'' he said
likewise, rodrigo quintanilla of argus research corp. said that while only west german and japanese institutions are in a financial position to take on the huge banking company, ``i still don't consider it to be a takeover target.'' ^by john c. given</byline>
texaco inc. on wednesday won final bankruptcy court approval for a plan that would settle its multibillion-dollar dispute with pennzoil co. and bring it out of chapter 11 protection early next month
after a day and a half of closing arguments, u.s. bankruptcy court judge howard schwartzberg confirmed the reorganization plan, which features an agreement by texaco to pay pennzoil co. $3 billion to drop a $10.3 billion judgement held by pennzoil against the nation's third-largest oil company
when the plan goes into effect, on april 7, texaco will deliver the money to pennzoil and will be officially free from the legal constraints that have limited its operations since the company filed for protection from its creditors last april 12
it was the largest corporate bankruptcy in u.s. history
texaco said it was driven to take that action to avoid having to pay a potentially ruinous $11 billion security bond while appealing the judgment held by pennzoil
a houston jury awarded the judgment to houston-based pennzoil in november 1985, after finding that texaco had improperly interfered with a pennzoil acquisition of part of getty oil company so texaco could buy getty itself
schwartzberg's approval marked the last step required for texaco to emerge from bankruptcy protection under federal law
texaco officials and pennzoil chairman j. hugh liedtke expressed profound relief that the four-year ordeal of litigation that had paralyzed both companies was finally over
i must say it has not been a particularly pleasant experience ... but it had to be done,'' said j. hugh liedtke, pennzoil's chairman
liedtke said he never doubted that the jury's verdict would be vindicated, despite lingering criticism from some quarters
quite frankly, all the smoke aside, people don't pay $3 billion for something who don't have some liability, '' he said
told of that remark, texaco chairman alfred c. decrane _ who at tuesday's hearing had stoutly defended texaco's view that it had done nothing wrong _ said: ``what we did here today is to settle this matter.''
noting that texaco's only other choice was a highly risky all-or-nothing attempt to win a u.s. supreme court reversal, he said the company settled ``to end that litigation.''
in announcing his decision to confirm the plan, schwartzberg noted that 96 percent of texaco's shares were voted in favor of the package, which was laboriously worked out among pennzoil, texaco, and committees representing texaco's creditors and shareholders
he also noted that the plan provides for full payment to texaco's creditors, with interest, and had been supported by representatives of all the principal parties during the final confirmation hearings
the only lingering bone of contention was the presence of provisions in the plan granting immunity to all parties involved in the original texaco-getty-pennzoil matter
on tuesday, dissident shareholders reluctantly dropped 16 suits against texaco, saying they would support the plan, knowing that the company would be in far worse condition if it were not approved
the dissidents contended _ along with texaco's largest shareholder, takeover artist carl c. icahn _ that the releases gave away a chance for texaco to recoup some of its losses by suing the parties responsible for texaco's ultimate defeat in houston
icahn, who owns 14.8 percent of texaco's stock, also protested that the measures served to entrench management and diminish its accountability to shareholders
while he voted in favor of the plan, he urged the court to strike the releases from the plan
schwartzberg refused to do so, agreeing with arguments by both pennzoil and texaco that the releases were, on balance ``in the best interest of texaco.''
noting that pennzoil, not texaco, had inserted the provisions, schwartzberg said it appeared inevitable that endless litigation would continue without the releases, which all parties wanted to avoid
he also suggested it was questionable that texaco officials could be found guilty of fiduciary irresponsibility for their roles in the getty affair
liedtke said the judge's action would trigger plans, already set up, to borrow a very substantial part of the $3 billion from a consortium of banks, which it will begin investing in short-term notes
when it receives the payment from texaco, it will then repay the banks, liedtke said
asked if pennzoil would be interested in buying any texaco assets, liedtke said it could not be done ``without their permission,'' because of a mutual agreement forestalling such action for five years
he said the company would be studying longer-range plans for the money, adding that decisions could not be expected for at least several weeks
with the case virtually closed, liedtke said he planned to ``sit and think a little bit,'' and that he hoped to retire from his chief executive post when the company holds its annual meeting next month
the european economic community threatened trade retaliation against the united states on tuesday unless it brings a tax on petroleum imports into line with an international agreement
christophe bail, an eec delegate, told a council meeting of the general agreement on tariffs and trade that the 12-nation economic bloc may seek trade restrictions that would offset the u.s. tax. he did not identify which u.s. products might be targeted
u.s. delegate michael samuels dismissed the threat as premature, said one source, who added that the eec has provided no evidence the current tax has harmed its trade
the reagan administration, in its 1989 budget proposal to congress, has sought a remedy with a uniform crude oil tax of 9.65 cents per barrel, samuels told delegates
the 96-nation gatt told the united states to change the tax last june on grounds that it violated international trade rules by discriminating against imports. the ruling followed complaints by mexico, canada and the eec
under the 1986 levy, u.s. domestic crude oil is taxed at 8.2 cents a barrel while imports are taxed at 11.7 cents. the proceeds finance the superfund hazardous waste cleanup program
gatt rules provide for retaliation if a member fails to act on a ruling
the dollar finished lower wednesday in dull domestic dealings, failing to react to the government's latest economic data
gold prices rose. republic national bank of new york quoted a bid price for gold of $451.15 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. est, up from tuesday's late bid of $448.65
traders said there was little activity throughout the session, and the dollar moved in a very narrow range
