in a case with implications for all north american automakers, a canadian trade panel wednesday ruled that low-price imports from hyundai motor co. of south korea had not injured domestic manufacturers
the tribunal found no evidence of material injury to the canadian subsidiaries of ford motor co. and and general motors corp., which had accused hyundai of dumping its hatchbacks and small sedans at below-cost prices to gain a foothold in the north american market
revenue canada, a department of the federal government, initially agreed with ford and gm and imposed preliminary duties of 26 percent on hyundai imports
but the key to the case was not whether hyundai was selling cars in canada at prices below those on the south korean domestic market. ford and gm also had to prove they suffered ``material injury'' and failed to do so, according to the three-member canadian import tribunal
the government panel found no evidence of damage and ordered the preliminary duties imposed last november refunded. it was the first case involving autos ever handled by the trade tribunal, officials said
all proceedings against hyundai motor co. with regard to dumping will be terminated,'' tribunal secretary art trudeau said in ottawa, where the decision was announced
hyundai spokesman greg young said the refund amounted to ``millions and millions'' of dollars posted in bonds
the feeling here today is like a cloud has been removed from over our head,'' said young
george peapples, president and general manager of general motors of canada, expressed disbelief at the finding
it has been and it remains our contention that continued unrestrained dumping by hyundai will result in lost jobs and investment in the canadian automotive industry,'' peapples said in a statement
given the deputy minister of revenue's findings of dumping margins in excess of 26 percent, it's difficult to comprehend that the tribunal did not find any injury whatsoever.''
gm spokesman nick hall said he could not comment on whether a judicial appeal will be made until the tribunal explains the reasons for its verdict next month. ``there's been a lot of time and effort spent on it already,'' hall said
ford of canada spokesman jim hartford said the ruling points to flaws in canadian trade law and dangers lurking in the comprehensive canada-u.s. free trade agreement scheduled for ratification this year
he said ford was unable to prove substantial injury from hyundai imports because canadian law looked solely at ford production and sales in canada, where small-car production has been phased out, instead of examining ford's integrated north american operations
the tribunal was severely handicapped by the narrow scope of trade law coverage in canada,'' hartford said. ``we're alarmed by the implications today's decision has for other industries which may become rationalized under the free-trade agreement.''
the canadian auto industry, responsible for 140,000 direct jobs, is integrally linked with u.s. operations under a duty-free 1965 auto pact between the two countries treating the continent as a single market
the canadian government made a crucial intervention on hyundai's behalf in the anti-dumping hearing that ended march 10. the bureau of competition policy said hyundai had fostered competition in the small-car market and kept car prices down
hyundai came to canada in 1984 and within a year had a 21 percent share of the subcompact market with sales of 79,072 ponies and stellars. the cheapest of its hatchbacks sold for $6,000 canadian, or $4,500 in american dollars
hyundai then entered the u.s. market where it grabbed a 2.6 percent share last year with sales of 264,000 excels
when ford and gm accused hyundai of dumping and the government initially concurred, hyundai's sales plummeted and some dealers resigned. the company expects to sell about 45,000 cars in canada this year, third behind honda and toyota in the small-car market
auto industry analysts said victory for ford and gm would have opened a pandora's box in which u.s. carmakers might have launched similar attacks on japanese importers, as well as hyundai operations south of the border
i can only assume other importers will evaluate the case today very closely and apply it to their operations,'' said young. uaw comment</note>
the supreme court, in a decision three justices called anti-union, said wednesday the government may limit a family's eligibility for food stamps when a family member is on strike
the court said a 1981 federal law imposing such limits does not violate any constitutional rights. the 5-3 decision reversed a federal judge's 1986 ruling that had struck down the law
justice byron r. white wrote for the court that the law represents a rational effort by congress to remain neutral in labor disputes. but the court's three dissenters, led by justice thurgood marshall, said the law ``amounts to a penalty on strikers, not neutrality.''
the 1981 law, amending the food stamp act, generally bars a family from becoming eligible for food stamps at a time when one of its members is on strike. families already receiving food stamps when a member goes on strike are not dropped from the program but are barred from receiving additional food stamps despite the loss of income
the law was challenged by the united auto workers, the united mine workers and some of their members. they said the law violated strikers' freedom of association and speech, and denied equal protection to strikers' families
but white said, ``exercising the right to strike inevitably risks economic hardship, but we are not inclined to hold that the right to association requires the government to minimize that result by qualifying the strikers for food stamps.''
he added, ``union strike funds should be responsible for providing support and benefits to strikers during labor-management disputes. it was no part of the purposes of the food stamp act to establish a program that would serve as a weapon in labor disputes.''
but marshall contended that the 1981 law amounted to such a ``weapon'' for managment
no other purpose can adequately explain the especially harsh treatment reserved for strikers and their families by the 1981 enactment,'' marshall said
uaw president owen bieber called the decision ``a blow to working families throughout america.''
in a democracy which affords its citizens the legal right to form trade unions and engage in peaceful strikes, it is hypocritical and inconsistent to punish the family members of those who choose to exercise that right,'' bieber said
he said his union would urge congress to do away with the 1981 amendment
the food stamp act generally excludes benefits for people, and the households of people, unwilling to work. but marshall noted that people who can prove they quit their jobs for ``good cause'' may collect food stamps if otherwise eligible _ while strikers may not
white was joined in upholding the law by chief justice william h. rehnquist and justices john paul stevens, sandra day o'connor and antonin scalia
justices william j. brennan and harry a. blackmun joined marshall's dissenting opinion
justice anthony m. kennedy did not participate in the decision
the nation's food stamp program, paid for by the federal government and administered by the states, has supplemented the food-buying power of millions of low-income families since 1964
participating households receive food stamp coupons that can be used for food purchases at retail stores. eligibility for food stamps is based on income and several other factors
households encompassing 21 million people received food stamps in 1984, and the federal government spent $10 billion on the food stamp program that year
in another decision wednesday, the court ruled in an illinois case that short-term notes used to finance public housing projects are not exempt from federal estate taxes. the 8-0 ruling is a victory for the reagan administration, which said more than $260 million in federal tax revenue was at stake
petroleum futures prices soared wednesday and brought precious metals along for the ride after opec finally committed to a date for next month's much-anticipated meeting of its price committee
the runup in oil prices also helped trim losses in stock-index futures, which moved steadily lower early wednesday because of the release of a barrage of anti-inflationary news from the federal government
on other markets, livestock and pork futures were mixed, wheat futures were mostly higher and soybean and corn futures were lower
the advances in oil came on a third day of frenzied activity at the new york mercantile exchange. crude lost 9 cents in the spot month monday and 40 cents tuesday as traders awaited word from opec president rilwanu lukman on when the pricing committee would meet
oil opened under pressure again wednesday, but rose when lukman finally announced the regularly scheduled meeting would take place in april. it surged 58 cents during one early afternoon stretch to the day's high of $16.96 a barrel after saudi arabia endorsed the opec gathering
when anyone else says that, the market takes it with a grain of salt,'' said bob murphy, analyst with e.f. hutton &amp; co., new york. ``but when the saudis do it, especially since they've been making noises recently about discounting their own product, the impact was almost immediate
