northwest airlines' new smoking ban hits the air-travel market at a time when anti-puffing campaigns are gaining momentum, but it may revive a debate that snuffed out a pioneer of smoke-free flying
muse air corp. of dallas tried and failed to establish itself as the nation's only no-smoking airline in 1985
the effort _ which offered passengers discounted tickets if they turned in their cigarettes at the gate _ was scrapped when the airline was purchased later that year by southwest airlines co. for $65 million
while the regional carrier had begun to draw its identity from its no-smoking policy, its research showed the practice was chasing away as many as 35 percent of potential passengers
surveys revealed that fliers find ``price, convenience and service more important than non-smoking'' in choosing an airline, muse spokeswoman shari cohen said at the time
she said muse may have been a bit ahead of its time by banning smoking and that the pioneer role may have hurt
even now, in the wake of the federal government's move to ban smoking on all air flights lasting less than two hours, some militant smokers are holding fast
the great american smoker's club of dallas is scheduled to make its grand entrance on april 22, a day before the government's ban goes into effect. the group, founded by two businessmen, aims to evade the ban by charging a membership fee
for $25 a year or $40 for a family, smokers can join the club and pay the same fares southwest charges to fly from dallas' love field to austin, houston, new orleans, oklahoma city, san antonio and tulsa
the club is leasing several planes from las vegas-based royal west airlines, said club president glenn herndon, who estimated the startup cost at $2 million
we want to offer cigarette smokers a choice to continue their right to smoke,'' he said. ``to fly on a plane nowadays, smokers are treated like second-class citizens and must sit on the back rows. when the smoking ban begins, we want to offer smokers an alternative _ and, hopefully, make some money.''
herndon said the club's target is to serve 63 cities from five hubs with 60 planes within two years
by the way, non-smokers will be allowed on board, but they will have to be ``tolerant,'' the club says. to gentlemen's sted gentleman's. picks up 3rd graf pvs, the survey ...</note>
american men place a premium on marriage and families and say the father's role in raising children is as important as that played by the mother, a survey said wednesday
while modern courtship and romance may seem confusing to many american men, family remains their anchor in life,'' the survey commissioned by gentlemen's quarterly magazine said
the survey said 73 percent of those responding to a questionnaire indicated they felt strongly that their family is the most important facet of their lives
it said 54 percent felt strongly that a man's most satisfying accomplishment is to be a father, while 84 percent felt strongly that a father's role is as important as the mother's in raising children
the survey said that 60 percent rated their marriage as more important than their job, friends or other family ties and that only 10 percent agreed strongly with the assertion that marriage ``makes you lose your personal identity.''
this is hardly a confirmation that the '80s man is afraid of commitment as is so often thought,'' the survey said
the survey was conducted by the independent research firm, significance inc. of ridgewood, n.j., which said it received 1,062 responses to questionnaires that were mailed in mid-november to about 2,600 men aged 18 years and older. the men were asked to rank their reactions to various assertions on a scale of 0 to 10
the firm said that the replies generally indicated that marketers should pay more attention to attitudes rather than age, income or occupation in fashioning marketing strategies
the researchers said 52 percent of those surveyed can be categorized as ``change-adapters'' _ those who generally share a positive self-image and thrive in an atmosphere of change
the remaining 48 percent, the firm said, can be called ``change-opposers'' _those who in varying degrees are experiencing some degree of alienation from society and ``are having trouble coping.''
marketers trying to reach these groups may do well to ``understand their frame of mind and view it that way rather than their time of life,'' said jack kliger, publisher of gq
among some other findings of the survey:
_while only 25 percent of those surveyed said they strongly support the women's movement, 79 percent expressed strong support for the statement, ``it's only fair that women should get equal pay for comparable work.''
_fifteen percent said they strongly agreed with the statement, ``it's just unrealistic to expect a married man never to have an extramartial affair.''
_twenty-six percent said they felt strongly that their career was the proudest accomplishment of their lives, and 40 percent said they strongly felt it is an important expression of who they are. but only 15 percent agreed strongly that their career ``means as much to me as my family or friends do.''
_one-third of those surveyed said they spend 30 minutes or less a day on grooming, another third spends between 30 minutes and 45 minutes and the remaining third spends more than 45 minutes a day on grooming
_forty-eight percent said they strongly felt women ``go for the good-looking men first'' before considering brains or personality. forty-six percent take women's suggestions on appearance seriously, but only 25 percent say they strongly like getting such advice
domestic car sales fell slightly in mid-march despite a selling surge at chrysler corp., automakers reported wednesday
analysts said an earlier flurry of higher-than-expected sales due to incentives and a stock-crash rebound appeared to be tapering off
the eight companies that make autos in the united states sold 189,245 cars in the eight sales days from march 11-20, down from 217,939 in nine sales days in the comparable 1987 period. the daily sales rate was down 2.3 percent
sales of domestically made light trucks totaled 109,509, down from 115,684 in the year ago period but still a 6.5 percent increase in daily sales
combined domestic car and light truck sales totaled 298,754, down from 333,623 for mid-march 1987 but up 0.7 percent on a daily basis
sales of foreign-made cars are reported at the end of the month
domestic sales were at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 6.4 million for the mid-march period
that would indicate a decline from the industry's 7.1 million in domestic sales in 1987. for the prior 30 days, however, sales ran at an 8.1 million seasonally adjusted annual rate
it looks like sales are beginning to drop back down to a more expected level,'' said chris cedergren, auto analyst at j.d. power &amp; associates in westlake village, calif
jeannette garretty, an analyst at the bank of america in san francisco, said sales surged prior to the mid-march period as consumers reacted to incentives and made purchases put off due to caution after the october stock market crash. ``now it is going to start to settle down,'' she said
industry leader general motors corp. sold 92,173 domestically made cars in the march 11-20 period, down from 105,438 in the comparable 1987 period. the daily sales rate was off 1.7 percent
ford motor co. auto sales of 54,186 were down from 67,672 in the year-earlier period, and down 9.9 percent on a daily basis
chrysler car sales jumped to 30,801 from 31,699 in the same period in 1987, up 9.3 percent on a daily sales basis, aided by strong sales of chrysler new yorker and landau luxury models, the company said
chrysler's domestic light truck sales jumped even more, totaling 24,691, up from 20,987 in the year-earlier period and up 32.4 percent in daily sales
it was the eighth straight period of rising car sales at chrysler, said tom pappert, group vice president for sales. ``we are clearly going into the spring selling season with momentum on our side.''
gm also was a gainer in truck sales with an eight-day total of 45,376, up from 43,515. the daily sales rate was up 17.3 percent
ford light truck sales sagged to 36,812, from 49,164 in the year-earlier period. the daily sales rate fell 15.8 percent
market shares of the big three automakers changed only slightly from the year-earlier period, with gm capturing 48.7 percent, compared with 48.4 percent; ford accounting for 28.6 percent, down from 31.1 percent, and chrysler moving up to 16.3 percent from 14.5 percent in the year-earlier period
aggressive incentives paid off for some japanese companies manufacturing cars in the united states. honda's sales of 7,270 represented a 9.8 percent increase in its daily sales rate
volkswagen of america sold 1,034 u.s.-made cars, down 12.5 percent from 1,330 a year earlier
the big three u.s. automakers accounted for 93.6 percent of u.s. sales of u.s.-made cars
we continue to be pleased with the strength of the market,'' said c.n. moore, vice president in charge of customer sales and service at gm
grolier inc. said wednesday its board had rejected as inadequate a $415 million takeover bid from french publisher hachette sa, and said it has talked with others who may be interested in making a rival proposal
on the new york stock exchange, grolier's stock rose 12{ cents a share to close at $26.50, a price that was well above the $21-a-share bid from hachette
the rejection of a $21 bid when the stock was at $26 was no great shock,'' said jane gilday, managing director of mckinley allsopp inc. in new york. ``grolier made it clear there are other bidders and they're committed to maximizing shareholder value.''
grolier said its board of directors was unanimous in rejecting as inadequate the unsolicited takeover offer from hachette
in this regard, representatives of grolier have had preliminary contact with several parties who have indicated an interest in making a proposal to acquire the company,'' robert b. clarke, chairman and chief executive, said in a statement. clarke did not name the companies
grolier said that if it is unable to negotiate an acquisition of the company on satisfactory terms, it will look at other alternatives such as a leveraged buyout or a financial restructuring
i think the next move is that grolier will now entertain these other bids,'' gilday said. ``and, hachette could raise its bid.''
hannah bruce, vice president of tucker anthony &amp; r.l. day in new york, said, ``the way the stock market has reacted throughout this whole two weeks, it appears the market feels grolier will be worth more.''
danbury-based grolier is a publisher of encyclopedias, reference and educational books and children's books, and owns a film processing firm. it earned $22.1 million on sales of $424.2 million in 1987. the company has 7,300 employees in 20 countries
hachette, france's biggest publisher, said last week that it was offering $21 a share in cash for the 95 percent of grolier's roughly 19.5 million shares that it did not already own
bruce said grolier has a strong management team and credited the company's turnaround in the last decade to clarke
the company was near bankruptcy in the late 1970s, clarke came in as chairman and he rebuilt it. he divested all non-publishing activity and structured the enclopedia group,'' bruce said. ``the company is very strong. ... earnings are growing 30 percent-plus a year.''
she said the company has some ``very attractive pieces,'' including its adult and childrens' book clubs
they basically sell their products to parents with young children,'' she said. ``they have a strong customer base.''
kansas city southern industries inc. said wednesday that a proposed buyout effort by a new york developer may be designed to stimulate trading in the company's stock and to draw attention to the developer's previously-disclosed plan to win two board seats
the railroad, data processing and financial services company noted that howard kaskel, the new york developer, had simply proposed talks toward a possible negotiated merger in his letter to the company this week
it said the letter did not contain an offer to shareholders, and does not state that financing for any transaction has been obtained
in the letter, kaskel proposed buying the 89 percent of the company's 11.1 million shares that his group doesn't already control for $60 a share in cash. such a transaction would be worth about $590 million
the letter appears to be an effort to stimulate trading in the kansas city southern industries' stock and perhaps to publicize kaskel's previously announced plan to nominate two persons for election to the kansas city southern industries' board of directors,'' the company's statement said
a call was placed after business hours to kaskel's lawyer for comment, but the lawyer could not be reached
wall street has indicated skepticism about whether an offer will be forthcoming. in trading on the new york stock exchange, kansas city southern fell $2 a share to $54.50 on wednesday
if mr. kaskel, as a large shareholder, wishes to nominate an individual ... we would certainly be pleased to consider such a person,'' kansas city southern president landon h. rowland was quoted as saying in his company's statement
the statement said the ``on-again, off-again efforts of the kaskel group to thwart kansas city southern industries' proposed acquisition of the southern pacific ... are viewed by management as inconsistent with the best interests of the company and its stockholders.''
rowland said earlier in the week that the kcsi board would consider the kaskel proposal at a special meeting, but declined to say when the meeting would be held. negotiating to terminate its management contract and to delete reference to los angeles and hong kong investors. picks up 9th graf, recreational properties...</note>
del e. webb corp. announced wednesday its board of directors approved a restructuring plan that includes selling off its casinos and other leisure operations and focusing instead on real estate
in recent years, webb's most profitable operations on a continuing basis have been real-estate oriented and particularly our adult community developments,'' said philip j. dion, the corporation's chairman. ``this, our greatest past and present strength, is where we will concentrate our efforts.''
present shareholder value will be maximized by the sale of our leisure facilities and use of the proceeds to strengthen the company's balance sheet and provide the capital necessary to continue expansion of our real estate business,'' dion said
the leisure operations the phoenix-based company owns and manages had revenue of $171 million in 1987, $127 million from the three nevada casino hotels and $44 million from recreational properties, dion said
gaming includes three casino hotels in nevada which del webb will reacquire complete control of next month _ the mint in las vegas, the high sierra at lake tahoe and the nevada club in laughlin
dion said the three casinos were sold to two limited partnerships run by webb executives in 1984
he said the reacquisition will allow for the orderly disposition of the properties by simplifying the ownership structure
the company also is negotiating with the limited partnership that owns the claridge hotel and casino in atlantic city, n.j., to terminate webb's contract to manage the hotel
recreational properties the company owns and operates include five marinas on lake powell in arizona and utah, and wilderness river adventures, a river-rafting company on the colorado river
when the restructuring is complete, dion said the company will consist of del e. webb communities inc. and del e. webb commercial properties corp. the communities concern is the developer of sun city west vistro in arizona and sun city summerlin, an adult community in las vegas
